rchive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n*David Morrison, founding employee of [[Lee Equity Partners]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dai|first=Shasha|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB115647195833745226|title=Lee Equity Partners Is Launched With Team of Seven Professionals|date=2006-08-25|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n*[[David A. Nadler|David Nadler]], American organizational theorist\n*[[Raphaela Neihausen]], American producer and filmmaker<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.docnyc.net/about-us/meet-the-team/|title=Meet the Team|last=|first=|date=|website=DOC NYC|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Niklas \u00d6stberg, co-founder of [[Delivery Hero]]\n* [[Antonia Romeo]], [[Permanent Secretary]] at the British [[Department for International Trade]]\n*Phyllis Rothschild, partner at [[McKinsey & Company]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mckinsey.com/our-people/phyllis-rothschild|title=Phyllis Rothschild|last=|first=|date=|website=McKinsey & Company|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Hector Sants]], former CEO of the British [[Financial Services Authority]]\n*Michael Schumann, former CEO of German [[:de:Geschichte der Arques Industries|Arques Industries AG]], predecessor to [[Gigaset Communications]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.europeanfinanceforum.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Schumann_-_CV.pdf|title=Dr. Michael Schumann - CV|last=|first=|date=|website=European Finance Forum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Adam Selipskyas, CEO of [[Tableau Software]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://finance.yahoo.com/news/tableau-software-appoints-former-amazon-204608647.html|title=Tableau Software Appoints Former Amazon Exec as CEO|last=|first=|date=2018-07-23|website=Yahoo Finance|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Scott Setrakian, co-founder of [[Applied Predictive Technologies]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siepr.stanford.edu/events/speakers/scott-setrakian|title=Scott Setrakian {{!}} SIEPR|last=|first=|date=|website=Stanford Institute for Economic Policy Research|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Premal Shah]], American entrepreneur and co-founder of [[Kiva]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20080509005071/en/Oliver-Wyman-Announces-Strategic-Alliance-Kiva-Worlds|title=Oliver Wyman Announces Strategic Alliance with Kiva, the World's Leading Person-to-Person Micro-Lending Website|last=|first=|date=2008-05-09|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Adrian Slywotzky]], American economist\n*[[Larry Tanz]], American entertainment industry executive\n*[[Miqdaad Versi]], assistant Secretary General to the [[Muslim Council of Britain]]\n* [[Jamie Whyte]], leader of [[ACT New Zealand]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11198243|title=Michele Hewitson interview: Jamie Whyte|last=|first=|date=2014-02-08|website=New Zealand Herald|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n*Stephen Wilcke, CEO of the British [[Asset Protection Agency]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hall|first=James|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/7791144/Revealed-Salaries-of-the-Citys-top-civil-servants.html|title=Revealed: Salaries of the City's top civil servants|date=2010-06-01|work=The Telegraph|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Mason|first2=Rowena|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n*[[Debbie Wosskow]], British entrepreneur and angel investor\n*[[Andrew Youn]], founder of [[One Acre Fund]]\n* [[Jeffrey Zients]], former Director of the [[National Economic Council (United States)|United States National Economic Council]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.oliverwyman.com Oliver Wyman]\n\n{{Consulting}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Consulting]]\n[[Category:International management consulting firms]]\n[[Category:Management consulting firms of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Pereneph", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAlumni", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oliver_Wyman"}
{"title_page": "Flynas", "text_new": "{{Infobox Airline\n| airline        = Flynas<br /><small>\u0637\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0646\u0627\u0633</small>\n| logo =Flynas_Logo.svg\n| fleet_size     = 32\n| destinations   = 23{{fact|date=October 2018}}\n| IATA           = XY\n| ICAO           = KNE\n| callsign       = NAS EXPRESS\n| parent         = National Air Services\n| company_slogan = ''The Kingdom's First Low-Cost Airline''\n| founded        = {{start date|2007}}\n| commenced      = {{start date|2007|2}}\n| headquarters   = [[Riyadh]], [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| key_people     = {{unbulleted list|Ayed Al Jeaid&nbsp;<small>([[Chairman of the Board]] of NAS Holding)</small><ref>{{cite web|title=NAS HOLDING APPOINTS BANDER AL-MOHANNA AS CEO OF THE GROUP|url=https://www.flynas.com/en/media-center/news-updates/238-ceo|publisher= flynas|date= 1 February 2015|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180626152431/https://www.flynas.com/en/media-center/news-updates/238-ceo|archive-date= 26 June 2018}}</ref>|Bander Al-Mohanna&nbsp;<small>([[CEO]] of flynas)</small><ref name=\"flynas Takes Delivery of its First Airbus A320neo Aircraft\">{{cite web|title= flynas Takes Delivery of its First Airbus A320neo Aircraft|publisher= flynas|date= 13 November 2018|url= https://www.flynas.com/en/media-center/news-updates/a320neo-arrived|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181114134017/https://www.flynas.com/en/media-center/news-updates/a320neo-arrived|archive-date= 14 November 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| bases          = {{plainlist|\n* [[King Abdulaziz International Airport]]\n* [[King Khalid International Airport]]\n* [[King Fahd International Airport]]<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.flynas.com/en/plan-my-trip/where-we-fly|title=flynas hubs|accessdate=25 March 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| secondary_hubs =\n| focus_cities   =\n| frequent_flyer =\n| lounge         =\n| website        = {{URL|www.flynas.com}}\n|image=|aoc=|hubs=|num_employees=}}\n\n'''Flynas''' ({{lang-ar|\u0637\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0646\u0627\u0633}}), stylized ''flynas'', formerly '''Nas Air''', is a domestic and international [[Low cost carrier|low-cost airline]] based in [[Saudi Arabia]], the country{{'s}} first [[budget airline]].<ref name=\"Saudi budget carrier flynas says to become profitable this year\" /> The company's head office is located in [[Riyadh]].<ref>{{cite web|title= flynas Headquarters|url= http://www.flynas.com/en/contact-us/office-locations|publisher= Flynas|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170702131541/http://www.flynas.com/en/contact-us/office-locations|archive-date= 2 July 2017|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{expand section|date=April 2014}}\n[[Saudia|Saudi Arabian Airlines]] was the only airline in the country until {{YEAR|2006}}, when budget carriers Nas Air and [[Sama (airline)|Sama Airlines]] got their licenses from the [[Saudi government|government]].<ref name=\"Saudi market opens up further\" /> Nas Air was founded in {{start date|2007}}.<ref name=\"Saudi Arabia's flynas long-haul LCC to Europe and Asia, introducing a new low cost alternative\" /> Operations started in February that year.<ref name=\"Saudi market opens up further\" /> In late 2007, Nas Air firmed up an order for the acquisition of 20 aircraft of the [[Airbus A320 family]].<ref name=\"Dubai 2007: NAS firms Airbus deal\" />\n\nThe company changed its name from ''Nasair'' to ''Flynas'' in {{start date|2013|11}}.<ref name=\"Saudi\u2019s Flynas seeks to renegotiate its A320 order\" /><ref name=\"Rebranded Nasair aiming for 20m passengers by 2020\" />\n\n==Corporate affairs==\n\n===Ownership===\n{{As of|2014|10}}, Flynas was owned in its majority by National Airline Services Holding (63%); the balance was held by [[Kingdom Holding]].<ref name=\"Saudi budget carrier flynas suspends long-haul services\" />\n\n== Destinations ==\n{{Main|List of Flynas destinations}}\n[[Assiut]] and [[Sharm el Sheikh]] in [[Egypt]] became served by the carrier for the first time in 2009, with flights to the latter initially operated on a seasonal basis.<ref name=\"Nasair launches new routes\" /> In 2011, the airline started services to three cities in Turkey: [[Adana]], [[Antakya]] and [[Istanbul]].<ref name=\"Saudi low cost carrier launches flights to Turkey\" /> Also that year, [[Lahore]] in [[Pakistan]] became the second city served in the country, after [[Karachi]].<ref name=\"Saudi's Nasair launches new Pakistan route\" /> In {{start date|2013|2}}, flights to [[Yanbu]] from [[Dammam]] were launched. Also that month, the airline started flying from Dammam to [[Khartoum]], with the [[Sudan]]ese capital becoming the first international destination ever to be linked to the Saudi city.<ref>{{cite press release|title= Nasair launches its first flights from Dammam to Yanbu and Khartoum, launched a new sales office in Jubail to serve Nasair customers in the region|publisher= Flynas|date= 25 February 2013|url= http://www.flynas.com/media-centre/news/2013/02/25/nasair-launches-its-first-flights-from-dammam-to-yanbu-and-khartoum-launched-a-new-sales-office-in-jubail-to-serve-nasair-customers-in-the-region|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140401224327/http://www.flynas.com/media-centre/news/2013/02/25/nasair-launches-its-first-flights-from-dammam-to-yanbu-and-khartoum-launched-a-new-sales-office-in-jubail-to-serve-nasair-customers-in-the-region|archivedate= 1 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn {{start date|2014|2}}, Flynas introduced its ''Global Flight Routes'' program, aimed at offering affordable rates to passengers for flights between Jeddah and points in Africa, Asia and Europe,<ref name=\"Flynas launches Global Flight Routes program\" /> and at carrying religious tourists to Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"Flynas abandons long-haul program\" /> In {{start date|2014|3}},<ref name=\"Flynas receives first Airbus 330 plane as part of fleet expansion\" /> Flynas incorporated the {{ordinal to word|1}} of {{cardinal to word|3}} [[Airbus A330]]s the carrier would lease from Portugal{{'s}} [[Hi Fly (airline)|Hi Fly]]. These aircraft, including both the [[Airbus A330-200|\u2013200]] and the [[Airbus A330-300|\u2013300]] models, would be used to start long-haul services.<ref name=\"Flynas takes delivery of first A330\" /> The airline also planned to add the [[Airbus A350]] to its fleet.<ref name=\"Saudi Carrier Flynas Keen on A350 Deal as Airbus Order Reviewed\" />\n\nFlynas became the first low-cost carrier to serve the Saudi Arabia-[[UK]] market when it launched the [[Jeddah]]\u2013[[London-Gatwick|London Gatwick]] service, its first European long-haul route, in {{start date|2014|4}}.<ref name=\"Flynas launches new service to London Gatwick airport\" /> Medium-haul routes to [[Karachi]] and [[Lahore]] were also planned, along with long-haul services to [[Jakarta]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Casablanca]], [[Manchester]] and [[Islamabad]].<ref name=\"flynas returns to short-haul flying as Saudi Arabia welcomes Al Maha Airways and SaudiGulf Airlines\" /> Flights to [[Iran]] were also due to commence by the same time.<ref>{{cite news|title= Saudi low-cost carrier plans expansion into Europe, Asia|first= Nada|last= Altuwaijri|work= Al Arabiya News|date= 18 December 2013|url= http://english.alarabiya.net/en/business/aviation-and-transport/2013/11/18/Saudi-low-cost-carrier-expansion-into-Europe-Asia.html}}</ref> Manchester became the airline{{'s}} {{ordinal to word|2}} destination in the United Kingdom on {{start date|2014|5|7|df=yes}}.<ref name=\"Saudia Arabian flight touches down in Manchester for first time\" /><ref name=\"Inaugural Flynas flight touches down at Manchester\" /> [[Cairo]] was made part of the route network in {{start date|2014|6}}, making the Egyptian capital the carrier{{'s}} {{ordinal to word|7}} destination in the country.<ref name=\"Flynas touches down in Cairo with daily non-stop flights\" /> The London-Gatwick\u2013Riyadh sector would also be served from 27 July the same year.<ref name=\"Saudi's flynas set to launch London Gatwick flights\" /> A month later, it was informed that services to Manchester would be discontinued starting {{start date|2014|8}}, just after {{cardinal to word|3}} months of operations.<ref name=\"Middle Eastern carriers drop routes\" /><ref name=\"Saudi\u2019s Flynas To Drop Manchester In August\" /> That month, the Indian market was expected to be served for the first time with flights to [[Hyderabad]], followed by [[Kozhikode|Calicut]] in {{start date|2014|9}}.<ref name=\"Saudi budget airline Flynas to begin operations next month\" /> Plans were also to serve [[France]] next as well as [[China]], [[Philippines]], [[Nigeria]] and [[South Africa]] later on.<ref name=\"Saudi Carrier Flynas Keen on A350 Deal as Airbus Order Reviewed\" /> Flynas also expected to serve the [[US]] market in {{YEAR|2015}}.<ref name=\"ROUTES: Flynas to start US flights in 2015\" /> However, Manchester was removed from the carrier{{'s}} list of destinations in early {{end date|2014|8}},<ref name=\"Flynas axes Manchester service\" /> and in October the same year the airline announced the cancellation of most of its long- and mid-haul services owing to poor performance.<ref name=\"Flynas abandons long-haul program\" /><ref>{{cite press release|title= Official statement from flynas regarding Global Flight Program flight suspension|publisher= Flynas|date= 15 October 2014|url= http://www.flynas.com/en/news/2014/10/15/official-statement-from-flynas-regarding-global-flight-program-flight-suspension|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141029012555/http://www.flynas.com/en/news/2014/10/15/official-statement-from-flynas-regarding-global-flight-program-flight-suspension|archivedate= 29 October 2014|df= dmy-all}}&nbsp;</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= flynas W14 Network Changes|date= 24 October 2014|work= Airline Route|url= http://airlineroute.net/2014/10/24/xy-w14update/|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141024120008/http://airlineroute.net/2014/10/24/xy-w14update/|archivedate= 24 October 2014|df= dmy-all}}&nbsp;</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, [[Prince Nayef bin Abdulaziz Regional Airport|Al-Qassim]] was incorporated to the route network.<ref name=\"AL-QASSIM IS NEWEST FLYNAS DESTINATION\" /> {{as of|2015|4|alt= At {{start date|2015|4}} }}, Flynas' three top domestic routes in terms of available seats were Jeddah (JED)\u2013Riyadh (RUH), Dammam (DMM)\u2013RUH and JED\u2013DMM.<ref name=\"flynas benefits from relaxed Saudi fare cap; could become the second Gulf partner for Cebu Pacific\" /> The carrier also performs [[Hajj]] services.<ref name=\"Flynas appoints new CEO, focuses on regional traffic\" /><ref name=\"Nigerian Pilgrims in High Spirit, Commend Officials for Improved Services\" />\n\n===Codeshare agreements===\nA [[codeshare agreement]] with [[Etihad Airways|Etihad]] that dates back to {{start date|2012}} sees Flynas placing its code on a number of flights operated by Etihad that radiate from Abu Dhabi.<ref name=\"flynas returns to short-haul flying as Saudi Arabia welcomes Al Maha Airways and SaudiGulf Airlines\" /><ref name=\"Etihad inks codeshare deal with Saudi's nasair\" /> In May 2016 the airline signed a codeshare agreement with [[Pegasus Airlines]].<ref>{{cite press release|url= https://www.flypgs.com/en/press-room/press-releases/pegasus-network-now-extends-to-saudi-arabia-via-flynas-codeshare-partership|title= Flynas and Pegasus code share details|publisher= Pegasus Airlines|date= 11 May 2016|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160520202615/https://www.flypgs.com/en/press-room/press-releases/pegasus-network-now-extends-to-saudi-arabia-via-flynas-codeshare-partership|archivedate= 20 May 2016|df= dmy-all}}&nbsp;</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Flynas joined the [[International Air Transport Association]] (IATA) which will help the company with \"greater co-operation\" with other member airlines and increase connectivity through codeshare agreements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://airlines.iata.org/news/saudi-carrier-flynas-joins-iata|title=Saudi carrier Flynas joins IATA {{!}} Airlines.|website=airlines.iata.org|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n==Fleet==\n===Current Fleet===\n[[File:Flynas A320-200 VP-CXR DXB 2014-11-22.jpg|thumb|A Flynas Airbus A320-200 at [[Dubai International Airport]] in 2014.]]\n{{as of|2019|11}}, the Flynas fleet consists of the following aircraft:<ref>{{cite web|title= Flynas Fleet|publisher= Flynas|url= https://www.flynas.com/en/about-us/fleet}}</ref><ref name=\"Airbus_Orders\">{{cite web|url= https://www.airbus.com/content/dam/corporate-topics/publications/o&d/ODs-Airbus-Commercial-Aircraft-August-2019.xlsx|title= Airbus orders and deliveries|publisher= Airbus|date= August 2019|archive-date= 6 September 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190906090916/https://www.airbus.com/content/dam/corporate-topics/publications/o%26d/ODs-Airbus-Commercial-Aircraft-August-2019.xlsx|access-date= 6 September 2019|url-status= live}}</ref>\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ '''Flynas fleet'''\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Aircraft\n!rowspan=\"2\"|In Fleet\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Orders\n!colspan=\"3\"|Passengers\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Notes\n|-\n!<abbr title=\"Business class\">J</abbr>\n!<abbr title=\"Economy class\">Y</abbr>\n!Total\n|-\n|[[Airbus A320 family|Airbus A319-100]]\n|1\n|&mdash;\n|colspan=\"3\"|TBA\n|\n|-\n|[[Airbus A320 family|Airbus A320-200]]\n|24\n|&mdash;\n|8\n|156\n|164\n|\n|-\n|[[Airbus A320neo family|Airbus A320neo]]\n|6\n|114<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flynas.com/en/media-center/news-updates/fourth-airbus-a32neo|title=flynas receives its fourth Airbus A32neo aircraft|last=Flynas|website=flynas.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref>\n|8\n|166\n|174\n|\n|-\n|[[Airbus A320neo family|Airbus A321XLR]]\n|&mdash;\n|10<ref>https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/dubai-flynas-firms-up-order-for-10-a321xlrs-462393/</ref>\n|colspan=\"3\"|TBA\n|\n|-\n!Total\n!33\n!127\n!colspan=\"5\"|\n|}\n</center>\n\n===Previously operated===\nThroughout its history the carrier operated the following equipment:\n* [[Airbus A310-300]]<ref name=\"ps\" />\n* [[Airbus A330-200]]<ref name=\"ch-aviation\">{{cite web|title= Flynas fleet|work= ch-aviation GmbH|url= http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/aircraft/search?search=1&cha=FXY|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141024113127/http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/aircraft/search?search=1&cha=FXY|archivedate= 24 October 2014|df= dmy-all}}&nbsp;</ref>\n* [[Boeing 737-500]]<ref name=\"ps\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.planespotters.net/Airline/Nas-Air |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115143848/https://www.planespotters.net/airline/Nas-Air |archive-date=15 November 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Boeing 757-200]]<ref name=\"ps\" />\n* [[Boeing 747-400]]<ref name=\"ch-aviation\" />\n* [[Boeing 767-300ER]]<ref name=\"ch-aviation\" />\n* [[Embraer 190LR]]<ref name=\"ps\" />\n* [[Embraer 195AR]]<ref name=\"ps\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Air Arabia]]\n* [[FlyDubai]]\n* [[Transport in Saudi Arabia]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"AL-QASSIM IS NEWEST FLYNAS DESTINATION\">{{cite press release|title= Al-Qassim is newest Flynas destination|publisher= Flynas|date= 16 October 2014|url= http://www.flynas.com/en/news/2014/10/16/al-qassim-is-newest-flynas-destination|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141024120945/http://www.flynas.com/en/news/2014/10/16/al-qassim-is-newest-flynas-destination|archivedate= 24 October 2014|df= dmy-all}}&nbsp;</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Dubai 2007: NAS firms Airbus deal\">{{cite news|title= Dubai 2007: NAS firms Airbus deal|agency= Flight Daily News|publisher= [[Flightglobal]]|date= 13 November 2007|url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/dubai-2007-nas-firms-airbus-deal-219677/|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180221134825/https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/dubai-2007-nas-firms-airbus-deal-219677/|archive-date= 21 February 2018}}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Etihad inks codeshare deal with Saudi's nasair\">{{cite news|title= Etihad inks codeshare deal with Saudi's nasair|first= Andy|last= Sambidge|work= arabianbusiness.com|date= 1 October 2012|url= http://www.arabianbusiness.com/etihad-inks-codeshare-deal-with-saudi-s-nasair-474886.html|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140703202820/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/etihad-inks-codeshare-deal-with-saudi-s-nasair-474886.html|archivedate= 3 July 2014 }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Flynas abandons long-haul program\">{{cite news|title= Flynas abandons long-haul program|first= Alan|last= Dron|work= [[Air Transport World]]|date= 28 October 2014|url= http://atwonline.com/airports-routes/flynas-abandons-long-haul-program|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141029005247/http://atwonline.com/airports-routes/flynas-abandons-long-haul-program|archivedate= 29 October 2014|df= dmy-all}}&nbsp;</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Flynas appoints new CEO, focuses on regional traffic\">{{cite news|title= Flynas appoints new CEO, focuses on regional traffic|first= Alexander|last= Cornwell|newspaper= [[Gulf News]]|date= 20 November 2014|url= http://gulfnews.com/business/aviation/flynas-appoints-new-ceo-focuses-on-regional-traffic-1.1415718|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141127001552/http://gulfnews.com/business/aviation/flynas-appoints-new-ceo-focuses-on-regional-traffic-1.1415718|archivedate= 27 November 2014|df= dmy-all}}&nbsp;</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Flynas axes Manchester service\">{{cite news|title= Flynas axes Manchester service|first= James|last= Graham|work= TheBusinessDesk|date= 5 August 2014|url= http://www.thebusinessdesk.com/northwest/news/652257-flynas-axes-manchester-service.html?news_section=4148|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140807112836/http://www.thebusinessdesk.com/northwest/news/652257-flynas-axes-manchester-service.html?news_section=4148|archivedate= 7 August 2014|df= dmy-all}}&nbsp;</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"flynas benefits from relaxed Saudi fare cap; could become the second Gulf partner for Cebu Pacific\">{{cite news|title= flynas benefits from relaxed Saudi fare cap; could become the second Gulf partner for Cebu Pacific|work= CAPA Centre for Aviation|date= 15 April 2015|url= http://centreforaviation.com/analysis/flynas-benefits-from-relaxed-saudi-fare-cap-could-become-the-second-gulf-partner-for-cebu-pacific-218686|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150416213511/http://centreforaviation.com/analysis/flynas-benefits-from-relaxed-saudi-fare-cap-could-become-the-second-gulf-partner-for-cebu-pacific-218686|archivedate= 16 April 2015|df= dmy-all}}&nbsp;</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Flynas launches Global Flight Routes program\">{{cite news|title= Flynas launches Global Flight Routes program|work= Arab News|date= 4 February 2014|url= http://www.arabnews.com/news/520046|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140703205814/http://www.arabnews.com/news/520046|archivedate= 3 July 2014 }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Flynas launches new service to London Gatwick airport\">{{cite news|title= Flynas launches new service to London Gatwick airport|work= Arab News|date= 12 April 2014|url= http://www.arabnews.com/news/554371|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140703204404/http://www.arabnews.com/news/554371|archivedate= 3 July 2014 }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Flynas receives first Airbus 330 plane as part of fleet expansion\">{{cite news|title= Flynas receives first Airbus 330 plane as part of fleet expansion|date= 29 March 2014|work= Arab News|url= http://www.arabnews.com/news/547321|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140401211708/http://www.arabnews.com/news/547321|archivedate= 1 April 2014 }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"flynas returns to short-haul flying as Saudi Arabia welcomes Al Maha Airways and SaudiGulf Airlines\">{{cite news|title= flynas returns to short-haul flying as Saudi Arabia welcomes Al Maha Airways and SaudiGulf Airlines|work= CAPA Centre for Aviation|date= 3 December 2014|url= http://centreforaviation.com/analysis/flynas-returns-to-short-haul-travel-as-saudi-arabia-welcomes-al-maha-airways-and-saudigulf-airlines-198614|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141203104048/http://centreforaviation.com/analysis/flynas-returns-to-short-haul-travel-as-saudi-arabia-welcomes-al-maha-airways-and-saudigulf-airlines-198614|archivedate= 3 December 2014|df= dmy-all}}&nbsp;</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Flynas takes delivery of first A330\">{{cite news|title= Flynas takes delivery of first A330|first= Alan|last= Dron|work= [[Air Transport World]]|date= 1 April 2014|url= http://atwonline.com/airframes/flynas-takes-delivery-first-a330|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140401204224/http://atwonline.com/airframes/flynas-takes-delivery-first-a330|archivedate= 1 April 2014 }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Flynas touches down in Cairo with daily non-stop flights\">{{cite news|title= Flynas touches down in Cairo with daily non-stop flights|work= [[Al Bawaba]]|date= 3 June 2014|url= http://www.albawaba.com/business/pr/flynas-cairo-non-stop-flights-580698|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140609203807/http://www.albawaba.com/business/pr/flynas-cairo-non-stop-flights-580698|archivedate= 9 June 2014 }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Inaugural Flynas flight touches down at Manchester\">{{cite news|title= Inaugural Flynas flight touches down at Manchester|work= Arabian Aerospace|date= 7 May 2014|url= http://www.arabianaerospace.aero/inaugural-flynas-flight-touches-down-at-manchester.html|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140509113956/http://www.arabianaerospace.aero/inaugural-flynas-flight-touches-down-at-manchester.html|archivedate= 9 May 2014 }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref 