 Onto the Couch |work=The New York Times |date=July 29, 2009 |accessdate=2009-08-02}}\n* {{cite news <!--|author=Pollan, Michael |authormask=1-->|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/10/opinion/10pollan.html |title=Big Food vs. Big Insurance |work=The New York Times |date=September 9, 2009 |accessdate=2009-09-14}}\n* {{cite journal <!--|author=Pollan, Michael |authormask=1-->|date=December 23\u201330, 2013 |title=A Reporter at Large: The Intelligent Plant |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |volume=89 |issue=42 |pages=92\u2013105 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2013/12/23/the-intelligent-plant |accessdate=2014-10-15}}\n* {{cite journal <!--|author=Pollan, Michael |authormask=1-->|date=February 9, 2015 |title=The trip treatment |department=Annals of Medicine |journal=The New Yorker |volume=90 |issue=47 |pages=36\u201347 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/02/09/trip-treatment |<!--accessdate=2019-09-13-->}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://michaelpollan.com/}}\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-n85-346809}}\n* [http://www.uctv.tv/search-details.aspx?showID=15882 (video) Michael Pollan on the Politics of Food] from [http://www.uctv.tv/ UC Television (UCTV)]\n* {{IMDb name|2293679}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Michael Pollan}}\n* \"[http://www.ted.com/talks/michael_pollan_gives_a_plant_s_eye_view The omnivore's next dilemma]\" at [[TED (conference)|TED Talks]]\n* [http://libwww.freelibrary.org/podcast/media/20080110-michael.mp3 \"In Defense of Food\"] at The [[Free Library of Philadelphia]], January 10, 2008\n* [http://www.grist.org/article/skewed-view-from-the-berkeley-hills/ Skewed View from the Berkeley Hills: Why Michael Pollan and Alice Waters should quit celebrating food-price hikes] by Tom Philpott, ''[[Grist (magazine)|Grist]]'', April 4, 2009.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120202014959/http://news21.jomc.unc.edu/index.php/michael-pollan-interview.html Food and Fossil Fuels] by Melissa Moser, UNC News 21 Project, [http://www.poweringanation.org], June 25, 2009\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090929082851/http://www.counterpunch.org/goodman09252009.html Why are Farmers Afraid of Michael Pollan?] by Jim Goodman, ''[[CounterPunch]]'', September 25, 2009\n* [http://www.democracynow.org/2010/2/8/michael_pollan_on_food_rules_an Michael Pollan on ''\"Food Rules: An Eater\u2019s Manual\"''] \u2013 video report by ''[[Democracy Now!]]''\n\n{{Michael Pollan}}\n{{veganism}}\n{{Orwell Award recipients}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pollan, Michael}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Mansfield College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American botanical writers]]\n[[Category:American food writers]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:American magazine editors]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction environmental writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Jewish American journalists]]\n[[Category:Bennington College alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Journalism teachers]]\n[[Category:Agricultural writers]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Diet food advocates]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:James Beard Foundation Award winners]]\n[[Category:Psychedelic drug advocates]]\n", "name_user": "Mhmnm", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Pollan"}
{"title_page": "Wallerfangen", "text_new": "{{Infobox German location\n|image_photo       = WallerfangenAltesRathaus.jpg\n|image_coa            = Wappen Wallerfangen.svg\n|coordinates       = {{coord|49|18|46|N|6|44|6|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan = Wallerfangen in SLS.svg\n|state        = Saarland\n|district         = Saarlouis\n|elevation              = 182\n|area            = 42.17\n|population         = 9603\n|Stand             = 2006-12-31\n|postal_code               = 66794\u201366798\n|area_code           = 06831, 06837\n|licence               = SLS\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 10 0 44 121\n|Adresse           = Fabrikplatz<br />66798 Wallerfangen\n|website           = [http://www.wallerfangen.de/ www.wallerfangen.de]\n|mayor     = Horst Trenz\n|party            = [[SPD]]\n}}\n\n'''Wallerfangen''' (French: ''Vaudrevange''/''Valdrevange'') is a municipality of [[Saarlouis (district)|Saarlouis district]], [[Saarland]], [[Germany]].  Located west of Saarlouis and along the [[France|French]] border, it is the seat of the villages of Ittersdorf, Ihn, Leidingen, St. Barbara, Kerlingen, Gisingen, Rammelfangen, Oberlimberg, Bedersdorf, and D\u00fcren.\n\n== History ==\nFormerly called Walderfinga, it was established by the [[Duchy of Lorraine]], and belonged to the Duchy until the [[Napoleonic Wars]] in the late 18th century, at which time it came under French control. Up until 1687, Wallerfangen possessed town privileges. In that year, the fortifications and most of the buildings were destroyed and the inhabitants were moved to the newly found town-fortress of [[Saarlouis]].\n\nIn 1815, under the [[Treaty of Paris (1815)|Treaty of Paris]], [[Prussia]] assumed control of the area. For all intents and purposes, it remained in the possession of the German Federation of States until 1919. The [[Treaty of Versailles]] created an independent and autonomous territory of [[Saargebiet]], administered by France and the [[League of Nations]] until 1935. Under the terms of Versailles, the citizens of the ''Saargebiet'' voted to become part of Germany, doing so in spite of [[Adolf Hitler]] having assumed power in 1933.\n\n[[World War II]] brought much despair and bloodshed for Wallerfangen and its citizens. Being the western border of the German Reich, the area became a battleground in 1944/45, and the area was evacuated ''en masse'' twice. After World War II, Wallerfangen belonged to the newly independent, but French-controlled, [[Saarland]].\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Irene Gammel]], author and biographer\n* [[Franz von Papen]], buried there\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cities and towns in Saarlouis (district)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Saarlouis (district)]]\n\n\n{{Saarland-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox German location\n|image_photo       = WallerfangenAltesRathaus.jpg\n|image_coa            = Wappen Wallerfangen.svg\n|coordinates       = {{coord|49|18|46|N|6|44|6|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan = Wallerfangen in SLS.svg\n|state        = Saarland\n|district         = Saarlouis\n|elevation              = 182\n|area            = 42.17\n|population         = 9603\n|Stand             = 2006-12-31\n|postal_code               = 66794\u201366798\n|area_code           = 06831, 06837\n|licence               = SLS\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 10 0 44 121\n|Adresse           = Fabrikplatz<br />66798 Wallerfangen\n|website           = [http://www.wallerfangen.de/ www.wallerfangen.de]\n|mayor     = Horst Trenz\n|party            = [[SPD]]\n}}\n\n'''Wallerfangen''' (French: ''Vaudrevange''/''Valdrevange'') is a municipality of [[Saarlouis (district)|Saarlouis district]], [[Saarland]], [[Germany]].  Located west of Saarlouis and along the [[France|French]] border, it is the seat of the villages of Ittersdorf, Ihn, Leidingen, St. Barbara, Kerlingen, Gisingen, Rammelfangen, Oberlimberg, Bedersdorf, and D\u00fcren.\n\n== History ==\nFormerly called Walderfinga, it was established by the [[Duchy of Lorraine]], and belonged to the Duchy until the [[Napoleonic Wars]] in the late 18th century, at which time it came under French control. Up until 1687, Wallerfangen possessed town privileges. In that year, the fortifications and most of the buildings were destroyed and the inhabitants were moved to the newly found town-fortress of [[Saarlouis]].\n\nIn 1815, under the [[Treaty of Paris (1815)|Treaty of Paris]], [[Prussia]] assumed control of the area. For all intents and purposes, it remained in the possession of the German Federation of States until 1919. The [[Treaty of Versailles]] created an independent and autonomous territory of [[Saargebiet]], administered by France and the [[League of Nations]] until 1935. Under the terms of Versailles, the citizens of the ''Saargebiet'' voted to become part of Germany, doing so in spite of [[Adolf Hitler]] having assumed power in 1933.\n\n[[World War II]] brought much despair and bloodshed for Wallerfangen and its citizens. Being the western border of the German Reich, the area became battleground in 1944/45, and the area was evacuated ''en masse'' twice. After World War II, Wallerfangen belonged to the newly independent, but French-controlled, [[Saarland]].\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Irene Gammel]], author and biographer\n* [[Franz von Papen]], buried there\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cities and towns in Saarlouis (district)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Saarlouis (district)]]\n\n\n{{Saarland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bigturtle", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u201cBattleground\u201d \u2014> \u201ca battleground\u201d", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wallerfangen"}
{"title_page": "WJBT", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=October 2012}}\n{{prose|date=October 2012}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2012}}\n}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name      = WJBT\n| image     = \n| city      = [[Callahan, Florida]]\n| area      = [[Jacksonville, Florida]]\n| branding  = 93.3 The Beat\n| slogan    = Jacksonville's Hip Hop and R&B Flava\n| airdate   = 1975 (at 92.7)\n| frequency = 93.3 [[Megahertz|MHz]] {{HD Radio}}\n| format    = {{ubl|[[Urban Contemporary]] |'''HD2:''' [[Classic hip hop]]|'''HD3:''' [[WZNZ]] [[simulcast]]}}\n| erp       = 100,000 [[watt]]s\n| haat      = {{Convert|302|m|ft|sp=us}}\n| class     = C1\n| facility_id = 51975\n| callsign_meaning = '''W'''e're '''J'''acksonville's '''B'''ea'''T'''\n| former_callsigns = WLKC (1983-1990)<br>WAIA (1990-1995)<br>WPLA (1995-2005)<br>WROO (2005-2008)\n| owner     = [[iHeartMedia, Inc.]]\n| licensee  = Clear Channel Broadcasting Licenses, Inc.\n| sister_stations = [[WQIK-FM]], [[W247CF]], [[WFXJ (AM)|WFXJ]], [[WKSL]], [[W295AZ]], [[WSOL-FM]], [[WWJK]]\n| webcast = [https://www.iheart.com/live/933-the-beat-517/ Listen Live]\n| website   = [https://wjbt.iheart.com/ https://wjbt.iheart.com/]\n}}\n\n'''WJBT''' (or '''93.3 The Beat''') is a commercial [[Urban Contemporary]] [[radio station]] in [[Jacksonville, Florida]] broadcasting on 93.3 [[MHz]].  The station is owned and operated by [[iHeartMedia, Inc.]] and is licensed to [[Callahan, Florida]].  The station's studios are located on Central Parkway in Jacksonville's Southside section, and the transmitter is in the Arlington section.\n\n==History of the 93.3 frequency==\nIn 1995 WAIA switched from [[Adult album alternative|Triple-A]] to [[modern rock]], becoming \"Planet Radio 93.3\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Vox Jox|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=July 29, 1995|volume=107|issue=30|page=114}}</ref>\n\n==Station history==\nWJBT has been in its current format since 1992 (when it was at 92.7), playing [[Hip hop music|Hip Hop]] and [[R&B]] music.  It is home to the nationally syndicated [[Doug Banks|Doug Banks Morning Show]] (but has been replaced with [[Steve Harvey]] after its move to 93.3).  Its only other competitor is its own sister station, [[Urban AC]] [[WSOL-FM]]. WJBT was the second Urban radio station to adopt \"The Beat\" branding after [[Los Angeles]]' [[KKLQ (FM)|KKBT]].\n\nWhen it was at 92.7, it served the Jacksonville area, but it did not have enough power to serve the northernmost and westernmost portions of the metro because its frequency was licensed to [[Green Cove Springs, Florida]].  However, it had no effect on the [[Arbitron]] ratings as it is still among the Top 5 (sometimes 10) most listened to stations in the city.\n\nOn November 2, 2007, Clear Channel spun off the 92.7 frequency to a private company (which moved the signal to the Palm Coast area as [[WBHQ]])<ref>[http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/110207/bus_214248206.shtml From The Florida Times-Union (November 2, 2007)]</ref> and on the evening of December 25 of that same year, moved the station and its format to the more powerful 93.3 signal (formerly the home of Country outlet WROO).<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/netgnomes/whats-coming-to-933-jacksonville/ From Radioinsight (December 6, 2007)]</ref> The reason for this was to comply with FCC ownership rules, since WJBT was in a waiver status in which Clear Channel was allowed to own six FMs and one AM in the market. But because of Clear Channel Communications being sold to a private investment group, WJBT's current frequency had to be divested. After Christmas Day 2007, 92.7 and 93.3 were simulcasting. However, on January 11, 2008, a new urban gospel station debuted on the 92.7 frequency named \"Hallelujah FM\", which is a moniker currently used for many Clear Channel-owned gospel stations nationwide. Also, the call letters were switched, with 92.7 becoming WROO and 93.3 becoming WJBT.<ref>[http://www.radioinsight.com]</ref>\n\nWith the move to a more powerful signal, WJBT also received an upgrade in power as well, going from 50&nbsp;kW to 100&nbsp;kW, thus covering most of Jacksonville and Northeastern Florida.\n\n==On-air personalities==\n* [[The Breakfast Club (radio show)|The Breakfast Club]]\n* Uptown Angela\n* T-Roy\n* Easy E\n* DJ Q45 \n* DJ Ian\n* Big Sue\n* Lil Tree Hugger\n\n==Mixers==\n* DJ Q45\n* DJ Dr. Doom\n\n==Station management==\n* '''Program Director''' G-Wiz\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://wjbt.iheart.com/ 93.3 The Beat]\n*{{FM station data|WJBT}}\n\n{{Jacksonville Radio}}\n{{Urban Radio Stations in Florida}}\n{{IHeartMedia}}\n\n{{coord|30.2811|N|81.5701|W|type:landmark_region:US_source:FCC|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Urban contemporary radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Jacksonville, Florida|JBT]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1983]]\n[[Category:IHeartMedia radio stations]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=October 2012}}\n{{prose|date=October 2012}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2012}}\n}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name      = WJBT\n| image     = \n| city      = [[Callahan, Florida]]\n| area      = [[Jacksonville, Florida]]\n| branding  = 93.3 The Beat\n| slogan    = Jacksonville's Hip Hop and R&B Flava\n| airdate   = 1975 (at 92.7)\n| frequency = 93.3 [[Megahertz|MHz]] {{HD Radio}}\n| format    = {{ubl|[[Urban Contemporary]] |'''HD2:''' [[Classic hip hop]]|'''HD3:''' [[WZNZ]] [[simulcast]]}}\n| erp       = 100,000 [[watt]]s\n| haat      = {{Convert|302|m|ft|sp=us}}\n| class     = C1\n| facility_id = 51975\n| callsign_meaning = '''W'''e're '''J'''acksonville's '''B'''ea'''T'''\n| former_callsigns = WLKC (1983-1990)<br>WAIA (1990-1995)<br>WPLA (1995-2005)<br>WROO (2005-2008)\n| owner     = [[iHeartMedia, Inc.]]\n| licensee  = Clear Channel Broadcasting Licenses, Inc.\n| sister_stations = [[WQIK-FM]], [[W247CF]], [[WFXJ (AM)|WFXJ]], [[WKSL]], [[W295AZ]], [[WSOL-FM]], [[WWJK]]\n| webcast = [https://www.iheart.com/live/933-the-beat-517/ Listen Live]\n| website   = [https://wjbt.iheart.com/ https://wjbt.iheart.com/]\n}}\n\n'''WJBT''' (or '''93.3 The Beat''') is a commercial [[Urban Contemporary]] [[radio station]] in [[Jacksonville, Florida]] broadcasting on 93.3 [[MHz]].  The station is owned and operated by [[iHeartMedia, Inc.]] and is licensed to [[Callahan, Florida]].  The station's studios are located on Central Parkway in Jacksonville's Southside section, and the transmitter is in the Arlington section.\n\n==History of the 93.3 frequency==\nIn 1995 WAIA switched from [[Adult album alternative|Triple-A]] to [[modern rock]], becoming \"Planet Radio 93.3\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Vox Jox|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=July 29, 1995|volume=107|issue=30|page=114}}</ref>\n\n==Station history==\nWJBT has been in its current format since 1992 (when it was at 92.7), playing [[Hip hop music|Hip Hop]] and [[R&B]] music.  It is home to the nationally syndicated [[Doug Banks|Doug Banks Morning Show]] (but has been replaced with [[Steve Harvey]] after its move to 93.3).  It's only other competitor is its own sister station, [[Urban AC]] [[WSOL-FM]]. WJBT was the second Urban radio station to adopt \"The Beat\" branding after [[Los Angeles]]' [[KKLQ (FM)|KKBT]].\n\nWhen it was at 92.7, it served the Jacksonville area, but it did not have enough power to serve the northernmost and westernmost portions of the metro because its frequency was licensed to [[Green Cove Springs, Florida]].  However, it had no effect on the [[Arbitron]] ratings as it is still among the Top 5 (sometimes 10) most listened to stations in the city.\n\nOn November 2, 2007, Clear Channel spun off the 92.7 frequency to a private company (which moved the signal to the Palm Coast area as [[WBHQ]])<ref>[http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/110207/bus_214248206.shtml From The Florida Times-Union (November 2, 2007)]</ref> and on the evening of December 25 of that same year, moved the station and its format to the more powerful 93.3 signal (formerly the home of Country outlet WROO).<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/netgnomes/whats-coming-to-933-jacksonville/ From Radioinsight (December 6, 2007)]</ref> The reason for this was to comply with FCC ownership rules, since WJBT was in a waiver status in which Clear Channel was allowed to own six FMs and one AM in the market. But because of Clear Channel Communications being sold to a private investment group, WJBT's current frequency had to be divested. After Christmas Day 2007, 92.7 and 93.3 were simulcasting. However, on January 11, 2008, a new urban gospel station debuted on the 92.7 frequency named \"Hallelujah FM\", which is a moniker currently used for many Clear Channel-owned gospel stations nationwide. Also, the call letters were switched, with 92.7 becoming WROO and 93.3 becoming WJBT.<ref>[http://www.radioinsight.com]</ref>\n\nWith the move to a more powerful signal, WJBT also received an upgrade in power as well, going from 50&nbsp;kW to 100&nbsp;kW, thus covering most of Jacksonville and Northeastern Florida.\n\n==On-air personalities==\n* [[The Breakfast Club (radio show)|The Breakfast Club]]\n* Uptown Angela\n* T-Roy\n* Easy E\n* DJ Q45 \n* DJ Ian\n* Big Sue\n* Lil Tree Hugger\n\n==Mixers==\n* DJ Q45\n* DJ Dr. Doom\n\n==Station management==\n* '''Program Director''' G-Wiz\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://wjbt.iheart.com/ 93.3 The Beat]\n*{{FM station data|WJBT}}\n\n{{Jacksonville Radio}}\n{{Urban Radio Stations in Florida}}\n{{IHeartMedia}}\n\n{{coord|30.2811|N|81.5701|W|type:landmark_region:US_source:FCC|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Urban contemporary radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Jacksonville, Florida|JBT]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1983]]\n[[Category:IHeartMedia radio stations]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStation history:spelling - it's->its", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WJBT"}
{"title_page": "Kilometres per hour", "text_new": "{{about||the South African airport with IATA code KMH |Johan Pienaar Airport|the Canadian TV Series| km/h (TV series)}}\n{{Infobox unit\n| name         = Kilometres per hour\n| image        = Metric speedometer from a 1992 Euro-spec Passat B3.jpg\n| caption      = A car [[speedometer]] that indicates measured speed in kilometres per hour.\n| standard     = derived\n| quantity     = [[speed]]\n| symbol       = km/h\n| units1       = [[Miles per hour|mph]]\n| inunits1     = 0.621371\n| units2       = [[Metre per second|m/s]]\n| inunits2     = 0.277778\n| units3       = [[Knot (unit)|kn]]\n| inunits3     = 0.539957\n| units4       = [[Foot per second|ft/s]]\n| inunits4     = 0.911344\n}}\nThe '''kilometre per hour''' ([[SI]] symbol: '''km/h'''; abbreviations: '''kph''', '''kmph''', '''km/hr''') is a [[Units of measurement|unit]] of [[speed]], expressing the number of [[kilometre]]s travelled in one [[hour]].\n\nInternationally, km/h is the most commonly used unit of speed on [[traffic sign]]s and road vehicle [[speedometer]]s.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n==History==\nAlthough the metre was formally defined in 1799, the term \"kilometres per hour\" did not come into immediate use \u2013 the myriametre ({{nowrap|10,000 metres}}) and myriametre per hour were preferred to kilometres and kilometres per hour. In 1802 the term \"''myriam\u00e8tres par heure''\" appeared in French literature<ref>{{cite book |title=Physique d'Emile: ou, Principes de la science de la nature |volume=1 |first=Emmanuel |last=Develey |year=1802 |location=Paris |url=https://books.google.com/?id=AFsIAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA90&lpg=PA90&dq=vitesse+myriametre#v=onepage&q=myriam%C3%A8tres&f=false}}</ref> and many French maps printed in the first half of the nineteenth century had scales in [[league (unit)|league]]s and [[myriametre]]s, but not in kilometres.{{cn|date=June 2019}} The Dutch on the other hand adopted the kilometre in 1817 but gave it the local name of the ''mijl'' ([[Mile#Other historical miles|Dutch mile]]).<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/allereerstegron00ramagoog |title=Allereerste Gronden der Cijferkunst |first=Jacob |last=de Gelder |location='s-Gravenhage and Amsterdam |language=Dutch |year=1824\n|pages=[https://archive.org/details/allereerstegron00ramagoog/page/n364 155]\u2013156 |publisher=de Gebroeders van Cleef |trans-title=Introduction to Numeracy |accessdate=2 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Notation history==\nThe SI representations, classified as symbols, are \"km/h\", \"{{nowrap|km h<sup>\u22121</sup>}}\" and \"{{nowrap|km\u00b7h<sup>\u22121</sup>}}\". Several other representations of \"kilometres per hour\" have been used since the term was introduced and many are still in use today; for example, dictionaries list \"km/h\", \"kmph\" and \"km/hr\" as English abbreviations.\n\n===Abbreviations===\nAbbreviations for \"kilometres per hour\" did not appear in the English language until the late nineteenth century.\n\nThe [[kilometre]], a unit of [[length]], first appeared in English in 1810,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/103403 |title=The Oxford English Dictionary |accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><!--<ref name=\"OED\">{{cite book |title=The Compact Edition of the Oxford English Dictionary |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1971 |pages=695}}</ref>--> and the compound unit of [[speed]] \"kilometers per hour\" was in use in the US by 1866.<ref>{{cite book |title=Journal of the Franklin Institute of the State of Pennsylvania for the Promotion of the Mechanic Arts |publisher=Franklin Institute |last=Frazer |first=John F. |date=November 1866 |location=Philadelphia |page=314 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kKIqAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA314&lpg=PA314&dq=%22kilometers+per+hour%22&source=bl&ots=Osx40Oy1Na&sig=RQHVQQeN1oWkgnlX5rgjd6kowpM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=pET-T47dJ6782gWCxPnKDw&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22kilometers%20per%20hour%22&f=false |volume=LII |number=5}}</ref> \"Kilometres per hour\" did not begin to be abbreviated in print until many years later, with several different abbreviations existing near-contemporaneously.\n\n{|\n|-\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:200pt;\"|\n* 1889: \"k. p. h.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=American meteorological journal: A monthly review of meteorology, medical climatology and geography |publisher=Meteorological Journal Company |last1=Harrington |first1=Mark W. |last2=Rotch |first2=A. Lawrence |last3=Herdman |first3=W. J. |date=May 1889 |page=226 |volume=6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0MEWAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA226&lpg=PA226&dq=%22km/h%22+%22kilometers+per+hour%22&source=bl&ots=9dJuM0-Tv3&sig=6Obk_ZTGNarHWdyvAFRn-2eNgTs&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bkf-T9CxD8aI2gWA2fjHDw&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22km%2Fh%22%20%22kilometers%20per%20hour%22&f=false}}</ref>\n* 1895: \"km:h\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I4hNAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA117&lpg=PA117&dq=%22km/h%22+%22kilometers+per+hour%22&source=bl&ots=WOqqVpscAB&sig=kue4ZLNbowkAqYytFDDV3fsx6wg&hl=en&sa=X&ei=00n-T7zXH6WO2QXKy4jqDw&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22km%2Fh%22%20%22kilometers%20per%20hour%22&f=false |title=Power consumed on electric railways |journal=The Street Railway Journal |date=February 1895 |volume=11 |issue=2 |pages=116\u2013117}}</ref>\n* 1898: \"km/h\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Bulletin \u2013 United States Geological Survey, Volumes 151\u2013152 |publisher=USGS |year=1898 |pages=ix |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QgwlAQAAIAAJ&q=%22km/h%22+kilometer&dq=%22km/h%22+kilometer&source=bl&ots=SQVFIN5ctK&sig=Hptqzifz899z3Q2rTwQC6fhX2hE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jFD-T7i3D8y02AXjy5XMBA&ved=0CEcQ6AEwAg}}</ref>\n* 1899: \"km./hr.\" <ref>{{cite journal |title=The Stability of the Motion of a Bicycle |last=Whipple |first=F. J. W. |journal=The Quarterly Journal of Pure and Applied Mathematics |year=1899 |volume=30 |page=342}}</ref>\n* 1900: \"kms./hr.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=The Theory of the Trace: Being a Discussion of the Principles of Location |last=Launhardt |first=Wilhelm |publisher=Lawrence Asylum Press |location=Madras |year=1900 |url=https://archive.org/details/theorytracebein00bewlgoog}}</ref>\n* 1902: \"k.m.p.h.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DB3nAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA207 |journal=The Railway Engineer |volume=23 |editor1-last=Saunders |editor1-first=Lawrence |editor2-last=Blundstone |editor2-first=S. R. |page=207 |date=July 1902 |title=The Electric Problem of Railways |last=Swinburne |first=J}}</ref>\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:200pt;\"|\n* 1903: \"KMph.\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i0s1AQAAMAAJ |title=Observations Made at the Royal Magnetical and Meteorological Observatory at Batavia |last=Figee |first=S. |publisher=Government of Netherlands East India |year=1903 |volume=24 |page=196}}</ref>\n* 1910: \"km ph\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/electrictrains00hobagoog |title=Electric Trains |last=Hobart |first=H. M. |publisher=D. Van Nostrand Company |location=New York |year=1910 |page=xix}}</ref>\n* 1911: \"K.P.H.\"<ref>{{cite journal |title=Foreign Notes on Aviation |last=Ball |first=Jack |journal=Town & Country |date=August 1911 |page=26 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1xhUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=%22kph%22+kilometer&source=bl&ots=qcyTcMQkdk&sig=HK14YIxFmt8UBcobLENErN0glHE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HFn-T_P8KMqe2wX1gv3lBA&sqi=2&ved=0CF4Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=%22kph%22%20kilometer&f=false}}</ref>\n* 1914: \"km. hr.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x9pQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1141&lpg=PA1141&dq=%22km/hr%22&source=bl&ots=4eohj9q92V&sig=phERDBIQUn5Mtf2UFGR4INs80Pk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Cbr_T4S_OofI2gW6tMWxBA&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22km%2Fhr%22&f=false |title=A Review of Some European Electric Locomotive Designs |last=Dodd |first=S. T. |journal=General Electric Review |date=January 1914 |volume=17 |issue=1 |page=1141}}</ref>\n* 1915: \"km/hour\"<ref name=\"Automobile1915\">{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oxVaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA710&lpg=PA710&dq=kph+%22kilometers+per+hour%22&source=bl&ots=oSV9840is5&sig=232C8QxgvKlEgItPZ3_fkfLywHQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5pz_T-7WD8y8qAGkhPSdBw&ved=0CEwQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=kph%20%22kilometers%20per%20hour%22&f=false |title=Data on Mixed Motor Fuels of Interest for American Export Trade |journal=The Automobile |date=October 1915 |volume=33 |issue=15 |page=709}}</ref>\n* 1915: \"km.-hr.\"<ref name=\"Automobile1915\" />\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:200pt;\"|\n* 1916: \"km. per hour\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O-MfAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA560&lpg=PA560&dq=kph+%22kilometers+per+hour%22&source=bl&ots=K_KMl6h4LJ&sig=3OPTvJsQMzVNZRNHfSL0AahG6KE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5pz_T-7WD8y8qAGkhPSdBw&ved=0CFcQ6AEwBg#v=snippet&q=%22km.%20per%20hour%22&f=false |title=Tractive resistance tests with an electric motor truck |journal=Engineering and Contracting |date=December 1916 |volume=46 |issue=25 |page=560}}</ref>\n* 1921: \"kms/hr.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Meteorological Report for the Year [1916?] |publisher=Ministry of Public Works, Egypt |page=xvii |url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=9iOmUv2oNcqiyAHCoIHYBA |year=1921 |first=Ma\u1e63la\u1e25at al-Ar\u1e63\u0101d |last=al-Jaww\u012byah}}</ref>\n* 1922: \"Kmph\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hRU6AQAAMAAJ |journal=Railway Electrical Engineer |volume=13 |page=392 |title=French Railway Begins Electrification Program |last1=Candee |first1=A. H. |last2=Lynde |first2=L. E. |publisher=Simmons Boardman |year=1922}}</ref>\n* 1927: \"kmph.\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y5lTAAAAMAAJ |title=Pressure Airships |last=Blakemore |first=Thos. L. |year=1927 |page=230 |publisher=Ronald Press}}</ref>\n* 1933: \"KPH\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Aircraft Year Book |publisher=Aerospace Industries Association of America, Manufacturers Aircraft Association, Aeronautical Chamber of Commerce of America |year=1933 |pages=391\u2013393 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=39cEAAAAMAAJ&q=%22kph%22+kilometer&dq=%22kph%22+kilometer&source=bl&ots=PyQ0_6UZCq&sig=8O5rmhK8Yjut3p0RsSoU3WItHPo&hl=en&sa=X&ei=tln-T9WMNsi-2gWfk6zcBA&ved=0CDwQ6AEwAQ |volume=15}}</ref>\n* 1939: \"kmph\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CWYjAQAAMAAJ |title=Bulletin |publisher=Central Electric Railfans' Association |year=1939 |page=cxii}}</ref>\n|}\n<!-- to be added\n* ????: \"km/hr\"\n* ????: \"KMHR\"\n* 1940: \"KMPH\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uA5LAAAAMAAJ |title=Electric Transportation |last=Thompson |first=Francis R. |year=1940 |page=165 }}</ref>\n-->\n\nWith no central authority to dictate the rules for abbreviations, various publishing houses have their own rules that dictate whether to use upper-case letters, lower-case letters, periods and so on, reflecting both changes in fashion and the image of the publishing house concerned.<ref>{{cite book |title=Eats Shoots and Leaves |first=Lynne |last=Truss |publisher=Profile Books |year=2003 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/eatsshootsleav00trus/page/188 188\u2013189] |isbn=1 86197 6127 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/eatsshootsleav00trus/page/188 }}</ref> For example, news organisations such as [[Reuters]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://handbook.reuters.com/extensions/docs/pdf/handbookofjournalism.pdf |page=278 |title=Reuters Handbook of Journalism |date=April 2008 |publisher=Reuters |access-date=2012-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518015851/http://handbook.reuters.com/extensions/docs/pdf/handbookofjournalism.pdf |archive-date=2016-05-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[The Economist]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.economist.com/style-guide/abbreviations |accessdate=9 December 2013 |title=Style Guide |newspaper=The Economist |date=27 September 2011}}</ref> \nrequire \"kph\".\n\nAustralian unofficial usage, km/h is more commonly pronounced \"Kays\". In military usage \"Klicks\" is heard, though written as km/h.<ref>{{cite web |date=June 2012 |url=http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/241046 |title=klick |work=[[Oxford English Dictionary]] |accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Unit symbols===\nIn 1879, four years after the signing of the [[Metre Convention|Treaty of the Metre]], the [[CIPM]] proposed a range of symbols for the various metric units then under the auspices of the [[CGPM]]. Among these were the use of the symbol \"km\" for \"kilometre\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=jlM907kFhcgC&pg=PA127&lpg=PA127&dq=cipm+1879+metre#v=onepage&q=cipm%201879%20metre&f=false |title=From Artefacts to Atoms: The BIPM and the Search for Ultimate Measurement Standards |first=Terry |last=Quinn |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-19-530786-3 |page=132 |location=Oxford |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, as part of its preparatory work for the [[SI]], the [[CGPM]] adopted symbols for many units of measure that did not have universally agreed symbols, one of which was the symbol \"h\" for \"hours\". At the same time the CGPM formalised the rules for combining units \u2013 quotients could be written in one of three formats resulting in {{nowrap|\"km/h\"}}, {{nowrap|\"km h<sup>\u22121</sup>\"}} and {{nowrap|\"km\u00b7h<sup>\u22121</sup>\"}} being valid representations of \"kilometres per hour\".<ref name=SI>{{SIbrochure8th|page=124}}</ref> The SI standards, which were [[MKS system of units|MKS-based]] rather than [[CGS|CGS-based]] were published in 1960 and have since then have been adopted by many authorities around the globe including academic publishers and legal authorities.\n\nThe SI explicitly states that unit symbols are not abbreviations and are to be written using a very specific set of rules.<ref name=SI/> M. Danloux-Dumesnils<ref>{{cite book |title=The Metric System: A Critical Study of its Principles and Practice |publisher=The Athlone Press of the University of London |author=Danloux-Dumesnils |year=1969 |page=32}}</ref> provides the following justification for this distinction:\n{{quote|text=It has already been stated that, according to Maxwell, when we write down the result of a measurement, the numerical value multiplies the unit. Hence the name of the unit can be replaced by a kind of algebraic symbol, which is shorter and easier to use in formulae. This symbol is not merely an abbreviation but a symbol which, like chemical symbols, must be used in a precise and prescribed manner.}}\n\nSI, and hence the use of {{nowrap|\"km/h\"}} (or {{nowrap|\"km h<sup>\u22121</sup>\"}} or {{nowrap|\"km\u00b7h<sup>\u22121</sup>\"}}) has now been adopted around the world in many areas related to health and safety<ref>{{cite web |url=http://intralibrary.rlo-cetl.ac.uk:8080/intralibrary/open_virtual_file_path/i1405n24399t/2.html |title=RLO: SI Units |accessdate=21 July 2012 |publisher=School of Nursing and Academic Division of Midwifery; University of Nottingham |date=1 December 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121223075728/http://intralibrary.rlo-cetl.ac.uk:8080/intralibrary/open_virtual_file_path/i1405n24399t/2.html |archivedate=23 December 2012 }}</ref> and in [[metrology]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Information and Harmonization |url=http://www.metrologyinfo.org/oiml-2.html |publisher=[[International Bureau of Weights and Measures]] and [[International Organization of Legal Metrology]] |accessdate=20 July 2012}}</ref> in addition to the SI unit [[metres per second]] ({{nowrap|\"m/s\"}}, {{nowrap|\"m s<sup>\u22121</sup>\"}} or {{nowrap|\"m\u00b7s<sup>\u22121</sup>\"}}). SI is also the preferred system of measure in academia and in education.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.tru.ca/library/pdf/tru-ol_editorial_style.pdf |title=OLA Editorial Style Guide |publisher=[[Open Learning Agency]] (OLA), Government of British Columbia |year=2000 |location=Burnaby, British Columbia |accessdate=26 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Alternative abbreviations in official use===\n\n*'''km/j''' or '''km/jam''' (Indonesia and Malaysia)\n*'''km/t''' or '''km/tim''' (Norway and Sweden; also use '''km/h''')\n*'''kmph''' (Sri Lanka and India)\n*'''\u0e01\u0e21./\u0e0a\u0e21.''' (Thailand; also uses '''km/hr''')\n*'''\u0643\u0645/\u0633''' or '''\u0643\u0645/\u0633\u0627\u0639\u0629''' ([[Arabic-speaking countries]], also use '''km/h''')\n\n== Regulatory use ==\nDuring the early years of the motor car, each country developed its own system of road signs. In 1968 the [[Vienna Convention on Road Signs and Signals]] was drawn up under the auspices of the [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]] to harmonise road signs across the world. Many countries have since signed the convention and adopted its proposals. Speed limits signs that are either directly authorised by the convention or have been influenced by the convention are shown below:\n\n<gallery perrow=\"6\" widths=\"120px\">\nFile:Hungary road sign C-033-100.svg|100&nbsp;km/h sign following the most common implementation of the Vienna Convention style (Hungary)\nFile:Sweden road sign C31-3.svg|Swedish 30&nbsp;km/h speed limit \u2013 the yellow background provides a contrast in case snow covers the background against which one perceives the road sign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grsproadsafety.org/our-knowledge/conspicuity-and-signs|title=Conspicuity and Signs: Road signing|publisher=[[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement#The International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies|International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies]]|year=2012|accessdate=19 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102080907/http://www.grsproadsafety.org/our-knowledge/conspicuity-and-signs|archive-date=2012-11-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nFile:Ireland road sign RUS 043.svg|Since the text \"km/h\" on this Irish speed limit sign is a symbol, not an abbreviation, it represents both \"kilometres per hour\" (English) and \"cilim\u00e9adar san uair\"([[Irish language|Irish]])<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.transport.ie/upload/general/12971-TSM_CHAPTER_1-1.PDF|title=Department of Transport / ''An Roinn Iompair''|date=November 2010|page=1|accessdate=16 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428064628/http://www.transport.ie/upload/general/12971-TSM_CHAPTER_1-1.PDF|archivedate=28 April 2012}} </ref>\nFile:UAE Speed Limit - 60 kmh.svg|60&nbsp;km/h speed limit in [[Arabic numerals]] (below) and Arabic script (above) ([[United Arab Emirates|UAE]])\nFile:Vesiliikennemerkki 11.svg|Waterways speed limit of 9&nbsp;km/h ([[Finland]])\nImage:Samoa - Speed Limit.svg|[[Samoa]] uses both [[miles per hour]] and kilometres per hour\nFile:Mexico road sign SR-09.svg|50&nbsp;km/h sign in [[Speed limits in Mexico|Mexico]]\n</gallery>\n\nIn 1972 the EU published a directive<ref>{{cite EU directive |serial=71/354/EEC |year=1971 |date=18 October 1971 |description=on the approximation of laws of Member States relating to units of measurement |eurlextag=DD:I:1971_III:31971L0354:EN:PDF}}</ref> (overhauled in 1979<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=CELEX:31980L0181:EN:NOT |author=The Council of the European Communities |title=Council Directive 80/181/EEC of 20 December 1979 on the approximation of the laws of the Member States relating to Unit of measurement and on the repeal of Directive 71/354/EEC |accessdate=7 February 2009}}</ref> to take British and Irish interests into account) that required member states to abandon CGS-based units in favour of SI. The use of SI implicitly required that member states use \"km/h\" as the shorthand for \"kilometres per hour\" on official<ref group=Note>Until 2010, the directive covered \"economic, public health, public safety or administrative purposes\"; since then [http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=CELEX:32009L0003:EN:NOT it covers all aspects] of the EU [[internal market]]</ref> documents.\n\nAnother EU directive, published in 1975, regulates the layout of speedometers within the European Union, and requires the text \"km/h\" in all languages,<ref>{{cite EU directive |serial=75/443/EEC |year=1975 |date=26 June 1975 |description=on the approximation of the laws of the Member States relating to the reverse and speedometer equipment of motor vehicles |eurlextag=CONSLEG:1975L0443:19970725:en:PDF}}</ref> even where that is not the natural abbreviation for the local version of \"kilometres per hour\". Examples include: \n*Dutch: \"''kilometer per uur''\" (\"hour\" is spelt \"''uur''\" \u2013 does not start with \"h\"),\n*Portuguese: \"''quil\u00f3metro por hora''\" (\"kilometre\" is spelt \"''quil\u00f3metro''\" \u2013 does not start with \"k\")\n*Greek: \"''\u03c7\u03b9\u03bb\u03b9\u03cc\u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b1\u03bd\u03ac \u03ce\u03c1\u03b1''\" (a different script).\n\nIn 1988 the United States [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] promulgated a rule stating that \"MPH and/or km/h\" were to be used in speedometer displays. On May 15, 2000 this was clarified to read \"MPH, or MPH and km/h\".<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.federalregister.gov/articles/2000/05/15/00-11493/federal-motor-vehicle-safety-standards-fmvss-101-technical-correction-speedometer-display |title=Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards; FMVSS 101--Technical Correction--Speedometer Display |author=National Highway Traffic Safety Administration |journal=Federal Register |date=May 2000 |volume=64 |issue=94 |pages=30915\u201330918}}</ref> However, the Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard number 101 (\"Controls and Displays\") allows \"any combination of upper- and lowercase letters\" to represent the units.<ref>{{cite book |title=Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard (101: Controls and Displays) |author=National Highway Traffic Safety Administration |page=237 |url=https://docs.google.com/gview?url=http://lemon.onecle.com/wp-content/uploads/fmvss/49cfr571.101.pdf&chrome=true}}</ref>\n\n==Conversions==\n* {{val|3.6|u=km/h}} \u2261 {{val|1|u=m/s}}, the [[SI unit]] of speed, [[metre per second]]\n* {{val|1|u=km/h}} \u2248 {{val|0.27778|u=m/s}}\n* {{val|1|u=km/h}} \u2248 {{val|0.62137|ul=mph}} \u2248 {{val|0.91134|ul=ft/s}}\n* {{val|1|ul=knot}} \u2261 {{val|1.852|u=km/h}} (exactly)\n* {{val|1|u=mph}} \u2261 {{val|1.609344|u=km/h}}\n\n{{Speed conversions}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Knot (unit)|Knot]]\n* [[Metre per second]]\n* [[Miles per hour]]\n* [[Orders of magnitude (speed)]]\n* [[Speed limits in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Speed limits in Canada#Signage|Speed limits in Canada]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist| group = Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{North America topic|Speed limits in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kilometres Per Hour}}\n[[Category:Units of velocity]]\n[[Category:Non-SI metric units]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the South African airport with IATA code KMH |Johan Pienaar Airport|the Canadian TV Series| km/h (TV series)}}\n{{Infobox unit\n| name         = Kilometres per hour\n| image        = Metric speedometer from a 1992 Euro-spec Passat B3.jpg\n| caption      = A car [[speedometer]] that indicates measured speed in kilometres per hour.\n| standard     = derived\n| quantity     = [[speed]]\n| symbol       = km/h\n| units1       = [[Miles per hour|mph]]\n| inunits1     = 0.621371\n| units2       = [[Metre per second|m/s]]\n| inunits2     = 0.277778\n| units3       = [[Knot (unit)|kn]]\n| inunits3     = 0.539957\n| units4       = [[Foot per second|ft/s]]\n| inunits4     = 0.911344\n}}\nThe '''kilometre per hour''' ([[SI]] symbol: '''km/h'''; abbreviations: '''kph''', '''kmph''', '''km/hr''') is a [[Units of measurement|unit]] of [[speed]], expressing the number of [[kilometre]]s travelled in one [[hour]].\n\nInternationally, km/h is the most commonly used unit of speed on [[traffic sign]]s and road vehicle [[speedometer]]s.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n==History==\nAlthough the metre was formally defined in 1799, the term \"kilometres per hour\" did not come into immediate use \u2013 the myriametre ({{nowrap|10,000 metres}}) and myriametre per hour were preferred to kilometres and kilometres per hour. In 1802 the term \"''myriam\u00e8tres par heure''\" appeared in French literature<ref>{{cite book |title=Physique d'Emile: ou, Principes de la science de la nature |volume=1 |first=Emmanuel |last=Develey |year=1802 |location=Paris |url=https://books.google.com/?id=AFsIAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA90&lpg=PA90&dq=vitesse+myriametre#v=onepage&q=myriam%C3%A8tres&f=false}}</ref> and many French maps printed in the first half of the nineteenth century had scales in [[league (unit)|league]]s and [[myriametre]]s, but not in kilometres.{{cn|date=June 2019}} The Dutch on the other hand adopted the kilometre in 1817 but gave it the local name of the ''mijl'' ([[Mile#Other historical miles|Dutch mile]]).<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/allereerstegron00ramagoog |title=Allereerste Gronden der Cijferkunst |first=Jacob |last=de Gelder |location='s-Gravenhage and Amsterdam |language=Dutch |year=1824\n|pages=[https://archive.org/details/allereerstegron00ramagoog/page/n364 155]\u2013156 |publisher=de Gebroeders van Cleef |trans-title=Introduction to Numeracy |accessdate=2 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Notation history==\nThe SI representations, classified as symbols, are \"km/h\", \"{{nowrap|km h<sup>\u22121</sup>}}\" and \"{{nowrap|km\u00b7h<sup>\u22121</sup>}}\". Several other representations of \"kilometres per hour\" have been used since the term was introduced and many are still in use today; for example, dictionaries list \"km/h\", \"kmph\" and \"km/hr\" as English abbreviations.\n\n===Abbreviations===\nAbbreviations for \"kilometres per hour\" did not appear in the English language until the late nineteenth century.\n\nThe [[kilometre]], a unit of [[length]], first appeared in English in 1810,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/103403 |title=The Oxford English Dictionary |accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><!--<ref name=\"OED\">{{cite book |title=The Compact Edition of the Oxford English Dictionary |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1971 |pages=695}}</ref>--> and the compound unit of [[speed]] \"kilometers per hour\" was in use in the US by 1866.<ref>{{cite book |title=Journal of the Franklin Institute of the State of Pennsylvania for the Promotion of the Mechanic Arts |publisher=Franklin Institute |last=Frazer |first=John F. |date=November 1866 |location=Philadelphia |page=314 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kKIqAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA314&lpg=PA314&dq=%22kilometers+per+hour%22&source=bl&ots=Osx40Oy1Na&sig=RQHVQQeN1oWkgnlX5rgjd6kowpM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=pET-T47dJ6782gWCxPnKDw&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22kilometers%20per%20hour%22&f=false |volume=LII |number=5}}</ref> \"Kilometres per hour\" did not begin to be abbreviated in print until many years later, with several different abbreviations existing near-contemporaneously.\n\n{|\n|-\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:200pt;\"|\n* 1889: \"k. p. h.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=American meteorological journal: A monthly review of meteorology, medical climatology and geography |publisher=Meteorological Journal Company |last1=Harrington |first1=Mark W. |last2=Rotch |first2=A. Lawrence |last3=Herdman |first3=W. J. |date=May 1889 |page=226 |volume=6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0MEWAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA226&lpg=PA226&dq=%22km/h%22+%22kilometers+per+hour%22&source=bl&ots=9dJuM0-Tv3&sig=6Obk_ZTGNarHWdyvAFRn-2eNgTs&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bkf-T9CxD8aI2gWA2fjHDw&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22km%2Fh%22%20%22kilometers%20per%20hour%22&f=false}}</ref>\n* 1895: \"km:h\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I4hNAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA117&lpg=PA117&dq=%22km/h%22+%22kilometers+per+hour%22&source=bl&ots=WOqqVpscAB&sig=kue4ZLNbowkAqYytFDDV3fsx6wg&hl=en&sa=X&ei=00n-T7zXH6WO2QXKy4jqDw&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22km%2Fh%22%20%22kilometers%20per%20hour%22&f=false |title=Power consumed on electric railways |journal=The Street Railway Journal |date=February 1895 |volume=11 |issue=2 |pages=116\u2013117}}</ref>\n* 1898: \"km/h\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Bulletin \u2013 United States Geological Survey, Volumes 151\u2013152 |publisher=USGS |year=1898 |pages=ix |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QgwlAQAAIAAJ&q=%22km/h%22+kilometer&dq=%22km/h%22+kilometer&source=bl&ots=SQVFIN5ctK&sig=Hptqzifz899z3Q2rTwQC6fhX2hE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jFD-T7i3D8y02AXjy5XMBA&ved=0CEcQ6AEwAg}}</ref>\n* 1899: \"km./hr.\" <ref>{{cite journal |title=The Stability of the Motion of a Bicycle |last=Whipple |first=F. J. W. |journal=The Quarterly Journal of Pure and Applied Mathematics |year=1899 |volume=30 |page=342}}</ref>\n* 1900: \"kms./hr.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=The Theory of the Trace: Being a Discussion of the Principles of Location |last=Launhardt |first=Wilhelm |publisher=Lawrence Asylum Press |location=Madras |year=1900 |url=https://archive.org/details/theorytracebein00bewlgoog}}</ref>\n* 1902: \"k.m.p.h.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DB3nAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA207 |journal=The Railway Engineer |volume=23 |editor1-last=Saunders |editor1-first=Lawrence |editor2-last=Blundstone |editor2-first=S. R. |page=207 |date=July 1902 |title=The Electric Problem of Railways |last=Swinburne |first=J}}</ref>\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:200pt;\"|\n* 1903: \"KMph.\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i0s1AQAAMAAJ |title=Observations Made at the Royal Magnetical and Meteorological Observatory at Batavia |last=Figee |first=S. |publisher=Government of Netherlands East India |year=1903 |volume=24 |page=196}}</ref>\n* 1910: \"km ph\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/electrictrains00hobagoog |title=Electric Trains |last=Hobart |first=H. M. |publisher=D. Van Nostrand Company |location=New York |year=1910 |page=xix}}</ref>\n* 1911: \"K.P.H.\"<ref>{{cite journal |title=Foreign Notes on Aviation |last=Ball |first=Jack |journal=Town & Country |date=August 1911 |page=26 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1xhUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=%22kph%22+kilometer&source=bl&ots=qcyTcMQkdk&sig=HK14YIxFmt8UBcobLENErN0glHE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HFn-T_P8KMqe2wX1gv3lBA&sqi=2&ved=0CF4Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=%22kph%22%20kilometer&f=false}}</ref>\n* 1914: \"km. hr.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x9pQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1141&lpg=PA1141&dq=%22km/hr%22&source=bl&ots=4eohj9q92V&sig=phERDBIQUn5Mtf2UFGR4INs80Pk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Cbr_T4S_OofI2gW6tMWxBA&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22km%2Fhr%22&f=false |title=A Review of Some European Electric Locomotive Designs |last=Dodd |first=S. T. |journal=General Electric Review |date=January 1914 |volume=17 |issue=1 |page=1141}}</ref>\n* 1915: \"km/hour\"<ref name=\"Automobile1915\">{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oxVaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA710&lpg=PA710&dq=kph+%22kilometers+per+hour%22&source=bl&ots=oSV9840is5&sig=232C8QxgvKlEgItPZ3_fkfLywHQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5pz_T-7WD8y8qAGkhPSdBw&ved=0CEwQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=kph%20%22kilometers%20per%20hour%22&f=false |title=Data on Mixed Motor Fuels of Interest for American Export Trade |journal=The Automobile |date=October 1915 |volume=33 |issue=15 |page=709}}</ref>\n* 1915: \"km.-hr.\"<ref name=\"Automobile1915\" />\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:200pt;\"|\n* 1916: \"km. per hour\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O-MfAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA560&lpg=PA560&dq=kph+%22kilometers+per+hour%22&source=bl&ots=K_KMl6h4LJ&sig=3OPTvJsQMzVNZRNHfSL0AahG6KE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5pz_T-7WD8y8qAGkhPSdBw&ved=0CFcQ6AEwBg#v=snippet&q=%22km.%20per%20hour%22&f=false |title=Tractive resistance tests with an electric motor truck |journal=Engineering and Contracting |date=December 1916 |volume=46 |issue=25 |page=560}}</ref>\n* 1921: \"kms/hr.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Meteorological Report for the Year [1916?] |publisher=Ministry of Public Works, Egypt |page=xvii |url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=9iOmUv2oNcqiyAHCoIHYBA |year=1921 |first=Ma\u1e63la\u1e25at al-Ar\u1e63\u0101d |last=al-Jaww\u012byah}}</ref>\n* 1922: \"Kmph\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hRU6AQAAMAAJ |journal=Railway Electrical Engineer |volume=13 |page=392 |title=French Railway Begins Electrification Program |last1=Candee |first1=A. H. |last2=Lynde |first2=L. E. |publisher=Simmons Boardman |year=1922}}</ref>\n* 1927: \"kmph.\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y5lTAAAAMAAJ |title=Pressure Airships |last=Blakemore |first=Thos. L. |year=1927 |page=230 |publisher=Ronald Press}}</ref>\n* 1933: \"KPH\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Aircraft Year Book |publisher=Aerospace Industries Association of America, Manufacturers Aircraft Association, Aeronautical Chamber of Commerce of America |year=1933 |pages=391\u2013393 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=39cEAAAAMAAJ&q=%22kph%22+kilometer&dq=%22kph%22+kilometer&source=bl&ots=PyQ0_6UZCq&sig=8O5rmhK8Yjut3p0RsSoU3WItHPo&hl=en&sa=X&ei=tln-T9WMNsi-2gWfk6zcBA&ved=0CDwQ6AEwAQ |volume=15}}</ref>\n* 1939: \"kmph\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CWYjAQAAMAAJ |title=Bulletin |publisher=Central Electric Railfans' Association |year=1939 |page=cxii}}</ref>\n|}\n<!-- to be added\n* ????: \"km/hr\"\n* ????: \"KMHR\"\n* 1940: \"KMPH\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uA5LAAAAMAAJ |title=Electric Transportation |last=Thompson |first=Francis R. |year=1940 |page=165 }}</ref>\n-->\n\nWith no central authority to dictate the rules for abbreviations, various publishing houses have their own rules that dictate whether to use upper-case letters, lower-case letters, periods and so on, reflecting both changes in fashion and the image of the publishing house concerned.<ref>{{cite book |title=Eats Shoots and Leaves |first=Lynne |last=Truss |publisher=Profile Books |year=2003 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/eatsshootsleav00trus/page/188 188\u2013189] |isbn=1 86197 6127 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/eatsshootsleav00trus/page/188 }}</ref> For example, news organisations such as [[Reuters]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://handbook.reuters.com/extensions/docs/pdf/handbookofjournalism.pdf |page=278 |title=Reuters Handbook of Journalism |date=April 2008 |publisher=Reuters |access-date=2012-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518015851/http://handbook.reuters.com/extensions/docs/pdf/handbookofjournalism.pdf |archive-date=2016-05-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[The Economist]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.economist.com/style-guide/abbreviations |accessdate=9 December 2013 |title=Style Guide |newspaper=The Economist |date=27 September 2011}}</ref> \nrequire \"kph\".\n\nAustralian unofficial usage, km/h is more commonly pronounced \"Kays\". In military usage \"Klicks\" is heard, though written as km/h.<ref>{{cite web |date=June 2012 |url=http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/241046 |title=klick |work=[[Oxford English Dictionary]] |accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Unit symbols===\nIn 1879, four years after the signing of the [[Metre Convention|Treaty of the Metre]], the [[CIPM]] proposed a range of symbols for the various metric units then under the auspices of the [[CGPM]]. Among these were the use of the symbol \"km\" for \"kilometre\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=jlM907kFhcgC&pg=PA127&lpg=PA127&dq=cipm+1879+metre#v=onepage&q=cipm%201879%20metre&f=false |title=From Artefacts to Atoms: The BIPM and the Search for Ultimate Measurement Standards |first=Terry |last=Quinn |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-19-530786-3 |page=132 |location=Oxford |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, as part of its preparatory work for the [[SI]], the [[CGPM]] adopted symbols for many units of measure that did not have universally agreed symbols, one of which was the symbol \"h\" for \"hours\". At the same time the CGPM formalised the rules for combining units \u2013 quotients could be written in one of three formats resulting in {{nowrap|\"km/h\"}}, {{nowrap|\"km h<sup>\u22121</sup>\"}} and {{nowrap|\"km\u00b7h<sup>\u22121</sup>\"}} being valid representations of \"kilometres per hour\".<ref name=SI>{{SIbrochure8th|page=124}}</ref> The SI standards, which were [[MKS system of units|MKS-based]] rather than [[CGS|CGS-based]] were published in 1960 and have since then have been adopted by many authorities around the globe including academic publishers and legal authorities.\n\nThe SI explicitly states that unit symbols are not abbreviations and are to be written using a very specific set of rules.<ref name=SI/> M. Danloux-Dumesnils<ref>{{cite book |title=The Metric System: A Critical Study of its Principles and Practice |publisher=The Athlone Press of the University of London |author=Danloux-Dumesnils |year=1969 |page=32}}</ref> provides the following justification for this distinction:\n{{quote|text=It has already been stated that, according to Maxwell, when we write down the result of a measurement, the numerical value multiplies the unit. Hence the name of the unit can be replaced by a kind of algebraic symbol, which is shorter and easier to use in formulae. This symbol is not merely an abbreviation but a symbol which, like chemical symbols, must be used in a precise and prescribed manner.}}\n\nSI, and hence the use of {{nowrap|\"km/h\"}} (or {{nowrap|\"km h<sup>\u22121</sup>\"}} or {{nowrap|\"km\u00b7h<sup>\u22121</sup>\"}}) has now been adopted around the world in many areas related to health and safety<ref>{{cite web |url=http://intralibrary.rlo-cetl.ac.uk:8080/intralibrary/open_virtual_file_path/i1405n24399t/2.html |title=RLO: SI Units |accessdate=21 July 2012 |publisher=School of Nursing and Academic Division of Midwifery; University of Nottingham |date=1 December 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121223075728/http://intralibrary.rlo-cetl.ac.uk:8080/intralibrary/open_virtual_file_path/i1405n24399t/2.html |archivedate=23 December 2012 }}</ref> and in [[metrology]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Information and Harmonization |url=http://www.metrologyinfo.org/oiml-2.html |publisher=[[International Bureau of Weights and Measures]] and [[International Organization of Legal Metrology]] |accessdate=20 July 2012}}</ref> in addition to the SI unit [[meters per second]] ({{nowrap|\"m/s\"}}, {{nowrap|\"m s<sup>\u22121</sup>\"}} or {{nowrap|\"m\u00b7s<sup>\u22121</sup>\"}}). SI is also the preferred system of measure in academia and in education.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.tru.ca/library/pdf/tru-ol_editorial_style.pdf |title=OLA Editorial Style Guide |publisher=[[Open Learning Agency]] (OLA), Government of British Columbia |year=2000 |location=Burnaby, British Columbia |accessdate=26 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Alternative abbreviations in official use===\n\n*'''km/j''' or '''km/jam''' (Indonesia and Malaysia)\n*'''km/t''' or '''km/tim''' (Norway and Sweden; also use '''km/h''')\n*'''kmph''' (Sri Lanka and India)\n*'''\u0e01\u0e21./\u0e0a\u0e21.''' (Thailand; also uses '''km/hr''')\n*'''\u0643\u0645/\u0633''' or '''\u0643\u0645/\u0633\u0627\u0639\u0629''' ([[Arabic-speaking countries]], also use '''km/h''')\n\n== Regulatory use ==\nDuring the early years of the motor car, each country developed its own system of road signs. In 1968 the [[Vienna Convention on Road Signs and Signals]] was drawn up under the auspices of the [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]] to harmonise road signs across the world. Many countries have since signed the convention and adopted its proposals. Speed limits signs that are either directly authorised by the convention or have been influenced by the convention are shown below:\n\n<gallery perrow=\"6\" widths=\"120px\">\nFile:Hungary road sign C-033-100.svg|100&nbsp;km/h sign following the most common implementation of the Vienna Convention style (Hungary)\nFile:Sweden road sign C31-3.svg|Swedish 30&nbsp;km/h speed limit \u2013 the yellow background provides a contrast in case snow covers the background against which one perceives the road sign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grsproadsafety.org/our-knowledge/conspicuity-and-signs|title=Conspicuity and Signs: Road signing|publisher=[[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement#The International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies|International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies]]|year=2012|accessdate=19 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102080907/http://www.grsproadsafety.org/our-knowledge/conspicuity-and-signs|archive-date=2012-11-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nFile:Ireland road sign RUS 043.svg|Since the text \"km/h\" on this Irish speed limit sign is a symbol, not an abbreviation, it represents both \"kilometres per hour\" (English) and \"cilim\u00e9adar san uair\"([[Irish language|Irish]])<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.transport.ie/upload/general/12971-TSM_CHAPTER_1-1.PDF|title=Department of Transport / ''An Roinn Iompair''|date=November 2010|page=1|accessdate=16 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428064628/http://www.transport.ie/upload/general/12971-TSM_CHAPTER_1-1.PDF|archivedate=28 April 2012}} </ref>\nFile:UAE Speed Limit - 60 kmh.svg|60&nbsp;km/h speed limit in [[Arabic numerals]] (below) and Arabic script (above) ([[United Arab Emirates|UAE]])\nFile:Vesiliikennemerkki 11.svg|Waterways speed limit of 9&nbsp;km/h ([[Finland]])\nImage:Samoa - Speed Limit.svg|[[Samoa]] uses both [[miles per hour]] and kilometres per hour\nFile:Mexico road sign SR-09.svg|50&nbsp;km/h sign in [[Speed limits in Mexico|Mexico]]\n</gallery>\n\nIn 1972 the EU published a directive<ref>{{cite EU directive |serial=71/354/EEC |year=1971 |date=18 October 1971 |description=on the approximation of laws of Member States relating to units of measurement |eurlextag=DD:I:1971_III:31971L0354:EN:PDF}}</ref> (overhauled in 1979<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=CELEX:31980L0181:EN:NOT |author=The Council of the European Communities |title=Council Directive 80/181/EEC of 20 December 1979 on the approximation of the laws of the Member States relating to Unit of measurement and on the repeal of Directive 71/354/EEC |accessdate=7 February 2009}}</ref> to take British and Irish interests into account) that required member states to abandon CGS-based units in favour of SI. The use of SI implicitly required that member states use \"km/h\" as the shorthand for \"kilometres per hour\" on official<ref group=Note>Until 2010, the directive covered \"economic, public health, public safety or administrative purposes\"; since then [http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=CELEX:32009L0003:EN:NOT it covers all aspects] of the EU [[internal market]]</ref> documents.\n\nAnother EU directive, published in 1975, regulates the layout of speedometers within the European Union, and requires the text \"km/h\" in all languages,<ref>{{cite EU directive |serial=75/443/EEC |year=1975 |date=26 June 1975 |description=on the approximation of the laws of the Member States relating to the reverse and speedometer equipment of motor vehicles |eurlextag=CONSLEG:1975L0443:19970725:en:PDF}}</ref> even where that is not the natural abbreviation for the local version of \"kilometres per hour\". Examples include: \n*Dutch: \"''kilometer per uur''\" (\"hour\" is spelt \"''uur''\" \u2013 does not start with \"h\"),\n*Portuguese: \"''quil\u00f3metro por hora''\" (\"kilometre\" is spelt \"''quil\u00f3metro''\" \u2013 does not start with \"k\")\n*Greek: \"''\u03c7\u03b9\u03bb\u03b9\u03cc\u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b1\u03bd\u03ac \u03ce\u03c1\u03b1''\" (a different script).\n\nIn 1988 the United States [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] promulgated a rule stating that \"MPH and/or km/h\" were to be used in speedometer displays. On May 15, 2000 this was clarified to read \"MPH, or MPH and km/h\".<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.federalregister.gov/articles/2000/05/15/00-11493/federal-motor-vehicle-safety-standards-fmvss-101-technical-correction-speedometer-display |title=Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards; FMVSS 101--Technical Correction--Speedometer Display |author=National Highway Traffic Safety Administration |journal=Federal Register |date=May 2000 |volume=64 |issue=94 |pages=30915\u201330918}}</ref> However, the Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard number 101 (\"Controls and Displays\") allows \"any combination of upper- and lowercase letters\" to represent the units.<ref>{{cite book |title=Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard (101: Controls and Displays) |author=National Highway Traffic Safety Administration |page=237 |url=https://docs.google.com/gview?url=http://lemon.onecle.com/wp-content/uploads/fmvss/49cfr571.101.pdf&chrome=true}}</ref>\n\n==Conversions==\n* {{val|3.6|u=km/h}} \u2261 {{val|1|u=m/s}}, the [[SI unit]] of speed, [[metre per second]]\n* {{val|1|u=km/h}} \u2248 {{val|0.27778|u=m/s}}\n* {{val|1|u=km/h}} \u2248 {{val|0.62137|ul=mph}} \u2248 {{val|0.91134|ul=ft/s}}\n* {{val|1|ul=knot}} \u2261 {{val|1.852|u=km/h}} (exactly)\n* {{val|1|u=mph}} \u2261 {{val|1.609344|u=km/h}}\n\n{{Speed conversions}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Knot (unit)|Knot]]\n* [[Metre per second]]\n* [[Miles per hour]]\n* [[Orders of magnitude (speed)]]\n* [[Speed limits in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Speed limits in Canada#Signage|Speed limits in Canada]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist| group = Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{North America topic|Speed limits in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kilometres Per Hour}}\n[[Category:Units of velocity]]\n[[Category:Non-SI metric units]]\n", "name_user": "Carbonaro.", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilometres_per_hour"}
{"title_page": "Gulf Cartel", "text_new": "{{short description|Criminal group based in Tamaulipas}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox Criminal organization\n| name = Gulf Cartel\n| image = GulfCartel-logo.jpg\n| caption = Logo of the Gulf Cartel\n| founded = 1930s\n| founding location = [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], [[Mexico]]\n| founded by = [[Juan Nepomuceno Guerra]], [[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]]\n| years active = 1930s\u2212present\n| territory = Northeastern Mexico (as well [[Tamaulipas]] and [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]]) and the [[United States|U.S.]] States of [[Texas]], and [[Georgia (U.S. State)|Georgia]]\n| ethnic makeup = Majority [[Mexican people|Mexican]], minority [[Guatemalan people|Guatemalan]]\n| leaders = Luis Alberto Flores Blanco (Pelochas), [[Juan Manuel Loza Salinas]]  (alias \"El Toro\")\n| criminal activities = [[Drug trafficking]], [[money laundering]], [[extortion]], [[kidnapping]], [[human trafficking]], [[robbery]], [[murder]], [[arms trafficking]], [[bribery]], [[Fence (criminal)|fencing]], [[counterfeiting]], [[police impersonation]], [[arson]], [[hate crimes]]\n| allies = [[Aryan Brotherhood of Texas]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCleskey|first1=Claire O'Neill|title=White Supremacist Gang Does Business with Gulf Cartel|url=http://www.insightcrime.org/news-briefs/white-supremacist-gang-does-business-with-gulf-cartel|publisher=InSight Crime|date=29 November 2012}}</ref> <br>[[Los Mexicles]]<br>[[Italian-American Mafia]]<ref name=\"guardianmafia\">{{cite news|title=Mexican cartels funneling shipments to Italian mafia through Texas|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/apr/22/mexico-drug-cartel-italy-mafia|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=9 February 2017|date=2009-04-22|last1=Newspapers|first1=Mcclatchy}}</ref><br>[['Ndrangheta]]<ref name=\"guardianmafia\"/> <br>[[Sinaloa Cartel]]\n| rivals =[[Los Zetas]]<br>[[Black Guerilla Family]]<br>[[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]]<br>[[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel]]<br>[[Tijuana Cartel]]<br>[[Guadalajara Cartel]]<br>[[Los Negros]] (disbanded)<br>[[Barrio Azteca]]<br>[[Los Santos (gang)|Los Santos]]<br>Siete Viejo <br>[[Los Zetas]] (Cartel Del Noreste) }}\nThe '''Gulf Cartel''' ({{lang-es|C\u00e1rtel del Golfo}}, ''Golfos'', or '''CDG''')<ref>{{cite news|title=La lucha entre 'golfos' y 'zetas' desgarra a Tamaulipas|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/laluchaentregolfosyzetasdesgarraatamaulipas-531921.html|newspaper=La Vanguardia|date=16 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El c\u00e1rtel del Golfo echa a Los Zetas de Tamaulipas|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/562a77fdb11ec7137554a9298b959641|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=5 April 2010|access-date=31 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110802181118/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/562a77fdb11ec7137554a9298b959641|archive-date=2 August 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is a criminal syndicate and [[Drug cartel|drug trafficking organization]] in [[Mexico]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel|url=http://insightcrime.org/criminal-groups/mexico/gulf-cartel|accessdate=19 September 2011|newspaper=Insight: Organized Crime in the Americas|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120702224457/http://www.insightcrime.org/criminal-groups/mexico/gulf-cartel|archivedate=2 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and perhaps one of the oldest organized crime groups in the country.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. AND MEXICAN RESPONSES TO MEXICAN DRUG TRAFFICKING ORGANIZATIONS|url=http://drugcaucus.senate.gov/Mexico-Report-Final-5-2011.pdf|newspaper=UNITED STATES SENATE CAUCUS|date=May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926190953/http://drugcaucus.senate.gov/Mexico-Report-Final-5-2011.pdf|archivedate=26 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is currently based in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], directly across the U.S. border from [[Brownsville, Texas]].\n\nTheir network is international, and are believed to have dealings with crime groups in [[Europe]], [[West Africa]], [[Asia]], [[Central America]], [[South America]], and the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Beittel|first=June S.|title=Mexico's Drug Trafficking Organizations: Source and Scope of the Rising Violence|journal=Congressional Research Service|date=7 September 2011|url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/row/R41576.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Campbell|first=Howard|title=Drug war zone: frontline dispatches from the streets of El Paso and Ju\u00e1rez|year=2009|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-0-292-72179-1|pages=310|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XO0zvdha0b8C&pg=PA22&dq=gulf+cartel#v=onepage&q=gulf%20cartel&f=false}}</ref> Besides [[drug trafficking]], the Gulf Cartel operates through [[protection racket]]s, [[assassination]]s, [[extortion]]s, [[kidnapping]]s, and other criminal activities.<ref>{{cite web|last=McCAUL|first=MICHAEL T.|title=A Line in the Sand: Confronting the Threat at the Southwest Border|url=http://www.house.gov/sites/members/tx10_mccaul/pdf/Investigaions-Border-Report.pdf|publisher=HOUSE COMMITTEE ON HOMELAND SECURITY|accessdate=12 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911170206/http://www.house.gov/sites/members/tx10_mccaul/pdf/Investigaions-Border-Report.pdf|archivedate=11 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The members of the Gulf Cartel are known for intimidating the population and for being particularly violent.<ref>{{cite book|last=Warner|first=Judith|title=U.S. Border Security: A Reference Handbook|year=2010|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-59884-407-8|pages=381|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HlcD0A0w6fgC&pg=PA192&dq=gulf+cartel#v=onepage&q=gulf%20cartel&f=false}}</ref>\n\nAlthough its founder [[Juan Nepomuceno Guerra]] smuggled alcohol in large quantities to the [[United States]] during the [[Prohibition in the United States|Prohibition]] era,<ref>{{cite book|last=Grillo|first=Ioan|title=El Narco: Inside Mexico's Criminal Insurgency|year=2011|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-60819-504-6|pages=256|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1G4FlXMOgfkC&pg=PT72&dq=gulf+cartel+prohibition#v=onepage&q=gulf%20cartel%20prohibition&f=false}}</ref> it was not until the 1980s that the cartel was formed and shifted to [[drug trafficking]]\u2014primarily [[cocaine]], [[methamphetamine]], and [[heroin]]\u2014under the command of Juan Nepomuceno Guerra and [[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Foundation: 1930s\u20131980s===\nThe Gulf Cartel, a drug cartel based in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], Mexico, was founded in the 1930s by [[Juan Nepomuceno Guerra]].{{sfn|Correa-Cabrera|2017|p=267}}<ref name=\"eZukP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/j/inl/narc/rewards/275633.htm|title=Narcotics Rewards Program|publisher=[[United States Department of State]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128145955/https://www.state.gov/j/inl/narc/rewards/275633.htm|archive-date=28 November 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Originally known as the Matamoros Cartel (Spanish: ''C\u00e1rtel de Matamoros''),<ref name=\"juanNguerra\">{{cite news|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=59269&tabla=nacion|title=Falleci\u00f3 el fundador del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|last=Peralta Gonz\u00e1lez|first=C\u00e9sar|date=12 July 2001|newspaper=El Universal|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328092305/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=59269&tabla=nacion|archivedate=28 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the Gulf Cartel initially [[Rum-running|smuggled alcohol]] and other illegal goods into the U.S.<ref name=\"eZukP\"/> Once the Prohibition era ended, the criminal group controlled gambling houses, prostitution rings, a car theft network, and other illegal smuggling.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2003/03/15/046n1soc.php?origen=soc-jus.html|title=La historia del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|last=Lira Saade|first=Carmen|date=15 March 2003|newspaper=La Jornada}}</ref> It grew significantly in the 1970s under the leadership of kingpin [[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]].<ref name=\"eZukP\"/>\n\n===Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego era (1980s-1990s)===\nBy the 1980s, Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego began incorporating [[cocaine]] into the drug trafficking operations, and started to have the upper hand on what was now considered the Gulf Cartel, the greatest criminal dynasty in the [[US-Mexico border]]. By negotiating with the [[Cali Cartel]],<ref>{{cite web|title=FBI Adds International Drug Dealer to \"Most-Wanted\" List|url=http://www.ndsn.org/april95/abrego.html|publisher=National Drug Strategy Network|accessdate=April 1995}}</ref> Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was able to secure 50% of the shipment out of [[Colombia]] as payment for delivery, instead of the US$1,500 per kilogram they were previously receiving. This renegotiation, however, forced Garcia \u00c1brego to guarantee the product's arrival from Colombia to its destination. Instead, he created [[warehouses]] along the Mexican's northern border to preserve hundreds of tons of [[cocaine]]; this allowed him to create a new distribution network and increase his political influence. In addition to trafficking drugs, Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego would ship cash to be [[Money laundering|laundered]], in the millions.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vindell|first=Tony|title=Reputed drug lord's brother under arrest|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/garcia-42481-abrego-arrest.html|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=15 October 1994}}</ref> Around 1994, it was estimated that the Gulf Cartel handled as much as \"one-third of all cocaine shipments\" into the United States from the [[Cali Cartel]] suppliers.<ref>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Peter H. |chapter=Drug Trafficking in Mexico |title=Coming together?: Mexico-United States relations |year=1997 |publisher=Brookings Institution Press |isbn=978-0-8157-1027-1 |page=132 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CxUU4tuC18YC&pg=PA132}}</ref> During the 1990s, the [[Attorney General of Mexico|PGR]], the Mexican attorney general's office, estimated that the Gulf Cartel was \"worth over $10 billion US dollars.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Jordan|first=David C.|title=Drug politics: dirty money and democracies|year=1999|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-3174-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/drugpolitics00davi/page/288 288]|url=https://archive.org/details/drugpolitics00davi|url-access=registration|quote=gulf cartel in U.S.}}</ref>\n\n====Corruption in the United States ====\nGarc\u00eda \u00c1brego's ties extended beyond the Mexican government corruption and into the [[United States]]. With the arrest of one of Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego's traffickers, Juan Antonio Ortiz, it became known the cartel would ship tons of cocaine in United States [[Immigration and Naturalization Service]] (INS) buses between the years of 1986 to 1990. The buses made great transportation, as Antonio Ortiz noted, since they were never stopped at the border.<ref name=\"Homage\">{{cite book|last=Weinberg|first=Bill|title=Homage to Chiapas: The New Indigenous Struggles in Mexico|url=https://archive.org/details/homagetochiapas00bill|url-access=registration|publisher=Verso Publishers|year=2000|pages=[https://archive.org/details/homagetochiapas00bill/page/371 371]|isbn=978-1-85984-372-7}}</ref>\n\nIt also became known that, in addition to the INS bus scam, Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego had a \"special deal\" with members of the [[Texas National Guard]] who would truck tons of cocaine and marijuana from South Texas to Houston for the cartel.<ref name=\"Homage\" />\n\nGarcia Abrego's reach became known when a United States [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) agent named Claude de la O, in 1986, stated in testimony against Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego that he received over US$100,000 in bribes and had leaked information that could have endangered an FBI informant as well as Mexican journalists. In 1989 Claude was removed  from the case for unknown reasons, retiring a year later. Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego bribed the agent in an attempt to gather more information on U.S. law enforcement operations.<ref name=\"NYTimes2\">{{cite news|title=At Drug Trial, Mexican Suspect Faces Accuser|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/20/world/at-drug-trial-mexican-suspect-faces-accuser.html|accessdate=18 September 2012|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=20 September 1996|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106002702/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/20/world/at-drug-trial-mexican-suspect-faces-accuser.html|archivedate=6 November 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Reign\">{{cite news|last=Dillon|first=Sam|title=Mexican Drug Gang's Reign of Blood|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/04/world/mexican-drug-gang-s-reign-of-blood.html|accessdate=18 September 2012|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=4 February 1996|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106002710/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/04/world/mexican-drug-gang-s-reign-of-blood.html|archivedate=6 November 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Arrest of \u00c1brego====\n[[File:Juan Garcia-Abrego.jpg|right|180px|thumb|[[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]], founder of the organization.]]\n[[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]]'s business had grown to such length that the [[FBI]] placed him on the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives, 1990s|Top Ten Most Wanted in 1995]]. He was the first drug trafficker to be on that list.<ref>{{cite news|title=Juan Garc\u00eda Abrego&nbsp;\u2013 Top Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1971762_1971761_1971728,00.html|newspaper=TIMES Magazine | date=23 June 2011}}</ref> On 14 January 1996, Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was arrested outside a ranch in [[Monterrey, Nuevo Le\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Mu\u00f1oz|first=Juan Miguel|title=M\u00e9xico detiene y entrega a Estados Unidos a su principal narcotraficante|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/internacional/COLOMBIA/ESTADOS_UNIDOS/MEXICO/Mexico/detiene/entrega/Estados/Unidos/principal/narcotraficante/elpepiint/19960116elpepiint_13/Tes|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|date=16 January 1996}}</ref> He was quickly extradited to the United States where he stood trial eight months after his arrest. Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was convicted for 22 counts of [[money laundering]], [[drug possession]] and [[drug trafficking]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mexican \"Gulf Cartel\" Leader Juan Garcia Abrego Convicted on U.S. Drug Charges|url=http://www.ndsn.org/nov96/abrego.html|publisher=National Drug Strategy Network|accessdate=November 1996}}</ref> Jurors also ordered the [[seizure]] of $350 million of Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego's [[assets]]&nbsp;\u2014 $75 million more than what was previously planned.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fineman|first=Mark|title=Mexican Drug Cartel Chief Convicted in U.S.|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1996-10-17/news/mn-57764_1_garcia-abrego|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=17 October 1996}}</ref> Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego is currently serving 11 life terms in a [[prison#Security levels|maximum security prison]] in [[Colorado|Colorado, U.S.]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Laura|title=Juan Garcia Abrego|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1971762_1971761_1971728,00.html|newspaper=TIME Special {{!}} CNN.com|date=23 June 2011}}</ref> In 1996, it was disclosed that Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego's organization paid millions of dollars in bribes to politicians and law enforcement officers for his protection. It was later proven after his arrest that the deputy attorney general in charge of Mexico's federal Judicial Police had accumulated more than $9 million US dollars for protecting Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego.<ref>{{cite book|last=Abadinsky|first=Howard|title=Organized Crime|year=2009|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-0-495-59966-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/organizedcrime00howa/page/462 462]|url=https://archive.org/details/organizedcrime00howa|url-access=registration|quote=gulf cartel.}}</ref>\n\nGarc\u00eda \u00c1brego's arrest was even subject to allegations of corruption. It is believed the Mexican government knew all Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego's whereabouts all along and had refused to arrest him due to information he possessed about the extent of corruption within the government. The arresting officer, a FJP commander, is believed to have received a [[bullet-proof]] [[Mercury Grand Marquis]] and US$500,000 from a rival cartel for enacting the arrest of Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego.<ref name=\"Organized\">{{cite book|last=Bailey|first=John J|author2=[[Roy Godson]]|title=Organized Crime and Democratic Governability: Mexico and the U.S.-Mexican Borderlands|publisher=University of Pittsburgh Press|year=2001|pages=48|isbn=978-0-8229-5758-4}}</ref>\n\nFurther theories put forward allege the arrest of Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was to satisfy U.S. demands and meet certification, from the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] (DOJ), as a trade partner, the vote set to take place on 1 March. Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was apprehended on 14 January 1996, and Mexico shortly after received certification on 1 March.<ref name=\"Pan\">{{cite book|last=Harrison|first=Lawrence E.|title=The Pan-American Dream: Do Latin America's Cultural Values Discourage True Partnership with the United States and Canada?|publisher=Westview Press|year=1997|pages=[https://archive.org/details/panamericandream00lawr/page/227 227, 228]|isbn=978-0-8133-3470-7|url=https://archive.org/details/panamericandream00lawr/page/227}}</ref>\n\n;United States v. Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego\nUpon his capture outside the city of [[Monterrey, Nuevo Le\u00f3n]], the drug lord was flown to [[Mexico City]] where U.S. federal agent took him on a private plane to [[Houston, Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Legendary Juan Garcia Abrego in U.S. custody|url=http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=28953_0_1_0_C|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120715121501/http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=28953_0_1_0_C|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 July 2012|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=16 January 1996}}</ref> Wearing slacks and a striped shirt, Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was immediately extradited to the [[United States]] where he was interviewed by a [[FBI]] agent, and confessed to have \"ordered people murdered and tortured,\" bribed top Mexican officials, and smuggled tons of narcotics into the United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=At Drug Trial, Mexican Suspect Faces Accuser|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/20/world/at-drug-trial-mexican-suspect-faces-accuser.html|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=20 September 1996}}</ref> His prosecutors, however, tried Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego as a U.S. citizen because he also had an American birth certificate, although Mexican authorities claimed the certificate was \"fraudulent.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Tedford|first=Deborah|title=Garcia Abrego is U.S. citizen, officials insist|url=http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl/1996_1322867/garcia-abrego-is-u-s-citizen-officials-insist.html|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Houston Chronicle|date=2 July 1996}}</ref> He also had an official birth certificate that claimed Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was indeed born in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Expulsion may have broken the law|url=http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=28901_0_1_0_C|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120715120503/http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=28901_0_1_0_C|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 July 2012|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=19 January 1996}}</ref> According to ''[[The Brownsville Herald]]'', Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego went into the courtroom grinning and talking animatedly with his lawyers who helped him translate his words from Spanish into the [[English language]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Langford|first=Terri|title=Life in jail for drug lord|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/abrego-23141-garcia-united.html|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=1 February 1997}}</ref> Hours after the judge told Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego that he was going to spend the rest of his life in prison, the [[death penalty]] was out of the question for the prosecutors.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Juan Garcia Abrego arraigned in U.S. FBI fugitive could spend life in prison|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/garcia-28967-abrego-fbi.html|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=17 January 1996}}</ref>\n\nThe factual documents presented in court on 8 May 1998, the Matamoros-based criminal syndicate of the Gulf Cartel was responsible for trafficking tremendous amounts of narcotics into the United States from the mid-1970s to the mid-1990s, and Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was given eleven life sentences in prison.<ref>{{cite web|title=UNITED STATES v. GARCIA ABREGO|url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-5th-circuit/1396381.html#footnote_ref_27|publisher=United States Court of Appeals: Fifth Circuit|accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref> During the four-week trial, 84 witnesses, ranging from \"law enforcement officers to convicted drug smugglers,\" confessed that Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego smuggled loads of Colombian cocaine on planes and then stored them in several border cities along the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]] before being smuggled to the [[Rio Grande Valley]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Marisa|title=Jury: Abrego guilty|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/garcia-32638-abrego-drug.html|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=17 October 1996}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, it was brought up that [[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego|Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]] had previously been arrested in [[Brownsville, Texas]] for six-year-old auto theft charges, but was released later with no charges whatsoever.<ref>{{cite news|last=Robbins|first=Maro|title=Garcia Abrego was allowed to go free|url=http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=35770_0_1_0_C|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120711202530/http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=35770_0_1_0_C|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 July 2012|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=27 August 1995}}</ref> Two men from the [[Rio Grande Valley]] were charged before the drug lord's arrest for laundering more than $30 million for Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Pe\u00f1a: Garcia Abrego hurt by huge bust Agents seize $22 million load of coke|url=http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=36985_0_1_0_C|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120714075942/http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=36985_0_1_0_C|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 July 2012|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=30 November 1995}}</ref> He was also held responsible in 1984 for the massacre of 6 people in La Cl\u00ednica Raya, a hospital where rival drug members were being treated, and was also blamed for the massacre of the Cereso prison in 1991, where 18 prisoners were slain\u2014both in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|last=P\u00e9rez Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Jorge|title=Mentes perversas|url=http://www.hoytamaulipas.net/?v1=notas&v2=59427|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=Hoy Tamaulipas|date=22 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Vindell|first=Tony|title=El Profe welcomes Garcia Abrego's downfall|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/abrego-28849-garcia-lopez.html|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=24 January 1996}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Althaus|first=Dudley|title=Texas-Mexico Borderlanconfrontads: The Slide Toward Chaos|journal=The International Journal of Continuing Social Work Education|year=2009|volume=12|issue=10974911|pages=57|url=http://www.profdevjournal.org/articles/122057.pdf|accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===After Garc\u00eda-\u00c1brego era ===\n\nFollowing \u00c1brego's 1996 arrest by Mexican authorities and subsequent deportation to the United States, a power vacuum was left and several top members fought for leadership.<ref>{{cite news|title=Historia y estructura del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.terra.com.mx/noticias/articulo/989908/Historia+y+estructura+del+Cartel+del+Golfo.htm|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=Terra Noticias}}</ref>\n\nHumberto Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego, brother of Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego, tried to take the lead of the Gulf Cartel, but ultimately failed in his attempt.<ref>{{cite news|last=Castillo|first=Gustavo|title=Desplazan a los Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego en liderato del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2009/05/02/politica/021n1pol|newspaper=La Jornada|date=2 May 2009}}</ref> He did not have the leadership skills nor the support of the Colombian drug-provisioners. In addition, he was under observation and was widely known, since his surname meant more of the same.<ref>{{cite news|last=Alzaga|first=Ignacio|title=Relegan a familia de Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego en c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8568516|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=1 May 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518012741/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8568516|archivedate=18 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was to be replaced by [[\u00d3scar Malherbe de Le\u00f3n]] and Ra\u00fal Valladares del \u00c1ngel, until their arrest a short time later,<ref>{{cite news|last=Weiner|first=Tim|title=Mexico Agrees To Extradite Drug Suspect To California|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/01/19/world/mexico-agrees-to-extradite-drug-suspect-to-california.html|newspaper=New York Times|date=19 January 2001}}</ref> causing several cartel lieutenants to fight for the leadership. Malherbe tried to bribe officials $2 million for his release, but it was denied.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lupsha|first=Peter|title=A Chronology {{!}} Murder, Money, & Mexico|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/mexico/etc/cron.html|publisher=University of New Mexico}}</ref> [[Hugo Baldomero Medina Garza]], known as ''El Se\u00f1or de los Tr\u00e1ilers'' (the lord of the Trailers), is considered one of the most important members in the rearticulation of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|last=Medell\u00edn|first=Alejandro|title=Medina Garza en 'La Palma'|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=46900&tabla=nacion|newspaper=El Universal|date=4 February 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328092001/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=46900&tabla=nacion|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was one of the top officials of the cartel for more than 40 years, trafficking about 20 tons of cocaine to the United States each month.<ref>{{cite news|last=Zendejas|first=Gabriel|title=Detectan a poderoso capo del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.oem.com.mx/esto/notas/n681175.htm|newspaper=La Prensa|accessdate=30 April 2008}}</ref> His luck ended in November 2000 when he was captured in [[Tampico]], [[Tamaulipas]] and imprisoned in [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1|La Palma]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ruiz|first=Jos\u00e9 Luis|title=Caen 21 miembros de c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=5327&tabla=primera|newspaper=El Universal|date=3 April 2001|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328092024/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=5327&tabla=primera|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After Medina Garza's arrest, his cousin Adalberto Garza Dragustinovis was investigated for allegedly forming part of the Gulf Cartel and for [[laundering money]], but the case is still open.<ref>{{cite news|title=Indagan a familiar de El Se\u00f1or de los Tr\u00e1ileres|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8055762|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120716191638/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8055762|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 July 2012|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=18 November 2008}}</ref> The next in line was Sergio G\u00f3mez alias ''El Checo'', however, his leadership was short lived when he was assassinated in April 1996 in [[Valle Hermoso, Tamaulipas|Valle Hermoso]], [[Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ram\u00edrez|first=Ignacio|title=La disputa del narcopoder|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=19691&tabla=nacion|newspaper=El Universal|date=10 April 2000|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328092114/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=19691&tabla=nacion|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After this, [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] took control of the cartel in July 1999 after assassinating Salvador G\u00f3mez Herrera alias ''El Chava'', co-leader of the Gulf Cartel and close friend of him, earning his name as the ''Mata Amigos'' (Friend Killer).<ref>{{cite news|title=Desde las entra\u00f1as del Ej\u00e9rcito, Los Zetas|url=http://www.blogdelnarco.info/desde-las-entranas-del-ejercito-los-zetas/|newspaper=Blog del Narco|date=23 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225120907/http://www.blogdelnarco.info/desde-las-entranas-del-ejercito-los-zetas/|archivedate=25 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n's era===\nAs confrontations with rival groups heated up, [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] sought and recruited over 30 deserters of the [[Mexican Army]]'s elite [[Grupo Aerom\u00f3vil de Fuerzas Especiales]] (GAFE) to form part of the cartel's armed wing.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Los Zetas\" se salen de control|url=http://www.eluniversal.mx/nacion/156964.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425031613/http://www.eluniversal.mx/nacion/156964.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=25 April 2012|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal}}</ref> [[Los Zetas]], as they are known, served as the hired private [[mercenary]] army of the Gulf Cartel. Nevertheless, after the arrest and [[extradition]] of C\u00e1rdenas, internal struggles led to a rupture between the Gulf and the Zetas.<ref>{{cite news|title=DEA: acuerdan 3 c\u00e1rteles alianza contra Los Zetas|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/562a77fdb11ec7137554a9298b28a727|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120629064442/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/562a77fdb11ec7137554a9298b28a727|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 June 2012|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=Milenio}}</ref>\n\n====Los Zetas====\n<!-- Commented out: [[File:OsielCardenasmugshot.jpg|left|140px|thumb|Mug shot of [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]]]] -->\nIn 1997 the Gulf Cartel began to recruit military personnel whom [[Jos\u00e9 de Jes\u00fas Guti\u00e9rrez Rebollo|Jes\u00fas Guti\u00e9rrez Rebollo]], an Army General of that time, had assigned as representatives from the [[Attorney General of Mexico|PGR]] offices in certain states across [[Mexico]]. After his imprisonment a short time later, Jorge Madrazo Cu\u00e9llar created the National Public Security System (SNSP), to fight the drug cartels along the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|U.S.\u2013Mexico border]]. After [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] took full control of the Gulf Cartel in 1999, he found himself in a no-holds-barred fight to keep his notorious organization and leadership untouched, and sought out members of the [[Grupo Aerom\u00f3vil de Fuerzas Especiales|Mexican Army Special Forces]] to become the military armed-wing of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u00bfQuienes son los Zetas?|url=http://www.blogdelnarco.info/%C2%BFquienes-son-los-zetas/|newspaper=Blog del Narco|date=7 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110729042942/http://www.blogdelnarco.info/%C2%BFquienes-son-los-zetas/|archivedate=29 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His goal was to protect himself from rival drug cartels and from the Mexican military, in order to perform vital functions  as the leader of the most powerful [[drug cartel]] in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|title=C\u00e1rtel de 'Los Zetas'|url=http://www.mundonarco.com/2011/01/cartel-del-los-zetas.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110118032606/http://www.mundonarco.com/2011/01/cartel-del-los-zetas.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 January 2011|newspaper=Mundo Narco|date=15 January 2011}}</ref> Among his first contacts was [[Arturo Guzm\u00e1n Decena]], an Army lieutenant who was reportedly asked by C\u00e1rdenas to look for the \"best men possible.\"<ref name=\"Grayson\">{{cite book|last=Grayson|first=George W.|title=Mexico: narco-violence and a failed state?|year=2010|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-1-4128-1151-4|pages=339|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ogjkeCd7RGoC&pg=PA180&lpg=PA180&dq=cardenas+reportedly+told+lt.+arturo+guzman+decenas+that+he+wanted+the+best+men+possible#v=onepage&q=wanted%20the%20best%20men%20possible&f=false}}</ref> Consequently, Guzm\u00e1n Decenas deserted from the Armed Forces and brought more than 30 army [[deserters]] to form part of C\u00e1rdenas' new  criminal paramilitary wing.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tobar|first=Hector|title=A cartel army's war within|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/may/20/world/fg-zetas20|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=20 May 2007}}</ref> They were enticed with salaries much higher than those of the Mexican Army.<ref>{{cite news|title=Los Zetas and Mexico's Transnational Drug War|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/04/los-zetas-and-mexicos-transnational.html|accessdate=9 December 2011|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]}}</ref> Among the original defectors were [[Jaime Gonz\u00e1lez Dur\u00e1n]],<ref>{{cite news| title=Los 'grandes capos' detenidos en la guerra contra el narcotr\u00e1fico de Calder\u00f3n| url=http://www.cnn.mx/nacional/2010/09/02/jaime-gonzalez-duran-el-hummer| newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico| date=6 November 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313101448/http://www.cnn.mx/nacional/2010/09/02/jaime-gonzalez-duran-el-hummer| archivedate=13 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Jes\u00fas Enrique Rej\u00f3n Aguilar]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Video Interrogatorio de Jes\u00fas Enrique Rej\u00f3n Aguilar \"El Mamito\"|url=http://www.mundonarco.com/2011/07/video-interrogatorio-jesus-enrique.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709024954/http://www.mundonarco.com/2011/07/video-interrogatorio-jesus-enrique.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 July 2011|newspaper=Mundo Narco|date=5 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Miguel Trevi\u00f1o Morales]],<ref>{{cite web| title=DEA Fugitive: TREVINO-MORALES, MIGUEL| url=http://www.justice.gov/dea/fugitives/houston/TREVINO-MORALES-miguel.html| publisher=U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510034621/http://www.justice.gov/dea//fugitives/houston/TREVINO-MORALES-miguel.html| archivedate=10 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Heriberto Lazcano]],<ref>{{cite news| title=Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano \"El Verdugo\"| url=http://www.blogdelnarco.info/heriberto-lazcano-lazcano-el-verdugo/| newspaper=Blog del Narco| date=3 March 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806204043/http://www.blogdelnarco.info/heriberto-lazcano-lazcano-el-verdugo/| archivedate=6 August 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> who would later become the supreme leader of the independent cartel of [[Los Zetas]]. The creation of Los Zetas brought a new era of [[drug trafficking]] in Mexico, and little did C\u00e1rdenas know that he was creating the most violent drug cartel in the country.<ref>{{cite news| last=Ware| first=Michael| title=Los Zetas called Mexico's most dangerous drug cartel| url=http://articles.cnn.com/2009-08-06/world/mexico.drug.cartels_1_los-zetas-drug-cartels-drug-war?_s=PM:WORLD| newspaper=CNN World| date=6 August 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015231342/http://articles.cnn.com/2009-08-06/world/mexico.drug.cartels_1_los-zetas-drug-cartels-drug-war?_s=PM:WORLD| archivedate=15 October 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Between 2001 and 2008, the organization of the Gulf Cartel and Los Zetas was collectively known as La Compa\u00f1\u00eda (''The Company'').<ref>{{cite news|last=Sherman|first=Chris|title=Texas jury convicts alleged Mexican cartel hit man|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/hit-58252-jury-mcallen.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120912194439/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/hit-58252-jury-mcallen.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 September 2012|accessdate=26 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=25 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOne of the first missions of Los Zetas was to eradicate Los Chachos, a group of drug traffickers under the orders of the [[Milenio Cartel]], who disputed the drug corridors of [[Tamaulipas]] with the Gulf Cartel in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=Surge nuevo 'narcoperfil|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=100976&tabla=nacion|accessdate=9 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111155629/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=100976&tabla=nacion|archivedate=11 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This gang was controlled by Dionisio Rom\u00e1n Garc\u00eda S\u00e1nchez alias ''El Chacho'', who had decided to betray the Gulf Cartel and switch his alliance with the [[Tijuana Cartel]]; however, he was eventually killed by Los Zetas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Organized crime and terrorist activity in Mexico, 1999-2002|url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/frd/pdf-files/OrgCrime_Mexico.pdf|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref> Once C\u00e1rdenas consolidated his position and supremacy, he expanded the responsibilities of Los Zetas, and as years passed, they became much more important for the Gulf Cartel. They began to organize [[kidnappings]];<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Narco gangster reveals the underworld|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/topstory/7607122.html#loopbegin|newspaper=Houston Chronicle}}</ref> impose taxes, collect debts, and operate [[protection racket]]s;<ref>{{cite web|title=The Mexican Drug War and the Thirty Years' War|url=http://bellum.stanfordreview.org/?p=3015|publisher=Bellum: The Stanford Review|accessdate=8 February 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110305074956/http://bellum.stanfordreview.org/?p=3015|archivedate=5 March 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> control the [[extortion]] business;<ref>{{cite news|title=Army troops capture a Zetas cartel boss in northern Mexico|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2011/02/15/army-troops-capture-zetas-cartel-boss-northern-mexico/|newspaper=Fox News Latino|date=15 February 2011}}</ref> securing [[cocaine]] supply and trafficking routes known as ''plazas'' (zones) and executing its foes, often with grotesque savagery.<ref name=\"Grayson\"/> In response to the rising power of the Gulf Cartel, the rival [[Sinaloa Cartel]]<ref>{{cite news|title=\u00bfQu\u00e9 es el Cartel de Sinaloa?|url=http://www.perfil.com/contenidos/2008/08/24/noticia_0023.html|newspaper=Perfil.com|date=24 August 2008}}</ref> established a heavily armed, well-trained enforcer group known as [[Los Negros]].<ref>{{cite news|last=S\u00e1nchez|first=Alex|title=Mexico's Drug War: Soldiers versus Narco-Soldiers|url=http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=f85a9ff12311fcc1895e0801f6df8d2f|newspaper=New American Media {{!}} La Prensa San Diego|date=4 June 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320042633/http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=f85a9ff12311fcc1895e0801f6df8d2f|archivedate=20 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The group operated similar to Los Zetas, but with less complexity and success. There is a circle of experts who believe that the start of the [[Mexican Drug War]] did not begin in 2006 (when [[Felipe Calder\u00f3n]] sent troops to Michoac\u00e1n to stop the increasing violence), but in 2004 in the border city of [[Nuevo Laredo]], when the Gulf Cartel and [[Los Zetas]] fought off the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] and [[Los Negros]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Fantz|first=Ashley|title=Saldo por el combate al narcotr\u00e1fico: muerte por un negocio millonario|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2012/01/22/saldo-por-el-combate-al-narcotrafico-muerte-por-un-negocio-millonario|accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=22 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123202055/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2012/01/22/saldo-por-el-combate-al-narcotrafico-muerte-por-un-negocio-millonario|archivedate=23 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, there were three main divisions of the Cartel, all ruled over by C\u00e1rdenas and led by: Jorge Eduardo \"[[Jorge Eduardo Costilla Sanchez|El Coss]]\" Costilla, Ezequiel \"[[Antonio Cardenas Guillen|Tony Tormenta]]\" C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n, and Heriberto \"[[Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano|El Lazca]]\" Lazcano.<ref name=BBTestimonyRafael>{{cite web |url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2012/09/cartel-boss-everyone-from-cops-to.html |title=Cartel boss: Everyone from cops to strippers worked for me |accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nUpon the arrest of the Gulf Cartel boss C\u00e1rdenas in 2003 and his [[extradition]] in 2007, the panorama for Los Zetas changed\u2014they started to become synonymous with the Gulf Cartel, and their influences grew greater within the organization.<ref>{{cite web|title=Drug Trafficking Organizations|url=http://www.justice.gov/ndic/pubs32/32781/dtos.htm|publisher=National Drug Intelligence Center|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref> Los Zetas began to grow independently from the Gulf Cartel, and eventually a rupture occurred between them in early 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Weekend shootouts in northeastern Mexico kill at least 9|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2010-04-12/world/mexico.deaths_1_zetas-gulf-cartel-familia-michoacana?_s=PM:WORLD|accessdate=9 December 2011|newspaper=CNN News|date=17 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315102415/http://articles.cnn.com/2010-04-12/world/mexico.deaths_1_zetas-gulf-cartel-familia-michoacana?_s=PM:WORLD|archivedate=15 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El origen de 'Los Zetas': brazo armado del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/05/el-origen-de-los-zetas-brazo-armado-del-cartel-del-golfo|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=5 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130128174447/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/05/el-origen-de-los-zetas-brazo-armado-del-cartel-del-golfo|archivedate=28 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Standoff with U.S. agents==\n{{Main|1999 Matamoros standoff}}\nOn 9 November 1999, two U.S. agents from the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA) and [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) were threatened at gunpoint by C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n and approximately fifteen of his henchmen in Matamoros. The two agents travelled to Matamoros with an informant to gather intelligence on the operations of the Gulf Cartel.<ref name=deastandoff>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mysanantonio.com/news/mexico/article/Dangers-higher-for-federal-agents-1033781.php|title=Dangers higher for federal agents|last=Buch|first=Json|date=28 February 2011|work=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127110405/https://www.mysanantonio.com/news/mexico/article/Dangers-higher-for-federal-agents-1033781.php|archive-date=27 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"deahouston\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/DEA-agent-breaks-silence-on-standoff-with-cartel-1713234.php|title=DEA agent breaks silence on standoff with cartel|last=Schiller|first=Dane|date=15 March 2010|work=[[The Houston Chronicle]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127193446/https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/DEA-agent-breaks-silence-on-standoff-with-cartel-1713234.php|archive-date=27 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n demanded the agents and the informant to get out of their vehicle, but they refused to obey his orders. The incident escalated as C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n threatened to kill them if they did not comply and as his gunmen prepared to shoot. The agents tried to reason with him that killing U.S. federal agents would bring a massive manhunt from the U.S. government. C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n eventually let them go and threatened to kill them if they ever returned to his home turf.<ref name=deastandoff/>\n\nThe standoff triggered a massive law enforcement effort to crackdown the leadership structure of the Gulf Cartel. Both the Mexican and U.S. government increased their efforts to apprehend C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n. Prior to the standoff, he was regarded as a minor player in the [[Illegal drug trade|international drug trade]], but this incident catapulted his reputation and made him one of the most-wanted criminals.<ref name=\"graysondea\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/valley/grayson-zapata-slaying-will-have-repercussions/article_9ea1164e-6747-5656-8dc9-10d46ea919bc.html|title=Grayson: Zapata slaying will have repercussions|last=|first=|date=17 February 2011|work=[[The Brownsville Herald]]|access-date=}}</ref> The FBI and the DEA mounted numerous charges against him and issued a US$2 million bounty for his arrest.<ref name=\"2milreward\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dea.gov/pubs/pressrel/pr121400.htm|title=$2 Million Reward Offered Leading To The Arrest or Conviction of Drug Traffickers|date=14 December 2000|publisher=[[Drug Enforcement Administration]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070203212334/https://www.dea.gov/pubs/pressrel/pr121400.htm|archive-date=3 February 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Arrest and extradition ===\n[[File:OsielCardenas-DEA.jpg|left|220px|thumb|[[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]]'s [[extradition]] to the United States from Mexico.]]\nThe former leader of the Gulf Cartel, [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], was captured in the city of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], on 14 March 2003  in a shootout between the Mexican military and Gulf Cartel gunmen.<ref name=\"arrest\">{{cite news | title='Drug boss' captured in Mexico | date=15 March 2003 |work=BBC News | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/2852197.stm | accessdate =25 February 2010 }}</ref> He was one of the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]], which was offering $2 million for his capture.<ref>{{cite web|title=Osiel Cardenas-Guillen|url=https://www.fbi.gov/houston/press-releases/2010/ho022410b.htm|publisher=Federal Bureau of Investigation|accessdate=24 February 2010}}</ref> According to government archives, this six-month military operation was planned and carried out in secret; the only people informed were the President [[Vicente Fox]], the Secretary of Defense in Mexico, Ricardo Clemente Vega Garc\u00eda, and Mexico's Attorney General, Rafael Macedo de la Concha.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cae Osiel C\u00e1rdenas: Se enfrent\u00f3 a tiros con el Ej\u00e9rcito|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=94595&tabla=Nacion_H|newspaper=El Universal|date=15 March 2003|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328092143/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=94595&tabla=Nacion_H|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After his capture, C\u00e1rdenas was sent to the federal, high-security prison [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1|La Palma]].<ref>{{cite news |agency=Notimex |title=Nuevo auto de formal prisi\u00f3n a Osiel C\u00e1rdenas |url=http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/466430.html |newspaper=Esmas.com |date=August 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004042205/http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/466430.html |archive-date=4 October 2012}}</ref> However, it was believed that C\u00e1rdenas still controlled the Gulf Cartel from prison,<ref>{{cite news|last=Aponte|first=David|title=L\u00edderes narcos pactan en La Palma trasriego de droga|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=119863&tabla=nacion|newspaper=El Universal|date=5 January 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328092221/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=119863&tabla=nacion|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and was later extradicted to the United States, where he was sentenced to 25 years in a prison in [[Houston, Texas]] for [[money laundering]], [[drug trafficking]], [[homicide]] and death threats to U.S. federal agents.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sentencian a Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n a 25 a\u00f1os de prisi\u00f3n en Texas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/02/24/sentencian-a-osiel-cardenas-guillen-a-25-anos-de-prision-en-texas|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=24 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904020823/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/02/24/sentencian-a-osiel-cardenas-guillen-a-25-anos-de-prision-en-texas|archivedate=4 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Reports from the [[Attorney General of Mexico|PGR]] and ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]'' state that while in prison, C\u00e1rdenas and [[Benjam\u00edn Arellano F\u00e9lix]], from the [[Tijuana Cartel]], formed an alliance. Moreover, through handwritten notes, C\u00e1rdenas gave orders on the movement of drugs along Mexico and to the United States, approved executions, and signed forms to allow the purchase of police forces.<ref name=\"BehindBars\">{{cite news|title=Maneja Osiel mafia desde la carcel, prueban|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=120380&tabla=nacion|accessdate=5 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419021522/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=120380&tabla=nacion|archivedate=19 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> And while his brother [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guillen|Antonio]] led the Gulf Cartel, C\u00e1rdenas still made vital orders from [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1|La Palma]] through messages from his lawyers and guards.<ref name=\"BehindBars\"/>\n\nThe arrest and extradition of C\u00e1rdenas, however, caused for several top lieutenants from both the Gulf Cartel and Los Zetas to fight over important [[drug corridor]]s to the [[United States]], especially the cities of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]], [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas|Nuevo Laredo]], [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas|Reynosa]], and [[Tampico, Tamaulipas|Tampico]]\u2014all situated in the state of [[Tamaulipas]]. They also fought for coastal cities [[Acapulco, Guerrero]] and [[Canc\u00fan, Quintana Roo]]; the state capital of [[Monterrey, Nuevo Le\u00f3n]], and the states of [[Veracruz (state)|Veracruz]] and [[San Luis Potos\u00ed (state)|San Luis Potos\u00ed]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Desertor del Ej\u00e9rcito, nuevo l\u00edder del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo: informes castrenses|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2008/02/03/index.php?section=politica&article=009n1pol|newspaper=La Jornada|date=3 February 2008}}</ref> Through his violence and intimidation, [[Heriberto Lazcano]] took control of both Los Zetas and the Gulf Cartel after Cardenas' extradition.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Notimex |title=Detienen a un l\u00edder del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo en Tabasco |url=http://www2.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/011667/detienen-lider-del-cartel-del-golfo-tabasco |newspaper=Esmas.com |date=7 September 2008}}</ref> Lieutenants that were once loyal to C\u00e1rdenas began following the commands of Lazcano, who tried to reorganize the cartel by appointing several lieutenants to control specific territories. [[Miguel Trevi\u00f1o Morales|Morales Trevi\u00f1o]] was appointed to look over [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Miguel Morales Trevi\u00f1o, Z-40, un narco violento ya est\u00e1 en la mira|url=http://www.mundonarco.com/2010/12/miguel-trevino-morales-alias-el-z-40-un.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223101533/http://www.mundonarco.com/2010/12/miguel-trevino-morales-alias-el-z-40-un.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 December 2010|newspaper=Mundo Narco|date=22 December 2010}}</ref> [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]] in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Loz Zetas: Grupo Paramilitar Mexicano|url=http://www.policiasysociedad.org/userfiles/aclaracionessobreloszetas_esp.pdf|publisher=Policias y Sociedad|accessdate=6 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626114555/http://www.policiasysociedad.org/userfiles/aclaracionessobreloszetas_esp.pdf|archive-date=26 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[H\u00e9ctor Manuel Sauceda Gamboa]], nicknamed ''El Karis'', took control of [[Nuevo Laredo]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Cartel leader believed slain in Reynosa violence|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/leader-23347-cartel-violence.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520033957/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/leader-23347-cartel-violence.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 May 2009|newspaper=The Monitor|date=17 February 2009}}</ref> Gregorio Sauceda Gamboa, known as ''El Goyo'', along with his brother Arturo, took control of the [[Reynosa]] plaza;<ref>{{cite news|title=Confirman militares enfrentamiento con narcotraficantes|url=http://www.juanruizhealy.com/articulos/notas_de_ventanas/el_manana.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020105081924/http://www.juanruizhealy.com/articulos/notas_de_ventanas/el_manana.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 January 2002|newspaper=El Ma\u00f1ana: Reynosa|date=27 November 2009}}</ref> Arturo Basurto Pe\u00f1a, alias ''El Grande'', and [[Iv\u00e1n Vel\u00e1zquez-Caballero]] alias ''El Talib\u00e1n'' took control of [[Quintana Roo]] and [[Guerrero]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Revelan que desertor del Ej\u00e9rcito mexicano liderea C\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.elporvenir.com.mx/notas.asp?nota_id=191211|newspaper=El Porvenir|date=3 February 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406214727/http://www.elporvenir.com.mx/notas.asp?nota_id=191211|archivedate=6 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Alberto S\u00e1nchez Hinojosa, alias ''Comandante Castillo'', took over [[Tabasco]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Capturan al l\u00edder de los 'Zetas' en Tabasco|url=http://www.tabascohoy.com/noticia.php?id_nota=162045|newspaper=Tabasco Hoy|date=8 September 2008}}</ref> However, continual disagreement was leading the Gulf Cartel and Los Zetas into an inevitable rupture.\nOn 18 August 2013, Gulf Cartel leader Mario Ramirez Trevino was captured.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico Gulf Cartel leader Mario Ramirez Trevino captured|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-23744425|newspaper=BBC News|date=18 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n;United States vs Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n\nIn 2007, C\u00e1rdenas was extradited to the United States and charged with the involvement of conspiracies to traffic large amounts of marijuana and cocaine, violating the \"continuing-criminal-enterprise statute\" (also known as the \"drug kingpin statute\"), and for threatening two U.S. federal officers.<ref>{{cite web|title=United States of America v. Cardenas-Guillen|url=http://www.ca5.uscourts.gov/opinions/pub/10/10-40221-CV0.wpd.pdf|publisher=United States Court of Appeals for the Southern District of Texas|accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> The standoff the two agents had with the drug lord in 1999 in the city of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]] led for the U.S. to indict C\u00e1rdenas and pressure the Mexican government to capture him.<ref>{{cite news|title=DEA agent talks of 1999 Matamoros standoff with Osiel Cardenas-Guillen|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/houston-109730-matamoros-agent.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=15 March 2010}}</ref> In 2010 he was finally sentenced to 25 years in prison after being charged with 22 [[Federal crime in the United States|federal charges]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Extradition: Past cases highlight limits|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/former-123571-boss-past.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=5 March 2011}}</ref> the courtroom was locked and the public prevented from witnessing the proceeding.<ref>{{cite news|last=Langford|first=Terri|title=New U.S. attorney no stranger to Houston|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/New-U-S-attorney-no-stranger-to-Houston-2261216.php|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Houston Chronicle|date=9 November 2011}}</ref> The proceedings took place in the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Texas]] in the border city of [[Brownsville, Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Perez|first=Emma|title=Cardenas Guillen awaits trial|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/guillen-90235-cardenas-trial.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=23 September 2008}}</ref> C\u00e1rdenas has been isolated from interacting with other prisoners in the [[supermax|supermax prison]] he is in.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Mexican drug lords decry U.S. prison conditions|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Mexican-drug-lords-decry-U-S-prison-conditions-2195808.php|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Houston Chronicle|date=30 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nNearly $30 million of the former drug lord's assets were distributed among several Texan law enforcement agencies.<ref>{{cite news|title=Assets from drug boss go to Texas law enforcement|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Assets-from-drug-boss-go-to-Texas-law-enforcement-2584517.php|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Houston Chronicle|date=17 January 2012}}</ref> In exchange for another life-sentence, C\u00e1rdenas agreed to collaborate with U.S. agents in intelligence information.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Trafficking defendant: I was a DEA informer|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Trafficking-defendant-I-was-a-DEA-informer-1717657.php|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Houston Chronicle|date=4 August 2011}}</ref> The U.S. federal court awarded two [[helicopters]] owned by C\u00e1rdenas to the [[Business Development Bank of Canada]] and the GE Canada Equipment Financing respectively, and both of them were brought from \"drug proceeds\".<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. turns over custody of Cardenas-Guillen helicopters to businesses|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/helicopters-48551-cardenas-guillen.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110402045519/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/helicopters-48551-cardenas-guillen.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 April 2011|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Rupture from Los Zetas ===\nIt is unclear which of the two{{snd}}the Gulf Cartel or Los Zetas{{snd}}started the conflict that led to their break up. It is clear, however, that after the capture and extradition of [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], Los Zetas outclassed the Gulf Cartel in revenue, membership, and influence.<ref>{{cite web |first=Dana M. |last=Grimes |date=2010 |title=Law and Order in Mexico |url=http://www.grimesandwarwick.com/law_and_order |website=GrimesandWarwick |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111132042/http://www.grimesandwarwick.com/law_and_order |archive-date=11 January 2012}}</ref> Some sources reveal that as a result of the supremacy of [[Los Zetas]], the Gulf Cartel felt threatened by the growing force of their own enforcer group and decided to curtail their influence, but eventually failed in their attempt, instigating a war.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico's Cartels Declare War on the Zetas|url=http://www.geopoliticalmonitor.com/mexicos-cartels-declare-war-on-the-zetas-1/|newspaper=Geopolitical Monitor|date=19 April 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329054530/http://www.geopoliticalmonitor.com/mexicos-cartels-declare-war-on-the-zetas-1/|archivedate=29 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to ''narco-banners'' left by the Gulf Cartel in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], and [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]], the reason for their rupture was that Los Zetas had expanded their operations to include [[extortion]], [[kidnapping]], assassinations, theft, and other actions with which it disagreed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel split with Zetas made public|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/03/gulf-cartel-split-with-zetas-public.html|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=10 March 2010}}</ref> Unwilling to stand for such abuse, [[Los Zetas]] responded and countered the accusations by posting their own banners throughout [[Tamaulipas]]. They pointedly noted that they had carried out [[execution]]s and [[kidnapping]]s under orders of the Gulf Cartel when they served as their enforcers, and they were originally created by them for that sole purpose.<ref name=Narcobanners>{{cite news|title=Mexican cartels strategize to win hearts and minds|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/strategize-48350-win-cartels.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614103932/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/strategize-48350-win-cartels.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 June 2012|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=The Monitor}}</ref> In addition, Los Zetas mentioned that the Gulf Cartel also kills innocent civilians, and then blames them for their atrocities.<ref name=Narcobanners/>\n\nNevertheless, other sources also reveal that [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] (a.k.a. ''Tony Tormenta''), brother of Osiel and one of the successors of the Gulf Cartel, was addicted to gambling, sex, and drugs, leading [[Los Zetas]] to consider his leadership as a threat to the organization.<ref>{{cite news|title=Otro C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n hereda la organizaci\u00f3n|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/otrocardenasguillenheredalaorganizacion-585572.html|newspaper=Vanguardia|date=8 November 2010}}</ref> Other reports mention, however, that the rupture occurred due to a disagreement on who would take on the leadership of the cartel after the extradition of Osiel. The candidates of the Gulf Cartel were Antonio C\u00e1rdenas and [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]], while Los Zetas wanted the leadership of their current head, [[Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Authorities: Gulf Cartel, Zetas gang up on each other as arrangement dies|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/gulf-36258-arrangement-reynosa.html|newspaper=The Monitor|date=10 March 2010<!-- 12:55 PM-->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120912222804/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/gulf-36258-arrangement-reynosa.html|archivedate=12 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Other sources, however, mention that the Gulf Cartel began looking to form a truce with their [[Sinaloa Cartel]] rivals, and Los Zetas did not want to recognize the treaty settlement, which led them to act independently and eventually break apart.<ref>{{cite news|title=War between Gulf Cartel, Zetas marks year anniversary|url=http://www.valleymorningstar.com/articles/year-89095-war-agent.html|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald: Valley Morning Star|date=7 March 2011}}</ref> On the other hand, other sources reveal that [[Los Zetas]] separated from the Gulf Cartel to form an alliance with [[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel]], which led to conflict between them.<ref>{{cite web|last=Longmire|first=Sylvia|title=TCO 101: The Gulf Cartel|url=http://borderviolenceanalysis.typepad.com/mexicos_drug_war/dto-101-the-gulf-cartel.html|publisher=Mexico's drug war|accessdate=9 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025095641/http://borderviolenceanalysis.typepad.com/mexicos_drug_war/dto-101-the-gulf-cartel.html|archivedate=25 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Other sources mention that what initiated the conflict between them was when Samuel Flores Borrego, alias ''El Metro 3'', lieutenant of the Gulf Cartel, killed Sergio Pe\u00f1a Mendoza, alias ''El Concorde 3'', lieutenant of Los Zetas, due to a disagreement for the drug corridor of [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]], whom both protected.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ejecuci\u00f3n de \"El Concorde\" deton\u00f3 guerra en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/176125.html|newspaper=El Universal|date=7 March 2010}}</ref> Soon after his death, [[Los Zetas]] demanded for the Gulf Cartel to hand over the killer, but they didn't, and observers believe that triggered the war.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Gulf-Zeta Split and the Praetorian Revolt|url=http://www.isn.ethz.ch/isn/Current-Affairs/Security-Watch-Archive/Detail/?id=114551&lng=en|newspaper=ISN|date=7 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Tamaulipas]] was mostly spared from the violence until early 2010, when the Gulf Cartel's enforcers, [[Los Zetas]], split from and turned against the Gulf Cartel, sparking a bloody turf war. When the hostilities began, the Gulf organization joined forces with its former rivals, the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] and [[La Familia Michoacana]], aiming to take out Los Zetas.<ref>{{cite news|title=M\u00e9xico: Los Zetas rompen con el Cartel del Golfo|url=http://www.semana.com/america-latina/mexico-zetas-rompen-cartel-del-golfo/135516-3.aspx|newspaper=BBC Mundo {{!}} Semana.com|date=26 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hern\u00e1ndez|first=Jaime|title=EU: alarma guerra \"Zetas\"-El Golfo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/176052.html|newspaper=El Universal|date=4 March 2010}}</ref> Consequently, Los Zetas allied with the [[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]], the [[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel]], and the [[Tijuana Cartel]].<ref>{{cite news|title=El c\u00e1rtel de los Zetas tiende acuerdos de \"no agresi\u00f3n y colaboraci\u00f3n\"|url=http://america.infobae.com/notas/20350-El-cartel-de-los-Zetas-tiende-acuerdos-de-no-agresion-y-colaboracion|accessdate=14 December 2011|newspaper=Infobae|date=8 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530081447/http://america.infobae.com/notas/20350-El-cartel-de-los-Zetas-tiende-acuerdos-de-no-agresion-y-colaboracion|archivedate=30 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel lieutenant's associates enter plea agreement|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/gulf-57270-lieutenant-agreement.html|accessdate=14 December 2011|newspaper=The Monitor|date=13 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614104050/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/gulf-57270-lieutenant-agreement.html|archivedate=14 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n's era===\nOsiel C\u00e1rdenas' brother, [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] (''Tony Tormenta''), along with [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]] (''El Coss''), a former policeman, filled in the vacuum left by Osiel and became the leaders of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tiene nuevo lider del cartel del Golfo|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=114708&tabla=nacion|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419021504/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=114708&tabla=nacion|archivedate=19 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The death of ''Tony Tormenta'', the nickname given to Antonio C\u00e1rdenas for his explosive behavior,<ref>{{cite news|title=Los 'grandes capos' detenidos en la guerra contra el narcotr\u00e1fico de Calder\u00f3n|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/06/arturo-ezequiel-cardenas-guillen-tony-tormenta|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=6 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403041516/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/06/arturo-ezequiel-cardenas-guillen-tony-tormenta|archivedate=3 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> allowed for Costilla S\u00e1nchez to become the co-leader of the Gulf Cartel and head of the Metros, one of the two factions within the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ej\u00e9rcito, Armada y PF van tras El Coss, segundo heredero del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2010/11/09/politica/009n1pol|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=La Jornada}}</ref> [[Mario C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], brother of Osiel and Antonio, is the other leader of Gulf Cartel and head of the Rojos, the other faction within the Gulf Cartel and the parallel version of the Metros.<ref>{{cite news|title=Another Cardenas-Guillen inherits the organization|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/11/another-cardenas-guillen-inherits-gulf.html|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Se lanza la PGR por m\u00e1s l\u00edderes del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.oem.com.mx/elmexicano/notas/n1848385.htm|publisher=Organizaci\u00f3n Editorial Mexicana|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nCostilla was often viewed as the \"strongest leader\" of the two, but collaborated with Antonio C\u00e1rdenas, who acted as representative of his jailed brother.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"El Coss\", nuevo \"amo\" del grupo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/181707.html|accessdate=7 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal}}</ref> However, Antonio died in an eight-hour shooting with the Mexican government forces on 5 November 2010 in the border city of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tony Tormenta muere abatido|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/721541.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=El Universal}}</ref>  Government sources claimed that this operation\u2014where more than 660 marines, 17 vehicles, and 3 helicopters participated\u2014left 8 dead: three marines, one soldier, and four gunmen, including Antonio C\u00e1rdenas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Operativo contra Tony Tormenta dej\u00f3 8 muertos|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/721586.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=El Universal}}</ref> Other sources mention that one news reporter was also killed in the crossfire.<ref>{{cite news|last=G. Garc\u00eda|first=Jacobo|title=Tres militares, 'Tony Tormenta' y un periodista|url=http://www.elmundo.es/america/2010/11/07/mexico/1289084614.html|newspaper=El Mundo|date=11 July 2010}}</ref> This military-led operation was a result of more than six months of intelligence work and some operational actions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexican drug cartel leader 'Tony Tormenta' killed during two-hour gun battle with marines|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1327188/Mexican-drug-cartel-leader-Tony-Tormenta-killed-hour-gun-battle-marines.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=Dailymail {{!}} UK|date=8 November 2010}}</ref> ''[[Milenio Television]]'' mentioned that the Mexican authorities had tried to apprehend C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n twice before this incident, but that his personal gunmen had distracted the Mexican forces and allowed him to be escorted in his armored vehicle.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mosso|first=Ruben|title=Operativo de seis meses llev\u00f3 a abatimiento de Tony Tormenta: Secretar\u00eda de Marina|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/d9733f1d182257206a2cdeac4f1ff29c|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120908000658/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/d9733f1d182257206a2cdeac4f1ff29c|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 September 2012|accessdate=27 December 2011|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=7 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe confrontations started around 10:00AM, and extended to 06:00PM, around the time C\u00e1rdenas Guil\u00e9n was killed. The intense shootings provoked the temporary closure of three international bridges in Matamoros,<ref>{{cite news|title=Cae \"Tony Tormenta\", lider del cartel del Golfo|url=http://www.abc.es/20101106/internacional/tony-tormenta-201011060055.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=ABC Internacional}}</ref> along with the [[University of Texas at Brownsville]], just across the border.<ref>{{cite news|title=In aftermath, UTB-TSC works to protect students|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/utb-119098-temporarily-texas.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald}}</ref> Public transportation and school classes in Matamoros were canceled, along with the suspension of activities throughout the [[Matamoros Municipality, Tamaulipas|municipality]], since the cartel members hijacked the units of public transport and made dozens of roadblocks to prevent the mobilization of the soldiers, marines, and federal police forces.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ocho horas de balaceras, en Matamoros|url=http://www2.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/estados/224820/ocho-horas-balaceras-matamoros|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=Esmas Noticias}}</ref> The street confrontations generated a wave of panic among the population and caused the publication and broadcast of messages through social networks like [[Twitter]] and [[Facebook]], reporting the clashes between authorities and the cartel members.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reputed Gulf cartel leader killed in Mexico shootout|url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/newupdated/ci_16536005|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=El Paso Times|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120729140838/http://www.elpasotimes.com/newupdated/ci_16536005|archivedate=29 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> When the Mexican authorities reached the spot where Antonio C\u00e1rdenas (''Tony Tormenta'') was present, the gunmen received the soldiers and cops with grenades and high-calibre shots. Reports mention that Antonio C\u00e1rdenas was being protected by the Los Escorpiones (''The Scorpions''), the alleged armed wing of the Gulf Cartel and the personal army of Antonio C\u00e1rdenas, who were serving as [[snipers]] and [[bodyguards]] for him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Secretar\u00eda de Marina, detenciones en tierra|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/23/antonio-ezequiel-cardenas-guillen-tony-tormenta|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=23 November 2010}}</ref> ''[[La Jornada]]'' newspaper mentioned that over 80 SUV's packed with gunmen fought to protect C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n, and over 300 grenades were used in the shootout that day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Detonaron m\u00e1s de 300 granadas en el operativo contra Tony Tormenta|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2010/11/08/opinion/005n1pol|accessdate=27 December 2011|newspaper=La Jornada|date=8 November 2010}}</ref> And even after the drug lord was killed, the roadblocks continued throughout the rest of the day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Muere Tony Tormenta luego de ocho horas de tiroteos con efectivos federales en Matamoros|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2010/11/06/politica/007n1pol|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=La Jornada}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper mentioned that in a [[YouTube]] video, a convoy of SUV's filled with gunmen and pickups packed with marines were seen in a chase through the streets of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]]. And although there wasn't any visible confrontation between the two, the intensity of the situation was clear through the background noises of grenades explosions and automatic gunfire.<ref>{{cite news|title=Top Mexican drugs lord killed in fierce gunbattle with military|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/nov/07/mexico-drugs-gulf-cartel-antonio-guillen|accessdate=9 December 2011|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Jo|last=Tuckman|date=7 November 2010}}</ref> A news video from [[Televisa]], also on [[YouTube]], shows images from the confrontations of that day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Muere Antonio Cardenas Guillen, alias \"Tony Tormenta,\" lider del cartel del Golfo|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p8B7SZTvugU|accessdate=9 December 2011|newspaper=Televisa}}</ref> Moreover, several bystanders also recorded the shootouts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Video in\u00e9dito del la muerte de Cardenas Guillen, \"Tony Tormenta\"|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0vFhROX88ik|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mexico Border War&nbsp;\u2013 Live Battle! Unbelievable!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nX2gtblTeqI|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Balacera Matamoros: Convoy de Marinos|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R9MN_MIHkLw|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, according to the newspapers ''[[The Brownsville Herald]]'' and ''[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]'' from across the border in [[Brownsville, Texas]] and [[McAllen, Texas]], around 50 people were killed in the gunfights.<ref>{{cite news|title=En una balacera, muere \"Tony Tormenta\"|url=http://america.infobae.com/notas/13214-En-una-balacera-muere-Tony-Tormenta|newspaper=EFE, Milenio, Reforma, La Jornada|date=11 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326141939/http://america.infobae.com/notas/13214-En-una-balacera-muere-Tony-Tormenta|archivedate=26 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dozens killed in Matamoros; Tony Tormenta dead|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/11/dozens-killed-in-matamoros-bridges.html|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=5 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Head of Gulf Cartel killed|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/confirmed-119010-mexican-ezequiel.html|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=5 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dozens killed in Matamoros; bridges closed|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/killed-118999-friday-matamoros.html|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Head of Gulf Cartel killed in Matamoros shootout|url=http://www.enctoday.com/articles/killed-44249-monitortx-matamoros-shootout.html|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=The Monitor|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421170755/http://www.enctoday.com/articles/killed-44249-monitortx-matamoros-shootout.html|archivedate=21 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Although not confirmed, ''[[KVEO-TV]]'', several online sources and witnesses, along with one law enforcement officer who preferred to keep his name anonymous, mentioned that more than 100 people died that day in Matamoros.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shootings in Matamoros Kill \"Tony Tormenta\" and Nearly 100 People|url=http://www.kveo.com/news/shootings-in-matamoros-kill-tony-tormenta-and-nearly-100-people|newspaper=KVEO News Center|date=8 November 2010|access-date=9 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321054220/http://www.kveo.com/news/shootings-in-matamoros-kill-tony-tormenta-and-nearly-100-people|archive-date=21 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Los Zetas tienen el plato servido tras muerte de 'Tony Tormenta': Expertos|url=http://www.elnuevoheraldo.com/articles/muerte-46134-plato-servido.html|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=El Nuevo Heraldo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424172940/http://www.elnuevoheraldo.com/articles/muerte-46134-plato-servido.html|archivedate=24 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Johnston|first=Robert|title=Data on Mexican drug war violence|url=http://www.johnstonsarchive.net/terrorism/mexicodrugwar.html|publisher=Terrorism, Counterterrorism, and Unconventional Warfare|accessdate=29 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Carnage along border continues|url=http://www.valleymorningstar.com/news/saturday-83458-border-herald.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel leader killed, 55 others in Matamoros, Mexico|url=http://www.newstaco.com/2010/11/08/gulf-cartel-leader-killed-47-others-in-matamoros-mexico/|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=News Taco: The Latino Daily}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Death toll mounts in Matamoros shootout as sporadic fighting continues|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/matamoros-44259-death-fighting.html|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=The Monitor|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614103943/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/matamoros-44259-death-fighting.html|archivedate=14 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Deibert|first=Michael|title=Cartel Wars|url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/mexicos_cartel_wars_20110516/|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=Truthdig, L.L.C|date=16 May 2011}}</ref> The death of Antonio C\u00e1rdenas (''Tony Tormenta'') also caused a spiral of violence in [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]] a number of days after he was killed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Narcobloqueos y Balaceras en Tamaulipas tras muerte de 'Tony Tormenta'.|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BdMgkY4oAuY|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=Milenio TV}}</ref> Moreover, his death also generated a turf war with [[Los Zetas]] in the city of [[Ciudad Mier, Tamaulipas]], resulting in the exodus of more than 95% of its population.<ref>{{cite news|title=600 militares llegan a Mier, una ciudad abandonada por sus habitantes|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/12/09/600-militares-llegan-a-mier-una-ciudad-abandonada-por-sus-habitantes|accessdate=11 December 2011|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=9 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905051127/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/12/09/600-militares-llegan-a-mier-una-ciudad-abandonada-por-sus-habitantes|archivedate=5 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Banners written by [[Los Zetas]], the Gulf Cartel's former armed wing, appeared all across [[Mexico]], celebrating the death of C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n.<ref>{{cite news|title=Zozobra en Tamaulipas luego de ca\u00edda del l\u00edder del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2010/11/07/politica/005n1pol|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=La Jornada}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Zetas celebran caida de \"Tony Tormenta\" con narcomantas y narcopintas|url=http://www.lapoliciaca.com/nota-roja/zetas-celebran-caida-de-tony-tormenta-con-narcomantas-y-narcopintas/|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=La Policiaca}}</ref> The [[United States]] president, [[Barack Obama]], called the president of Mexico, [[Felipe Calder\u00f3n]], congratulating him and the Mexican forces for the operation in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]], and reiterated his effort against organized crime.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barack Obama expresa su apoyo a Calder\u00f3n por la muerte de 'Tony Tormenta'|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/06/barack-obama-expresa-su-apoyo-a-calderon-por-la-muerte-de-tony-tormenta|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=6 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120906013944/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/06/barack-obama-expresa-su-apoyo-a-calderon-por-la-muerte-de-tony-tormenta|archivedate=6 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter this incident, there was a huge division of opinions over the fate of the Gulf Cartel. Some experts believed that the death of [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n|Ezekiel]] would be dreadful for the Gulf Cartel, and that [[Los Zetas]] would overthrow them and eventually take control of [[Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Cattan|first=Nacha|title=Killing of top Mexico drug lord 'Tony Tormenta' may boost rival Zetas cartel|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Americas/2010/1107/Killing-of-top-Mexico-drug-lord-Tony-Tormenta-may-boost-rival-Zetas-cartel|newspaper=CSMonitor|date=7 November 2010}}</ref> Others explained how his death allowed [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez|Costilla S\u00e1nchez]] to take full directive of the cartel, and that would tighten relations with [[Colombia]] and straighten the Gulf Cartel's path, something quite difficult with [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n|Ezekiel]] as co-leader.<ref>{{cite web|last=Longmire|first=Sylvia|title=Authorities Say Cartel Leader's Death Won't Curb Violence.|url=http://borderviolenceanalysis.typepad.com/mexicos_drug_war/2010/11/authorities-say-cartel-leaders-death-wont-curb-violence.html|work=Mexico's Drug War|accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n====Los Escorpiones====\nLos Escorpiones, also called Grupo Escorpios,<ref>{{cite news|title=Los Escorpiones, temible escolta de Tormenta|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/losescorpionestemibleescoltadetormenta-584523.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=Vanguardia}}</ref> (''The Scorpions''), was believed to be the mercenary group that protected [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], the former leader of the organization.<ref>{{cite news|title=Matamoros braces for more violence|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/matamoros-44355-braces-violence.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=The Monitor|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405095633/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/matamoros-44355-braces-violence.html|archivedate=5 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to reports by the Mexican government, Los Escorpiones was created by Antonio C\u00e1rdenas (''Tony Tormenta'') and is composed of over 60 civilians, former police officers, and ex-military officials. According to ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]'', there are several music videos on [[YouTube]] that exalt the power of this armed group through ''[[narcocorridos]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Los Escorpiones, temible escolta de Tormenta|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/721570.html|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=5 November 2010}}</ref> After the rupture between the Gulf Cartel and [[Los Zetas]] (which until then had served as the cartel's armed wing), Los Escorpiones became the armed wing of the entire Gulf organization.<ref>{{cite news|title=Identifican a nuevo grupo armado del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo que proteg\u00eda a Tony Tormenta|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/identificananuevogrupoarmadodelcarteldelgolfoqueprotegiaatonytormenta-585439.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=Vanguardia}}</ref> The first mention of Los Escorpiones on the media was in 2008, when ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]'' wrote an article about some \"protected witnesses\" from the Gulf Cartel who denounced the alliance between the [[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel]] and [[Los Zetas]] to the Mexican authorities, and that the Gulf Cartel had created Los Escorpiones to stop and balance the growing hegemony of Los Zetas.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gomez|first=Francisco|title=\"Los Zetas\" por dentro|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/164819.html|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=31 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nHowever, his brother [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] disapproved the existence of this mercenary group, since he had created [[Los Zetas]], the parallel version of Los Escorpiones, and they had turned against the organization.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tony Tormenta, el capo que 'cuidaba' las fronteras de Tamaulipas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/05/tony-tormenta-el-capo-que-cuidaba-las-fronteras-de-tamaulipas|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=5 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130303023518/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/05/tony-tormenta-el-capo-que-cuidaba-las-fronteras-de-tamaulipas|archivedate=3 March 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]'' reported that Mexican authorities identified the gunmen that where engaging in confrontations against the troops in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]] as members of the Los Escorpiones group. Along with [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], the following members of Los Escorpiones were killed: Sergio Antonio Fuentes, alias ''El Tyson'' or ''Escorpi\u00f3n 1''; Ra\u00fal Marmolejo G\u00f3mez, alias ''Escorpi\u00f3n 18''; Hugo Lira, alias ''Escorpi\u00f3n 26''; and Refugio Adalberto Vargas Cort\u00e9s, alias ''Escorpi\u00f3n 42''.<ref>{{cite news|title=New details released about Gulf Cartel leader's death|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=537299#.TtVcknNFHFg|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=Action 4 News}}</ref> The arrests of Marco Antonio Cortez Rodr\u00edguez alias ''Escorpi\u00f3n 37'' and of Josu\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez Rodr\u00edguez alias ''Escorpi\u00f3n 43''\u2014the two who were hospitalized after the shootout of 5 November 2010\u2014allowed for the Mexican forces to understand the structure of Los Escorpiones.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tony Tormenta escap\u00f3 en 2 ocasiones: Marina|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8861695|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=8 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Present-day==\n\n===Metros and Rojos infighting===\n{{Main|Infighting in the Gulf Cartel}}\nIn the late 1990s, [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], the former leader of the Gulf cartel, had other similar groups besides [[Los Zetas]] established in several cities in Tamaulipas.<ref name=mrl>{{cite news|title=Internal struggle in the Gulf Cartel could weaken the organization|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/struggle-56156-internal-cartel.html|accessdate=9 August 2012|newspaper=[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]|date=29 October 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816073550/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/struggle-56156-internal-cartel.html|archivedate=16 August 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Each of these groups were identified by their radio codes: ''the Rojos'' (The Red ones) were based in [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas|Reynosa]]; ''the Metros'' were headquartered in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]]; and ''the Lobos'' (The wolves) were established in [[Nuevo Laredo|Laredo]].<ref name=mrl/> The infighting between the Metros and the Rojos of the Gulf cartel began in 2010, when [[Juan Mej\u00eda Gonz\u00e1lez]], nicknamed ''El R-1'', was overlooked as the candidate of the regional boss of Reynosa and was sent to the \"Frontera Chica,\" an area that encompasses [[Ciudad Miguel Alem\u00e1n, Tamaulipas|Miguel Alem\u00e1n]], [[Camargo, Tamaulipas|Camargo]] and [[Ciudad Mier, Tamaulipas|Ciudad Mier]]&nbsp;\u2013 directly across the U.S.\u2013Mexico border from [[Starr County, Texas]]. The area that Mej\u00eda Gonz\u00e1lez wanted was given to [[Samuel Flores Borrego]], suggesting that the Metros were above the Rojos.<ref name=mrl/>\n\n[[File:Flores-Borrego.jpg|120px|thumb|left|[[Samuel Flores Borrego]], former Gulf Cartel high-ranking member.]]\nUnconfirmed information released by ''[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]'' indicated that two leaders of the Rojos, Mej\u00eda Gonz\u00e1lez and [[Rafael C\u00e1rdenas Vela]], teamed up to kill Flores Borrego.<ref name=mrl/> C\u00e1rdenas Vela had held a grudge on Flores Borrego and the Metros because he believed that they had led the Mexican military to track down and kill his uncle [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] (''Tony Tormenta'') on 5 November 2010.<ref name=mrl/><ref name=betrayal>{{cite news|title=Major Arrests Expected to Shake Up Gulf Cartel|url=http://www.krgv.com/news/major-arrests-expected-to-shake-up-gulf-cartel/|accessdate=10 August 2012|newspaper=[[KRGV-TV]]|date=13 December 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130127091503/http://www.krgv.com/news/major-arrests-expected-to-shake-up-gulf-cartel/|archivedate=27 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Other sources indicate that the infighting could have been caused by the suspicions that the Rojos were \"too soft\" on the Gulf cartel's bitter enemy, [[Los Zetas]].<ref name=rojossoft>{{cite news|last=Pachico|first=Elyssa|title=Death of Gulf Cartel 'Finance Chief' Sign of Internal Strife?|url=http://www.insightcrime.org/component/k2/item/1699-death-of-gulf-cartel-finance-chief-sign-of-internal-strife|accessdate=9 August 2012|newspaper=[[InSight Crime]]|date=11 October 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120809223008/http://www.insightcrime.org/component/k2/item/1699-death-of-gulf-cartel-finance-chief-sign-of-internal-strife|archivedate=9 August 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> When the Gulf cartel and Los Zetas split in early 2010, some members of the Rojos stayed with the Gulf cartel, while others decided to leave and join the forces of Los Zetas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico: Gulf Cartel lieutenant, his right-hand man captured|url=http://www.themonitor.com/news/gulf-54262-hand-right.html|accessdate=9 August 2012|newspaper=[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]|date=30 August 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120809223928/http://www.themonitor.com/news/gulf-54262-hand-right.html|archivedate=9 August 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[InSight Crime]] explains that the fundamental disagreement between the Rojos and the Metros was over leadership. Those who were more loyal to the C\u00e1rdenas family stayed with the Rojos, while those loyal to [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]], like Flores Borrego, defended the Metros.<ref name=rojossoft/>\n\nOriginally, the Gulf cartel was running smoothly, but the infighting between the two factions in the Gulf cartel triggered when Flores Borrego was killed on 2 September 2011.<ref name=mrl/> When the Rojos turned on the Metros, the largest faction in the Gulf cartel, firefights broke throughout Tamaulipas and drug loads were stolen among each other, but the Metros managed to retain control of the major cities that stretched from [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]] to [[Ciudad Miguel Alem\u00e1n, Tamaulipas|Miguel Alem\u00e1n, Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel lieutenant linked to various incidents on U.S side of border|url=http://www.themonitor.com/news/mcallen-57691-cartel-side.html|accessdate=10 August 2012|newspaper=[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]|date=2 January 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120818085345/http://www.themonitor.com/news/mcallen-57691-cartel-side.html|archivedate=18 August 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSome experts have found it difficult to argue that the Gulf Cartel does not impose a direct threat to the [[State (polity)|state]], since they \"do not seek political change,\" and that they only want to be left alone with their [[drug trafficking|business]]. Observations indicate that the Gulf Cartel actually controls territories and imposes its own rules\u2014often violent and bloody\u2014over the population. And in doing so, they inherently become a \"competitor\" with the state, who also claims sovereignty over its territories.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brophy|first=Stephanie|title=Mexico: Cartels, Corruption and Cocaine: A Profile of the Gulf Cartel|journal=Global Crime|date=August 2008|volume=9|issue=3|pages=248\u2013261|doi=10.1080/17440570802254353}}</ref> Like other drug trafficking organizations, the Gulf Cartel also subverts government institutions, particularly at [[Tamaulipas|state]] and local levels, by using their large profits to [[bribery|bribe]] officials.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ford|first=Jess T.|title=U.S. Assistance Has Helped Mexican Counternarcotics Efforts, but the Flow of Illicit Drugs into the United States Remains High|journal=[[Government Accountability Office]]|date=25 October 2007|pages=27|url=http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d08215t.pdf|accessdate=12 August 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712144545/http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d08215t.pdf|archivedate=12 July 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Presence in the U.S.===\nThe Gulf Cartel has important cells operating inside the United States\u2014in [[Mission, Texas|Mission]], [[Roma, Texas|Roma]], and [[Rio Grande City, Texas|Rio Grande City]]\u2014for example, and their presence is expanding.<ref>{{cite book|last=Adler|first=Patricia A.|title=Drugs and the American Dream: An Anthology|year=2012|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|isbn=978-0-470-67027-9|pages=456|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_s_9tfNlfGkC&pg=PA300&dq=gulf+cartel#v=onepage&q=gulf%20cartel&f=false}}</ref> [[Thomas A. Shannon, Jr.|Thomas A. Shannon]], a U.S. diplomat and ambassador, stated that criminal organizations like the Gulf Cartel have \"substantially weakened\" the institutions in Mexico and [[Central America]], and have generated a surge of violence in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Testimony of Thomas A. Shannon| url=http://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/ShannonTestimony071115p.pdf|publisher=United States Senate| accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref> The U.S. National Drug Threat Assessment mentioned that the drug trafficking organizations like the Gulf Cartel tend to be less structured in U.S. than in Mexico, and often rely on street gangs to operate inside the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=DTOs Have Expanded Operations in the United States|url=http://www.gao.gov/htext/d071018.html|publisher=U.S. Government Accountability Office|accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref> The arrest of several Gulf Cartel lieutenants, along with the drug-related violence and [[kidnapping]]s, have raised concerns among Texas officials that the drug war in Mexico and the drug cartels are taking hold in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Arrests of Mexican drug cartel leaders in Texas raise concerns|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/45156204/ns/us_news/t/arrests-mexican-drug-cartel-leaders-texas-raise-concerns/#.TwJ_MSO3CFc|accessdate=3 January 2012|newspaper=MSN BC News|date=3 November 2011}}{{dead link|date=November 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The strong ties the Gulf Cartel has with the prison gangs in the United States have also raised concern to American officials.<ref>{{cite news|last=Buch|first=Jason|title=Cartels cooperate with prison gangs|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Cartels-cooperate-with-prison-gangs-2436265.php|accessdate=3 January 2012|newspaper=The Houston Chronicle|date=1 January 2012}}</ref> Reports mention that Mexican drug cartels operate in more than 1,000 cities in the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Morasch|first=Charlie|title=FBI: Trucking 'significant' in cartels' U.S. profitability|url=http://www.landlinemag.com/todays_news/Daily/2011/Dec11/120511/120611-03.shtml|accessdate=3 January 2012|newspaper=Landline|date=6 December 2011}}</ref> In 2013, high ranking Gulf Cartel member Aurelio Cano Flores became the highest cartel member to be convicted by a U.S. jury in 15 years<Ref>https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/high-ranking-gulf-cartel-member-sentenced-washington-dc-35-years-prison-drug-trafficking</ref> In January 2020, high-ranking U.S. Gulf Cartel member Jorge Costilla-Sanchez pleaded guilty to an international drug trafficking conspiracy to distribute cocaine and marijuana into the United States.<ref>https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/former-gulf-cartel-leader-convicted-international-drug-trafficking-conspiracy</ref>\n\n===Presence in Europe===\nThe Gulf Cartel is believed to have ties with the [['Ndrangheta]], an organized crime group in [[Italy]] that also has ties with [[Los Zetas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cartel Inc: In the company of Narcos|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/01/14/us-drugs-mexico-business-idUSTRE60D4XS20100114|accessdate=3 January 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=14 January 2010}}</ref> Reports indicated that the Gulf Cartel was using the [[BlackBerry]] smartphones to communicate with 'Ndrangheta, since the texts are \"normally difficult to intercept\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Narco-mafia se comunican por Blackberry|url=http://www.cnnexpansion.com/actualidad/2009/02/19/mafia-italiana-en-contacto-con-narcos|accessdate=20 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Expansion|date=19 February 2009}}</ref> In 2009, the Gulf organization concluded that expanding their market opportunities in [[Europe]], combined with the euro strength against the U.S. dollar, justified establishing an extensive network in that continent. The main areas of demand and drug consumption are in Eastern Europe, the successor states of the [[Soviet Union]]. In Western Europe, the primarily increase has been in the use of cocaine.<ref>{{cite news|last=Carpenter|first=Ted Galen|title=Undermining Mexico's Dangerous Drug Cartels|url=http://www.cato.org/pubs/pas/PA688.pdf|accessdate=3 January 2012|newspaper=Policy Analysis|date=15 November 2011}}</ref> Along with the market in the United States, the drug market in [[Europe]] is among the most lucrative in the world, where the Mexican drug cartels are believed to have deals with the mafia groups of Europe.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ortiz|first=Carlos|title=Private armed forces and global security: a guide to the issues|year=2010|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-35592-9|pages=250|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Ui5-NOXAvtwC&pg=PA74&lpg=PA74&dq=eastern+europe+gulf+cartel#v=onepage&q=eastern%20europe%20gulf%20cartel&f=false}}</ref>\n\n===Presence in Africa===\nThe Gulf Cartel and other Mexican drug trafficking groups are active in the northern and western parts of [[Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mexican Cartels Exploit North Africa Turmoil|url=http://insightcrime.org/insight-latest-news/item/731-mexican-cartels-exploit-north-africa-turmoil|publisher=Insight Crime|accessdate=3 January 2012|date=April 2011}}</ref> Although cocaine is not grown in Africa, Mexican organizations, such as the Gulf Cartel, are currently exploiting West Africa's struggling rule-of-law caused by war, crime and poverty, in order to stage and expand supply routes to the increasingly lucrative European illegal drug market.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brice|first=Arthur|title=Latin American drug cartels find home in West Africa|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2009-09-21/world/africa.drug.cartels_1_drug-cartels-european-market-cocaine?_s=PM:WORLD|accessdate=3 January 2012|newspaper=CNN|date=21 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811040726/http://articles.cnn.com/2009-09-21/world/africa.drug.cartels_1_drug-cartels-european-market-cocaine?_s=PM:WORLD|archive-date=11 August 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cocaine trafficking in Western Africa|url=http://www.unodc.org/documents/data-and-analysis/Cocaine-trafficking-Africa-en.pdf|publisher=United Nations: Office on Drugs and Crime|accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Gulf Cartel vs. Los Zetas===\nThe rumors of the broken alliance between the Gulf Cartel and [[Los Zetas]] began on blogs and mass emails in September 2009, but it remained pretty much the same throughout that year\u2014a rumor. But on 24 February 2010, hundreds of trucks marked with ''C.D.G'', ''XXX'', and ''M3'' (the insignias of the Gulf Cartel) began to hit the streets of northern [[Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel vs. Los Zetas... One year later|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2011/02/cdg-vs-zetas-one-year-later.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=26 February 2011}}</ref> The clash between these two groups first happened in [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]], and then expanded to [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas|Nuevo Laredo]] and [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Penhaul|first=Kent|title=La ley del silencio en Reynosa s\u00f3lo la rompe... Twitter|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/06/21/la-ley-del-silencio-en-reynosa-solo-la-rompe-twitter|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=21 June 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129120041/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/06/21/la-ley-del-silencio-en-reynosa-solo-la-rompe-twitter|archivedate=29 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The war then spread out through 11 municipalities of [[Tamaulipas]], 9 of them bordering the state of [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=La guerra Golfo-zetas, en 11 municipios tamaulipecos; nueve son fronterizos con EU|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2010/11/12/politica/007n1pol|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=La Jornada|date=12 November 2010}}</ref> Soon, the violence generated between these two groups had spread to Tamaulipas' neighboring states of [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]] and [[Veracruz]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Los Zetas y el c\u00e1rtel del Golfo se pelean por Monterrey|url=http://noticias.univision.com/narcotrafico/reportajes/slideshow/2011-07-11/los-zetas-cartel-del-golfo-pelean-monterrey|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=Univision}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=La batalla del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo y \"Los Zetas\" por la Huasteca|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=293299|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=Proceso|date=31 December 2011}}</ref> Their conflict has even occurred on U.S. soil, where the Gulf Cartel killed two Zeta members in [[Brownsville, Texas]] on 5 October 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two Zetas executed in Brownsville, Texas|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/10/two-zetas-executed-in-brownsville-texas.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=25 October 2010}}</ref> In the midsts of violence and panic, local authorities and the media tried to minimize the situation and claim that \"nothing was occurring\", but the facts were impossible to cover up.<ref>{{cite news|title=La guerra del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo y Los Zetas, ma\u00f1ana 24 de febrero se cumple un a\u00f1o|url=http://www.mundonarco.org/2011/02/la-guerra-de-el-cartel-del-golfo-y-los.html?zx=862b69e2d65cce53|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216183527/http://www.mundonarco.org/2011/02/la-guerra-de-el-cartel-del-golfo-y-los.html?zx=862b69e2d65cce53|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 December 2013|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=Mundo Narco|date=23 February 2011}}</ref> Confrontations between these two groups have paralyzed entire cities in broad daylight.<ref>{{cite news|title=Enfrentamientos entre el c\u00e1rtel del Golfo y Los Zetas paralizaron Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2011/05/20/politica/013n1pol|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=La Jornada|date=20 May 2011}}</ref> Several witnesses claimed that many of the municipalities throughout Tamaulipas were \"war zones\", and that many businesses and houses were burned down, leaving areas in \"total destruction\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The Missing in Tamaulipas|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/04/missing-in-tamaulipas.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=26 April 2010}}</ref> The bloodbath in Tamaulipas has caused thousands of deaths, but most of shootings and body counts often go unreported.<ref>{{cite news|title=All Tamaulipas, a War Zone|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/04/all-tamaulipas-war-zone.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=22 April 2010}}</ref> The complexity and territorial advantage of [[Los Zetas]] forced the Gulf Cartel to seek for an alliance with the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] and [[La Familia Michoacana]]; in addition, [[Stratfor]] mentioned that these three organizations also united because they hold a \"profound hate\" for Los Zetas.<ref>{{cite news|title=DEA: acuerdan 3 c\u00e1rteles alianza contra Los Zetas|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8729891|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=5 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114015453/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8729891|archivedate=14 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Consequently, Los Zetas joined forces with the [[Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Cartel]] and the [[Tijuana Cartel]] to counterattack the opposing cartels.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sicarios de los Beltr\u00e1n Leyva y Zetas atacan a gente del Chapo en Sonora|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/7c954b2a681dd8c89db2c26caf9ab0a9|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=2 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120905172137/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/7c954b2a681dd8c89db2c26caf9ab0a9|archivedate=5 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 November 2014, a document from the Mexican government was released to the media and claimed that Los Rojos faction of the Gulf Cartel was planning to form an alliance with Los Zetas. The potential alliance was conducted by [[Juan Reyes Mej\u00eda Gonz\u00e1lez]] (alias \"R1\"), from the Gulf Cartel; and [[Rogelio Gonz\u00e1lez Piza\u00f1a]] (alias \"Z-2\"), from Los Zetas. The latter was released from prison months earlier even though he was scheduled to serve 16-years behind bars in January. Authorities believe that Gonz\u00e1lez Piza\u00f1a reincorporated in organized crime and decided to join with the Gulf Cartel to end the war with Los Zetas, and bring back the \"old school\" ways when they were together.<ref>{{cite news|title=Facciones del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo y Los Zetas buscan aliarse para poner fin a agresiones contra la poblaci\u00f3n|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=387306|accessdate=11 November 2014|publisher=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|date=11 November 2014|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==Tamaulipas: State corruption==\n\n===Political corruption===\nThe drug violence and political corruption that has plagued [[Tamaulipas]], the homestate of the Gulf Cartel and Los Zetas, has fueled thoughts of Tamaulipas becoming a \"failed state\" and a haven for drug traffickers and criminals of all kinds.<ref>{{cite news|last=N\u00e1jar|first=Alberto|title=Tamaulipas, \u00bfen camino de convertirse en un estado fallido?|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mundo/noticias/2011/04/110413_mexico_tamaulipas_estado_fallido_an.shtml|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=BBC Mundo|date=13 April 2011}}</ref> The massacre of the [[2010 San Fernando massacre|72 migrants]] and the clandestine [[2011 San Fernando massacre|mass graves]] with more than 250 bodies in [[San Fernando, Tamaulipas]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Migrantes, 72 muertos de fosa en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/704017.html|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|date=25 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=S\u00e1nchez L\u00f3pez|first=Daniel|title=Sin resolver origen de narcofosas en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.sexenio.com.mx/articulo.php?id=3814|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=Sexenio|date=9 April 2011}}</ref> mounted with the assassination of the state candidate [[Rodolfo Torre Cant\u00fa]] (2010),<ref>{{cite news|title=Asesinan a Rodolfo Torre Cant\u00fa, candidato al gobierno de Tamaulipas|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/7c954b2a681dd8c89db2c26caf6dabe3|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=28 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013055401/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/7c954b2a681dd8c89db2c26caf6dabe3|archivedate=13 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the increasing violence generated between drug groups, and the state's inability to ensure tranquility, has led specialists to conclude that \"neither the regional nor federal government have control over the territory of Tamaulipas.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Miglierini|first=Julian|title=Tamaulipas: 'Failed state' in Mexico's war on drugs|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-13061452|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=BBC News, Mexico City|date=13 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:RodolfoTorreCantu-PRI.jpg|left|140px|thumb|[[Rodolfo Torre Cant\u00fa]], politician killed in Tamaulipas.]] -->\nAlthough drug-related violence has existed since the early beginnings of the Gulf Cartel, it often happened in low-profile levels, while the government agreed to \"look the other way\" while the drug traffickers went about their business\u2014as long as they behaved.<ref>{{cite web|last=Longmire|first=Sylvia|title=Mexico's PRI Names Presidential Candidate.|url=http://borderviolenceanalysis.typepad.com/mexicos_drug_war/2011/12/mexicos-pri-names-presidential-candidate.html|publisher=Mexico's Drug War|accessdate=28 December 2011}}</ref> Back in the days of the 71-year rule of the [[Institutional Revolutionary Party]] (PRI), it was believed that they ran exactly that show: if the drug cartels got off the line, the Mexican government would conduct some arrests, make some disappearances, and the drug lords would get their people straight and back on the line again.<ref>{{cite book|last=Andreas|first=Peter|title=The Political Economy of Narco-Corruption in Mexico|date=April 1998|publisher=Brown University|url=http://www.brown.edu/Departments/Political_Science/people/documents/ThePoliticalEconomyofNarco-CorruptioninMexico.pdf}}</ref>  After the PRI lost the presidency in 2000 to the [[National Action Party (Mexico)|National Action Party]] (PAN), the arrangement between the government and the cartels was lost, as well the ''pax mafiosa''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico's drug war: A pax narcotica?|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/americasview/2011/01/mexicos_drug_wars|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=The Economist|date=7 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Klepak|first=Hal|title=Mexico: Current and Future Political, Economic and Security Trends|journal=Canadian Defence & Foreign Affairs Institute|date=August 2010|url=http://www.cdfai.org/PDF/Mexico%20-%20Current%20and%20Future%20Political%20Economic%20and%20Security%20Trends.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426074349/http://www.cdfai.org/PDF/Mexico%20-%20Current%20and%20Future%20Political%20Economic%20and%20Security%20Trends.pdf|archivedate=26 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Moreover, the state of [[Tamaulipas]] was no exception; according to [[Santiago Creel]], a PAN politician and pre-candidate for the 2012 presidency, the PRI in Tamaulipas has protected the Gulf Cartel for years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hay pruebas sobre nexos de priistas con narco: PAN|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=55220&tabla=estados|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|date=21 October 2004|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419021612/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=55220&tabla=estados|archivedate=19 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Narcopol\u00edtica en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/178728.html|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|date=29 June 2010}}</ref> In addition, ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]'' newspaper mentions that the narco-corruption in Tamaulipas is due to the fact the opposing political parties, the PAN and the [[Party of the Democratic Revolution]] (PRD), rarely win an election and \"practically do not exist\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Alem\u00e1n|first=Ricardo|title=Tamaulipas; PRI y narco|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/columnas/81779.html|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|date=12 January 2010}}</ref> PRI's main opposition party, the [[National Action Party (Mexico)|PAN]], claimed that government elections in [[Tamaulipas]] are likely to encounter an \"organized crime influence.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Salas|first=Alejandro|title=Blindaje contra narcopol\u00edticos en Tamaulipas|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8713347|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120716190610/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8713347|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-07-16|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=February 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]'' newspaper reported that the former governors of [[Tamaulipas]], [[Manuel Cavazos Lerma]] (1993\u20131999), [[Tom\u00e1s Yarrington]] (1999\u20132004), and [[Eugenio Hern\u00e1ndez Flores]] (2005\u20132010) have had close ties with the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moreno|first=Mart\u00edn|title=Tamaulipas: gobierno fallido|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&id_nota=718789|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=Exc\u00e9lsior|date=10 April 2011}}</ref> On 30 January 2012, the [[Attorney General of Mexico]] issued a communiqu\u00e9 ordering the past three governors of [[Tamaulipas]] and their families to remain in the country as they are being investigated for possible correlation with the Mexican drug cartels.<ref>{{cite news|title=Busca PGR contra 3 ex gobernadores de Tamaulipas|url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/703223.busca-pgr-contra-3-ex-gobernadores-de-tamaulipas.html|accessdate=31 January 2012|newspaper=El Siglo de Torreon|date=30 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PGR emiti\u00f3 alerta migratoria contra tres ex gobernadores de Tamaulipas|url=http://noticias.univision.com/mexico/noticias/article/2012-01-30/pgr-alerta-tres-ex-gobernadores-tamaulipas#axzz1l0fmTS00|accessdate=31 January 2012|newspaper=Univision|date=30 January 2012}}</ref> The municipal president of [[Tampico, Tamaulipas]], \u00d3scar P\u00e9rez Inguanzo, was arrested 12 November 2011 due to his \"improper exercise of public functions and forgery\" of certain documents.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arrestan nuevamente a \u00d3scar P\u00e9rez Inguanzo, ex alcalde de Tampico|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/8ab83f37d6b1f800d866257f6acbf566|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130128170839/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/8ab83f37d6b1f800d866257f6acbf566|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 January 2013|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=12 November 2011}}</ref> In addition, ''[[La Jornada]]'' mentions that the Gulf Cartel owns \"all of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]]\", where they act as the State itself and conduct all forms of criminal activities.<ref>{{cite news|title=El c\u00e1rtel del Golfo, junto con sus nuevos socios, es due\u00f1o de todo en Matamoros|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2011/05/08/politica/012n1pol|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=La Jornada|date=8 May 2011}}</ref> In mid-2010, [[Eugenio Hern\u00e1ndez Flores]], the governor of Tamaulipas, and \u00d3scar Luebbert Guti\u00e9rrez, the mayor of [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]]\u2014both members of the ''[[Institutional Revolutionary Party]]'' (PRI)\u2014were criticized for claiming that there were no armed confrontations in Tamaulipas and that the violence was \"only a rumor.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Ciudadana graba evidencias de balaceras en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/estados/75031.html|accessdate=4 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=2 March 2010}}</ref> Months later, Hern\u00e1ndez Flores finally recognized that several parts of Tamaulipas were \"being overrun by organized crime violence.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=La violencia nos rebas\u00f3, acepta Eugenio Hern\u00e1ndez|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8823265|accessdate=4 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=28 August 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831020132/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8823265|archivedate=31 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Luebbert Guti\u00e9rrez later recognized the work of the federal troops and acknowledged that his city was experiencing \"an escalation in violence.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Alcalde admite psicosis por violencia en Reynosa|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/661544.html|accessdate=4 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=25 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 June 2016, citizens from Tamaulipas elected a governor from the opposition party, Fransico Javier Garcia Cabeza de Vaca member of Accion Nacional (National Action). It is the first time in 87 years, a governor from the opposition wins in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/articulo/nacion/politica/2016/06/6/garcia-cabeza-de-vaca-gana-priista-hinojosa|title=Garc\u00eda Cabeza de Vaca gana a pri\u00edsta Hinojosa|publisher=|accessdate=11 December 2016|date=2016-06-06}}</ref> He won under the slogan \"winds of change are coming\" to Tamaulipas.<ref>http://lavozdetamaulipas.net/soplan-fuertes-vientos-de-cambio-en-tamaulipas-cabeza-de-vaca/{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> While his election did not had that much substance in a public policy perspective, its rhetoric of a peaceful transition, enabled him to defeat by double digits the candidate from the ruling party, Baltazar Manuel Hinijosa Ochoa.<ref>http://www.preptam.org/#/ {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703002550/http://www.preptam.org/ |date=3 July 2016 }}</ref>\n\nBoth candidates have and continue to face accusations of receiving illicity money from the Gulf Cartel, while being mayors of two border towns. In 1986, according to Proceso, Cabeza de Vaca was arrested for stealing weapons under the orders for a Drug Trafficking Organization (DTOs) of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/121266/tamaulipas-rastros-de-narco-en-el-precandidato-panista-2|title=Tamaulipas: Rastros de narco en el precandidato panista - Proceso|date=16 December 2009|publisher=|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> Cabeza de Vaca is accused by a Bloomberg/El Financiero of having a big and unexplained wealth of 951 million pesos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/nacional/como-funcionario-cabeza-de-vaca-amasa-fortuna-de-951-mdp.html|title=Como funcionario, Cabeza de Vaca amasa fortuna de 951 mdp|publisher=|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> Cabeza de Vaca is accused of not reporting its total wealth, and having properities both in Texas, Tamaulipas, and Mexico City. Cabeza de Vaca has been for 11 years a public servant, which questions according El Financiero, the origin of its wealth. Balatazar Hinojosa Ochoa is also accused of coopting with DTOs of the Gulf Cartel while being mayor of Matamoros in 2006. In goes into the extent, in a recent book called ''Tamaulipas; La casta de de los narcogobernadores: un eastern mexicano'' is accused of being present while former governor Tomas Yarrigton, also accused of involvements with DTOs of the Gulf Cartel, received illicit money from the Gulf Cartel to finance its campaign for governor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/442099/tamaulipas-gobernadores-narco-hermanados|title=Tamaulipas: gobernadores y narco, hermanados - Proceso|date=28 May 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> Also according to Proceso, Baltazar Hinojosa is under investigation by the United States Department of Tresuary for laundering money through the Panama Papers target, the law firm Mossack Fonseca. According to the media outlet, Baltazar Hinojosa brother in law, owns a shell company created by the law firm, where its board of directors' members are his wife and three daughters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/442618/departamento-del-tesoro-investiga-a-candidato-del-pri-al-gobierno-tamaulipas-lavado-dinero|title=Departamento del Tesoro investiga a candidato del PRI al gobierno de Tamaulipas por lavado - Proceso|date=1 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Prison breaks===\nOn 25 March 2010 in the city of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], 40 inmates escaped from a federal prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se fugan 40 reos de penal en Matamoros|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/668521.html|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=25 March 2010}}</ref>  Authorities are still trying to understand how the prisoners escaped.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se fugan 40 reos de Penal de Matamoros|url=http://eleconomista.com.mx/estados/2010/03/25/se-fugan-40-reos-penal-matamoros|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Economista|date=25 March 2010}}</ref> The authorities mentioned that the incident is \"under investigation,\" but did not give further information.<ref>{{cite news|title=40 reos se fugan de penal de Matamoros|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/03/25/40-reos-se-fugan-de-penal-de-matamoros|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=25 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183645/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/03/25/40-reos-se-fugan-de-penal-de-matamoros|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the border city of [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]], 85 inmates escaped from a prison on 10 September 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=85 reos escaparon del penal de Reynosa, precisa el gobierno|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/09/10/un-grupo-de-reos-escapo-del-penal-de-reynosa-precisa-el-gobierno|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=10 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183312/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/09/10/un-grupo-de-reos-escapo-del-penal-de-reynosa-precisa-el-gobierno|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Reports first indicated that there were 71 fugitives, but the correct figures were later released.<ref>{{cite news|title=Al menos 71 reos se fugan de un penal de Reynosa, en Tamaulipas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/09/10/al-menos-71-reos-se-fugan-de-un-penal-de-reynosa-en-tamaulipas|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=10 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183629/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/09/10/al-menos-71-reos-se-fugan-de-un-penal-de-reynosa-en-tamaulipas|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 5 April 2010, in the same prison, a convoy of 10 trucks filled with gunmen broke into the cells and liberated 13 inmates, and the authorities later mentioned that 11 of them were \"extremely dangerous.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Un comando libera a trece prisioneros de un penal de Reynosa|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/04/05/un-comando-libera-a-trece-prisioneros-de-un-penal-de-reynosa|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=5 April 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183651/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/04/05/un-comando-libera-a-trece-prisioneros-de-un-penal-de-reynosa|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas]] on 17 December 2010, about 141 inmates escaped from a federal prison. At first, estimates mentioned that 148 inmates had escaped, but later counts gave the exact figures.<ref>{{cite news|title=Al menos 148 presos se escapan de una c\u00e1rcel de Tamaulipas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/mundo/2010/12/17/al-menos-148-presos-se-escapan-de-una-carcel-de-tamaulipas|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNNM\u00e9xico|date=17 December 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183238/http://mexico.cnn.com/mundo/2010/12/17/al-menos-148-presos-se-escapan-de-una-carcel-de-tamaulipas|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The federal government \"strongly condemned\" the prison breaks and said that the work by the state and municipal authorities of [[Tamaulipas]] \"lack effective control measures\" and urged them to strengthen their institutions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamaulipas cesa a directivos de penal por la fuga de los 141 reos|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/12/17/tamaulipas-cesa-a-directivos-de-penal-por-la-fuga-de-los-141-reos|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=17 December 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101104819/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/12/17/tamaulipas-cesa-a-directivos-de-penal-por-la-fuga-de-los-141-reos|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A confrontation inside a maximum security prison in [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas]] on 15 July 2011 left 7 inmates dead and 59 escaped.<ref>{{cite news|title=Al menos siete muertos y 59 reos fugados en una c\u00e1rcel de Nuevo Laredo|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/15/al-menos-siete-muertos-y-59-reos-fugados-en-una-carcel-de-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=15 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101233601/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/15/al-menos-siete-muertos-y-59-reos-fugados-en-una-carcel-de-nuevo-laredo|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The 5 guards that were supposed to supervise have not been found, and the [[Federal government of Mexico]] urged the state and municipal authorities to strengthen the security of their prisons.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se fugan 59 reos en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/estados/81218.html|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=16 July 2011}}</ref> Consequently, the federal government did not hesitate to assign the [[Mexican Army]] and the [[Federal Police (Mexico)|Federal Police]] to vigilate the prisons until further notice; they were also left in charge of searching for the fugitives.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se fugan 59 reos en Nuevo Laredo tras enfrentamiento|url=http://www.terra.mx/noticias/articulo/1159803/Se+fugan+59+reos+en+Nuevo+Laredo+tras+enfrentamiento.htm|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Terra Noticias|date=15 July 2011}}</ref> ''[[CNN]]'' mentioned that the state government of Tamaulipas later recognized \"their inability to work with the federal government.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Tras las fugas de reos en Tamaulipas, el gobierno federal se defiende|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/04/07/gobierno-federal-reitara-su-apoyo-a-tamaulipas-en-lucha-contra-el-crimen|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=7 April 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183554/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/04/07/gobierno-federal-reitara-su-apoyo-a-tamaulipas-en-lucha-contra-el-crimen|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a prison in the state of [[Zacatecas]], on 16 May 2009, an armed commando liberated 53 Gulf Cartel members using 10 trucks and even a helicopter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Narco libera reos en Zacatecas|url=http://www.cnnexpansion.com/actualidad/2009/05/16/narco-libera-reos-en-zacatecas|accessdate=20 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Expansion|date=16 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[CNN]]'', more than 400 prison inmates escaped from several prisons in [[Tamaulipas]] from January 2010 to March 2011 due to corruption.<ref>{{cite news|title=M\u00e1s de 400 reos se fugaron de c\u00e1rceles de Tamaulipas en 14 meses|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/15/mas-de-400-reos-se-fugaron-de-carceles-de-tamaulipas-en-14-meses|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=15 July 2011|language=es|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101233449/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/15/mas-de-400-reos-se-fugaron-de-carceles-de-tamaulipas-en-14-meses|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Police corruption===\nThe ''[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]'' newspaper mentioned that the police forces in the state of [[Tamaulipas]] are the \"worst paid in Mexico\" despite being \"one of the states hardest hit by violence.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Polic\u00edas de Tamaulipas ganan 3 mil 618 pesos|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&id_nota=770508#.TwIwTyO3CFc|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Excelsior|date=25 September 2011|language=es}}</ref> They also reported that in [[Aguascalientes]], a state where violence levels are much lower, policemen are paid five times more than in Tamaulipas. In fact, they are paid around $3,618 [[Mexican peso|pesos]] (about $260 US dollars) a month in all of [[Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Polic\u00edas de Tamaulipas, los peores pagados de M\u00e9xico; ganan menos de 4 mil pesos al mes|url=http://www.animalpolitico.com/2011/09/policias-de-tamaulipas-los-peores-pagados-de-mexico-ganan-menos-de-4-mil-pesos-al-mes/|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Animal Politico|date=26 September 2011|language=es}}</ref> As a result, most of the police forces in Tamaulipas are believed to be \"corrupt\" due to their low wages and the presence of organized crime, who can easily bribe them.<ref>{{cite news|title=Polic\u00edas de Tamaulipas aun no son confiables: Lomel\u00ed|url=http://www.hoytamaulipas.net/notas/45682/Policias-aun-no-son-confiables-Rafael-Lomeli.html|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Hoy Tamaulipas|date=7 November 2011|language=es}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May 2011, the Mexican government, along with [[Secretariat of National Defense|Sedena]], disarmed all police forces in the state of [[Tamaulipas]], beginning with the cities of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]] and [[Reynosa]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sedena desarma a polic\u00edas de Tamaulipas|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYW7mvmIfbc|newspaper=TV Milenio|date=9 May 2011}}</ref> In June 2011, the state government of Tamaulipas requested the federal government to send in troops to combat the drug cartels in the area, in order to \"consolidate actions on public safety\" and \"strengthen the capacity of their institutions.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=El gobierno de M\u00e9xico desplegar\u00e1 2,790 militares en Tamaulipas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/06/24/el-gobierno-de-mexico-desplegara-2790-militares-en-tamaulipas|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=24 June 2011|language=es|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183342/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/06/24/el-gobierno-de-mexico-desplegara-2790-militares-en-tamaulipas|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Joint Operation Nuevo Le\u00f3n-Tamaulipas]] issued in 2007, along with several other military-led operation by the federal government, have brought thousands of troops to restore order in [[Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=M\u00e9xico enviar\u00e1 m\u00e1s Fuerzas Armadas a Nuevo Le\u00f3n y Tamaulipas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/24/mexico-enviara-mas-fuerzas-armadas-a-nuevo-leon-y-tamaulipas|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=24 November 2011|language=es|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120102051554/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/24/mexico-enviara-mas-fuerzas-armadas-a-nuevo-leon-y-tamaulipas|archivedate=2 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[CNN]]'' news mentioned that the troops \"replaced half of the policemen\" in the state of Tamaulipas.<ref>{{cite news|last=Castillo|first=Mariano|title=Tropas mexicanas reemplazan a los polic\u00edas en la mitad de Tamaulipas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/06/26/tropas-mexicanas-reemplazan-a-los-policias-en-la-mitad-de-tamaulipas|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=26 June 2011|language=es|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222052600/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/06/26/tropas-mexicanas-reemplazan-a-los-policias-en-la-mitad-de-tamaulipas|archivedate=22 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 7 November 2011, about 1,660 policemen were released from their duties because they had either failed their control tests or refused to take them.<ref>{{cite news|title=Expulsan a mil 650 polic\u00edas de Tamaulipas por p\u00e9rdida de confianza|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&seccion=seccion-nacional&cat=1&id_nota=781202#.TwI8byO3CFc|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Excelsior|date=7 November 2011|language=es}}</ref>\n\nAlthough there have been efforts by the federal government to wipe out police corruption, [[Terra Networks]] published an article of a witness who said that the police forces in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]] work as \"informants for the Gulf Cartel\" and report on the activity of the Mexican military, and even \"wave at [the cartel members]\" when they see them in the streets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Opini\u00f3n sobre posible corrupci\u00f3n en Matamoros|url=http://www.terra.com.mx/articulo.aspx?articuloId=1104266|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Terra|date=5 May 2011|language=es}}</ref> ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]'' released an article which said that the National Public Security System (SNSP) has condemned the cops' salaries, and demanded the state and municipal authorities to create better paying programs for the policemen so they can have a \"[[Just price|just wage]]\" for themselves and their families.<ref>{{cite news|title=Acusan a estados de incumplir homologaci\u00f3n salarial policiaca|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/primera/37801.html|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=26 September 2011|language=es}}</ref> The federal government is also constructing three military bases in Tamaulipas: in [[Ciudad Mier]], [[San Fernando, Tamaulipas|San Fernando]], and [[Ciudad Mante, Tamaulipas|Ciudad Mante]].<ref>{{cite news|title='Batallones son parte de la estrategia de seguridad'|url=http://eldiariodevictoria.com.mx/2011/11/16/%E2%80%98batallones-son-parte-de-la-estrategia-de-seguridad%E2%80%99/|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Diario de Ciudad Victoria|date=16 November 2011|language=es}}</ref>\n\n==Alliances==\nIn 2003, the arrest of several high-profile cartel leaders, including the heads of the [[Tijuana Cartel]] and Gulf Cartel, [[Benjam\u00edn Arellano F\u00e9lix]] and [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], turned the war on drugs into a trilateral war. While in prison, C\u00e1rdenas and Arellano formed an alliance to defend themselves from the [[Sinaloa Cartel|Sinaloa]] and [[Juarez Cartel]]s,<ref>{{cite web|last=Ensinger|first=Jason|title=Mexico's War On Drugs|url=http://www.shavemagazine.com/politics/090201|publisher=Shave Magazine}}</ref> who had also formed an alliance with each other, and were planning to take over the smuggling routes and territories of the Gulf and [[Tijuana Cartel]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cook|first=Colleen W.|title=CRS Report for Congress: Mexico's Drug Cartels|journal=Congressional Research Service|date=October 2007|pages=35|url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/row/RL34215.pdf}}</ref> After a dispute, however, C\u00e1rdenas ordered Arellano beaten, and the Gulf-Tijuana alliance ceased to exist at that point. It was reported that after the fallout, C\u00e1rdenas ordered [[Los Zetas]] to [[Baja California]] to wipe out the Tijuana Cartel.<ref>{{cite book|last=Logan|first=Sam|title=The Reality of the Mexican Mega Cartel|year=2006|pages=21|url=http://www.samuellogan.com/publications/The-Reality-of-a-Mega-Cartel.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe Sinaloa-Juarez alliance ceased to exist as well due to an unpaid debt in 2007, and now the Sinaloa and Juarez Cartel are at war against each other.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rompen pacto c\u00e1rteles de Ju\u00e1rez y de Sinaloa|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/159369.html|newspaper=El Universal|date= 10 May 2008|language=es}}</ref> Since February 2010, the major cartels have aligned in two factions, one integrated by the [[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]], Tijuana Cartel, Los Zetas and the [[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel]];<ref>{{cite news|last=Granados|first=Omar|title=\"El Chapo\" y Los Zetas dominan reacomodo de c\u00e1rteles|url=http://www.animalpolitico.com/2011/05/el-chapo-y-los-zetas-dominan-el-reacomodo-de-carteles/|newspaper=Animal Pol\u00edtico|date=6 May 2011|language=es}}</ref> the other faction integrated by the Gulf Cartel, Sinaloa Cartel, [[La Familia Michoacana|La Familia Cartel]] (now extinct) and the [[Knights Templar (gang)|Knights Templar Cartel]].<ref name=\"Aug 2011\">{{cite news | first = Aurora | last = Vega | title = Surgen cuatro grupos del narco en 2011; El Chapo es el capo m\u00e1s poderoso | date = 7 August 2011 | url = http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&id_nota=759098 | work = Excelsior | accessdate =7 August 2011 | language = Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mosso|first=Rub\u00e9n|title=Presentan a \"El Yupo\" l\u00edder de \"Los Caballeros Templarios\" en Apatzing\u00e1n|url=http://tampico.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/8e8cb7bc4e8cf619c658bc3f7b7283c2|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=1 August 2011|language=es|access-date=2 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805235311/http://tampico.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/8e8cb7bc4e8cf619c658bc3f7b7283c2|archive-date=5 August 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\n[[File:Gulf Cartel Hierarchy.JPG|thumb|Gulf Cartel [[hierarchy]]]]\n\nThe rupture from [[Los Zetas]] left [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]] and [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n|Antonio Ezekiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] in full control of the Gulf Cartel. However, Ezekiel died in a shooting with the Mexican Marines in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]] in 2010,<ref>{{cite news|title=Cae abatido por la Marina 'Tony Tormenta' en Matamoros|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/f093ccf4edf26d1cdb9c4181baf05c90|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=5 November 2010|access-date=6 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015225924/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/f093ccf4edf26d1cdb9c4181baf05c90|archive-date=15 October 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and Costilla Sanchez became the sole head of the cartel until his arrest in September 2012.<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\">{{cite news |first=Tracy |last=Wilkinson |title=Latest Mexico drug arrest may cripple Gulf cartel |date=13 September 2012 |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/sep/13/world/la-fg-mexico-gulf-cartel-20120914 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=12 October 2012}}</ref> [[Mario C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], brother of both Osiel and Antonio, became one of the top lieutenants in the organization after his release from prison in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vega|first=Aurora|title=Otro C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n hereda la organizaci\u00f3n|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&id_nota=682536|newspaper=Excelsior|date=6 November 2010}}</ref> In addition, within the Gulf Cartel there is believed to be two groups\u2014the Rojos and the [[Los Metros|Metros]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sources: Fatal gunshots on McAllen expressway point to Gulf Cartel|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/mcallen-55174-point-expressway.html|newspaper=The Monitor|date=27 September 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811061018/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/mcallen-55174-point-expressway.html|archivedate=11 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[modus operandi]] (\"mode of operation\") of the Gulf Cartel changes whenever the United States attempts to strengthen their domestic policy in reinforcing the borders. When drug trafficking tightens, they usually invest in more sophisticated methods to smuggle drugs, recruit new members, corrupt more officials, seek new ways to remove obstacles that impede the immediate success of the organization, along with many others.<ref>{{cite book|last=Payan|first=Tony|title=Three United States-Mexico border wars|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-98818-0|pages=164|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Y1ETNeJow9IC&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=modus+operandi+gulf+cartel#v=onepage&q=modus%20operandi%20gulf%20cartel&f=false}}</ref> Below is the basic structure of the [[drug cartel]]:\n\n*Falcons (''Halcones''): Considered the \"eyes and ears\" of the streets, the falcons are the lowest rank position in any drug cartel. They are responsible for supervising and reporting on the activities of the Mexican military and of their rival groups.<ref>{{cite news|title=Va Marina por 'halcones' del crimen organizado|url=http://www.mundonarco.com/2011/04/va-marina-por-halcones-del-crimen.html|newspaper=Blog del Narco|date=21 April 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827061101/http://www.mundonarco.com/2011/04/va-marina-por-halcones-del-crimen.html|archivedate=27 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*Hitmen (''Sicarios''): They are the armed group within the drug cartel; they are responsible for carrying out assassinations, kidnappings, thefts, extortions, operating protection rackets, and defending their plaza from the rival groups and the military.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bowden|first=Charles|title=El sicario, un documental proscrito en M\u00e9xico (1)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7C45xR_48mQ|date=6 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bowden|first=Charles|title=El sicario, un documental proscrito en M\u00e9xico (2)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LDFDxtjGuuI|date=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n*Lieutenants (''Lugartenientes''): The second highest position in the drug cartel organization; they are responsible for supervising the ''sicarios'' and ''halcones'' within their own territory. They are allowed to carry low-profile executions without permission from their bosses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ej\u00e9rcito detiene a lugarteniente del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/602145.html|newspaper=El Universal|date=2 June 2009}}</ref>\n*Drug lords (''Capos''): This is the highest position in any drug cartel; they are responsible supervising the entire drug industry, appointing territorial leaders, making alliances, and planning high-profile executions.<ref>{{cite news|title=DATOS&nbsp;\u2013 Principales capos de la droga en M\u00e9xico|url=http://mx.ibtimes.com/articles/6593/20101106/lideres-droga-mexico-narcotrafico.htm|newspaper=International Business Times|accessdate=6 November 2010|language=es|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120715171715/http://mx.ibtimes.com/articles/6593/20101106/lideres-droga-mexico-narcotrafico.htm|archivedate=15 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIt's worth noting that there are other operating groups within the drug cartels. For example, the drug producers and suppliers,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Uncovering the link between the Mexican drug cartels|journal=National Defense University: Center for Hemispheric Defense Studies|url=http://www.ndu.edu/chds/SRC-peru07/SRC_PAPERS/TRACK%201/VELARDE_SPA%20final.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615194812/http://www.ndu.edu/chds/SRC-peru07/SRC_PAPERS/TRACK%201/VELARDE_SPA%20final.pdf|archivedate=15 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> although not considered in  the basic structure, are critical operators of any drug cartel, along with the financers and money launderers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Las 5 caras del lavado de dinero|url=http://www.cnnexpansion.com/economia/2010/06/07/lavado-de-dinero-narco-mexico-eu|newspaper=CNNExpansi\u00f3n|date=8 June 2010|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cae \"El Adal\" operador financiero de los Zetas|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qBEDcgepE6M|accessdate=3 August 2011|newspaper=TV Milenio|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cae \"El M\u00edchel\" operador financiero de Los Zetas en Aguascalientes|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IpM93oU7ICM|accessdate=3 August 2011|newspaper=Tele Diario|language=es}}</ref> In addition, the arms suppliers operate in a completely different circle,<ref>{{cite news|title=Entrevista a el Mamito, presunto fundador de los Zetas|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HacDTEn2TDs|newspaper=CNN Videos|date=6 July 2011|language=es}}</ref> and are technically not considered part of the cartel's logistics.\n\nIn June 2019, Carlos Abraham R\u00edos Su\u00e1rez, also known as El Oaxaco, was arrested. He served as head of cartel's operations in [[Oaxaca]].<ref>https://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/gulf-cartels-oaxaca-plaza-chief/</ref>\n\n==Modus operandi==\n'''Protection racketeering'''\nOrganized crime groups opt for [[protection racketeering]] in an effort to control markets and \"maintaining internal order.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Varese|first=Federico|title=Mafias on the move: how organized crime conquers new territories|year=2011|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-12855-9|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mafiasonmovehowo00vare/page/278 278]|url=https://archive.org/details/mafiasonmovehowo00vare|url-access=registration|quote=protection racketeering.}}</ref> It is generally seen as a way where criminals change the legal face of security and provide their own form of \"insurance\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Bryden|first=Alan|title=Private actors and security governance|year=2006|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|isbn=978-3-8258-9840-3|pages=314|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iVsIAP_iiboC&pg=PA113&dq=protection+racketeering#v=onepage&q=protection%20racketeering&f=false}}</ref> This practice of extorting money from people is also seen in the [[human trafficking]] business in [[Mexico]]; the cartels threaten smugglers to pay a fee for using the corridors, and if they refuse to pay, drug traffickers respond in a deadly form.<ref>{{cite book|last=Payan|first=Tony|title=Human rights along the U.S.-Mexico border: gendered violence and insecurity|year=2009|publisher=University of Arizona Press|isbn=978-0-8165-2872-1|pages=230|url=https://books.google.com/?id=qb9_w99QtEEC&pg=PA76&dq=mexico+protection+money#v=onepage&q=mexico%20protection%20money&f=false}}</ref> The Gulf Cartel operates in a similar way, and often extorts businesses for protection money in the areas where it operates, pledging to kill those who do not agree to pay the fee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crimen cobra cuotas a vecinos: Elizondo|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8560457|accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=15 April 2009|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091221064330/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8560457|archive-date=21 December 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In addition, the Mexican drug cartels also tax several Mexican businesses inside the [[United States]], and threaten them with property damage and murder if they do not comply.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gomora|first=Doris|title=C\u00e1rteles \"cobran piso\" en EU: DEA|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/primera/38445.html|accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=25 December 2011|language=es}}</ref>\n\n'''Kidnappings'''\nThe Gulf Cartel, along with their rival group [[Los Zetas]], have been the two drug cartels with the most [[kidnapping]]s in all of [[Mexico]], and \"more than half of the country's kidnappings are attributed to them.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Detenidas con Calder\u00f3n, 223 bandas de secuestradores|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/9087563|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=31 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114104255/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/9087563|archive-date=14 January 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> And, there are several kidnapping rings of the Gulf Cartel throughout several parts of [[Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Presentan a banda de secuestradores en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/be0e93a852354ad9e833b2ddff5eeac5|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=9 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108012300/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/be0e93a852354ad9e833b2ddff5eeac5|archive-date=8 January 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Mexican military mentioned that in the states of Tamaulipas and [[Nuevo Leon]], where the Gulf Cartel and Los Zetas fight for territory, abductions are carried out very commonly. An intelligence agency mentioned that the Gulf Cartel kidnaps for three reasons:\n# To increase the ranks of their cartel after the deaths or arrests of their own members;\n# To exterminate members of their rival gangs;\n# To kidnap people for money and other ransom.<ref>{{cite news|title=Van mil 700 desaparecidos en Nuevo Le\u00f3n y Tamaulipas, seg\u00fan reportes a militares|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/vanmil700desaparecidosennuevoleonytamaulipassegunreportesamilitares-563396.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=La Vanguardia|date=4 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011 in the border city of [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]], 68 kidnapped victims from different parts of Mexico and [[Central America]] were found in a safe house of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rescatan a 68 inmigrantes secuestrados por el C\u00e1rtel del Golfo en Reynosa, Tamaulipas|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_C7HF4ugWS0|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio TV|date=10 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rescatan a 51 inmigrantes secuestrados cerca de frontera|url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/620530.rescatan-a-51-inmigrantes-secuestrados-cerca.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=El Siglo de Torreon|date=April 2011}}</ref> [[Omar Ortiz]], best known for his nickname ''El Gato'', was a former soccer star from [[C.F. Monterrey]] who was arrested in January 2012 for working in a kidnapping ring within the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexican soccer star arrested for working in kidnapping ring that took pop singer's husband|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2012/01/mexican-soccer-star-arrested-for.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=8 January 2012}}</ref> The Mexican [[Lucha libre]] wrestler L\u00e1zaro Gurrola, known as the ''Estrella Dorada'' (Golden Star), was also arrested for kidnapping people for the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=El luchador mexicano 'Estrella Dorada' es acusado de secuestro|url=http://noticias.univision.com/mexico/noticias/article/2012-01-10/luchador-estrella-dorada-es-acusado-de-narco#axzz1k8NJHb3F|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Univision|date=10 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[United States]], the Gulf Cartel has been responsible for several kidnappings, primarily in [[McAllen\u2013Edinburg\u2013Mission metropolitan area|the McAllen metropolitan area]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lopez|first=Katie|title=San Juan kidnapping ring suspects face judge|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?list=195030&id=688470#.Txs202O3CFc|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Action 4 News|date=18 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104062754/http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?list=195030&id=688470#.Txs202O3CFc|archive-date=4 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel lieutenant linked to various incidents in the U.S side|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/linked-135370-mcallen-cartel.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=2 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Caranza|first=Rafael|title=Alleged Gulf Cartel members charged with Hidalgo kidnapping|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=683073#.TxsxF2O3CFc|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Valley Central|date=4 November 2011}}</ref> Investigators believe that more unreported kidnappings have occurred in nearby locations.<ref>{{cite news|title=San Juan kidnapping ring reportedly had Gulf Cartel ties|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?list=195030&id=687844#.Txs3a2O3CFc|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Action 4 News|date=17 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104062339/http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?list=195030&id=687844#.Txs3a2O3CFc|archive-date=4 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> When victims are kidnapped by the drug cartels on American territory, kidnappers usually hide them in the trunk of a car and take them to [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ortiz|first=Ildelfonso|title=Gulf Cartel members charged in Hidalgo kidnapping|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/hidalgo-56346-charged-gulf.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=4 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101162702/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/hidalgo-56346-charged-gulf.html|archive-date=1 January 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> FBI investigators said that victims are \"kidnapped, threatened, assaulted, drugged and transported into Mexico to meet with Cartel members.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel kidnapping of U.S. citizens|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/01/gulf-cartel-kidnappings-of-us-citizens.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=27 January 2010}}</ref> Reports indicated that kidnappers working for the Gulf Cartel train with [[paintball]] equipment \"to practice simulated kidnapping schemes in order to prepare for the actual kidnapping they intended to commit.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Dodge|first=Angela|title=JURY CONVICTS CARTEL ASSOCIATE OF CONSPIRACY TO KIDNAP AND KIDNAPPING|url=http://www.justice.gov/usao/txs/1News/Releases/2010%20January/012210%20Avila_print.htm|publisher=Department of Justice|accessdate=21 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104045804/http://www.justice.gov/usao/txs/1News/Releases/2010%20January/012210%20Avila_print.htm|archive-date=4 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In one reported incident, Isaac Sanchez Gutierrez, a man from [[Palmview, Texas]], said he faced an ultimatum: pay $10 million to the Gulf Cartel, or transport 50 drug loads from Mexico into the U.S. in order to free his kidnapped brother.<ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Jared|title=Palmview chase suspect: Gulf Cartel forced me to smuggle|url=http://www.valleymorningstar.com/articles/-97170--.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=21 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''Human trafficking'''\n{{See also|Human trafficking in Mexico}}\nBefore 2010, it was not clear whether the Gulf Cartel controls the [[human trafficking]] business in its territory or whether it simply taxes operators for using their smuggling corridors.<ref>{{cite book|last=Spener|first=David|title=Clandestine crossings: migrants and coyotes on the Texas-Mexico border|year=2009|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-7589-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/clandestinecross00spen/page/298 298]|url=https://archive.org/details/clandestinecross00spen|url-access=registration|quote=gulf cartel human trafficking.}}</ref> ''[[La Jornada]]'' mentioned that before the rupture with [[Los Zetas]] in 2007, the corridor of [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]] was often used for human smuggling.<ref>{{cite news|title=Captura PGR a El Barbas y otros cuatro presuntos narcotraficantes|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2007/04/18/index.php?section=politica&article=005n2pol|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=La Jornada|date=18 April 2007|language=es}}</ref> [[People smuggling]] is currently controlled by a cell within the Gulf Cartel known as ''Los Flacos'', dedicated to the kidnapping and smuggling of undocumented migrants as far as [[South America]] to the United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=EJERCIT\u00d3 PGR ACCI\u00d3N PENAL CONTRA DOS PERSONAS, POR DELINCUENCIA ORGANIZADA Y SECUESTRO|url=http://pgr.gob.mx/Prensa/2007/bol11/Nov/b156711.shtm|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Procuraduria General de la Republica|date=14 November 2011|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104030205/http://pgr.gob.mx/Prensa/2007/bol11/Nov/b156711.shtm|archive-date=4 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It operates primarily on the [[Tabasco]]\u2013[[Veracruz]]\u2013[[Tamaulipas]] corridor.<ref>{{cite news|last=Carvallo Guzm\u00e1n|first=Indira|title=En Veracruz, PGR captura a tres personas por el tr\u00e1fico de personas en el sur|url=http://www.diariopresencia.com/nota.aspx?ID=42853&List=%7BE99F52BD-B89D-4D80-A5BB-BCD1566AE98A%7D|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Diario Presencia|date=14 November 2011|language=es}}</ref> Human trafficking in the [[Rio Grande Valley]] has become \"ground zero\" and was considered the \"new Arizona\" in December 2011 by the ''Homeland Security Today''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kimery|first=Anthony|title=Drug, Human Smuggling, Cartel Shootouts With Police Escalate In Rio Grande Valley|url=http://www.hstoday.us/blogs/the-kimery-report/blog/drug-human-smuggling-cartel-shootouts-with-police-escalate-in-rio-grande-valley/b55c95b14c1708ee4691b22a8bcb70f5.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Homeland Security Today|date=6 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nA U.S. agent mentioned that the drug cartels that operate on the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]], and principally across from [[Texas]], are \"in control of not only the narcotrafficking, but also the human smuggling.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Sutton|first=Barbara|title=Security disarmed: critical perspectives on gender, race, and militarization|year=2008|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=978-0-8135-4360-4|pages=308|url=https://books.google.com/?id=o9SzGdYrBfYC&pg=PA88&dq=gulf+cartel+human+smuggling#v=onepage&q=gulf%20cartel%20human%20smuggling&f=false}}</ref>\n<!-- This was the Zetas' realm. Include if updated.\n'''Extortion'''\nIn August 2007, ''La Ma\u00f1a'' gang, an alleged sub-group of the criminal group [[Los Zetas]] and the Gulf Cartel, was reported to have controlled the [[extortion]] business in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico: La Ma\u00f1a gang; whether this group is involved in smuggling people into the United States (US); whether this group has links to the criminal group Los Zetas|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/publisher,IRBC,,MEX,49b92b381e,0.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada|date=16 October 2008}}</ref> The newspaper ''[[La Vanguardia]]'' mentioned that the Gulf Cartel receives \"large sums of money by extorting businesses\" all around Tamaulipas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Federales capturan a l\u00edderes del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/federalescapturanalideresdelcarteldelgolfoentamaulipas-665445.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=La Vanguardia|date=5 March 2011}}</ref> Many of the extortions are first carried out on the phone.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sin freno, extorsiones telef\u00f3nicas|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8049490|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=18 November 2008}}</ref> -->\nCritics say that the strategy of capturing drug kingpins often resulted in the increase in [[extortion]], as the cartels look for other sources of money.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico's drugs war: Lessons and challenges|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-16337488|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=31 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''Bribery'''\nWhen the Gulf Cartel was moving tons of cocaine to the [[United States]] and moving millions of dollars in cash along the border in the 1970s, [[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]] decided that he needed more protection. Court documents indicated that Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was bribing several law enforcement officials, prosecutors, and politicians on both sides on the border to keep himself impune and untouched.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drug Lord's Web of Payoffs Spans U.S.-Mexico Border|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1995-09-04/news/mn-42137_1_garcia-abrego|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=4 September 1995|first=Mark|last=Fineman}}</ref> His former friends and associates mentioned that the drug lord was paying one of [[Carlos Salinas de Gortari]]'s deputy attorneys general more than $1.5 million a month for his protection.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fineman|first=Mark|title=Mexican Drug Cartel Chief Convicted in U.S.|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1996-10-17/news/mn-57764_1_garcia-abrego|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=17 October 1996}}</ref> He is allegedly reported to have been protected by a large private army of gunmen.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dillon|first=Sam|title=Mexico Arrests A Top Suspect In Drug Trade|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/01/16/world/mexico-arrests-a-top-suspect-in-drug-trade.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=16 January 1996}}</ref> A retired FBI agent and expert in drug trafficking explained that the Gulf Cartel \"relied on bribery\" to build its drug empire and consolidate its prominence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexican Drug Empire Built With Murder, Ex-agent Says|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1996-09-19/news/9609181151_1_abrego-cartel-fbi-agent|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Orlando Sentinel|date=19 September 1996}}</ref>\n\n[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) agents have claimed that the Gulf Cartel moves millions of dollars in cash through the [[Rio Grande Valley]] each month, a tempting amount for many U.S. officials.<ref>{{cite news|last=Del Valle|first=Fernando|title=Cartel bribery spreads to Valley|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/san-120505-spreads-valley.html|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=13 December 2010}}</ref> Much of the money stays in the area, which has caused several officials\u2014both federal and state\u2014to succumb to the \"easy money aspect\" the drug money has to offer.<ref>{{cite news|title=FBI: Drug money threatens to corrupt Valley cops|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/san-45693-cops-threatens.html|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=25 December 2010}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The Gulf Cartel also bribes [[journalists]] to persuade them not to mention any violent incidents in the media.<ref>{{cite news|title=El c\u00e1rtel del Golfo soborna a periodistas para que no cubran los sucesos violentos|url=http://globedia.com/cartel-golfo-soborna-periodistas-cubran-sucesos-violentos|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Globedia|date=3 December 2010}}</ref> In addition, due to the low-paying salaries of many policemen, the Gulf Cartel often \"buys\" many law enforcement officers in Mexico.<ref>{{cite news|title=Comprar un polic\u00eda cuesta $3,500 en NL|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8585825|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=3 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110409022325/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8585825|archive-date=9 April 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''Theft'''\nStealing oil from [[PEMEX]] and selling it illegally has been one of the many funding activities of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Zetas desalojaron campo de Pemex en Tamaulipas|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8725004|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100810005325/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8725004|archive-date=10 August 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> They were reported to have stolen around 40% of the oil products in 2011 in northern Mexico and then selling it illegally in Mexico and in the American black market.<ref>{{cite news|title=Robo de combustible en M\u00e9xico, en manos de c\u00e1rteles del narcotr\u00e1fico|url=http://noticias.univision.com/narcotrafico/article/2011-12-28/robo-combustibles-mexico-carteles-narcotrafico#axzz1k8NJHb3F|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Univision|date=28 December 2011}}</ref> One leader of the Gulf Cartel confessed after his apprehension that \"drug trafficking is their main business, but due to the difficulties they have been encountering, oil theft has been an important financial cushion\" for the cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pemex, bot\u00edn del narco y de mafias internas: escritora|url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/692011.html|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=El Siglo de Torreon|date=28 December 2011|language=es}}</ref> They have also been reported to steal vehicles.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rendon|first=Francisco|title=Desintegr\u00f3 PFP peligrosa c\u00e9lula del Cartel del Golfo|url=http://www.elregional.com.mx/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=23234:desintegro-pfp-peligrosa-celula-del-cartel-del-golfo&catid=39&Itemid=37|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=El Regional del Sur|date=9 November 2011|language=es}}</ref>\n\n'''Money laundering'''\nSome of the revenue of the Gulf Cartel is often [[Money laundering|laundered]] in several bank accounts, properties, vehicles, and gasoline stations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Desarticula PGR red de lavado de dinero del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.cronica.com.mx/nota.php?id_nota=466307|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=La Cronica|date=3 March 2011|language=es}}</ref> Bars and casinos are often the hubs for money laundering of the drug cartels.<ref>{{cite news|title=Detienen a presunto implicado en lavado de dinero|url=http://www.elsiglodedurango.com.mx/noticia/240903.detienen-a-presunto-implicado-en-lavado-de-di.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=El Siglo de Torreon|date=23 November 2009|language=es}}</ref> Top leaders of the Gulf organization, like [[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]], [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]], and [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], among others, have been charged by the U.S. government for laundering millions of dollars.<ref>{{cite book|last=Richards|first=James R.|title=Transnational criminal organizations, cybercrime, and money laundering|year=1999|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-0-8493-2806-0|pages=318|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RmGi5zDus7gC&pg=PA22&dq=gulf+cartel+money+laundering#v=onepage&q=gulf%20cartel%20money%20laundering&f=false}}</ref> Bank accounts inside the United States also launder millions of dollars for the drug lords of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=El dinero del narco, principal reto para el sistema financiero de EU|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/mundo/2011/10/13/el-dinero-del-narco-principal-reto-para-el-sistema-financiero-de-eu|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=13 October 2011|language=es}}</ref> ''[[The Economist]]'' mentioned in 1997 that the drug money from the Gulf Cartel in the [[Rio Grande Valley]] was perhaps moving about $20 billion, and that around 15% of the retailers' gains were from drug money.<ref>{{cite news|title=One river, one country|url=http://www.uwec.edu/geography/Ivogeler/w188/articles/txmx.htm|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=The Economist|year=1997|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130222081319/http://www.uwec.edu/geography/Ivogeler/w188/articles/txmx.htm|archive-date=22 February 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''Arms trafficking'''\nFor the most part, the [[arms trafficking]] circles of the Gulf Cartel operate directly across the border in the [[United States]], just like most of the criminal groups in Mexico.<ref>{{cite news|title=El Mamito: \"\"All the weapons are bought in the United States\"|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2011/07/el-mamito-all-our-weapons-are-bought-in.html|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=6 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ringleader behind Gulf Cartel gun, drug trafficking ring in McAllen pleads guilty|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/mcallen-54500-ring-guilty.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120914083217/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/mcallen-54500-ring-guilty.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 September 2012|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=6 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Jared|title=Shots near Weslaco lead cops to Gulf Cartel arms smuggling|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/lead-56653-mcallen-arms.html|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=17 November 2011}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Nonetheless, there are indeed circles within the Gulf Cartel that coordinate the arms trafficking routes inside Mexico.<ref>{{cite news|title=Caen l\u00edderes del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.eldiariodecoahuila.com.mx/notas/2011/3/6/nacional-221582.asp|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=El Diario de Coahuila|date=6 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712182834/http://www.eldiariodecoahuila.com.mx/notas/2011/3/6/nacional-221582.asp|archive-date=12 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Arms trafficking from the U.S. to Mexico, however, is often carried out individually, and there is no criminal group in Mexico or an international organization that is solely dedicated to this activity.<ref>{{cite news|last=De la Luz Gonzalez|first=Maria|title=Operaci\u00f3n 'hormiga', en el tr\u00e1fico de armas|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/164626.html|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=22 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn a side note, [[Jes\u00fas Enrique Rej\u00f3n Aguilar]], a top-tier Los Zetas boss, was caught on 3 July 2011, and claimed in an interview that was aired on national television that the Gulf Cartel, unlike Los Zetas, has an \"easier and quicker accessibility to arms in the United States\", and probably works \"with some people in the government\" to traffic weapons south of the U.S. border.<ref>{{cite news|title=Armamento de 'Los Zetas' se compra en EU, dice fundador del grupo criminal|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/05/armamento-de-los-zetas-se-compra-en-eu-dice-fundador-del-grupo-criminal|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=5 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928211427/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/05/armamento-de-los-zetas-se-compra-en-eu-dice-fundador-del-grupo-criminal|archivedate=28 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''Prostitution network'''\n[[Prostitution]] circles are believed to be used by the Gulf Cartel to persuade journalists to favor them in the media.<ref>{{cite news|title=El c\u00e1rtel del Golfo compra periodistas con \"narcod\u00f3lares\", prostitutas y alcohol|url=http://www.tribunalatina.com/es/Viewer_100_1columna.php?IDN=24293|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Tribuna Latina|date=3 March 2010|language=es}}</ref> Prostitutes are also used as informants and spies, and provide their sexual favors to extract information from certain targets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se triplica n\u00famero de homicidios de prostitutas relacionadas con el narco|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2011/07/21/politica/021n2pol|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=La Jornada|date=21 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''Counterfeiting'''\nThe Mexican criminal organizations like the Gulf Cartel launder money through [[counterfeiting]], since they are free from taxes and more accessible to people who cannot buy original products.<ref>{{cite news |title=El narco lava dinero con pirater\u00eda |url=http://www.cnnexpansion.com/economia/2010/07/16/el-narco-lava-dinero-con-pirateria |access-date=22 January 2012 |newspaper=CNN Expansion |date=16 July 2010}}</ref> The products sold can be clothing, TVs, video games, music, computer programs, and movies.<ref>{{cite news|title=La pirater\u00eda asuela a la industria legal|url=http://www.cnnexpansion.com/economia/2010/07/15/falsificaciones-productos-pirata-cine|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Expansion|date=15 July 2010}}</ref> In 2008 in the state of [[Michoac\u00e1n]], the Gulf Cartel was reported to have controlled the counterfeit business, where it produced and sold millions of fake CDs and movies.<ref>{{cite news|last=Castillo Garc\u00eda|first=Gustavo|title=El c\u00e1rtel del Golfo controla la pirater\u00eda en Michoac\u00e1n|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2008/04/02/index.php?section=politica&article=014n2pol|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=La Jornada|date=2 April 2008}}</ref>\n\n'''Police impersonation'''\nReports indicate that gunmen from the Gulf Cartel often [[Police impersonation|impersonate]] law enforcement officers, using military uniforms to confuse rival drug gangs and move freely through city streets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Militares piratas en M\u00e9xico|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/militarespiratasenmexico-523317.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=La Vanguardia|date=23 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n'''Transportation'''\nDue to the Gulf Cartel's territory in northern [[Tamaulipas]], primarily in the border cities of [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]] and [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], they have been able to establish a sophisticated and extensive drug trafficking and distribution network along the U.S.\u2013Mexico border in [[South Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|title=South Texas High Intensity Drug Trafficking Area Drug Market Analysis|url=http://www.justice.gov/ndic/pubs27/27513/drugover.htm|publisher=National Drug Intelligence Center|accessdate=8 December 2011}}</ref> The Mexican drug cartels that operate in the area are currently employing gang members to distribute drugs and conduct other criminal activities on their behalf.<ref>{{cite web|title=South Texas High Intensity Drug Trafficking Area|url=http://www.justice.gov/ndic/dmas/South_Texas_DMA-2011(U).pdf|publisher=U.S. Department of Justice|accessdate=8 December 2011}}</ref> Among these gangs, that range from street gangs to prison gangs, are the [[Texas Syndicate]], the [[Latin Kings (gang)|Latin Kings]], the [[Mexican Mafia]], the Tango Blast (Vallucos), the Hermandad de Pistoleros Latinos, and the Tri-City Bombers\u2014all based in the [[Rio Grande Valley]] and [[Webb County, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Texas Gang Threat Assessment 2010|url=http://montgomerytx.countymonitor.com/files/2010/10/TxGngThrtAssessment2010.pdf|publisher=Texas Department of Public Safety|accessdate=8 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426041257/http://montgomerytx.countymonitor.com/files/2010/10/TxGngThrtAssessment2010.pdf|archive-date=26 April 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Narco submarine seized in Ecuador 2010-07-02 1.jpg|thumb|A [[narco submarine]] seized in Ecuador in July 2010]]\nWhile the entire [[Mexico\u2013United States border]] has experienced high levels of drug trafficking and other illegal smuggling activities for decades, this activity tends to be concentrated in certain sectors within Texas. Two such sectors are the [[Rio Grande Valley]] and [[West Texas]], near the [[El Paso\u2013Ju\u00e1rez]] metropolitan area. The high level of legitimate travel and movement of goods and services between border cities in the U.S. and Mexico facilitates the drug business in the area. The majority of the commerce between the United States and Mexico passes through the state of Texas.<ref>{{cite web|title=An Overview of Federal Drug Control Programs on the Southwest Border|url=https://www.ncjrs.gov/ondcppubs/publications/enforce/border/intro_2.html|publisher=Office of National Drug Control Policy|accessdate=8 December 2011}}</ref> Due to its multifaceted transportation networks and proximity to major production areas right across the border in Mexico, Texas is a major hub for drug trafficking. According to the [[National Drug Intelligence Center]], drug traffickers commonly use private vehicles and commercial trucks to traffic narcotics throughout the state. The drug organizations usually use the Interstates [[Interstate 10 in Texas|10]], [[Interstate 20 in Texas|20]], [[Interstate 25|25]], [[Interstate 30|30]], and [[Interstate 35 in Texas|35]], as well as U.S. Highways [[U.S. Route 59 in Texas|59]], [[U.S. Route 77|77]], [[U.S. Route 83|83]], and [[U.S. Route 281|281]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Texas Drug Threat Assessment|url=http://www.justice.gov/ndic/pubs5/5624/overview.htm|publisher=National Drug Intelligence Center|accessdate=8 December 2011}}</ref> The [[Gulf of Mexico]] also presents a danger to the flow of drugs to Texas; the [[Port of Houston]] and the [[Port of Brownsville]] enable traffickers to use small vessels and pleasure craft to transport illicit drugs into and from southern Texas.<ref>{{cite web|title=South Texas Border and San Antonio Market Areas (2008)|url=http://www.justice.gov/ndic/pubs27/27513/border.htm|publisher=National Drug Intelligence Center|accessdate=8 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIllicit drugs also are smuggled into and through Texas via commercial aircraft, cars, buses, passenger trains, pedestrians, and package delivery services. Narcotics are also smuggled through the railroads that connect the U.S. and Mexico. Moreover, the Mexican drug traffickers often use small boats to transport drugs through the coastal areas of South Texas, usually operating at night to prevent them from being spotted by law enforcement officials.<ref>{{cite web|title=South Texas Border and San Antonio Market Areas (2007)|url=http://www.justice.gov/ndic/pubs22/22796/border.htm|publisher=National Drug Intelligence Center}}</ref> Another avenue that they have implemented is to construct [[tunnel]]s to get their product across the border. By constructing a tunnel, the cartel is able to get their product across the tight border security with the possibility of no detection.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nogales drug tunnel found|url=https://www.usatoday.com/USCP/PNI/NEWS/2011-11-23-PNI1123met-nogales-tunnelPNIBrd_ST_U.htm|accessdate=8 December 2011|newspaper=USA Today|date=23 November 2011}}</ref> Apart from using these common ways, once the product is across the border, common cars and trucks are utilized for faster distribution in different cities. In an effort to use the seas, the cartel also implemented the use of [[narco submarine]]s.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Kraul | title=Drug traffickers use submersibles to ferry narcotics | date=6 November 2007 |work=Los Angeles Times | url =https://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-narcosub6nov06,0,6804696.story | accessdate =19 February 2010 }}</ref><ref name=jitfs>{{Cite journal |title=Self-Propelled Semi-Submersible (SPSS) - Fact Sheet |publisher=Joint Interagency Task Force South |year=2008 |url=http://media.mcclatchydc.com/smedia/2008/07/18/17/Hall-SPSS-factsheet.source.prod_affiliate.91.pdf |access-date=19 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=Tamil >{{cite news | first=David | last=Kushner | title=Drug-Sub Culture | date=23 April 2009 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/26/magazine/26drugs-t.html?_r=1 | work =The New York Times | accessdate =25 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Indictments==\nOn 21 July 2009, the United States [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]] announced coordinated actions against the Gulf Cartel and [[Los Zetas]] drug trafficking organizations.  [[Antonio Ezequiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]], [[Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano]] and 15 of their top lieutenants, have been charged in U.S. federal courts with drug trafficking-related crimes,<ref name=drive >{{cite news | first= Glenn| last= Somerville| title=U.S. launches drive against Mexican drug cartel | date=20 July 2009 | url =https://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSN2091449 | work =Reuters | accessdate =18 August 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Alleged Mexican Cartel Leaders, Associates Targeted in Newest Effort to Combat Drug Trafficking Organizations|url=http://www.justice.gov/dea/pubs/pressrel/pr072009.html|accessdate=14 December 2011|newspaper=Drug Enforcement Administration|date=20 July 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114044432/http://www.justice.gov/dea/pubs/pressrel/pr072009.html|archive-date=14 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> while the U.S. State Department announced rewards totaling $50 million [[USD]] for information leading to their capture.<ref name=drive />\n\nIn May 2013, [[Aurelio Cano Flores]] (alias ''El Yankee'') was sentenced to 35 years in prison for conspiring to import multi-ton quantities of marijuana and cocaine into the United States. Cano Flores, also known as \"Yeyo\", was a former Mexican police officer and is the highest ranking Gulf Cartel member to be convicted by a U.S. jury in 15 years.<ref name=BBYankee>{{cite press release |title=CDG's 'El Yankee' Sentenced in D.C. to 35 Years |url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2013/05/cdgs-el-yankee-sentenced-in-dc-to-35.html|website=Borderland Beat |publisher=DEA-DOJ}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 June 2019, Mario Alberto C\u00e1rdenas Medina, the son of Osiel's brother Mario, was arrested in the state of Mexico.<ref>https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&u=https://www.univision.com/noticias/america-latina/autoridades-mexicanas-capturan-a-mario-cardenas-el-betito-sobrino-del-exlider-del-cartel-del-golfo&prev=search</ref><ref>https://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/cae-en-naucalpan-el-betito-sobrino-de-osiel-cardenas/1321715</ref> He was arrested with a female companion identified as Miriam \"M\" and is accused of being responsible for recent violence in Tamaulipas<ref>https://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/police-arrest-ex-drug-lords-nephew/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Illegal drug trade in Colombia]]\n*[[List of gangs in Mexico]]\n* [[List of Mexico's 37 most-wanted drug lords]]\n* [[M\u00e9rida Initiative]]\n* [[Mexican Drug War]]\n* [[Operation Solare]]\n* [[Timeline of the Mexican Drug War]]\n* [[War on Drugs]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/mexico/etc/gulf.html PBS Frontline: The Gulf Cartel], ''PBS'' (1997)\n* [http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/mexicos_cartel_wars_20110516/ Cartel Wars by Michael Deibert, Truthdig, 16 May 2011]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Drug Wars: Narco Warfare in the twenty first century. Flemming, Gary. Booksurge, 2008.\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3HEpDwAAQBAJ&dq|title=Los Zetas Inc.: Criminal Corporations, Energy, and Civil War in Mexico|last=Correa-Cabrera|first=Guadalupe|publisher=[[University of Texas Press]]|year=2017|isbn=978-1477312773|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Mexican Drug War}}\n\n{{Organized crime groups in America}}\n\n[[Category:Drug cartels in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Gangs in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mexican Drug War]]\n[[Category:Hispanic-American gangs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Criminal group based in Tamaulipas}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox Criminal organization\n| name = Gulf Cartel\n| image = GulfCartel-logo.jpg\n| caption = Logo of the Gulf Cartel\n| founded = 1930s\n| founding location = [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], [[Mexico]]\n| founded by = [[Juan Nepomuceno Guerra]], [[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]]\n| years active = 1930s\u2212present\n| territory = Northeastern Mexico (as well [[Tamaulipas]] and [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]]) and the [[United States|U.S.]] States of [[Texas]], and [[Georgia (U.S. State)|Georgia]]\n| ethnic makeup = Majority [[Mexican people|Mexican]], minority [[Guatemalan people|Guatemalan]]\n| leaders = Luis Alberto Flores Blanco (Pelochas), [[Juan Manuel Loza Salinas]]  (alias \"El Toro\")\n| criminal activities = [[Drug trafficking]], [[money laundering]], [[extortion]], [[kidnapping]], [[human trafficking]], [[robbery]], [[murder]], [[arms trafficking]], [[bribery]], [[Fence (criminal)|fencing]], [[counterfeiting]], [[police impersonation]], [[arson]], [[hate crimes]]\n| allies = [[Aryan Brotherhood of Texas]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCleskey|first1=Claire O'Neill|title=White Supremacist Gang Does Business with Gulf Cartel|url=http://www.insightcrime.org/news-briefs/white-supremacist-gang-does-business-with-gulf-cartel|publisher=InSight Crime|date=29 November 2012}}</ref> <br>[[Los Mexicles]]<br>[[Italian-American Mafia]]<ref name=\"guardianmafia\">{{cite news|title=Mexican cartels funneling shipments to Italian mafia through Texas|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/apr/22/mexico-drug-cartel-italy-mafia|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=9 February 2017|date=2009-04-22|last1=Newspapers|first1=Mcclatchy}}</ref><br>[['Ndrangheta]]<ref name=\"guardianmafia\"/> <br>[[Sinaloa Cartel]]\n| rivals =[[Los Zetas]]<br>[[Black Guerilla Family]]<br>[[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]]<br>[[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel]]<br>[[Tijuana Cartel]]<br>[[Guadalajara Cartel]]<br>[[Los Negros]] (disbanded)<br>[[Barrio Azteca]]<br>[[Los Santos (gang)|Los Santos]]<br>Siete Viejo <br>[[Los Zetas]] (Cartel Del Noreste) }}\nThe '''Gulf Cartel''' ({{lang-es|C\u00e1rtel del Golfo}}, ''Golfos'', or '''CDG''')<ref>{{cite news|title=La lucha entre 'golfos' y 'zetas' desgarra a Tamaulipas|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/laluchaentregolfosyzetasdesgarraatamaulipas-531921.html|newspaper=La Vanguardia|date=16 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El c\u00e1rtel del Golfo echa a Los Zetas de Tamaulipas|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/562a77fdb11ec7137554a9298b959641|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=5 April 2010|access-date=31 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110802181118/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/562a77fdb11ec7137554a9298b959641|archive-date=2 August 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is a criminal syndicate and [[Drug cartel|drug trafficking organization]] in [[Mexico]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel|url=http://insightcrime.org/criminal-groups/mexico/gulf-cartel|accessdate=19 September 2011|newspaper=Insight: Organized Crime in the Americas|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120702224457/http://www.insightcrime.org/criminal-groups/mexico/gulf-cartel|archivedate=2 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and perhaps one of the oldest organized crime groups in the country.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. AND MEXICAN RESPONSES TO MEXICAN DRUG TRAFFICKING ORGANIZATIONS|url=http://drugcaucus.senate.gov/Mexico-Report-Final-5-2011.pdf|newspaper=UNITED STATES SENATE CAUCUS|date=May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926190953/http://drugcaucus.senate.gov/Mexico-Report-Final-5-2011.pdf|archivedate=26 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is currently based in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], directly across the U.S. border from [[Brownsville, Texas]].\n\nTheir network is international, and are believed to have dealings with crime groups in [[Europe]], [[West Africa]], [[Asia]], [[Central America]], [[South America]], and the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Beittel|first=June S.|title=Mexico's Drug Trafficking Organizations: Source and Scope of the Rising Violence|journal=Congressional Research Service|date=7 September 2011|url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/row/R41576.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Campbell|first=Howard|title=Drug war zone: frontline dispatches from the streets of El Paso and Ju\u00e1rez|year=2009|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-0-292-72179-1|pages=310|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XO0zvdha0b8C&pg=PA22&dq=gulf+cartel#v=onepage&q=gulf%20cartel&f=false}}</ref> Besides [[drug trafficking]], the Gulf Cartel operates through [[protection racket]]s, [[assassination]]s, [[extortion]]s, [[kidnapping]]s, and other criminal activities.<ref>{{cite web|last=McCAUL|first=MICHAEL T.|title=A Line in the Sand: Confronting the Threat at the Southwest Border|url=http://www.house.gov/sites/members/tx10_mccaul/pdf/Investigaions-Border-Report.pdf|publisher=HOUSE COMMITTEE ON HOMELAND SECURITY|accessdate=12 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911170206/http://www.house.gov/sites/members/tx10_mccaul/pdf/Investigaions-Border-Report.pdf|archivedate=11 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The members of the Gulf Cartel are known for intimidating the population and for being particularly violent.<ref>{{cite book|last=Warner|first=Judith|title=U.S. Border Security: A Reference Handbook|year=2010|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-59884-407-8|pages=381|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HlcD0A0w6fgC&pg=PA192&dq=gulf+cartel#v=onepage&q=gulf%20cartel&f=false}}</ref>\n\nAlthough its founder [[Juan Nepomuceno Guerra]] smuggled alcohol in large quantities to the [[United States]] during the [[Prohibition in the United States|Prohibition]] era,<ref>{{cite book|last=Grillo|first=Ioan|title=El Narco: Inside Mexico's Criminal Insurgency|year=2011|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-60819-504-6|pages=256|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1G4FlXMOgfkC&pg=PT72&dq=gulf+cartel+prohibition#v=onepage&q=gulf%20cartel%20prohibition&f=false}}</ref> it was not until the 1980s that the cartel was formed and shifted to [[drug trafficking]]\u2014primarily [[cocaine]], [[methamphetamine]], and [[heroin]]\u2014under the command of Juan Nepomuceno Guerra and [[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Foundation: 1930s\u20131980s===\nThe Gulf Cartel, a drug cartel based in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], Mexico, was founded in the 1930s by [[Juan Nepomuceno Guerra]].{{sfn|Correa-Cabrera|2017|p=267}}<ref name=\"eZukP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/j/inl/narc/rewards/275633.htm|title=Narcotics Rewards Program|publisher=[[United States Department of State]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128145955/https://www.state.gov/j/inl/narc/rewards/275633.htm|archive-date=28 November 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Originally known as the Matamoros Cartel (Spanish: ''C\u00e1rtel de Matamoros''),<ref name=\"juanNguerra\">{{cite news|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=59269&tabla=nacion|title=Falleci\u00f3 el fundador del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|last=Peralta Gonz\u00e1lez|first=C\u00e9sar|date=12 July 2001|newspaper=El Universal|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328092305/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=59269&tabla=nacion|archivedate=28 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the Gulf Cartel initially [[Rum-running|smuggled alcohol]] and other illegal goods into the U.S.<ref name=\"eZukP\"/> Once the Prohibition era ended, the criminal group controlled gambling houses, prostitution rings, a car theft network, and other illegal smuggling.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2003/03/15/046n1soc.php?origen=soc-jus.html|title=La historia del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|last=Lira Saade|first=Carmen|date=15 March 2003|newspaper=La Jornada}}</ref> It grew significantly in the 1970s under the leadership of kingpin [[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]].<ref name=\"eZukP\"/>\n\n===Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego era (1980s-1990s)===\nBy the 1980s, Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego began incorporating [[cocaine]] into the drug trafficking operations, and started to have the upper hand on what was now considered the Gulf Cartel, the greatest criminal dynasty in the [[US-Mexico border]]. By negotiating with the [[Cali Cartel]],<ref>{{cite web|title=FBI Adds International Drug Dealer to \"Most-Wanted\" List|url=http://www.ndsn.org/april95/abrego.html|publisher=National Drug Strategy Network|accessdate=April 1995}}</ref> Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was able to secure 50% of the shipment out of [[Colombia]] as payment for delivery, instead of the US$1,500 per kilogram they were previously receiving. This renegotiation, however, forced Garcia \u00c1brego to guarantee the product's arrival from Colombia to its destination. Instead, he created [[warehouses]] along the Mexican's northern border to preserve hundreds of tons of [[cocaine]]; this allowed him to create a new distribution network and increase his political influence. In addition to trafficking drugs, Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego would ship cash to be [[Money laundering|laundered]], in the millions.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vindell|first=Tony|title=Reputed drug lord's brother under arrest|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/garcia-42481-abrego-arrest.html|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=15 October 1994}}</ref> Around 1994, it was estimated that the Gulf Cartel handled as much as \"one-third of all cocaine shipments\" into the United States from the [[Cali Cartel]] suppliers.<ref>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Peter H. |chapter=Drug Trafficking in Mexico |title=Coming together?: Mexico-United States relations |year=1997 |publisher=Brookings Institution Press |isbn=978-0-8157-1027-1 |page=132 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CxUU4tuC18YC&pg=PA132}}</ref> During the 1990s, the [[Attorney General of Mexico|PGR]], the Mexican attorney general's office, estimated that the Gulf Cartel was \"worth over $10 billion US dollars.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Jordan|first=David C.|title=Drug politics: dirty money and democracies|year=1999|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-3174-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/drugpolitics00davi/page/288 288]|url=https://archive.org/details/drugpolitics00davi|url-access=registration|quote=gulf cartel in U.S.}}</ref>\n\n====Corruption in the United States ====\nGarc\u00eda \u00c1brego's ties extended beyond the Mexican government corruption and into the [[United States]]. With the arrest of one of Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego's traffickers, Juan Antonio Ortiz, it became known the cartel would ship tons of cocaine in United States [[Immigration and Naturalization Service]] (INS) buses between the years of 1986 to 1990. The buses made great transportation, as Antonio Ortiz noted, since they were never stopped at the border.<ref name=\"Homage\">{{cite book|last=Weinberg|first=Bill|title=Homage to Chiapas: The New Indigenous Struggles in Mexico|url=https://archive.org/details/homagetochiapas00bill|url-access=registration|publisher=Verso Publishers|year=2000|pages=[https://archive.org/details/homagetochiapas00bill/page/371 371]|isbn=978-1-85984-372-7}}</ref>\n\nIt also became known that, in addition to the INS bus scam, Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego had a \"special deal\" with members of the [[Texas National Guard]] who would truck tons of cocaine and marijuana from South Texas to Houston for the cartel.<ref name=\"Homage\" />\n\nGarcia Abrego's reach became known when a United States [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) agent named Claude de la O, in 1986, stated in testimony against Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego that he received over US$100,000 in bribes and had leaked information that could have endangered an FBI informant as well as Mexican journalists. In 1989 Claude was removed  from the case for unknown reasons, retiring a year later. Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego bribed the agent in an attempt to gather more information on U.S. law enforcement operations.<ref name=\"NYTimes2\">{{cite news|title=At Drug Trial, Mexican Suspect Faces Accuser|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/20/world/at-drug-trial-mexican-suspect-faces-accuser.html|accessdate=18 September 2012|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=20 September 1996|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106002702/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/20/world/at-drug-trial-mexican-suspect-faces-accuser.html|archivedate=6 November 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Reign\">{{cite news|last=Dillon|first=Sam|title=Mexican Drug Gang's Reign of Blood|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/04/world/mexican-drug-gang-s-reign-of-blood.html|accessdate=18 September 2012|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=4 February 1996|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106002710/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/04/world/mexican-drug-gang-s-reign-of-blood.html|archivedate=6 November 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Arrest of \u00c1brego====\n[[File:Juan Garcia-Abrego.jpg|right|180px|thumb|[[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]], founder of the organization.]]\n[[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]]'s business had grown to such length that the [[FBI]] placed him on the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives, 1990s|Top Ten Most Wanted in 1995]]. He was the first drug trafficker to be on that list.<ref>{{cite news|title=Juan Garc\u00eda Abrego&nbsp;\u2013 Top Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1971762_1971761_1971728,00.html|newspaper=TIMES Magazine | date=23 June 2011}}</ref> On 14 January 1996, Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was arrested outside a ranch in [[Monterrey, Nuevo Le\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Mu\u00f1oz|first=Juan Miguel|title=M\u00e9xico detiene y entrega a Estados Unidos a su principal narcotraficante|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/internacional/COLOMBIA/ESTADOS_UNIDOS/MEXICO/Mexico/detiene/entrega/Estados/Unidos/principal/narcotraficante/elpepiint/19960116elpepiint_13/Tes|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|date=16 January 1996}}</ref> He was quickly extradited to the United States where he stood trial eight months after his arrest. Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was convicted for 22 counts of [[money laundering]], [[drug possession]] and [[drug trafficking]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mexican \"Gulf Cartel\" Leader Juan Garcia Abrego Convicted on U.S. Drug Charges|url=http://www.ndsn.org/nov96/abrego.html|publisher=National Drug Strategy Network|accessdate=November 1996}}</ref> Jurors also ordered the [[seizure]] of $350 million of Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego's [[assets]]&nbsp;\u2014 $75 million more than what was previously planned.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fineman|first=Mark|title=Mexican Drug Cartel Chief Convicted in U.S.|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1996-10-17/news/mn-57764_1_garcia-abrego|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=17 October 1996}}</ref> Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego is currently serving 11 life terms in a [[prison#Security levels|maximum security prison]] in [[Colorado|Colorado, U.S.]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Laura|title=Juan Garcia Abrego|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1971762_1971761_1971728,00.html|newspaper=TIME Special {{!}} CNN.com|date=23 June 2011}}</ref> In 1996, it was disclosed that Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego's organization paid millions of dollars in bribes to politicians and law enforcement officers for his protection. It was later proven after his arrest that the deputy attorney general in charge of Mexico's federal Judicial Police had accumulated more than $9 million US dollars for protecting Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego.<ref>{{cite book|last=Abadinsky|first=Howard|title=Organized Crime|year=2009|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-0-495-59966-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/organizedcrime00howa/page/462 462]|url=https://archive.org/details/organizedcrime00howa|url-access=registration|quote=gulf cartel.}}</ref>\n\nGarc\u00eda \u00c1brego's arrest was even subject to allegations of corruption. It is believed the Mexican government knew all Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego's whereabouts all along and had refused to arrest him due to information he possessed about the extent of corruption within the government. The arresting officer, a FJP commander, is believed to have received a [[bullet-proof]] [[Mercury Grand Marquis]] and US$500,000 from a rival cartel for enacting the arrest of Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego.<ref name=\"Organized\">{{cite book|last=Bailey|first=John J|author2=[[Roy Godson]]|title=Organized Crime and Democratic Governability: Mexico and the U.S.-Mexican Borderlands|publisher=University of Pittsburgh Press|year=2001|pages=48|isbn=978-0-8229-5758-4}}</ref>\n\nFurther theories put forward allege the arrest of Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was to satisfy U.S. demands and meet certification, from the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] (DOJ), as a trade partner, the vote set to take place on 1 March. Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was apprehended on 14 January 1996, and Mexico shortly after received certification on 1 March.<ref name=\"Pan\">{{cite book|last=Harrison|first=Lawrence E.|title=The Pan-American Dream: Do Latin America's Cultural Values Discourage True Partnership with the United States and Canada?|publisher=Westview Press|year=1997|pages=[https://archive.org/details/panamericandream00lawr/page/227 227, 228]|isbn=978-0-8133-3470-7|url=https://archive.org/details/panamericandream00lawr/page/227}}</ref>\n\n;United States v. Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego\nUpon his capture outside the city of [[Monterrey, Nuevo Le\u00f3n]], the drug lord was flown to [[Mexico City]] where U.S. federal agent took him on a private plane to [[Houston, Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Legendary Juan Garcia Abrego in U.S. custody|url=http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=28953_0_1_0_C|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120715121501/http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=28953_0_1_0_C|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 July 2012|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=16 January 1996}}</ref> Wearing slacks and a striped shirt, Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was immediately extradited to the [[United States]] where he was interviewed by a [[FBI]] agent, and confessed to have \"ordered people murdered and tortured,\" bribed top Mexican officials, and smuggled tons of narcotics into the United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=At Drug Trial, Mexican Suspect Faces Accuser|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/20/world/at-drug-trial-mexican-suspect-faces-accuser.html|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=20 September 1996}}</ref> His prosecutors, however, tried Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego as a U.S. citizen because he also had an American birth certificate, although Mexican authorities claimed the certificate was \"fraudulent.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Tedford|first=Deborah|title=Garcia Abrego is U.S. citizen, officials insist|url=http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl/1996_1322867/garcia-abrego-is-u-s-citizen-officials-insist.html|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Houston Chronicle|date=2 July 1996}}</ref> He also had an official birth certificate that claimed Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was indeed born in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Expulsion may have broken the law|url=http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=28901_0_1_0_C|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120715120503/http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=28901_0_1_0_C|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 July 2012|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=19 January 1996}}</ref> According to ''[[The Brownsville Herald]]'', Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego went into the courtroom grinning and talking animatedly with his lawyers who helped him translate his words from Spanish into the [[English language]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Langford|first=Terri|title=Life in jail for drug lord|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/abrego-23141-garcia-united.html|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=1 February 1997}}</ref> Hours after the judge told Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego that he was going to spend the rest of his life in prison, the [[death penalty]] was out of the question for the prosecutors.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Juan Garcia Abrego arraigned in U.S. FBI fugitive could spend life in prison|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/garcia-28967-abrego-fbi.html|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=17 January 1996}}</ref>\n\nThe factual documents presented in court on 8 May 1998, the Matamoros-based criminal syndicate of the Gulf Cartel was responsible for trafficking tremendous amounts of narcotics into the United States from the mid-1970s to the mid-1990s, and Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was given eleven life sentences in prison.<ref>{{cite web|title=UNITED STATES v. GARCIA ABREGO|url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-5th-circuit/1396381.html#footnote_ref_27|publisher=United States Court of Appeals: Fifth Circuit|accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref> During the four-week trial, 84 witnesses, ranging from \"law enforcement officers to convicted drug smugglers,\" confessed that Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego smuggled loads of Colombian cocaine on planes and then stored them in several border cities along the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]] before being smuggled to the [[Rio Grande Valley]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Marisa|title=Jury: Abrego guilty|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/garcia-32638-abrego-drug.html|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=17 October 1996}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, it was brought up that [[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego|Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]] had previously been arrested in [[Brownsville, Texas]] for six-year-old auto theft charges, but was released later with no charges whatsoever.<ref>{{cite news|last=Robbins|first=Maro|title=Garcia Abrego was allowed to go free|url=http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=35770_0_1_0_C|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120711202530/http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=35770_0_1_0_C|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 July 2012|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=27 August 1995}}</ref> Two men from the [[Rio Grande Valley]] were charged before the drug lord's arrest for laundering more than $30 million for Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Pe\u00f1a: Garcia Abrego hurt by huge bust Agents seize $22 million load of coke|url=http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=36985_0_1_0_C|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120714075942/http://old.brownsvilleherald.com/comments.php?id=36985_0_1_0_C|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 July 2012|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=30 November 1995}}</ref> He was also held responsible in 1984 for the massacre of 6 people in La Cl\u00ednica Raya, a hospital where rival drug members were being treated, and was also blamed for the massacre of the Cereso prison in 1991, where 18 prisoners were slain\u2014both in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|last=P\u00e9rez Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Jorge|title=Mentes perversas|url=http://www.hoytamaulipas.net/?v1=notas&v2=59427|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=Hoy Tamaulipas|date=22 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Vindell|first=Tony|title=El Profe welcomes Garcia Abrego's downfall|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/abrego-28849-garcia-lopez.html|accessdate=27 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=24 January 1996}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Althaus|first=Dudley|title=Texas-Mexico Borderlanconfrontads: The Slide Toward Chaos|journal=The International Journal of Continuing Social Work Education|year=2009|volume=12|issue=10974911|pages=57|url=http://www.profdevjournal.org/articles/122057.pdf|accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===After Garc\u00eda-\u00c1brego era ===\n\nFollowing \u00c1brego's 1996 arrest by Mexican authorities and subsequent deportation to the United States, a power vacuum was left and several top members fought for leadership.<ref>{{cite news|title=Historia y estructura del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.terra.com.mx/noticias/articulo/989908/Historia+y+estructura+del+Cartel+del+Golfo.htm|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=Terra Noticias}}</ref>\n\nHumberto Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego, brother of Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego, tried to take the lead of the Gulf Cartel, but ultimately failed in his attempt.<ref>{{cite news|last=Castillo|first=Gustavo|title=Desplazan a los Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego en liderato del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2009/05/02/politica/021n1pol|newspaper=La Jornada|date=2 May 2009}}</ref> He did not have the leadership skills nor the support of the Colombian drug-provisioners. In addition, he was under observation and was widely known, since his surname meant more of the same.<ref>{{cite news|last=Alzaga|first=Ignacio|title=Relegan a familia de Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego en c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8568516|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=1 May 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518012741/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8568516|archivedate=18 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was to be replaced by [[\u00d3scar Malherbe de Le\u00f3n]] and Ra\u00fal Valladares del \u00c1ngel, until their arrest a short time later,<ref>{{cite news|last=Weiner|first=Tim|title=Mexico Agrees To Extradite Drug Suspect To California|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/01/19/world/mexico-agrees-to-extradite-drug-suspect-to-california.html|newspaper=New York Times|date=19 January 2001}}</ref> causing several cartel lieutenants to fight for the leadership. Malherbe tried to bribe officials $2 million for his release, but it was denied.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lupsha|first=Peter|title=A Chronology {{!}} Murder, Money, & Mexico|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/mexico/etc/cron.html|publisher=University of New Mexico}}</ref> [[Hugo Baldomero Medina Garza]], known as ''El Se\u00f1or de los Tr\u00e1ilers'' (the lord of the Trailers), is considered one of the most important members in the rearticulation of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|last=Medell\u00edn|first=Alejandro|title=Medina Garza en 'La Palma'|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=46900&tabla=nacion|newspaper=El Universal|date=4 February 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328092001/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=46900&tabla=nacion|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was one of the top officials of the cartel for more than 40 years, trafficking about 20 tons of cocaine to the United States each month.<ref>{{cite news|last=Zendejas|first=Gabriel|title=Detectan a poderoso capo del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.oem.com.mx/esto/notas/n681175.htm|newspaper=La Prensa|accessdate=30 April 2008}}</ref> His luck ended in November 2000 when he was captured in [[Tampico]], [[Tamaulipas]] and imprisoned in [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1|La Palma]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ruiz|first=Jos\u00e9 Luis|title=Caen 21 miembros de c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=5327&tabla=primera|newspaper=El Universal|date=3 April 2001|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328092024/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=5327&tabla=primera|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After Medina Garza's arrest, his cousin Adalberto Garza Dragustinovis was investigated for allegedly forming part of the Gulf Cartel and for [[laundering money]], but the case is still open.<ref>{{cite news|title=Indagan a familiar de El Se\u00f1or de los Tr\u00e1ileres|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8055762|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120716191638/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8055762|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 July 2012|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=18 November 2008}}</ref> The next in line was Sergio G\u00f3mez alias ''El Checo'', however, his leadership was short lived when he was assassinated in April 1996 in [[Valle Hermoso, Tamaulipas|Valle Hermoso]], [[Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ram\u00edrez|first=Ignacio|title=La disputa del narcopoder|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=19691&tabla=nacion|newspaper=El Universal|date=10 April 2000|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328092114/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=19691&tabla=nacion|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After this, [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] took control of the cartel in July 1999 after assassinating Salvador G\u00f3mez Herrera alias ''El Chava'', co-leader of the Gulf Cartel and close friend of him, earning his name as the ''Mata Amigos'' (Friend Killer).<ref>{{cite news|title=Desde las entra\u00f1as del Ej\u00e9rcito, Los Zetas|url=http://www.blogdelnarco.info/desde-las-entranas-del-ejercito-los-zetas/|newspaper=Blog del Narco|date=23 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225120907/http://www.blogdelnarco.info/desde-las-entranas-del-ejercito-los-zetas/|archivedate=25 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n's era===\nAs confrontations with rival groups heated up, [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] sought and recruited over 30 deserters of the [[Mexican Army]]'s elite [[Grupo Aerom\u00f3vil de Fuerzas Especiales]] (GAFE) to form part of the cartel's armed wing.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Los Zetas\" se salen de control|url=http://www.eluniversal.mx/nacion/156964.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425031613/http://www.eluniversal.mx/nacion/156964.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=25 April 2012|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal}}</ref> [[Los Zetas]], as they are known, served as the hired private [[mercenary]] army of the Gulf Cartel. Nevertheless, after the arrest and [[extradition]] of C\u00e1rdenas, internal struggles led to a rupture between the Gulf and the Zetas.<ref>{{cite news|title=DEA: acuerdan 3 c\u00e1rteles alianza contra Los Zetas|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/562a77fdb11ec7137554a9298b28a727|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120629064442/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/562a77fdb11ec7137554a9298b28a727|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 June 2012|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=Milenio}}</ref>\n\n====Los Zetas====\n<!-- Commented out: [[File:OsielCardenasmugshot.jpg|left|140px|thumb|Mug shot of [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]].]] -->\nIn 1997 the Gulf Cartel began to recruit military personnel whom [[Jos\u00e9 de Jes\u00fas Guti\u00e9rrez Rebollo|Jes\u00fas Guti\u00e9rrez Rebollo]], an Army General of that time, had assigned as representatives from the [[Attorney General of Mexico|PGR]] offices in certain states across [[Mexico]]. After his imprisonment a short time later, Jorge Madrazo Cu\u00e9llar created the National Public Security System (SNSP), to fight the drug cartels along the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|U.S.\u2013Mexico border]]. After [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] took full control of the Gulf Cartel in 1999, he found himself in a no-holds-barred fight to keep his notorious organization and leadership untouched, and sought out members of the [[Grupo Aerom\u00f3vil de Fuerzas Especiales|Mexican Army Special Forces]] to become the military armed-wing of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u00bfQuienes son los Zetas?|url=http://www.blogdelnarco.info/%C2%BFquienes-son-los-zetas/|newspaper=Blog del Narco|date=7 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110729042942/http://www.blogdelnarco.info/%C2%BFquienes-son-los-zetas/|archivedate=29 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His goal was to protect himself from rival drug cartels and from the Mexican military, in order to perform vital functions  as the leader of the most powerful [[drug cartel]] in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|title=C\u00e1rtel de 'Los Zetas'|url=http://www.mundonarco.com/2011/01/cartel-del-los-zetas.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110118032606/http://www.mundonarco.com/2011/01/cartel-del-los-zetas.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 January 2011|newspaper=Mundo Narco|date=15 January 2011}}</ref> Among his first contacts was [[Arturo Guzm\u00e1n Decena]], an Army lieutenant who was reportedly asked by C\u00e1rdenas to look for the \"best men possible.\"<ref name=\"Grayson\">{{cite book|last=Grayson|first=George W.|title=Mexico: narco-violence and a failed state?|year=2010|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-1-4128-1151-4|pages=339|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ogjkeCd7RGoC&pg=PA180&lpg=PA180&dq=cardenas+reportedly+told+lt.+arturo+guzman+decenas+that+he+wanted+the+best+men+possible#v=onepage&q=wanted%20the%20best%20men%20possible&f=false}}</ref> Consequently, Guzm\u00e1n Decenas deserted from the Armed Forces and brought more than 30 army [[deserters]] to form part of C\u00e1rdenas' new  criminal paramilitary wing.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tobar|first=Hector|title=A cartel army's war within|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/may/20/world/fg-zetas20|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=20 May 2007}}</ref> They were enticed with salaries much higher than those of the Mexican Army.<ref>{{cite news|title=Los Zetas and Mexico's Transnational Drug War|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/04/los-zetas-and-mexicos-transnational.html|accessdate=9 December 2011|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]}}</ref> Among the original defectors were [[Jaime Gonz\u00e1lez Dur\u00e1n]],<ref>{{cite news| title=Los 'grandes capos' detenidos en la guerra contra el narcotr\u00e1fico de Calder\u00f3n| url=http://www.cnn.mx/nacional/2010/09/02/jaime-gonzalez-duran-el-hummer| newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico| date=6 November 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313101448/http://www.cnn.mx/nacional/2010/09/02/jaime-gonzalez-duran-el-hummer| archivedate=13 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Jes\u00fas Enrique Rej\u00f3n Aguilar]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Video Interrogatorio de Jes\u00fas Enrique Rej\u00f3n Aguilar \"El Mamito\"|url=http://www.mundonarco.com/2011/07/video-interrogatorio-jesus-enrique.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709024954/http://www.mundonarco.com/2011/07/video-interrogatorio-jesus-enrique.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 July 2011|newspaper=Mundo Narco|date=5 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Miguel Trevi\u00f1o Morales]],<ref>{{cite web| title=DEA Fugitive: TREVINO-MORALES, MIGUEL| url=http://www.justice.gov/dea/fugitives/houston/TREVINO-MORALES-miguel.html| publisher=U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510034621/http://www.justice.gov/dea//fugitives/houston/TREVINO-MORALES-miguel.html| archivedate=10 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Heriberto Lazcano]],<ref>{{cite news| title=Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano \"El Verdugo\"| url=http://www.blogdelnarco.info/heriberto-lazcano-lazcano-el-verdugo/| newspaper=Blog del Narco| date=3 March 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806204043/http://www.blogdelnarco.info/heriberto-lazcano-lazcano-el-verdugo/| archivedate=6 August 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> who would later become the supreme leader of the independent cartel of [[Los Zetas]]. The creation of Los Zetas brought a new era of [[drug trafficking]] in Mexico, and little did C\u00e1rdenas know that he was creating the most violent drug cartel in the country.<ref>{{cite news| last=Ware| first=Michael| title=Los Zetas called Mexico's most dangerous drug cartel| url=http://articles.cnn.com/2009-08-06/world/mexico.drug.cartels_1_los-zetas-drug-cartels-drug-war?_s=PM:WORLD| newspaper=CNN World| date=6 August 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015231342/http://articles.cnn.com/2009-08-06/world/mexico.drug.cartels_1_los-zetas-drug-cartels-drug-war?_s=PM:WORLD| archivedate=15 October 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Between 2001 and 2008, the organization of the Gulf Cartel and Los Zetas was collectively known as La Compa\u00f1\u00eda (''The Company'').<ref>{{cite news|last=Sherman|first=Chris|title=Texas jury convicts alleged Mexican cartel hit man|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/hit-58252-jury-mcallen.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120912194439/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/hit-58252-jury-mcallen.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 September 2012|accessdate=26 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=25 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOne of the first missions of Los Zetas was to eradicate Los Chachos, a group of drug traffickers under the orders of the [[Milenio Cartel]], who disputed the drug corridors of [[Tamaulipas]] with the Gulf Cartel in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=Surge nuevo 'narcoperfil|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=100976&tabla=nacion|accessdate=9 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111155629/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=100976&tabla=nacion|archivedate=11 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This gang was controlled by Dionisio Rom\u00e1n Garc\u00eda S\u00e1nchez alias ''El Chacho'', who had decided to betray the Gulf Cartel and switch his alliance with the [[Tijuana Cartel]]; however, he was eventually killed by Los Zetas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Organized crime and terrorist activity in Mexico, 1999-2002|url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/frd/pdf-files/OrgCrime_Mexico.pdf|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref> Once C\u00e1rdenas consolidated his position and supremacy, he expanded the responsibilities of Los Zetas, and as years passed, they became much more important for the Gulf Cartel. They began to organize [[kidnappings]];<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Narco gangster reveals the underworld|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/topstory/7607122.html#loopbegin|newspaper=Houston Chronicle}}</ref> impose taxes, collect debts, and operate [[protection racket]]s;<ref>{{cite web|title=The Mexican Drug War and the Thirty Years' War|url=http://bellum.stanfordreview.org/?p=3015|publisher=Bellum: The Stanford Review|accessdate=8 February 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110305074956/http://bellum.stanfordreview.org/?p=3015|archivedate=5 March 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> control the [[extortion]] business;<ref>{{cite news|title=Army troops capture a Zetas cartel boss in northern Mexico|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2011/02/15/army-troops-capture-zetas-cartel-boss-northern-mexico/|newspaper=Fox News Latino|date=15 February 2011}}</ref> securing [[cocaine]] supply and trafficking routes known as ''plazas'' (zones) and executing its foes, often with grotesque savagery.<ref name=\"Grayson\"/> In response to the rising power of the Gulf Cartel, the rival [[Sinaloa Cartel]]<ref>{{cite news|title=\u00bfQu\u00e9 es el Cartel de Sinaloa?|url=http://www.perfil.com/contenidos/2008/08/24/noticia_0023.html|newspaper=Perfil.com|date=24 August 2008}}</ref> established a heavily armed, well-trained enforcer group known as [[Los Negros]].<ref>{{cite news|last=S\u00e1nchez|first=Alex|title=Mexico's Drug War: Soldiers versus Narco-Soldiers|url=http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=f85a9ff12311fcc1895e0801f6df8d2f|newspaper=New American Media {{!}} La Prensa San Diego|date=4 June 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320042633/http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=f85a9ff12311fcc1895e0801f6df8d2f|archivedate=20 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The group operated similar to Los Zetas, but with less complexity and success. There is a circle of experts who believe that the start of the [[Mexican Drug War]] did not begin in 2006 (when [[Felipe Calder\u00f3n]] sent troops to Michoac\u00e1n to stop the increasing violence), but in 2004 in the border city of [[Nuevo Laredo]], when the Gulf Cartel and [[Los Zetas]] fought off the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] and [[Los Negros]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Fantz|first=Ashley|title=Saldo por el combate al narcotr\u00e1fico: muerte por un negocio millonario|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2012/01/22/saldo-por-el-combate-al-narcotrafico-muerte-por-un-negocio-millonario|accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=22 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123202055/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2012/01/22/saldo-por-el-combate-al-narcotrafico-muerte-por-un-negocio-millonario|archivedate=23 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, there were three main divisions of the Cartel, all ruled over by C\u00e1rdenas and led by: Jorge Eduardo \"[[Jorge Eduardo Costilla Sanchez|El Coss]]\" Costilla, Ezequiel \"[[Antonio Cardenas Guillen|Tony Tormenta]]\" C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n, and Heriberto \"[[Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano|El Lazca]]\" Lazcano.<ref name=BBTestimonyRafael>{{cite web |url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2012/09/cartel-boss-everyone-from-cops-to.html |title=Cartel boss: Everyone from cops to strippers worked for me |accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nUpon the arrest of the Gulf Cartel boss C\u00e1rdenas in 2003 and his [[extradition]] in 2007, the panorama for Los Zetas changed\u2014they started to become synonymous with the Gulf Cartel, and their influences grew greater within the organization.<ref>{{cite web|title=Drug Trafficking Organizations|url=http://www.justice.gov/ndic/pubs32/32781/dtos.htm|publisher=National Drug Intelligence Center|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref> Los Zetas began to grow independently from the Gulf Cartel, and eventually a rupture occurred between them in early 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Weekend shootouts in northeastern Mexico kill at least 9|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2010-04-12/world/mexico.deaths_1_zetas-gulf-cartel-familia-michoacana?_s=PM:WORLD|accessdate=9 December 2011|newspaper=CNN News|date=17 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315102415/http://articles.cnn.com/2010-04-12/world/mexico.deaths_1_zetas-gulf-cartel-familia-michoacana?_s=PM:WORLD|archivedate=15 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El origen de 'Los Zetas': brazo armado del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/05/el-origen-de-los-zetas-brazo-armado-del-cartel-del-golfo|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=5 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130128174447/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/05/el-origen-de-los-zetas-brazo-armado-del-cartel-del-golfo|archivedate=28 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Standoff with U.S. agents==\n{{Main|1999 Matamoros standoff}}\nOn 9 November 1999, two U.S. agents from the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA) and [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) were threatened at gunpoint by C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n and approximately fifteen of his henchmen in Matamoros. The two agents travelled to Matamoros with an informant to gather intelligence on the operations of the Gulf Cartel.<ref name=deastandoff>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mysanantonio.com/news/mexico/article/Dangers-higher-for-federal-agents-1033781.php|title=Dangers higher for federal agents|last=Buch|first=Json|date=28 February 2011|work=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127110405/https://www.mysanantonio.com/news/mexico/article/Dangers-higher-for-federal-agents-1033781.php|archive-date=27 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"deahouston\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/DEA-agent-breaks-silence-on-standoff-with-cartel-1713234.php|title=DEA agent breaks silence on standoff with cartel|last=Schiller|first=Dane|date=15 March 2010|work=[[The Houston Chronicle]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127193446/https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/DEA-agent-breaks-silence-on-standoff-with-cartel-1713234.php|archive-date=27 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n demanded the agents and the informant to get out of their vehicle, but they refused to obey his orders. The incident escalated as C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n threatened to kill them if they did not comply and as his gunmen prepared to shoot. The agents tried to reason with him that killing U.S. federal agents would bring a massive manhunt from the U.S. government. C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n eventually let them go and threatened to kill them if they ever returned to his home turf.<ref name=deastandoff/>\n\nThe standoff triggered a massive law enforcement effort to crackdown the leadership structure of the Gulf Cartel. Both the Mexican and U.S. government increased their efforts to apprehend C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n. Prior to the standoff, he was regarded as a minor player in the [[Illegal drug trade|international drug trade]], but this incident catapulted his reputation and made him one of the most-wanted criminals.<ref name=\"graysondea\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/valley/grayson-zapata-slaying-will-have-repercussions/article_9ea1164e-6747-5656-8dc9-10d46ea919bc.html|title=Grayson: Zapata slaying will have repercussions|last=|first=|date=17 February 2011|work=[[The Brownsville Herald]]|access-date=}}</ref> The FBI and the DEA mounted numerous charges against him and issued a US$2 million bounty for his arrest.<ref name=\"2milreward\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dea.gov/pubs/pressrel/pr121400.htm|title=$2 Million Reward Offered Leading To The Arrest or Conviction of Drug Traffickers|date=14 December 2000|publisher=[[Drug Enforcement Administration]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070203212334/https://www.dea.gov/pubs/pressrel/pr121400.htm|archive-date=3 February 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Arrest and extradition ===\n[[File:OsielCardenas-DEA.jpg|left|220px|thumb|Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n's [[extradition]] to the United States from Mexico.]]\nThe former leader of the Gulf Cartel, [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], was captured in the city of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], on 14 March 2003  in a shootout between the Mexican military and Gulf Cartel gunmen.<ref name=\"arrest\">{{cite news | title='Drug boss' captured in Mexico | date=15 March 2003 |work=BBC News | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/2852197.stm | accessdate =25 February 2010 }}</ref> He was one of the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]], which was offering $2 million for his capture.<ref>{{cite web|title=Osiel Cardenas-Guillen|url=https://www.fbi.gov/houston/press-releases/2010/ho022410b.htm|publisher=Federal Bureau of Investigation|accessdate=24 February 2010}}</ref> According to government archives, this six-month military operation was planned and carried out in secret; the only people informed were the President [[Vicente Fox]], the Secretary of Defense in Mexico, Ricardo Clemente Vega Garc\u00eda, and Mexico's Attorney General, Rafael Macedo de la Concha.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cae Osiel C\u00e1rdenas: Se enfrent\u00f3 a tiros con el Ej\u00e9rcito|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=94595&tabla=Nacion_H|newspaper=El Universal|date=15 March 2003|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328092143/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=94595&tabla=Nacion_H|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After his capture, C\u00e1rdenas was sent to the federal, high-security prison [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1|La Palma]].<ref>{{cite news |agency=Notimex |title=Nuevo auto de formal prisi\u00f3n a Osiel C\u00e1rdenas |url=http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/466430.html |newspaper=Esmas.com |date=August 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004042205/http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/466430.html |archive-date=4 October 2012}}</ref> However, it was believed that C\u00e1rdenas still controlled the Gulf Cartel from prison,<ref>{{cite news|last=Aponte|first=David|title=L\u00edderes narcos pactan en La Palma trasriego de droga|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=119863&tabla=nacion|newspaper=El Universal|date=5 January 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328092221/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=119863&tabla=nacion|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and was later extradicted to the United States, where he was sentenced to 25 years in a prison in [[Houston, Texas]] for [[money laundering]], [[drug trafficking]], [[homicide]] and death threats to U.S. federal agents.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sentencian a Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n a 25 a\u00f1os de prisi\u00f3n en Texas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/02/24/sentencian-a-osiel-cardenas-guillen-a-25-anos-de-prision-en-texas|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=24 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904020823/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/02/24/sentencian-a-osiel-cardenas-guillen-a-25-anos-de-prision-en-texas|archivedate=4 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Reports from the [[Attorney General of Mexico|PGR]] and ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]'' state that while in prison, C\u00e1rdenas and [[Benjam\u00edn Arellano F\u00e9lix]], from the [[Tijuana Cartel]], formed an alliance. Moreover, through handwritten notes, C\u00e1rdenas gave orders on the movement of drugs along Mexico and to the United States, approved executions, and signed forms to allow the purchase of police forces.<ref name=\"BehindBars\">{{cite news|title=Maneja Osiel mafia desde la carcel, prueban|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=120380&tabla=nacion|accessdate=5 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419021522/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=120380&tabla=nacion|archivedate=19 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> And while his brother [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guillen|Antonio]] led the Gulf Cartel, C\u00e1rdenas still made vital orders from [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1|La Palma]] through messages from his lawyers and guards.<ref name=\"BehindBars\"/>\n\nThe arrest and extradition of C\u00e1rdenas, however, caused for several top lieutenants from both the Gulf Cartel and Los Zetas to fight over important [[drug corridor]]s to the [[United States]], especially the cities of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]], [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas|Nuevo Laredo]], [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas|Reynosa]], and [[Tampico, Tamaulipas|Tampico]]\u2014all situated in the state of [[Tamaulipas]]. They also fought for coastal cities [[Acapulco, Guerrero]] and [[Canc\u00fan, Quintana Roo]]; the state capital of [[Monterrey, Nuevo Le\u00f3n]], and the states of [[Veracruz (state)|Veracruz]] and [[San Luis Potos\u00ed (state)|San Luis Potos\u00ed]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Desertor del Ej\u00e9rcito, nuevo l\u00edder del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo: informes castrenses|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2008/02/03/index.php?section=politica&article=009n1pol|newspaper=La Jornada|date=3 February 2008}}</ref> Through his violence and intimidation, [[Heriberto Lazcano]] took control of both Los Zetas and the Gulf Cartel after Cardenas' extradition.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Notimex |title=Detienen a un l\u00edder del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo en Tabasco |url=http://www2.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/011667/detienen-lider-del-cartel-del-golfo-tabasco |newspaper=Esmas.com |date=7 September 2008}}</ref> Lieutenants that were once loyal to C\u00e1rdenas began following the commands of Lazcano, who tried to reorganize the cartel by appointing several lieutenants to control specific territories. [[Miguel Trevi\u00f1o Morales|Morales Trevi\u00f1o]] was appointed to look over [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Miguel Morales Trevi\u00f1o, Z-40, un narco violento ya est\u00e1 en la mira|url=http://www.mundonarco.com/2010/12/miguel-trevino-morales-alias-el-z-40-un.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223101533/http://www.mundonarco.com/2010/12/miguel-trevino-morales-alias-el-z-40-un.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 December 2010|newspaper=Mundo Narco|date=22 December 2010}}</ref> [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]] in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Loz Zetas: Grupo Paramilitar Mexicano|url=http://www.policiasysociedad.org/userfiles/aclaracionessobreloszetas_esp.pdf|publisher=Policias y Sociedad|accessdate=6 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626114555/http://www.policiasysociedad.org/userfiles/aclaracionessobreloszetas_esp.pdf|archive-date=26 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[H\u00e9ctor Manuel Sauceda Gamboa]], nicknamed ''El Karis'', took control of [[Nuevo Laredo]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Cartel leader believed slain in Reynosa violence|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/leader-23347-cartel-violence.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520033957/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/leader-23347-cartel-violence.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 May 2009|newspaper=The Monitor|date=17 February 2009}}</ref> Gregorio Sauceda Gamboa, known as ''El Goyo'', along with his brother Arturo, took control of the [[Reynosa]] plaza;<ref>{{cite news|title=Confirman militares enfrentamiento con narcotraficantes|url=http://www.juanruizhealy.com/articulos/notas_de_ventanas/el_manana.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020105081924/http://www.juanruizhealy.com/articulos/notas_de_ventanas/el_manana.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 January 2002|newspaper=El Ma\u00f1ana: Reynosa|date=27 November 2009}}</ref> Arturo Basurto Pe\u00f1a, alias ''El Grande'', and [[Iv\u00e1n Vel\u00e1zquez-Caballero]] alias ''El Talib\u00e1n'' took control of [[Quintana Roo]] and [[Guerrero]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Revelan que desertor del Ej\u00e9rcito mexicano liderea C\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.elporvenir.com.mx/notas.asp?nota_id=191211|newspaper=El Porvenir|date=3 February 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406214727/http://www.elporvenir.com.mx/notas.asp?nota_id=191211|archivedate=6 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Alberto S\u00e1nchez Hinojosa, alias ''Comandante Castillo'', took over [[Tabasco]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Capturan al l\u00edder de los 'Zetas' en Tabasco|url=http://www.tabascohoy.com/noticia.php?id_nota=162045|newspaper=Tabasco Hoy|date=8 September 2008}}</ref> However, continual disagreement was leading the Gulf Cartel and Los Zetas into an inevitable rupture.\nOn 18 August 2013, Gulf Cartel leader Mario Ramirez Trevino was captured.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico Gulf Cartel leader Mario Ramirez Trevino captured|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-23744425|newspaper=BBC News|date=18 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n;United States vs Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n\nIn 2007, [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] was extradited to the United States and charged with the involvement of conspiracies to traffic large amounts of marijuana and cocaine, violating the \"continuing-criminal-enterprise statute\" (also known as the \"drug kingpin statute\"), and for threatening two U.S. federal officers.<ref>{{cite web|title=United States of America v. Cardenas-Guillen|url=http://www.ca5.uscourts.gov/opinions/pub/10/10-40221-CV0.wpd.pdf|publisher=United States Court of Appeals for the Southern District of Texas|accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> The standoff the two agents had with the drug lord in 1999 in the city of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]] led for the U.S. to indict C\u00e1rdenas and pressure the Mexican government to capture him.<ref>{{cite news|title=DEA agent talks of 1999 Matamoros standoff with Osiel Cardenas-Guillen|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/houston-109730-matamoros-agent.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=15 March 2010}}</ref> In 2010 he was finally sentenced to 25 years in prison after being charged with 22 [[Federal crime in the United States|federal charges]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Extradition: Past cases highlight limits|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/former-123571-boss-past.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=5 March 2011}}</ref> the courtroom was locked and the public prevented from witnessing the proceeding.<ref>{{cite news|last=Langford|first=Terri|title=New U.S. attorney no stranger to Houston|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/New-U-S-attorney-no-stranger-to-Houston-2261216.php|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Houston Chronicle|date=9 November 2011}}</ref> The proceedings took place in the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Texas]] in the border city of [[Brownsville, Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Perez|first=Emma|title=Cardenas Guillen awaits trial|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/guillen-90235-cardenas-trial.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=23 September 2008}}</ref> C\u00e1rdenas has been isolated from interacting with other prisoners in the [[supermax|supermax prison]] he is in.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Mexican drug lords decry U.S. prison conditions|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Mexican-drug-lords-decry-U-S-prison-conditions-2195808.php|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Houston Chronicle|date=30 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nNearly $30 million of the former drug lord's assets were distributed among several Texan law enforcement agencies.<ref>{{cite news|title=Assets from drug boss go to Texas law enforcement|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Assets-from-drug-boss-go-to-Texas-law-enforcement-2584517.php|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Houston Chronicle|date=17 January 2012}}</ref> In exchange for another life-sentence, C\u00e1rdenas agreed to collaborate with U.S. agents in intelligence information.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Trafficking defendant: I was a DEA informer|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Trafficking-defendant-I-was-a-DEA-informer-1717657.php|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Houston Chronicle|date=4 August 2011}}</ref> The U.S. federal court awarded two [[helicopters]] owned by C\u00e1rdenas to the [[Business Development Bank of Canada]] and the GE Canada Equipment Financing respectively, and both of them were brought from \"drug proceeds\".<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. turns over custody of Cardenas-Guillen helicopters to businesses|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/helicopters-48551-cardenas-guillen.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110402045519/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/helicopters-48551-cardenas-guillen.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 April 2011|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Rupture from Los Zetas ===\nIt is unclear which of the two\u2014the Gulf Cartel or Los Zetas\u2014started the conflict that led to their break up. It is clear, however, that after the capture and extradition of [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], Los Zetas outclassed the Gulf Cartel in revenue, membership, and influence.<ref>{{cite web |first=Dana M. |last=Grimes |date=2010 |title=Law and Order in Mexico |url=http://www.grimesandwarwick.com/law_and_order |website=GrimesandWarwick |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111132042/http://www.grimesandwarwick.com/law_and_order |archive-date=11 January 2012}}</ref> Some sources reveal that as a result of the supremacy of [[Los Zetas]], the Gulf Cartel felt threatened by the growing force of their own enforcer group and decided to curtail their influence, but eventually failed in their attempt, instigating a war.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico's Cartels Declare War on the Zetas|url=http://www.geopoliticalmonitor.com/mexicos-cartels-declare-war-on-the-zetas-1/|newspaper=Geopolitical Monitor|date=19 April 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329054530/http://www.geopoliticalmonitor.com/mexicos-cartels-declare-war-on-the-zetas-1/|archivedate=29 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to ''narco-banners'' left by the Gulf Cartel in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], and [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]], the reason for their rupture was that Los Zetas had expanded their operations to include [[extortion]], [[kidnapping]], assassinations, theft, and other actions with which it disagreed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel split with Zetas made public|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/03/gulf-cartel-split-with-zetas-public.html|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=10 March 2010}}</ref> Unwilling to stand for such abuse, [[Los Zetas]] responded and countered the accusations by posting their own banners throughout [[Tamaulipas]]. They pointedly noted that they had carried out [[execution]]s and [[kidnapping]]s under orders of the Gulf Cartel when they served as their enforcers, and they were originally created by them for that sole purpose.<ref name=Narcobanners>{{cite news|title=Mexican cartels strategize to win hearts and minds|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/strategize-48350-win-cartels.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614103932/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/strategize-48350-win-cartels.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 June 2012|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=The Monitor}}</ref> In addition, Los Zetas mentioned that the Gulf Cartel also kills innocent civilians, and then blames them for their atrocities.<ref name=Narcobanners/>\n\nNevertheless, other sources also reveal that [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] (a.k.a. ''Tony Tormenta''), brother of Osiel and one of the successors of the Gulf Cartel, was addicted to gambling, sex, and drugs, leading [[Los Zetas]] to consider his leadership as a threat to the organization.<ref>{{cite news|title=Otro C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n hereda la organizaci\u00f3n|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/otrocardenasguillenheredalaorganizacion-585572.html|newspaper=Vanguardia|date=8 November 2010}}</ref> Other reports mention, however, that the rupture occurred due to a disagreement on who would take on the leadership of the cartel after the extradition of Osiel Cardenas. The candidates of the Gulf Cartel were Antonio C\u00e1rdenas and [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]], while Los Zetas wanted the leadership of their current head, [[Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Authorities: Gulf Cartel, Zetas gang up on each other as arrangement dies|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/gulf-36258-arrangement-reynosa.html|newspaper=The Monitor|date=10 March 2010<!-- 12:55 PM-->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120912222804/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/gulf-36258-arrangement-reynosa.html|archivedate=12 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Other sources, however, mention that the Gulf Cartel began looking to form a truce with their [[Sinaloa Cartel]] rivals, and Los Zetas did not want to recognize the treaty settlement, which led them to act independently and eventually break apart.<ref>{{cite news|title=War between Gulf Cartel, Zetas marks year anniversary|url=http://www.valleymorningstar.com/articles/year-89095-war-agent.html|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald: Valley Morning Star|date=7 March 2011}}</ref> On the other hand, other sources reveal that [[Los Zetas]] separated from the Gulf Cartel to form an alliance with [[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel]], which led to conflict between them.<ref>{{cite web|last=Longmire|first=Sylvia|title=TCO 101: The Gulf Cartel|url=http://borderviolenceanalysis.typepad.com/mexicos_drug_war/dto-101-the-gulf-cartel.html|publisher=Mexico's drug war|accessdate=9 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025095641/http://borderviolenceanalysis.typepad.com/mexicos_drug_war/dto-101-the-gulf-cartel.html|archivedate=25 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Other sources mention that what initiated the conflict between them was when Samuel Flores Borrego, alias ''El Metro 3'', lieutenant of the Gulf Cartel, killed Sergio Pe\u00f1a Mendoza, alias ''El Concorde 3'', lieutenant of Los Zetas, due to a disagreement for the drug corridor of [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]], whom both protected.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ejecuci\u00f3n de \"El Concorde\" deton\u00f3 guerra en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/176125.html|newspaper=El Universal|date=7 March 2010}}</ref> Soon after his death, [[Los Zetas]] demanded for the Gulf Cartel to hand over the killer, but they didn't, and observers believe that triggered the war.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Gulf-Zeta Split and the Praetorian Revolt|url=http://www.isn.ethz.ch/isn/Current-Affairs/Security-Watch-Archive/Detail/?id=114551&lng=en|newspaper=ISN|date=7 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Tamaulipas]] was mostly spared from the violence until early 2010, when the Gulf Cartel's enforcers, [[Los Zetas]], split from and turned against the Gulf Cartel, sparking a bloody turf war. When the hostilities began, the Gulf organization joined forces with its former rivals, the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] and [[La Familia Michoacana]], aiming to take out Los Zetas.<ref>{{cite news|title=M\u00e9xico: Los Zetas rompen con el Cartel del Golfo|url=http://www.semana.com/america-latina/mexico-zetas-rompen-cartel-del-golfo/135516-3.aspx|newspaper=BBC Mundo {{!}} Semana.com|date=26 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hern\u00e1ndez|first=Jaime|title=EU: alarma guerra \"Zetas\"-El Golfo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/176052.html|newspaper=El Universal|date=4 March 2010}}</ref> Consequently, Los Zetas allied with the [[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]], the [[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel]], and the [[Tijuana Cartel]].<ref>{{cite news|title=El c\u00e1rtel de los Zetas tiende acuerdos de \"no agresi\u00f3n y colaboraci\u00f3n\"|url=http://america.infobae.com/notas/20350-El-cartel-de-los-Zetas-tiende-acuerdos-de-no-agresion-y-colaboracion|accessdate=14 December 2011|newspaper=Infobae|date=8 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530081447/http://america.infobae.com/notas/20350-El-cartel-de-los-Zetas-tiende-acuerdos-de-no-agresion-y-colaboracion|archivedate=30 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel lieutenant's associates enter plea agreement|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/gulf-57270-lieutenant-agreement.html|accessdate=14 December 2011|newspaper=The Monitor|date=13 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614104050/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/gulf-57270-lieutenant-agreement.html|archivedate=14 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n's era===\nOsiel C\u00e1rdenas' brother, [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] (''Tony Tormenta''), along with [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]] (alias ''El Coss''), a former policeman, filled in the vacuum left by Osiel and became the leaders of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tiene nuevo lider del cartel del Golfo|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=114708&tabla=nacion|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419021504/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=114708&tabla=nacion|archivedate=19 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The death of ''Tony Tormenta'', the nickname given to Antonio C\u00e1rdenas for his explosive behavior,<ref>{{cite news|title=Los 'grandes capos' detenidos en la guerra contra el narcotr\u00e1fico de Calder\u00f3n|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/06/arturo-ezequiel-cardenas-guillen-tony-tormenta|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=6 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403041516/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/06/arturo-ezequiel-cardenas-guillen-tony-tormenta|archivedate=3 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> allowed for Costilla S\u00e1nchez to become the co-leader of the Gulf Cartel and head of the Metros, one of the two factions within the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ej\u00e9rcito, Armada y PF van tras El Coss, segundo heredero del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2010/11/09/politica/009n1pol|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=La Jornada}}</ref> [[Mario C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], brother of Osiel and Antonio, is the other leader of Gulf Cartel and head of the Rojos, the other faction within the Gulf Cartel and the parallel version of the Metros.<ref>{{cite news|title=Another Cardenas-Guillen inherits the organization|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/11/another-cardenas-guillen-inherits-gulf.html|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Se lanza la PGR por m\u00e1s l\u00edderes del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.oem.com.mx/elmexicano/notas/n1848385.htm|publisher=Organizaci\u00f3n Editorial Mexicana|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nCostilla was often viewed as the \"strongest leader\" of the two, but collaborated with Antonio C\u00e1rdenas, who acted as representative of his jailed brother.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"El Coss\", nuevo \"amo\" del grupo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/181707.html|accessdate=7 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal}}</ref> However, Antonio died in an eight-hour shooting with the Mexican government forces on 5 November 2010 in the border city of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tony Tormenta muere abatido|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/721541.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=El Universal}}</ref>  Government sources claimed that this operation\u2014where more than 660 marines, 17 vehicles, and 3 helicopters participated\u2014left 8 dead: three marines, one soldier, and four gunmen, including Antonio C\u00e1rdenas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Operativo contra Tony Tormenta dej\u00f3 8 muertos|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/721586.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=El Universal}}</ref> Other sources mention that one news reporter was also killed in the crossfire.<ref>{{cite news|last=G. Garc\u00eda|first=Jacobo|title=Tres militares, 'Tony Tormenta' y un periodista|url=http://www.elmundo.es/america/2010/11/07/mexico/1289084614.html|newspaper=El Mundo|date=11 July 2010}}</ref> This military-led operation was a result of more than six months of intelligence work and some operational actions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexican drug cartel leader 'Tony Tormenta' killed during two-hour gun battle with marines|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1327188/Mexican-drug-cartel-leader-Tony-Tormenta-killed-hour-gun-battle-marines.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=Dailymail {{!}} UK|date=8 November 2010}}</ref> ''[[Milenio Television]]'' mentioned that the Mexican authorities had tried to apprehend C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n twice before this incident, but that his personal gunmen had distracted the Mexican forces and allowed him to be escorted in his armored vehicle.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mosso|first=Ruben|title=Operativo de seis meses llev\u00f3 a abatimiento de Tony Tormenta: Secretar\u00eda de Marina|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/d9733f1d182257206a2cdeac4f1ff29c|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120908000658/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/d9733f1d182257206a2cdeac4f1ff29c|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 September 2012|accessdate=27 December 2011|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=7 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe confrontations started around 10:00AM, and extended to 06:00PM, around the time C\u00e1rdenas Guil\u00e9n was killed. The intense shootings provoked the temporary closure of three international bridges in Matamoros,<ref>{{cite news|title=Cae \"Tony Tormenta\", lider del cartel del Golfo|url=http://www.abc.es/20101106/internacional/tony-tormenta-201011060055.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=ABC Internacional}}</ref> along with the [[University of Texas at Brownsville]], just across the border.<ref>{{cite news|title=In aftermath, UTB-TSC works to protect students|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/utb-119098-temporarily-texas.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald}}</ref> Public transportation and school classes in Matamoros were canceled, along with the suspension of activities throughout the [[Matamoros Municipality, Tamaulipas|municipality]], since the cartel members hijacked the units of public transport and made dozens of roadblocks to prevent the mobilization of the soldiers, marines, and federal police forces.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ocho horas de balaceras, en Matamoros|url=http://www2.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/estados/224820/ocho-horas-balaceras-matamoros|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=Esmas Noticias}}</ref> The street confrontations generated a wave of panic among the population and caused the publication and broadcast of messages through social networks like [[Twitter]] and [[Facebook]], reporting the clashes between authorities and the cartel members.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reputed Gulf cartel leader killed in Mexico shootout|url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/newupdated/ci_16536005|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=El Paso Times|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120729140838/http://www.elpasotimes.com/newupdated/ci_16536005|archivedate=29 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> When the Mexican authorities reached the spot where Antonio C\u00e1rdenas (''Tony Tormenta'') was present, the gunmen received the soldiers and cops with grenades and high-calibre shots. Reports mention that Antonio C\u00e1rdenas was being protected by the Los Escorpiones (''The Scorpions''), the alleged armed wing of the Gulf Cartel and the personal army of Antonio C\u00e1rdenas, who were serving as [[snipers]] and [[bodyguards]] for him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Secretar\u00eda de Marina, detenciones en tierra|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/23/antonio-ezequiel-cardenas-guillen-tony-tormenta|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=23 November 2010}}</ref> ''[[La Jornada]]'' newspaper mentioned that over 80 SUV's packed with gunmen fought to protect C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n, and over 300 grenades were used in the shootout that day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Detonaron m\u00e1s de 300 granadas en el operativo contra Tony Tormenta|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2010/11/08/opinion/005n1pol|accessdate=27 December 2011|newspaper=La Jornada|date=8 November 2010}}</ref> And even after the drug lord was killed, the roadblocks continued throughout the rest of the day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Muere Tony Tormenta luego de ocho horas de tiroteos con efectivos federales en Matamoros|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2010/11/06/politica/007n1pol|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=La Jornada}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper mentioned that in a [[YouTube]] video, a convoy of SUV's filled with gunmen and pickups packed with marines were seen in a chase through the streets of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]]. And although there wasn't any visible confrontation between the two, the intensity of the situation was clear through the background noises of grenades explosions and automatic gunfire.<ref>{{cite news|title=Top Mexican drugs lord killed in fierce gunbattle with military|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/nov/07/mexico-drugs-gulf-cartel-antonio-guillen|accessdate=9 December 2011|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Jo|last=Tuckman|date=7 November 2010}}</ref> A news video from [[Televisa]], also on [[YouTube]], shows images from the confrontations of that day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Muere Antonio Cardenas Guillen, alias \"Tony Tormenta,\" lider del cartel del Golfo|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p8B7SZTvugU|accessdate=9 December 2011|newspaper=Televisa}}</ref> Moreover, several bystanders also recorded the shootouts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Video in\u00e9dito del la muerte de Cardenas Guillen, \"Tony Tormenta\"|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0vFhROX88ik|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mexico Border War&nbsp;\u2013 Live Battle! Unbelievable!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nX2gtblTeqI|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Balacera Matamoros: Convoy de Marinos|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R9MN_MIHkLw|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, according to the newspapers ''[[The Brownsville Herald]]'' and ''[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]'' from across the border in [[Brownsville, Texas]] and [[McAllen, Texas]], around 50 people were killed in the gunfights.<ref>{{cite news|title=En una balacera, muere \"Tony Tormenta\"|url=http://america.infobae.com/notas/13214-En-una-balacera-muere-Tony-Tormenta|newspaper=EFE, Milenio, Reforma, La Jornada|date=11 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326141939/http://america.infobae.com/notas/13214-En-una-balacera-muere-Tony-Tormenta|archivedate=26 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dozens killed in Matamoros; Tony Tormenta dead|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/11/dozens-killed-in-matamoros-bridges.html|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=5 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Head of Gulf Cartel killed|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/confirmed-119010-mexican-ezequiel.html|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=5 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dozens killed in Matamoros; bridges closed|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/killed-118999-friday-matamoros.html|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Head of Gulf Cartel killed in Matamoros shootout|url=http://www.enctoday.com/articles/killed-44249-monitortx-matamoros-shootout.html|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=The Monitor|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421170755/http://www.enctoday.com/articles/killed-44249-monitortx-matamoros-shootout.html|archivedate=21 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Although not confirmed, ''[[KVEO-TV]]'', several online sources and witnesses, along with one law enforcement officer who preferred to keep his name anonymous, mentioned that more than 100 people died that day in Matamoros.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shootings in Matamoros Kill \"Tony Tormenta\" and Nearly 100 People|url=http://www.kveo.com/news/shootings-in-matamoros-kill-tony-tormenta-and-nearly-100-people|newspaper=KVEO News Center|date=8 November 2010|access-date=9 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321054220/http://www.kveo.com/news/shootings-in-matamoros-kill-tony-tormenta-and-nearly-100-people|archive-date=21 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Los Zetas tienen el plato servido tras muerte de 'Tony Tormenta': Expertos|url=http://www.elnuevoheraldo.com/articles/muerte-46134-plato-servido.html|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=El Nuevo Heraldo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424172940/http://www.elnuevoheraldo.com/articles/muerte-46134-plato-servido.html|archivedate=24 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Johnston|first=Robert|title=Data on Mexican drug war violence|url=http://www.johnstonsarchive.net/terrorism/mexicodrugwar.html|publisher=Terrorism, Counterterrorism, and Unconventional Warfare|accessdate=29 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Carnage along border continues|url=http://www.valleymorningstar.com/news/saturday-83458-border-herald.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel leader killed, 55 others in Matamoros, Mexico|url=http://www.newstaco.com/2010/11/08/gulf-cartel-leader-killed-47-others-in-matamoros-mexico/|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=News Taco: The Latino Daily}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Death toll mounts in Matamoros shootout as sporadic fighting continues|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/matamoros-44259-death-fighting.html|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=The Monitor|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614103943/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/matamoros-44259-death-fighting.html|archivedate=14 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Deibert|first=Michael|title=Cartel Wars|url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/mexicos_cartel_wars_20110516/|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=Truthdig, L.L.C|date=16 May 2011}}</ref> The death of Antonio C\u00e1rdenas (''Tony Tormenta'') also caused a spiral of violence in [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]] a number of days after he was killed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Narcobloqueos y Balaceras en Tamaulipas tras muerte de 'Tony Tormenta'.|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BdMgkY4oAuY|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=Milenio TV}}</ref> Moreover, his death also generated a turf war with [[Los Zetas]] in the city of [[Ciudad Mier, Tamaulipas]], resulting in the exodus of more than 95% of its population.<ref>{{cite news|title=600 militares llegan a Mier, una ciudad abandonada por sus habitantes|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/12/09/600-militares-llegan-a-mier-una-ciudad-abandonada-por-sus-habitantes|accessdate=11 December 2011|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=9 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905051127/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/12/09/600-militares-llegan-a-mier-una-ciudad-abandonada-por-sus-habitantes|archivedate=5 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Banners written by [[Los Zetas]], the Gulf Cartel's former armed wing, appeared all across [[Mexico]], celebrating the death of C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n.<ref>{{cite news|title=Zozobra en Tamaulipas luego de ca\u00edda del l\u00edder del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2010/11/07/politica/005n1pol|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=La Jornada}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Zetas celebran caida de \"Tony Tormenta\" con narcomantas y narcopintas|url=http://www.lapoliciaca.com/nota-roja/zetas-celebran-caida-de-tony-tormenta-con-narcomantas-y-narcopintas/|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=La Policiaca}}</ref> The [[United States]] president, [[Barack Obama]], called the president of Mexico, [[Felipe Calder\u00f3n]], congratulating him and the Mexican forces for the operation in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]], and reiterated his effort against organized crime.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barack Obama expresa su apoyo a Calder\u00f3n por la muerte de 'Tony Tormenta'|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/06/barack-obama-expresa-su-apoyo-a-calderon-por-la-muerte-de-tony-tormenta|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=6 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120906013944/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/06/barack-obama-expresa-su-apoyo-a-calderon-por-la-muerte-de-tony-tormenta|archivedate=6 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter this incident, there was a huge division of opinions over the fate of the Gulf Cartel. Some experts believed that the death of [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n|Ezekiel]] would be dreadful for the Gulf Cartel, and that [[Los Zetas]] would overthrow them and eventually take control of [[Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Cattan|first=Nacha|title=Killing of top Mexico drug lord 'Tony Tormenta' may boost rival Zetas cartel|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Americas/2010/1107/Killing-of-top-Mexico-drug-lord-Tony-Tormenta-may-boost-rival-Zetas-cartel|newspaper=CSMonitor|date=7 November 2010}}</ref> Others explained how his death allowed [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez|Costilla S\u00e1nchez]] to take full directive of the cartel, and that would tighten relations with [[Colombia]] and straighten the Gulf Cartel's path, something quite difficult with [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n|Ezekiel]] as co-leader.<ref>{{cite web|last=Longmire|first=Sylvia|title=Authorities Say Cartel Leader's Death Won't Curb Violence.|url=http://borderviolenceanalysis.typepad.com/mexicos_drug_war/2010/11/authorities-say-cartel-leaders-death-wont-curb-violence.html|work=Mexico's Drug War|accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n====Los Escorpiones====\nLos Escorpiones, also called Grupo Escorpios,<ref>{{cite news|title=Los Escorpiones, temible escolta de Tormenta|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/losescorpionestemibleescoltadetormenta-584523.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=Vanguardia}}</ref> (''The Scorpions''), was believed to be the mercenary group that protected [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], the former leader of the organization.<ref>{{cite news|title=Matamoros braces for more violence|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/matamoros-44355-braces-violence.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=The Monitor|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405095633/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/matamoros-44355-braces-violence.html|archivedate=5 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to reports by the Mexican government, Los Escorpiones was created by Antonio C\u00e1rdenas (''Tony Tormenta'') and is composed of over 60 civilians, former police officers, and ex-military officials. According to ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]'', there are several music videos on [[YouTube]] that exalt the power of this armed group through ''[[narcocorridos]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Los Escorpiones, temible escolta de Tormenta|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/721570.html|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=5 November 2010}}</ref> After the rupture between the Gulf Cartel and [[Los Zetas]] (which until then had served as the cartel's armed wing), Los Escorpiones became the armed wing of the entire Gulf organization.<ref>{{cite news|title=Identifican a nuevo grupo armado del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo que proteg\u00eda a Tony Tormenta|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/identificananuevogrupoarmadodelcarteldelgolfoqueprotegiaatonytormenta-585439.html|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=Vanguardia}}</ref> The first mention of Los Escorpiones on the media was in 2008, when ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]'' wrote an article about some \"protected witnesses\" from the Gulf Cartel who denounced the alliance between the [[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel]] and [[Los Zetas]] to the Mexican authorities, and that the Gulf Cartel had created Los Escorpiones to stop and balance the growing hegemony of Los Zetas.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gomez|first=Francisco|title=\"Los Zetas\" por dentro|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/164819.html|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=31 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nHowever, his brother [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] disapproved the existence of this mercenary group, since he had created [[Los Zetas]], the parallel version of Los Escorpiones, and they had turned against the organization.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tony Tormenta, el capo que 'cuidaba' las fronteras de Tamaulipas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/05/tony-tormenta-el-capo-que-cuidaba-las-fronteras-de-tamaulipas|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=5 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130303023518/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/05/tony-tormenta-el-capo-que-cuidaba-las-fronteras-de-tamaulipas|archivedate=3 March 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]'' reported that Mexican authorities identified the gunmen that where engaging in confrontations against the troops in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]] as members of the Los Escorpiones group. Along with [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], the following members of Los Escorpiones were killed: Sergio Antonio Fuentes, alias ''El Tyson'' or ''Escorpi\u00f3n 1''; Ra\u00fal Marmolejo G\u00f3mez, alias ''Escorpi\u00f3n 18''; Hugo Lira, alias ''Escorpi\u00f3n 26''; and Refugio Adalberto Vargas Cort\u00e9s, alias ''Escorpi\u00f3n 42''.<ref>{{cite news|title=New details released about Gulf Cartel leader's death|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=537299#.TtVcknNFHFg|accessdate=29 November 2011|newspaper=Action 4 News}}</ref> The arrests of Marco Antonio Cortez Rodr\u00edguez alias ''Escorpi\u00f3n 37'' and of Josu\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez Rodr\u00edguez alias ''Escorpi\u00f3n 43''\u2014the two who were hospitalized after the shootout of 5 November 2010\u2014allowed for the Mexican forces to understand the structure of Los Escorpiones.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tony Tormenta escap\u00f3 en 2 ocasiones: Marina|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8861695|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=8 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Present-day==\n\n===Metros and Rojos infighting===\n{{Main|Infighting in the Gulf Cartel}}\nIn the late 1990s, [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], the former leader of the Gulf cartel, had other similar groups besides [[Los Zetas]] established in several cities in Tamaulipas.<ref name=mrl>{{cite news|title=Internal struggle in the Gulf Cartel could weaken the organization|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/struggle-56156-internal-cartel.html|accessdate=9 August 2012|newspaper=[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]|date=29 October 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816073550/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/struggle-56156-internal-cartel.html|archivedate=16 August 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Each of these groups were identified by their radio codes: ''the Rojos'' (The Red ones) were based in [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas|Reynosa]]; ''the Metros'' were headquartered in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]]; and ''the Lobos'' (The wolves) were established in [[Nuevo Laredo|Laredo]].<ref name=mrl/> The infighting between the Metros and the Rojos of the Gulf cartel began in 2010, when [[Juan Mej\u00eda Gonz\u00e1lez]], nicknamed ''El R-1'', was overlooked as the candidate of the regional boss of Reynosa and was sent to the \"Frontera Chica,\" an area that encompasses [[Ciudad Miguel Alem\u00e1n, Tamaulipas|Miguel Alem\u00e1n]], [[Camargo, Tamaulipas|Camargo]] and [[Ciudad Mier, Tamaulipas|Ciudad Mier]]&nbsp;\u2013 directly across the U.S.\u2013Mexico border from [[Starr County, Texas]]. The area that Mej\u00eda Gonz\u00e1lez wanted was given to [[Samuel Flores Borrego]], suggesting that the Metros were above the Rojos.<ref name=mrl/>\n\n[[File:Flores-Borrego.jpg|120px|thumb|left|[[Samuel Flores Borrego]], former Gulf Cartel high-ranking member.]]\nUnconfirmed information released by ''[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]'' indicated that two leaders of the Rojos, Mej\u00eda Gonz\u00e1lez and [[Rafael C\u00e1rdenas Vela]], teamed up to kill Flores Borrego.<ref name=mrl/> C\u00e1rdenas Vela had held a grudge on Flores Borrego and the Metros because he believed that they had led the Mexican military to track down and kill his uncle [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] (''Tony Tormenta'') on 5 November 2010.<ref name=mrl/><ref name=betrayal>{{cite news|title=Major Arrests Expected to Shake Up Gulf Cartel|url=http://www.krgv.com/news/major-arrests-expected-to-shake-up-gulf-cartel/|accessdate=10 August 2012|newspaper=[[KRGV-TV]]|date=13 December 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130127091503/http://www.krgv.com/news/major-arrests-expected-to-shake-up-gulf-cartel/|archivedate=27 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Other sources indicate that the infighting could have been caused by the suspicions that the Rojos were \"too soft\" on the Gulf cartel's bitter enemy, [[Los Zetas]].<ref name=rojossoft>{{cite news|last=Pachico|first=Elyssa|title=Death of Gulf Cartel 'Finance Chief' Sign of Internal Strife?|url=http://www.insightcrime.org/component/k2/item/1699-death-of-gulf-cartel-finance-chief-sign-of-internal-strife|accessdate=9 August 2012|newspaper=[[InSight Crime]]|date=11 October 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120809223008/http://www.insightcrime.org/component/k2/item/1699-death-of-gulf-cartel-finance-chief-sign-of-internal-strife|archivedate=9 August 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> When the Gulf cartel and Los Zetas split in early 2010, some members of the Rojos stayed with the Gulf cartel, while others decided to leave and join the forces of Los Zetas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico: Gulf Cartel lieutenant, his right-hand man captured|url=http://www.themonitor.com/news/gulf-54262-hand-right.html|accessdate=9 August 2012|newspaper=[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]|date=30 August 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120809223928/http://www.themonitor.com/news/gulf-54262-hand-right.html|archivedate=9 August 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[InSight Crime]] explains that the fundamental disagreement between the Rojos and the Metros was over leadership. Those who were more loyal to the C\u00e1rdenas family stayed with the Rojos, while those loyal to [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]], like Flores Borrego, defended the Metros.<ref name=rojossoft/>\n\nOriginally, the Gulf cartel was running smoothly, but the infighting between the two factions in the Gulf cartel triggered when Flores Borrego was killed on 2 September 2011.<ref name=mrl/> When the Rojos turned on the Metros, the largest faction in the Gulf cartel, firefights broke throughout Tamaulipas and drug loads were stolen among each other, but the Metros managed to retain control of the major cities that stretched from [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]] to [[Ciudad Miguel Alem\u00e1n, Tamaulipas|Miguel Alem\u00e1n, Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel lieutenant linked to various incidents on U.S side of border|url=http://www.themonitor.com/news/mcallen-57691-cartel-side.html|accessdate=10 August 2012|newspaper=[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]|date=2 January 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120818085345/http://www.themonitor.com/news/mcallen-57691-cartel-side.html|archivedate=18 August 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSome experts have found it difficult to argue that the Gulf Cartel does not impose a direct threat to the [[State (polity)|state]], since they \"do not seek political change,\" and that they only want to be left alone with their [[drug trafficking|business]]. Observations indicate that the Gulf Cartel actually controls territories and imposes its own rules\u2014often violent and bloody\u2014over the population. And in doing so, they inherently become a \"competitor\" with the state, who also claims sovereignty over its territories.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brophy|first=Stephanie|title=Mexico: Cartels, Corruption and Cocaine: A Profile of the Gulf Cartel|journal=Global Crime|date=August 2008|volume=9|issue=3|pages=248\u2013261|doi=10.1080/17440570802254353}}</ref> Like other drug trafficking organizations, the Gulf Cartel also subverts government institutions, particularly at [[Tamaulipas|state]] and local levels, by using their large profits to [[bribery|bribe]] officials.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ford|first=Jess T.|title=U.S. Assistance Has Helped Mexican Counternarcotics Efforts, but the Flow of Illicit Drugs into the United States Remains High|journal=[[Government Accountability Office]]|date=25 October 2007|pages=27|url=http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d08215t.pdf|accessdate=12 August 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712144545/http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d08215t.pdf|archivedate=12 July 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Presence in the U.S.===\nThe Gulf Cartel has important cells operating inside the United States\u2014in [[Mission, Texas|Mission]], [[Roma, Texas|Roma]], and [[Rio Grande City, Texas|Rio Grande City]]\u2014for example, and their presence is expanding.<ref>{{cite book|last=Adler|first=Patricia A.|title=Drugs and the American Dream: An Anthology|year=2012|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|isbn=978-0-470-67027-9|pages=456|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_s_9tfNlfGkC&pg=PA300&dq=gulf+cartel#v=onepage&q=gulf%20cartel&f=false}}</ref> [[Thomas A. Shannon, Jr.|Thomas A. Shannon]], a U.S. diplomat and ambassador, stated that criminal organizations like the Gulf Cartel have \"substantially weakened\" the institutions in Mexico and [[Central America]], and have generated a surge of violence in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Testimony of Thomas A. Shannon| url=http://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/ShannonTestimony071115p.pdf|publisher=United States Senate| accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref> The U.S. National Drug Threat Assessment mentioned that the drug trafficking organizations like the Gulf Cartel tend to be less structured in U.S. than in Mexico, and often rely on street gangs to operate inside the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=DTOs Have Expanded Operations in the United States|url=http://www.gao.gov/htext/d071018.html|publisher=U.S. Government Accountability Office|accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref> The arrest of several Gulf Cartel lieutenants, along with the drug-related violence and [[kidnapping]]s, have raised concerns among Texas officials that the drug war in Mexico and the drug cartels are taking hold in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Arrests of Mexican drug cartel leaders in Texas raise concerns|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/45156204/ns/us_news/t/arrests-mexican-drug-cartel-leaders-texas-raise-concerns/#.TwJ_MSO3CFc|accessdate=3 January 2012|newspaper=MSN BC News|date=3 November 2011}}{{dead link|date=November 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The strong ties the Gulf Cartel has with the prison gangs in the United States have also raised concern to American officials.<ref>{{cite news|last=Buch|first=Jason|title=Cartels cooperate with prison gangs|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Cartels-cooperate-with-prison-gangs-2436265.php|accessdate=3 January 2012|newspaper=The Houston Chronicle|date=1 January 2012}}</ref> Reports mention that Mexican drug cartels operate in more than 1,000 cities in the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Morasch|first=Charlie|title=FBI: Trucking 'significant' in cartels' U.S. profitability|url=http://www.landlinemag.com/todays_news/Daily/2011/Dec11/120511/120611-03.shtml|accessdate=3 January 2012|newspaper=Landline|date=6 December 2011}}</ref> In 2013, high ranking Gulf Cartel member Aurelio Cano Flores became the highest cartel member to be convicted by a U.S. jury in 15 years<Ref>https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/high-ranking-gulf-cartel-member-sentenced-washington-dc-35-years-prison-drug-trafficking</ref> In January 2020, high-ranking U.S. Gulf Cartel member Jorge Costilla-Sanchez pleaded guilty to an international drug trafficking conspiracy to distribute cocaine and marijuana into the United States.<ref>https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/former-gulf-cartel-leader-convicted-international-drug-trafficking-conspiracy</ref>\n\n===Presence in Europe===\nThe Gulf Cartel is believed to have ties with the [['Ndrangheta]], an organized crime group in [[Italy]] that also has ties with [[Los Zetas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cartel Inc: In the company of Narcos|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/01/14/us-drugs-mexico-business-idUSTRE60D4XS20100114|accessdate=3 January 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=14 January 2010}}</ref> Reports indicated that the Gulf Cartel was using the [[BlackBerry]] smartphones to communicate with 'Ndrangheta, since the texts are \"normally difficult to intercept\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Narco-mafia se comunican por Blackberry|url=http://www.cnnexpansion.com/actualidad/2009/02/19/mafia-italiana-en-contacto-con-narcos|accessdate=20 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Expansion|date=19 February 2009}}</ref> In 2009, the Gulf organization concluded that expanding their market opportunities in [[Europe]], combined with the euro strength against the U.S. dollar, justified establishing an extensive network in that continent. The main areas of demand and drug consumption are in Eastern Europe, the successor states of the [[Soviet Union]]. In Western Europe, the primarily increase has been in the use of cocaine.<ref>{{cite news|last=Carpenter|first=Ted Galen|title=Undermining Mexico's Dangerous Drug Cartels|url=http://www.cato.org/pubs/pas/PA688.pdf|accessdate=3 January 2012|newspaper=Policy Analysis|date=15 November 2011}}</ref> Along with the market in the United States, the drug market in [[Europe]] is among the most lucrative in the world, where the Mexican drug cartels are believed to have deals with the mafia groups of Europe.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ortiz|first=Carlos|title=Private armed forces and global security: a guide to the issues|year=2010|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-35592-9|pages=250|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Ui5-NOXAvtwC&pg=PA74&lpg=PA74&dq=eastern+europe+gulf+cartel#v=onepage&q=eastern%20europe%20gulf%20cartel&f=false}}</ref>\n\n===Presence in Africa===\nThe Gulf Cartel and other Mexican drug trafficking groups are active in the northern and western parts of [[Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mexican Cartels Exploit North Africa Turmoil|url=http://insightcrime.org/insight-latest-news/item/731-mexican-cartels-exploit-north-africa-turmoil|publisher=Insight Crime|accessdate=3 January 2012|date=April 2011}}</ref> Although cocaine is not grown in Africa, Mexican organizations, such as the Gulf Cartel, are currently exploiting West Africa's struggling rule-of-law caused by war, crime and poverty, in order to stage and expand supply routes to the increasingly lucrative European illegal drug market.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brice|first=Arthur|title=Latin American drug cartels find home in West Africa|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2009-09-21/world/africa.drug.cartels_1_drug-cartels-european-market-cocaine?_s=PM:WORLD|accessdate=3 January 2012|newspaper=CNN|date=21 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811040726/http://articles.cnn.com/2009-09-21/world/africa.drug.cartels_1_drug-cartels-european-market-cocaine?_s=PM:WORLD|archive-date=11 August 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cocaine trafficking in Western Africa|url=http://www.unodc.org/documents/data-and-analysis/Cocaine-trafficking-Africa-en.pdf|publisher=United Nations: Office on Drugs and Crime|accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Gulf Cartel vs. Los Zetas===\nThe rumors of the broken alliance between the Gulf Cartel and [[Los Zetas]] began on blogs and mass emails in September 2009, but it remained pretty much the same throughout that year\u2014a rumor. But on 24 February 2010, hundreds of trucks marked with ''C.D.G'', ''XXX'', and ''M3'' (the insignias of the Gulf Cartel) began to hit the streets of northern [[Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel vs. Los Zetas... One year later|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2011/02/cdg-vs-zetas-one-year-later.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=26 February 2011}}</ref> The clash between these two groups first happened in [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]], and then expanded to [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas|Nuevo Laredo]] and [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Penhaul|first=Kent|title=La ley del silencio en Reynosa s\u00f3lo la rompe... Twitter|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/06/21/la-ley-del-silencio-en-reynosa-solo-la-rompe-twitter|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=21 June 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129120041/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/06/21/la-ley-del-silencio-en-reynosa-solo-la-rompe-twitter|archivedate=29 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The war then spread out through 11 municipalities of [[Tamaulipas]], 9 of them bordering the state of [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=La guerra Golfo-zetas, en 11 municipios tamaulipecos; nueve son fronterizos con EU|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2010/11/12/politica/007n1pol|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=La Jornada|date=12 November 2010}}</ref> Soon, the violence generated between these two groups had spread to Tamaulipas' neighboring states of [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]] and [[Veracruz]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Los Zetas y el c\u00e1rtel del Golfo se pelean por Monterrey|url=http://noticias.univision.com/narcotrafico/reportajes/slideshow/2011-07-11/los-zetas-cartel-del-golfo-pelean-monterrey|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=Univision}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=La batalla del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo y \"Los Zetas\" por la Huasteca|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=293299|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=Proceso|date=31 December 2011}}</ref> Their conflict has even occurred on U.S. soil, where the Gulf Cartel killed two Zeta members in [[Brownsville, Texas]] on 5 October 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two Zetas executed in Brownsville, Texas|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/10/two-zetas-executed-in-brownsville-texas.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=25 October 2010}}</ref> In the midsts of violence and panic, local authorities and the media tried to minimize the situation and claim that \"nothing was occurring\", but the facts were impossible to cover up.<ref>{{cite news|title=La guerra del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo y Los Zetas, ma\u00f1ana 24 de febrero se cumple un a\u00f1o|url=http://www.mundonarco.org/2011/02/la-guerra-de-el-cartel-del-golfo-y-los.html?zx=862b69e2d65cce53|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216183527/http://www.mundonarco.org/2011/02/la-guerra-de-el-cartel-del-golfo-y-los.html?zx=862b69e2d65cce53|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 December 2013|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=Mundo Narco|date=23 February 2011}}</ref> Confrontations between these two groups have paralyzed entire cities in broad daylight.<ref>{{cite news|title=Enfrentamientos entre el c\u00e1rtel del Golfo y Los Zetas paralizaron Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2011/05/20/politica/013n1pol|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=La Jornada|date=20 May 2011}}</ref> Several witnesses claimed that many of the municipalities throughout Tamaulipas were \"war zones\", and that many businesses and houses were burned down, leaving areas in \"total destruction\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The Missing in Tamaulipas|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/04/missing-in-tamaulipas.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=26 April 2010}}</ref> The bloodbath in Tamaulipas has caused thousands of deaths, but most of shootings and body counts often go unreported.<ref>{{cite news|title=All Tamaulipas, a War Zone|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/04/all-tamaulipas-war-zone.html|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=22 April 2010}}</ref> The complexity and territorial advantage of [[Los Zetas]] forced the Gulf Cartel to seek for an alliance with the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] and [[La Familia Michoacana]]; in addition, [[Stratfor]] mentioned that these three organizations also united because they hold a \"profound hate\" for Los Zetas.<ref>{{cite news|title=DEA: acuerdan 3 c\u00e1rteles alianza contra Los Zetas|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8729891|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=5 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114015453/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8729891|archivedate=14 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Consequently, Los Zetas joined forces with the [[Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Cartel]] and the [[Tijuana Cartel]] to counterattack the opposing cartels.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sicarios de los Beltr\u00e1n Leyva y Zetas atacan a gente del Chapo en Sonora|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/7c954b2a681dd8c89db2c26caf9ab0a9|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=2 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120905172137/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/7c954b2a681dd8c89db2c26caf9ab0a9|archivedate=5 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 November 2014, a document from the Mexican government was released to the media and claimed that Los Rojos faction of the Gulf Cartel was planning to form an alliance with Los Zetas. The potential alliance was conducted by [[Juan Reyes Mej\u00eda Gonz\u00e1lez]] (alias \"R1\"), from the Gulf Cartel; and [[Rogelio Gonz\u00e1lez Piza\u00f1a]] (alias \"Z-2\"), from Los Zetas. The latter was released from prison months earlier even though he was scheduled to serve 16-years behind bars in January. Authorities believe that Gonz\u00e1lez Piza\u00f1a reincorporated in organized crime and decided to join with the Gulf Cartel to end the war with Los Zetas, and bring back the \"old school\" ways when they were together.<ref>{{cite news|title=Facciones del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo y Los Zetas buscan aliarse para poner fin a agresiones contra la poblaci\u00f3n|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=387306|accessdate=11 November 2014|publisher=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|date=11 November 2014|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==Tamaulipas: State corruption==\n\n===Political corruption===\nThe drug violence and political corruption that has plagued [[Tamaulipas]], the homestate of the Gulf Cartel and Los Zetas, has fueled thoughts of Tamaulipas becoming a \"failed state\" and a haven for drug traffickers and criminals of all kinds.<ref>{{cite news|last=N\u00e1jar|first=Alberto|title=Tamaulipas, \u00bfen camino de convertirse en un estado fallido?|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mundo/noticias/2011/04/110413_mexico_tamaulipas_estado_fallido_an.shtml|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=BBC Mundo|date=13 April 2011}}</ref> The massacre of the [[2010 San Fernando massacre|72 migrants]] and the clandestine [[2011 San Fernando massacre|mass graves]] with more than 250 bodies in [[San Fernando, Tamaulipas]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Migrantes, 72 muertos de fosa en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/704017.html|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|date=25 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=S\u00e1nchez L\u00f3pez|first=Daniel|title=Sin resolver origen de narcofosas en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.sexenio.com.mx/articulo.php?id=3814|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=Sexenio|date=9 April 2011}}</ref> mounted with the assassination of the state candidate [[Rodolfo Torre Cant\u00fa]] (2010),<ref>{{cite news|title=Asesinan a Rodolfo Torre Cant\u00fa, candidato al gobierno de Tamaulipas|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/7c954b2a681dd8c89db2c26caf6dabe3|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=28 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013055401/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/7c954b2a681dd8c89db2c26caf6dabe3|archivedate=13 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the increasing violence generated between drug groups, and the state's inability to ensure tranquility, has led specialists to conclude that \"neither the regional nor federal government have control over the territory of Tamaulipas.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Miglierini|first=Julian|title=Tamaulipas: 'Failed state' in Mexico's war on drugs|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-13061452|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=BBC News, Mexico City|date=13 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:RodolfoTorreCantu-PRI.jpg|left|140px|thumb|[[Rodolfo Torre Cant\u00fa]], politician killed in Tamaulipas.]] -->\nAlthough drug-related violence has existed since the early beginnings of the Gulf Cartel, it often happened in low-profile levels, while the government agreed to \"look the other way\" while the drug traffickers went about their business\u2014as long as they behaved.<ref>{{cite web|last=Longmire|first=Sylvia|title=Mexico's PRI Names Presidential Candidate.|url=http://borderviolenceanalysis.typepad.com/mexicos_drug_war/2011/12/mexicos-pri-names-presidential-candidate.html|publisher=Mexico's Drug War|accessdate=28 December 2011}}</ref> Back in the days of the 71-year rule of the [[Institutional Revolutionary Party]] (PRI), it was believed that they ran exactly that show: if the drug cartels got off the line, the Mexican government would conduct some arrests, make some disappearances, and the drug lords would get their people straight and back on the line again.<ref>{{cite book|last=Andreas|first=Peter|title=The Political Economy of Narco-Corruption in Mexico|date=April 1998|publisher=Brown University|url=http://www.brown.edu/Departments/Political_Science/people/documents/ThePoliticalEconomyofNarco-CorruptioninMexico.pdf}}</ref>  After the PRI lost the presidency in 2000 to the [[National Action Party (Mexico)|National Action Party]] (PAN), the arrangement between the government and the cartels was lost, as well the ''pax mafiosa''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico's drug war: A pax narcotica?|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/americasview/2011/01/mexicos_drug_wars|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=The Economist|date=7 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Klepak|first=Hal|title=Mexico: Current and Future Political, Economic and Security Trends|journal=Canadian Defence & Foreign Affairs Institute|date=August 2010|url=http://www.cdfai.org/PDF/Mexico%20-%20Current%20and%20Future%20Political%20Economic%20and%20Security%20Trends.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426074349/http://www.cdfai.org/PDF/Mexico%20-%20Current%20and%20Future%20Political%20Economic%20and%20Security%20Trends.pdf|archivedate=26 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Moreover, the state of [[Tamaulipas]] was no exception; according to [[Santiago Creel]], a PAN politician and pre-candidate for the 2012 presidency, the PRI in Tamaulipas has protected the Gulf Cartel for years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hay pruebas sobre nexos de priistas con narco: PAN|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=55220&tabla=estados|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|date=21 October 2004|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419021612/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=55220&tabla=estados|archivedate=19 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Narcopol\u00edtica en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/178728.html|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|date=29 June 2010}}</ref> In addition, ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]'' newspaper mentions that the narco-corruption in Tamaulipas is due to the fact the opposing political parties, the PAN and the [[Party of the Democratic Revolution]] (PRD), rarely win an election and \"practically do not exist\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Alem\u00e1n|first=Ricardo|title=Tamaulipas; PRI y narco|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/columnas/81779.html|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=El Universal|date=12 January 2010}}</ref> PRI's main opposition party, the [[National Action Party (Mexico)|PAN]], claimed that government elections in [[Tamaulipas]] are likely to encounter an \"organized crime influence.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Salas|first=Alejandro|title=Blindaje contra narcopol\u00edticos en Tamaulipas|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8713347|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120716190610/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8713347|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-07-16|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=February 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]'' newspaper reported that the former governors of [[Tamaulipas]], [[Manuel Cavazos Lerma]] (1993\u20131999), [[Tom\u00e1s Yarrington]] (1999\u20132004), and [[Eugenio Hern\u00e1ndez Flores]] (2005\u20132010) have had close ties with the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moreno|first=Mart\u00edn|title=Tamaulipas: gobierno fallido|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&id_nota=718789|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=Exc\u00e9lsior|date=10 April 2011}}</ref> On 30 January 2012, the [[Attorney General of Mexico]] issued a communiqu\u00e9 ordering the past three governors of [[Tamaulipas]] and their families to remain in the country as they are being investigated for possible correlation with the Mexican drug cartels.<ref>{{cite news|title=Busca PGR contra 3 ex gobernadores de Tamaulipas|url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/703223.busca-pgr-contra-3-ex-gobernadores-de-tamaulipas.html|accessdate=31 January 2012|newspaper=El Siglo de Torreon|date=30 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PGR emiti\u00f3 alerta migratoria contra tres ex gobernadores de Tamaulipas|url=http://noticias.univision.com/mexico/noticias/article/2012-01-30/pgr-alerta-tres-ex-gobernadores-tamaulipas#axzz1l0fmTS00|accessdate=31 January 2012|newspaper=Univision|date=30 January 2012}}</ref> The municipal president of [[Tampico, Tamaulipas]], \u00d3scar P\u00e9rez Inguanzo, was arrested 12 November 2011 due to his \"improper exercise of public functions and forgery\" of certain documents.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arrestan nuevamente a \u00d3scar P\u00e9rez Inguanzo, ex alcalde de Tampico|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/8ab83f37d6b1f800d866257f6acbf566|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130128170839/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/8ab83f37d6b1f800d866257f6acbf566|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 January 2013|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=12 November 2011}}</ref> In addition, ''[[La Jornada]]'' mentions that the Gulf Cartel owns \"all of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]]\", where they act as the State itself and conduct all forms of criminal activities.<ref>{{cite news|title=El c\u00e1rtel del Golfo, junto con sus nuevos socios, es due\u00f1o de todo en Matamoros|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2011/05/08/politica/012n1pol|accessdate=28 December 2011|newspaper=La Jornada|date=8 May 2011}}</ref> In mid-2010, [[Eugenio Hern\u00e1ndez Flores]], the governor of Tamaulipas, and \u00d3scar Luebbert Guti\u00e9rrez, the mayor of [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]]\u2014both members of the ''[[Institutional Revolutionary Party]]'' (PRI)\u2014were criticized for claiming that there were no armed confrontations in Tamaulipas and that the violence was \"only a rumor.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Ciudadana graba evidencias de balaceras en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/estados/75031.html|accessdate=4 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=2 March 2010}}</ref> Months later, Hern\u00e1ndez Flores finally recognized that several parts of Tamaulipas were \"being overrun by organized crime violence.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=La violencia nos rebas\u00f3, acepta Eugenio Hern\u00e1ndez|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8823265|accessdate=4 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=28 August 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831020132/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8823265|archivedate=31 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Luebbert Guti\u00e9rrez later recognized the work of the federal troops and acknowledged that his city was experiencing \"an escalation in violence.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Alcalde admite psicosis por violencia en Reynosa|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/661544.html|accessdate=4 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=25 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 June 2016, citizens from Tamaulipas elected a governor from the opposition party, Fransico Javier Garcia Cabeza de Vaca member of Accion Nacional (National Action). It is the first time in 87 years, a governor from the opposition wins in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/articulo/nacion/politica/2016/06/6/garcia-cabeza-de-vaca-gana-priista-hinojosa|title=Garc\u00eda Cabeza de Vaca gana a pri\u00edsta Hinojosa|publisher=|accessdate=11 December 2016|date=2016-06-06}}</ref> He won under the slogan \"winds of change are coming\" to Tamaulipas.<ref>http://lavozdetamaulipas.net/soplan-fuertes-vientos-de-cambio-en-tamaulipas-cabeza-de-vaca/{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> While his election did not had that much substance in a public policy perspective, its rhetoric of a peaceful transition, enabled him to defeat by double digits the candidate from the ruling party, Baltazar Manuel Hinijosa Ochoa.<ref>http://www.preptam.org/#/ {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703002550/http://www.preptam.org/ |date=3 July 2016 }}</ref>\n\nBoth candidates have and continue to face accusations of receiving illicity money from the Gulf Cartel, while being mayors of two border towns. In 1986, according to Proceso, Cabeza de Vaca was arrested for stealing weapons under the orders for a Drug Trafficking Organization (DTOs) of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/121266/tamaulipas-rastros-de-narco-en-el-precandidato-panista-2|title=Tamaulipas: Rastros de narco en el precandidato panista - Proceso|date=16 December 2009|publisher=|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> Cabeza de Vaca is accused by a Bloomberg/El Financiero of having a big and unexplained wealth of 951 million pesos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/nacional/como-funcionario-cabeza-de-vaca-amasa-fortuna-de-951-mdp.html|title=Como funcionario, Cabeza de Vaca amasa fortuna de 951 mdp|publisher=|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> Cabeza de Vaca is accused of not reporting its total wealth, and having properities both in Texas, Tamaulipas, and Mexico City. Cabeza de Vaca has been for 11 years a public servant, which questions according El Financiero, the origin of its wealth. Balatazar Hinojosa Ochoa is also accused of coopting with DTOs of the Gulf Cartel while being mayor of Matamoros in 2006. In goes into the extent, in a recent book called ''Tamaulipas; La casta de de los narcogobernadores: un eastern mexicano'' is accused of being present while former governor Tomas Yarrigton, also accused of involvements with DTOs of the Gulf Cartel, received illicit money from the Gulf Cartel to finance its campaign for governor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/442099/tamaulipas-gobernadores-narco-hermanados|title=Tamaulipas: gobernadores y narco, hermanados - Proceso|date=28 May 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> Also according to Proceso, Baltazar Hinojosa is under investigation by the United States Department of Tresuary for laundering money through the Panama Papers target, the law firm Mossack Fonseca. According to the media outlet, Baltazar Hinojosa brother in law, owns a shell company created by the law firm, where its board of directors' members are his wife and three daughters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/442618/departamento-del-tesoro-investiga-a-candidato-del-pri-al-gobierno-tamaulipas-lavado-dinero|title=Departamento del Tesoro investiga a candidato del PRI al gobierno de Tamaulipas por lavado - Proceso|date=1 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Prison breaks===\nOn 25 March 2010 in the city of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], 40 inmates escaped from a federal prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se fugan 40 reos de penal en Matamoros|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/668521.html|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=25 March 2010}}</ref>  Authorities are still trying to understand how the prisoners escaped.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se fugan 40 reos de Penal de Matamoros|url=http://eleconomista.com.mx/estados/2010/03/25/se-fugan-40-reos-penal-matamoros|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Economista|date=25 March 2010}}</ref> The authorities mentioned that the incident is \"under investigation,\" but did not give further information.<ref>{{cite news|title=40 reos se fugan de penal de Matamoros|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/03/25/40-reos-se-fugan-de-penal-de-matamoros|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=25 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183645/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/03/25/40-reos-se-fugan-de-penal-de-matamoros|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the border city of [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]], 85 inmates escaped from a prison on 10 September 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=85 reos escaparon del penal de Reynosa, precisa el gobierno|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/09/10/un-grupo-de-reos-escapo-del-penal-de-reynosa-precisa-el-gobierno|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=10 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183312/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/09/10/un-grupo-de-reos-escapo-del-penal-de-reynosa-precisa-el-gobierno|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Reports first indicated that there were 71 fugitives, but the correct figures were later released.<ref>{{cite news|title=Al menos 71 reos se fugan de un penal de Reynosa, en Tamaulipas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/09/10/al-menos-71-reos-se-fugan-de-un-penal-de-reynosa-en-tamaulipas|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=10 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183629/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/09/10/al-menos-71-reos-se-fugan-de-un-penal-de-reynosa-en-tamaulipas|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 5 April 2010, in the same prison, a convoy of 10 trucks filled with gunmen broke into the cells and liberated 13 inmates, and the authorities later mentioned that 11 of them were \"extremely dangerous.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Un comando libera a trece prisioneros de un penal de Reynosa|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/04/05/un-comando-libera-a-trece-prisioneros-de-un-penal-de-reynosa|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=5 April 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183651/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/04/05/un-comando-libera-a-trece-prisioneros-de-un-penal-de-reynosa|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas]] on 17 December 2010, about 141 inmates escaped from a federal prison. At first, estimates mentioned that 148 inmates had escaped, but later counts gave the exact figures.<ref>{{cite news|title=Al menos 148 presos se escapan de una c\u00e1rcel de Tamaulipas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/mundo/2010/12/17/al-menos-148-presos-se-escapan-de-una-carcel-de-tamaulipas|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNNM\u00e9xico|date=17 December 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183238/http://mexico.cnn.com/mundo/2010/12/17/al-menos-148-presos-se-escapan-de-una-carcel-de-tamaulipas|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The federal government \"strongly condemned\" the prison breaks and said that the work by the state and municipal authorities of [[Tamaulipas]] \"lack effective control measures\" and urged them to strengthen their institutions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamaulipas cesa a directivos de penal por la fuga de los 141 reos|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/12/17/tamaulipas-cesa-a-directivos-de-penal-por-la-fuga-de-los-141-reos|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=17 December 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101104819/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/12/17/tamaulipas-cesa-a-directivos-de-penal-por-la-fuga-de-los-141-reos|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A confrontation inside a maximum security prison in [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas]] on 15 July 2011 left 7 inmates dead and 59 escaped.<ref>{{cite news|title=Al menos siete muertos y 59 reos fugados en una c\u00e1rcel de Nuevo Laredo|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/15/al-menos-siete-muertos-y-59-reos-fugados-en-una-carcel-de-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=15 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101233601/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/15/al-menos-siete-muertos-y-59-reos-fugados-en-una-carcel-de-nuevo-laredo|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The 5 guards that were supposed to supervise have not been found, and the [[Federal government of Mexico]] urged the state and municipal authorities to strengthen the security of their prisons.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se fugan 59 reos en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/estados/81218.html|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=16 July 2011}}</ref> Consequently, the federal government did not hesitate to assign the [[Mexican Army]] and the [[Federal Police (Mexico)|Federal Police]] to vigilate the prisons until further notice; they were also left in charge of searching for the fugitives.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se fugan 59 reos en Nuevo Laredo tras enfrentamiento|url=http://www.terra.mx/noticias/articulo/1159803/Se+fugan+59+reos+en+Nuevo+Laredo+tras+enfrentamiento.htm|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Terra Noticias|date=15 July 2011}}</ref> ''[[CNN]]'' mentioned that the state government of Tamaulipas later recognized \"their inability to work with the federal government.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Tras las fugas de reos en Tamaulipas, el gobierno federal se defiende|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/04/07/gobierno-federal-reitara-su-apoyo-a-tamaulipas-en-lucha-contra-el-crimen|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=7 April 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183554/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/04/07/gobierno-federal-reitara-su-apoyo-a-tamaulipas-en-lucha-contra-el-crimen|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a prison in the state of [[Zacatecas]], on 16 May 2009, an armed commando liberated 53 Gulf Cartel members using 10 trucks and even a helicopter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Narco libera reos en Zacatecas|url=http://www.cnnexpansion.com/actualidad/2009/05/16/narco-libera-reos-en-zacatecas|accessdate=20 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Expansion|date=16 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[CNN]]'', more than 400 prison inmates escaped from several prisons in [[Tamaulipas]] from January 2010 to March 2011 due to corruption.<ref>{{cite news|title=M\u00e1s de 400 reos se fugaron de c\u00e1rceles de Tamaulipas en 14 meses|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/15/mas-de-400-reos-se-fugaron-de-carceles-de-tamaulipas-en-14-meses|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico|date=15 July 2011|language=es|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101233449/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/15/mas-de-400-reos-se-fugaron-de-carceles-de-tamaulipas-en-14-meses|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Police corruption===\nThe ''[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]'' newspaper mentioned that the police forces in the state of [[Tamaulipas]] are the \"worst paid in Mexico\" despite being \"one of the states hardest hit by violence.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Polic\u00edas de Tamaulipas ganan 3 mil 618 pesos|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&id_nota=770508#.TwIwTyO3CFc|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Excelsior|date=25 September 2011|language=es}}</ref> They also reported that in [[Aguascalientes]], a state where violence levels are much lower, policemen are paid five times more than in Tamaulipas. In fact, they are paid around $3,618 [[Mexican peso|pesos]] (about $260 US dollars) a month in all of [[Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Polic\u00edas de Tamaulipas, los peores pagados de M\u00e9xico; ganan menos de 4 mil pesos al mes|url=http://www.animalpolitico.com/2011/09/policias-de-tamaulipas-los-peores-pagados-de-mexico-ganan-menos-de-4-mil-pesos-al-mes/|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Animal Politico|date=26 September 2011|language=es}}</ref> As a result, most of the police forces in Tamaulipas are believed to be \"corrupt\" due to their low wages and the presence of organized crime, who can easily bribe them.<ref>{{cite news|title=Polic\u00edas de Tamaulipas aun no son confiables: Lomel\u00ed|url=http://www.hoytamaulipas.net/notas/45682/Policias-aun-no-son-confiables-Rafael-Lomeli.html|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Hoy Tamaulipas|date=7 November 2011|language=es}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May 2011, the Mexican government, along with [[Secretariat of National Defense|Sedena]], disarmed all police forces in the state of [[Tamaulipas]], beginning with the cities of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]] and [[Reynosa]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sedena desarma a polic\u00edas de Tamaulipas|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYW7mvmIfbc|newspaper=TV Milenio|date=9 May 2011}}</ref> In June 2011, the state government of Tamaulipas requested the federal government to send in troops to combat the drug cartels in the area, in order to \"consolidate actions on public safety\" and \"strengthen the capacity of their institutions.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=El gobierno de M\u00e9xico desplegar\u00e1 2,790 militares en Tamaulipas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/06/24/el-gobierno-de-mexico-desplegara-2790-militares-en-tamaulipas|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=24 June 2011|language=es|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101183342/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/06/24/el-gobierno-de-mexico-desplegara-2790-militares-en-tamaulipas|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Joint Operation Nuevo Le\u00f3n-Tamaulipas]] issued in 2007, along with several other military-led operation by the federal government, have brought thousands of troops to restore order in [[Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=M\u00e9xico enviar\u00e1 m\u00e1s Fuerzas Armadas a Nuevo Le\u00f3n y Tamaulipas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/24/mexico-enviara-mas-fuerzas-armadas-a-nuevo-leon-y-tamaulipas|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=24 November 2011|language=es|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120102051554/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/11/24/mexico-enviara-mas-fuerzas-armadas-a-nuevo-leon-y-tamaulipas|archivedate=2 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[CNN]]'' news mentioned that the troops \"replaced half of the policemen\" in the state of Tamaulipas.<ref>{{cite news|last=Castillo|first=Mariano|title=Tropas mexicanas reemplazan a los polic\u00edas en la mitad de Tamaulipas|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/06/26/tropas-mexicanas-reemplazan-a-los-policias-en-la-mitad-de-tamaulipas|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=26 June 2011|language=es|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222052600/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/06/26/tropas-mexicanas-reemplazan-a-los-policias-en-la-mitad-de-tamaulipas|archivedate=22 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 7 November 2011, about 1,660 policemen were released from their duties because they had either failed their control tests or refused to take them.<ref>{{cite news|title=Expulsan a mil 650 polic\u00edas de Tamaulipas por p\u00e9rdida de confianza|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&seccion=seccion-nacional&cat=1&id_nota=781202#.TwI8byO3CFc|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Excelsior|date=7 November 2011|language=es}}</ref>\n\nAlthough there have been efforts by the federal government to wipe out police corruption, [[Terra Networks]] published an article of a witness who said that the police forces in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]] work as \"informants for the Gulf Cartel\" and report on the activity of the Mexican military, and even \"wave at [the cartel members]\" when they see them in the streets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Opini\u00f3n sobre posible corrupci\u00f3n en Matamoros|url=http://www.terra.com.mx/articulo.aspx?articuloId=1104266|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=Terra|date=5 May 2011|language=es}}</ref> ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]'' released an article which said that the National Public Security System (SNSP) has condemned the cops' salaries, and demanded the state and municipal authorities to create better paying programs for the policemen so they can have a \"[[Just price|just wage]]\" for themselves and their families.<ref>{{cite news|title=Acusan a estados de incumplir homologaci\u00f3n salarial policiaca|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/primera/37801.html|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=26 September 2011|language=es}}</ref> The federal government is also constructing three military bases in Tamaulipas: in [[Ciudad Mier]], [[San Fernando, Tamaulipas|San Fernando]], and [[Ciudad Mante, Tamaulipas|Ciudad Mante]].<ref>{{cite news|title='Batallones son parte de la estrategia de seguridad'|url=http://eldiariodevictoria.com.mx/2011/11/16/%E2%80%98batallones-son-parte-de-la-estrategia-de-seguridad%E2%80%99/|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=El Diario de Ciudad Victoria|date=16 November 2011|language=es}}</ref>\n\n==Alliances==\nIn 2003, the arrest of several high-profile cartel leaders, including the heads of the [[Tijuana Cartel]] and Gulf Cartel, [[Benjam\u00edn Arellano F\u00e9lix]] and [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], turned the war on drugs into a trilateral war. While in prison, C\u00e1rdenas and Arellano formed an alliance to defend themselves from the [[Sinaloa Cartel|Sinaloa]] and [[Juarez Cartel]]s,<ref>{{cite web|last=Ensinger|first=Jason|title=Mexico's War On Drugs|url=http://www.shavemagazine.com/politics/090201|publisher=Shave Magazine}}</ref> who had also formed an alliance with each other, and were planning to take over the smuggling routes and territories of the Gulf and [[Tijuana Cartel]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cook|first=Colleen W.|title=CRS Report for Congress: Mexico's Drug Cartels|journal=Congressional Research Service|date=October 2007|pages=35|url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/row/RL34215.pdf}}</ref> After a dispute, however, C\u00e1rdenas ordered Arellano beaten, and the Gulf-Tijuana alliance ceased to exist at that point. It was reported that after the fallout, C\u00e1rdenas ordered [[Los Zetas]] to [[Baja California]] to wipe out the Tijuana Cartel.<ref>{{cite book|last=Logan|first=Sam|title=The Reality of the Mexican Mega Cartel|year=2006|pages=21|url=http://www.samuellogan.com/publications/The-Reality-of-a-Mega-Cartel.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe Sinaloa-Juarez alliance ceased to exist as well due to an unpaid debt in 2007, and now the Sinaloa and Juarez Cartel are at war against each other.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rompen pacto c\u00e1rteles de Ju\u00e1rez y de Sinaloa|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/159369.html|newspaper=El Universal|date= 10 May 2008|language=es}}</ref> Since February 2010, the major cartels have aligned in two factions, one integrated by the [[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]], Tijuana Cartel, Los Zetas and the [[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel]];<ref>{{cite news|last=Granados|first=Omar|title=\"El Chapo\" y Los Zetas dominan reacomodo de c\u00e1rteles|url=http://www.animalpolitico.com/2011/05/el-chapo-y-los-zetas-dominan-el-reacomodo-de-carteles/|newspaper=Animal Pol\u00edtico|date=6 May 2011|language=es}}</ref> the other faction integrated by the Gulf Cartel, Sinaloa Cartel, [[La Familia Michoacana|La Familia Cartel]] (now extinct) and the [[Knights Templar (gang)|Knights Templar Cartel]].<ref name=\"Aug 2011\">{{cite news | first = Aurora | last = Vega | title = Surgen cuatro grupos del narco en 2011; El Chapo es el capo m\u00e1s poderoso | date = 7 August 2011 | url = http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&id_nota=759098 | work = Excelsior | accessdate =7 August 2011 | language = Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mosso|first=Rub\u00e9n|title=Presentan a \"El Yupo\" l\u00edder de \"Los Caballeros Templarios\" en Apatzing\u00e1n|url=http://tampico.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/8e8cb7bc4e8cf619c658bc3f7b7283c2|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=1 August 2011|language=es|access-date=2 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805235311/http://tampico.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/8e8cb7bc4e8cf619c658bc3f7b7283c2|archive-date=5 August 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\n[[File:Gulf Cartel Hierarchy.JPG|thumb|Gulf Cartel [[hierarchy]]]]\n\nThe rupture from [[Los Zetas]] left [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]] and [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n|Antonio Ezekiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] in full control of the Gulf Cartel. However, Ezekiel died in a shooting with the Mexican Marines in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]] in 2010,<ref>{{cite news|title=Cae abatido por la Marina 'Tony Tormenta' en Matamoros|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/f093ccf4edf26d1cdb9c4181baf05c90|newspaper=Milenio Noticias|date=5 November 2010|access-date=6 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015225924/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/f093ccf4edf26d1cdb9c4181baf05c90|archive-date=15 October 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and Costilla Sanchez became the sole head of the cartel until his arrest in September 2012.<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\">{{cite news |first=Tracy |last=Wilkinson |title=Latest Mexico drug arrest may cripple Gulf cartel |date=13 September 2012 |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/sep/13/world/la-fg-mexico-gulf-cartel-20120914 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=12 October 2012}}</ref> [[Mario C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], brother of both Osiel and Antonio, became one of the top lieutenants in the organization after his release from prison in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vega|first=Aurora|title=Otro C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n hereda la organizaci\u00f3n|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&id_nota=682536|newspaper=Excelsior|date=6 November 2010}}</ref> In addition, within the Gulf Cartel there is believed to be two groups\u2014the Rojos and the [[Los Metros|Metros]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sources: Fatal gunshots on McAllen expressway point to Gulf Cartel|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/mcallen-55174-point-expressway.html|newspaper=The Monitor|date=27 September 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811061018/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/mcallen-55174-point-expressway.html|archivedate=11 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[modus operandi]] (\"mode of operation\") of the Gulf Cartel changes whenever the United States attempts to strengthen their domestic policy in reinforcing the borders. When drug trafficking tightens, they usually invest in more sophisticated methods to smuggle drugs, recruit new members, corrupt more officials, seek new ways to remove obstacles that impede the immediate success of the organization, along with many others.<ref>{{cite book|last=Payan|first=Tony|title=Three United States-Mexico border wars|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-98818-0|pages=164|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Y1ETNeJow9IC&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=modus+operandi+gulf+cartel#v=onepage&q=modus%20operandi%20gulf%20cartel&f=false}}</ref> Below is the basic structure of the [[drug cartel]]:\n\n*Falcons (''Halcones''): Considered the \"eyes and ears\" of the streets, the falcons are the lowest rank position in any drug cartel. They are responsible for supervising and reporting on the activities of the Mexican military and of their rival groups.<ref>{{cite news|title=Va Marina por 'halcones' del crimen organizado|url=http://www.mundonarco.com/2011/04/va-marina-por-halcones-del-crimen.html|newspaper=Blog del Narco|date=21 April 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827061101/http://www.mundonarco.com/2011/04/va-marina-por-halcones-del-crimen.html|archivedate=27 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*Hitmen (''Sicarios''): They are the armed group within the drug cartel; they are responsible for carrying out assassinations, kidnappings, thefts, extortions, operating protection rackets, and defending their plaza from the rival groups and the military.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bowden|first=Charles|title=El sicario, un documental proscrito en M\u00e9xico (1)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7C45xR_48mQ|date=6 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bowden|first=Charles|title=El sicario, un documental proscrito en M\u00e9xico (2)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LDFDxtjGuuI|date=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n*Lieutenants (''Lugartenientes''): The second highest position in the drug cartel organization; they are responsible for supervising the ''sicarios'' and ''halcones'' within their own territory. They are allowed to carry low-profile executions without permission from their bosses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ej\u00e9rcito detiene a lugarteniente del c\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/602145.html|newspaper=El Universal|date=2 June 2009}}</ref>\n*Drug lords (''Capos''): This is the highest position in any drug cartel; they are responsible supervising the entire drug industry, appointing territorial leaders, making alliances, and planning high-profile executions.<ref>{{cite news|title=DATOS&nbsp;\u2013 Principales capos de la droga en M\u00e9xico|url=http://mx.ibtimes.com/articles/6593/20101106/lideres-droga-mexico-narcotrafico.htm|newspaper=International Business Times|accessdate=6 November 2010|language=es|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120715171715/http://mx.ibtimes.com/articles/6593/20101106/lideres-droga-mexico-narcotrafico.htm|archivedate=15 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIt's worth noting that there are other operating groups within the drug cartels. For example, the drug producers and suppliers,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Uncovering the link between the Mexican drug cartels|journal=National Defense University: Center for Hemispheric Defense Studies|url=http://www.ndu.edu/chds/SRC-peru07/SRC_PAPERS/TRACK%201/VELARDE_SPA%20final.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615194812/http://www.ndu.edu/chds/SRC-peru07/SRC_PAPERS/TRACK%201/VELARDE_SPA%20final.pdf|archivedate=15 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> although not considered in  the basic structure, are critical operators of any drug cartel, along with the financers and money launderers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Las 5 caras del lavado de dinero|url=http://www.cnnexpansion.com/economia/2010/06/07/lavado-de-dinero-narco-mexico-eu|newspaper=CNNExpansi\u00f3n|date=8 June 2010|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cae \"El Adal\" operador financiero de los Zetas|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qBEDcgepE6M|accessdate=3 August 2011|newspaper=TV Milenio|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cae \"El M\u00edchel\" operador financiero de Los Zetas en Aguascalientes|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IpM93oU7ICM|accessdate=3 August 2011|newspaper=Tele Diario|language=es}}</ref> In addition, the arms suppliers operate in a completely different circle,<ref>{{cite news|title=Entrevista a el Mamito, presunto fundador de los Zetas|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HacDTEn2TDs|newspaper=CNN Videos|date=6 July 2011|language=es}}</ref> and are technically not considered part of the cartel's logistics.\n\nIn June 2019, Carlos Abraham R\u00edos Su\u00e1rez, also known as El Oaxaco, was arrested. He served as head of cartel's operations in [[Oaxaca]].<ref>https://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/gulf-cartels-oaxaca-plaza-chief/</ref>\n\n==Modus operandi==\n'''Protection racketeering'''\nOrganized crime groups opt for [[protection racketeering]] in an effort to control markets and \"maintaining internal order.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Varese|first=Federico|title=Mafias on the move: how organized crime conquers new territories|year=2011|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-12855-9|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mafiasonmovehowo00vare/page/278 278]|url=https://archive.org/details/mafiasonmovehowo00vare|url-access=registration|quote=protection racketeering.}}</ref> It is generally seen as a way where criminals change the legal face of security and provide their own form of \"insurance\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Bryden|first=Alan|title=Private actors and security governance|year=2006|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|isbn=978-3-8258-9840-3|pages=314|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iVsIAP_iiboC&pg=PA113&dq=protection+racketeering#v=onepage&q=protection%20racketeering&f=false}}</ref> This practice of extorting money from people is also seen in the [[human trafficking]] business in [[Mexico]]; the cartels threaten smugglers to pay a fee for using the corridors, and if they refuse to pay, drug traffickers respond in a deadly form.<ref>{{cite book|last=Payan|first=Tony|title=Human rights along the U.S.-Mexico border: gendered violence and insecurity|year=2009|publisher=University of Arizona Press|isbn=978-0-8165-2872-1|pages=230|url=https://books.google.com/?id=qb9_w99QtEEC&pg=PA76&dq=mexico+protection+money#v=onepage&q=mexico%20protection%20money&f=false}}</ref> The Gulf Cartel operates in a similar way, and often extorts businesses for protection money in the areas where it operates, pledging to kill those who do not agree to pay the fee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crimen cobra cuotas a vecinos: Elizondo|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8560457|accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=15 April 2009|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091221064330/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8560457|archive-date=21 December 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In addition, the Mexican drug cartels also tax several Mexican businesses inside the [[United States]], and threaten them with property damage and murder if they do not comply.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gomora|first=Doris|title=C\u00e1rteles \"cobran piso\" en EU: DEA|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/primera/38445.html|accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=25 December 2011|language=es}}</ref>\n\n'''Kidnappings'''\nThe Gulf Cartel, along with their rival group [[Los Zetas]], have been the two drug cartels with the most [[kidnapping]]s in all of [[Mexico]], and \"more than half of the country's kidnappings are attributed to them.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Detenidas con Calder\u00f3n, 223 bandas de secuestradores|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/9087563|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=31 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114104255/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/9087563|archive-date=14 January 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> And, there are several kidnapping rings of the Gulf Cartel throughout several parts of [[Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Presentan a banda de secuestradores en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/be0e93a852354ad9e833b2ddff5eeac5|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=9 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108012300/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/be0e93a852354ad9e833b2ddff5eeac5|archive-date=8 January 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Mexican military mentioned that in the states of Tamaulipas and [[Nuevo Leon]], where the Gulf Cartel and Los Zetas fight for territory, abductions are carried out very commonly. An intelligence agency mentioned that the Gulf Cartel kidnaps for three reasons:\n# To increase the ranks of their cartel after the deaths or arrests of their own members;\n# To exterminate members of their rival gangs;\n# To kidnap people for money and other ransom.<ref>{{cite news|title=Van mil 700 desaparecidos en Nuevo Le\u00f3n y Tamaulipas, seg\u00fan reportes a militares|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/vanmil700desaparecidosennuevoleonytamaulipassegunreportesamilitares-563396.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=La Vanguardia|date=4 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011 in the border city of [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]], 68 kidnapped victims from different parts of Mexico and [[Central America]] were found in a safe house of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rescatan a 68 inmigrantes secuestrados por el C\u00e1rtel del Golfo en Reynosa, Tamaulipas|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_C7HF4ugWS0|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio TV|date=10 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rescatan a 51 inmigrantes secuestrados cerca de frontera|url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/620530.rescatan-a-51-inmigrantes-secuestrados-cerca.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=El Siglo de Torreon|date=April 2011}}</ref> [[Omar Ortiz]], best known for his nickname ''El Gato'', was a former soccer star from [[C.F. Monterrey]] who was arrested in January 2012 for working in a kidnapping ring within the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexican soccer star arrested for working in kidnapping ring that took pop singer's husband|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2012/01/mexican-soccer-star-arrested-for.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=8 January 2012}}</ref> The Mexican [[Lucha libre]] wrestler L\u00e1zaro Gurrola, known as the ''Estrella Dorada'' (Golden Star), was also arrested for kidnapping people for the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=El luchador mexicano 'Estrella Dorada' es acusado de secuestro|url=http://noticias.univision.com/mexico/noticias/article/2012-01-10/luchador-estrella-dorada-es-acusado-de-narco#axzz1k8NJHb3F|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Univision|date=10 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[United States]], the Gulf Cartel has been responsible for several kidnappings, primarily in [[McAllen\u2013Edinburg\u2013Mission metropolitan area|the McAllen metropolitan area]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lopez|first=Katie|title=San Juan kidnapping ring suspects face judge|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?list=195030&id=688470#.Txs202O3CFc|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Action 4 News|date=18 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104062754/http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?list=195030&id=688470#.Txs202O3CFc|archive-date=4 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel lieutenant linked to various incidents in the U.S side|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/linked-135370-mcallen-cartel.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=2 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Caranza|first=Rafael|title=Alleged Gulf Cartel members charged with Hidalgo kidnapping|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=683073#.TxsxF2O3CFc|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Valley Central|date=4 November 2011}}</ref> Investigators believe that more unreported kidnappings have occurred in nearby locations.<ref>{{cite news|title=San Juan kidnapping ring reportedly had Gulf Cartel ties|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?list=195030&id=687844#.Txs3a2O3CFc|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Action 4 News|date=17 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104062339/http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?list=195030&id=687844#.Txs3a2O3CFc|archive-date=4 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> When victims are kidnapped by the drug cartels on American territory, kidnappers usually hide them in the trunk of a car and take them to [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ortiz|first=Ildelfonso|title=Gulf Cartel members charged in Hidalgo kidnapping|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/hidalgo-56346-charged-gulf.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=4 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101162702/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/hidalgo-56346-charged-gulf.html|archive-date=1 January 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> FBI investigators said that victims are \"kidnapped, threatened, assaulted, drugged and transported into Mexico to meet with Cartel members.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Gulf Cartel kidnapping of U.S. citizens|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2010/01/gulf-cartel-kidnappings-of-us-citizens.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=27 January 2010}}</ref> Reports indicated that kidnappers working for the Gulf Cartel train with [[paintball]] equipment \"to practice simulated kidnapping schemes in order to prepare for the actual kidnapping they intended to commit.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Dodge|first=Angela|title=JURY CONVICTS CARTEL ASSOCIATE OF CONSPIRACY TO KIDNAP AND KIDNAPPING|url=http://www.justice.gov/usao/txs/1News/Releases/2010%20January/012210%20Avila_print.htm|publisher=Department of Justice|accessdate=21 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104045804/http://www.justice.gov/usao/txs/1News/Releases/2010%20January/012210%20Avila_print.htm|archive-date=4 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In one reported incident, Isaac Sanchez Gutierrez, a man from [[Palmview, Texas]], said he faced an ultimatum: pay $10 million to the Gulf Cartel, or transport 50 drug loads from Mexico into the U.S. in order to free his kidnapped brother.<ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Jared|title=Palmview chase suspect: Gulf Cartel forced me to smuggle|url=http://www.valleymorningstar.com/articles/-97170--.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=21 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''Human trafficking'''\n{{See also|Human trafficking in Mexico}}\nBefore 2010, it was not clear whether the Gulf Cartel controls the [[human trafficking]] business in its territory or whether it simply taxes operators for using their smuggling corridors.<ref>{{cite book|last=Spener|first=David|title=Clandestine crossings: migrants and coyotes on the Texas-Mexico border|year=2009|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-7589-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/clandestinecross00spen/page/298 298]|url=https://archive.org/details/clandestinecross00spen|url-access=registration|quote=gulf cartel human trafficking.}}</ref> ''[[La Jornada]]'' mentioned that before the rupture with [[Los Zetas]] in 2007, the corridor of [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]] was often used for human smuggling.<ref>{{cite news|title=Captura PGR a El Barbas y otros cuatro presuntos narcotraficantes|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2007/04/18/index.php?section=politica&article=005n2pol|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=La Jornada|date=18 April 2007|language=es}}</ref> [[People smuggling]] is currently controlled by a cell within the Gulf Cartel known as ''Los Flacos'', dedicated to the kidnapping and smuggling of undocumented migrants as far as [[South America]] to the United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=EJERCIT\u00d3 PGR ACCI\u00d3N PENAL CONTRA DOS PERSONAS, POR DELINCUENCIA ORGANIZADA Y SECUESTRO|url=http://pgr.gob.mx/Prensa/2007/bol11/Nov/b156711.shtm|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Procuraduria General de la Republica|date=14 November 2011|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104030205/http://pgr.gob.mx/Prensa/2007/bol11/Nov/b156711.shtm|archive-date=4 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It operates primarily on the [[Tabasco]]\u2013[[Veracruz]]\u2013[[Tamaulipas]] corridor.<ref>{{cite news|last=Carvallo Guzm\u00e1n|first=Indira|title=En Veracruz, PGR captura a tres personas por el tr\u00e1fico de personas en el sur|url=http://www.diariopresencia.com/nota.aspx?ID=42853&List=%7BE99F52BD-B89D-4D80-A5BB-BCD1566AE98A%7D|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Diario Presencia|date=14 November 2011|language=es}}</ref> Human trafficking in the [[Rio Grande Valley]] has become \"ground zero\" and was considered the \"new Arizona\" in December 2011 by the ''Homeland Security Today''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kimery|first=Anthony|title=Drug, Human Smuggling, Cartel Shootouts With Police Escalate In Rio Grande Valley|url=http://www.hstoday.us/blogs/the-kimery-report/blog/drug-human-smuggling-cartel-shootouts-with-police-escalate-in-rio-grande-valley/b55c95b14c1708ee4691b22a8bcb70f5.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Homeland Security Today|date=6 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nA U.S. agent mentioned that the drug cartels that operate on the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]], and principally across from [[Texas]], are \"in control of not only the narcotrafficking, but also the human smuggling.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Sutton|first=Barbara|title=Security disarmed: critical perspectives on gender, race, and militarization|year=2008|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=978-0-8135-4360-4|pages=308|url=https://books.google.com/?id=o9SzGdYrBfYC&pg=PA88&dq=gulf+cartel+human+smuggling#v=onepage&q=gulf%20cartel%20human%20smuggling&f=false}}</ref>\n<!-- This was the Zetas' realm. Include if updated.\n'''Extortion'''\nIn August 2007, ''La Ma\u00f1a'' gang, an alleged sub-group of the criminal group [[Los Zetas]] and the Gulf Cartel, was reported to have controlled the [[extortion]] business in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico: La Ma\u00f1a gang; whether this group is involved in smuggling people into the United States (US); whether this group has links to the criminal group Los Zetas|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/publisher,IRBC,,MEX,49b92b381e,0.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada|date=16 October 2008}}</ref> The newspaper ''[[La Vanguardia]]'' mentioned that the Gulf Cartel receives \"large sums of money by extorting businesses\" all around Tamaulipas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Federales capturan a l\u00edderes del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/federalescapturanalideresdelcarteldelgolfoentamaulipas-665445.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=La Vanguardia|date=5 March 2011}}</ref> Many of the extortions are first carried out on the phone.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sin freno, extorsiones telef\u00f3nicas|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8049490|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=18 November 2008}}</ref> -->\nCritics say that the strategy of capturing drug kingpins often resulted in the increase in [[extortion]], as the cartels look for other sources of money.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico's drugs war: Lessons and challenges|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-16337488|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=31 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''Bribery'''\nWhen the Gulf Cartel was moving tons of cocaine to the [[United States]] and moving millions of dollars in cash along the border in the 1970s, [[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]] decided that he needed more protection. Court documents indicated that Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was bribing several law enforcement officials, prosecutors, and politicians on both sides on the border to keep himself impune and untouched.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drug Lord's Web of Payoffs Spans U.S.-Mexico Border|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1995-09-04/news/mn-42137_1_garcia-abrego|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=4 September 1995|first=Mark|last=Fineman}}</ref> His former friends and associates mentioned that the drug lord was paying one of [[Carlos Salinas de Gortari]]'s deputy attorneys general more than $1.5 million a month for his protection.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fineman|first=Mark|title=Mexican Drug Cartel Chief Convicted in U.S.|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1996-10-17/news/mn-57764_1_garcia-abrego|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=17 October 1996}}</ref> He is allegedly reported to have been protected by a large private army of gunmen.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dillon|first=Sam|title=Mexico Arrests A Top Suspect In Drug Trade|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/01/16/world/mexico-arrests-a-top-suspect-in-drug-trade.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=16 January 1996}}</ref> A retired FBI agent and expert in drug trafficking explained that the Gulf Cartel \"relied on bribery\" to build its drug empire and consolidate its prominence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexican Drug Empire Built With Murder, Ex-agent Says|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1996-09-19/news/9609181151_1_abrego-cartel-fbi-agent|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Orlando Sentinel|date=19 September 1996}}</ref>\n\n[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) agents have claimed that the Gulf Cartel moves millions of dollars in cash through the [[Rio Grande Valley]] each month, a tempting amount for many U.S. officials.<ref>{{cite news|last=Del Valle|first=Fernando|title=Cartel bribery spreads to Valley|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/articles/san-120505-spreads-valley.html|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=The Brownsville Herald|date=13 December 2010}}</ref> Much of the money stays in the area, which has caused several officials\u2014both federal and state\u2014to succumb to the \"easy money aspect\" the drug money has to offer.<ref>{{cite news|title=FBI: Drug money threatens to corrupt Valley cops|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/san-45693-cops-threatens.html|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=25 December 2010}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The Gulf Cartel also bribes [[journalists]] to persuade them not to mention any violent incidents in the media.<ref>{{cite news|title=El c\u00e1rtel del Golfo soborna a periodistas para que no cubran los sucesos violentos|url=http://globedia.com/cartel-golfo-soborna-periodistas-cubran-sucesos-violentos|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Globedia|date=3 December 2010}}</ref> In addition, due to the low-paying salaries of many policemen, the Gulf Cartel often \"buys\" many law enforcement officers in Mexico.<ref>{{cite news|title=Comprar un polic\u00eda cuesta $3,500 en NL|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8585825|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=3 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110409022325/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8585825|archive-date=9 April 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''Theft'''\nStealing oil from [[PEMEX]] and selling it illegally has been one of the many funding activities of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Zetas desalojaron campo de Pemex en Tamaulipas|url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8725004|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Milenio|date=February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100810005325/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8725004|archive-date=10 August 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> They were reported to have stolen around 40% of the oil products in 2011 in northern Mexico and then selling it illegally in Mexico and in the American black market.<ref>{{cite news|title=Robo de combustible en M\u00e9xico, en manos de c\u00e1rteles del narcotr\u00e1fico|url=http://noticias.univision.com/narcotrafico/article/2011-12-28/robo-combustibles-mexico-carteles-narcotrafico#axzz1k8NJHb3F|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=Univision|date=28 December 2011}}</ref> One leader of the Gulf Cartel confessed after his apprehension that \"drug trafficking is their main business, but due to the difficulties they have been encountering, oil theft has been an important financial cushion\" for the cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pemex, bot\u00edn del narco y de mafias internas: escritora|url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/692011.html|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=El Siglo de Torreon|date=28 December 2011|language=es}}</ref> They have also been reported to steal vehicles.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rendon|first=Francisco|title=Desintegr\u00f3 PFP peligrosa c\u00e9lula del Cartel del Golfo|url=http://www.elregional.com.mx/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=23234:desintegro-pfp-peligrosa-celula-del-cartel-del-golfo&catid=39&Itemid=37|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=El Regional del Sur|date=9 November 2011|language=es}}</ref>\n\n'''Money laundering'''\nSome of the revenue of the Gulf Cartel is often [[Money laundering|laundered]] in several bank accounts, properties, vehicles, and gasoline stations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Desarticula PGR red de lavado de dinero del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.cronica.com.mx/nota.php?id_nota=466307|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=La Cronica|date=3 March 2011|language=es}}</ref> Bars and casinos are often the hubs for money laundering of the drug cartels.<ref>{{cite news|title=Detienen a presunto implicado en lavado de dinero|url=http://www.elsiglodedurango.com.mx/noticia/240903.detienen-a-presunto-implicado-en-lavado-de-di.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=El Siglo de Torreon|date=23 November 2009|language=es}}</ref> Top leaders of the Gulf organization, like [[Juan Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego]], [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]], and [[Antonio C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], among others, have been charged by the U.S. government for laundering millions of dollars.<ref>{{cite book|last=Richards|first=James R.|title=Transnational criminal organizations, cybercrime, and money laundering|year=1999|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-0-8493-2806-0|pages=318|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RmGi5zDus7gC&pg=PA22&dq=gulf+cartel+money+laundering#v=onepage&q=gulf%20cartel%20money%20laundering&f=false}}</ref> Bank accounts inside the United States also launder millions of dollars for the drug lords of the Gulf Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|title=El dinero del narco, principal reto para el sistema financiero de EU|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/mundo/2011/10/13/el-dinero-del-narco-principal-reto-para-el-sistema-financiero-de-eu|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=13 October 2011|language=es}}</ref> ''[[The Economist]]'' mentioned in 1997 that the drug money from the Gulf Cartel in the [[Rio Grande Valley]] was perhaps moving about $20 billion, and that around 15% of the retailers' gains were from drug money.<ref>{{cite news|title=One river, one country|url=http://www.uwec.edu/geography/Ivogeler/w188/articles/txmx.htm|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=The Economist|year=1997|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130222081319/http://www.uwec.edu/geography/Ivogeler/w188/articles/txmx.htm|archive-date=22 February 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''Arms trafficking'''\nFor the most part, the [[arms trafficking]] circles of the Gulf Cartel operate directly across the border in the [[United States]], just like most of the criminal groups in Mexico.<ref>{{cite news|title=El Mamito: \"\"All the weapons are bought in the United States\"|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2011/07/el-mamito-all-our-weapons-are-bought-in.html|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=6 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ringleader behind Gulf Cartel gun, drug trafficking ring in McAllen pleads guilty|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/mcallen-54500-ring-guilty.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120914083217/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/mcallen-54500-ring-guilty.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 September 2012|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=6 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Jared|title=Shots near Weslaco lead cops to Gulf Cartel arms smuggling|url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/lead-56653-mcallen-arms.html|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=The Monitor|date=17 November 2011}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Nonetheless, there are indeed circles within the Gulf Cartel that coordinate the arms trafficking routes inside Mexico.<ref>{{cite news|title=Caen l\u00edderes del C\u00e1rtel del Golfo|url=http://www.eldiariodecoahuila.com.mx/notas/2011/3/6/nacional-221582.asp|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=El Diario de Coahuila|date=6 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712182834/http://www.eldiariodecoahuila.com.mx/notas/2011/3/6/nacional-221582.asp|archive-date=12 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Arms trafficking from the U.S. to Mexico, however, is often carried out individually, and there is no criminal group in Mexico or an international organization that is solely dedicated to this activity.<ref>{{cite news|last=De la Luz Gonzalez|first=Maria|title=Operaci\u00f3n 'hormiga', en el tr\u00e1fico de armas|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/164626.html|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal|date=22 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn a side note, [[Jes\u00fas Enrique Rej\u00f3n Aguilar]], a top-tier Los Zetas boss, was caught on 3 July 2011, and claimed in an interview that was aired on national television that the Gulf Cartel, unlike Los Zetas, has an \"easier and quicker accessibility to arms in the United States\", and probably works \"with some people in the government\" to traffic weapons south of the U.S. border.<ref>{{cite news|title=Armamento de 'Los Zetas' se compra en EU, dice fundador del grupo criminal|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/05/armamento-de-los-zetas-se-compra-en-eu-dice-fundador-del-grupo-criminal|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Mexico|date=5 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928211427/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/07/05/armamento-de-los-zetas-se-compra-en-eu-dice-fundador-del-grupo-criminal|archivedate=28 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''Prostitution network'''\n[[Prostitution]] circles are believed to be used by the Gulf Cartel to persuade journalists to favor them in the media.<ref>{{cite news|title=El c\u00e1rtel del Golfo compra periodistas con \"narcod\u00f3lares\", prostitutas y alcohol|url=http://www.tribunalatina.com/es/Viewer_100_1columna.php?IDN=24293|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=Tribuna Latina|date=3 March 2010|language=es}}</ref> Prostitutes are also used as informants and spies, and provide their sexual favors to extract information from certain targets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se triplica n\u00famero de homicidios de prostitutas relacionadas con el narco|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2011/07/21/politica/021n2pol|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=La Jornada|date=21 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''Counterfeiting'''\nThe Mexican criminal organizations like the Gulf Cartel launder money through [[counterfeiting]], since they are free from taxes and more accessible to people who cannot buy original products.<ref>{{cite news |title=El narco lava dinero con pirater\u00eda |url=http://www.cnnexpansion.com/economia/2010/07/16/el-narco-lava-dinero-con-pirateria |access-date=22 January 2012 |newspaper=CNN Expansion |date=16 July 2010}}</ref> The products sold can be clothing, TVs, video games, music, computer programs, and movies.<ref>{{cite news|title=La pirater\u00eda asuela a la industria legal|url=http://www.cnnexpansion.com/economia/2010/07/15/falsificaciones-productos-pirata-cine|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=CNN Expansion|date=15 July 2010}}</ref> In 2008 in the state of [[Michoac\u00e1n]], the Gulf Cartel was reported to have controlled the counterfeit business, where it produced and sold millions of fake CDs and movies.<ref>{{cite news|last=Castillo Garc\u00eda|first=Gustavo|title=El c\u00e1rtel del Golfo controla la pirater\u00eda en Michoac\u00e1n|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2008/04/02/index.php?section=politica&article=014n2pol|accessdate=22 January 2012|newspaper=La Jornada|date=2 April 2008}}</ref>\n\n'''Police impersonation'''\nReports indicate that gunmen from the Gulf Cartel often [[Police impersonation|impersonate]] law enforcement officers, using military uniforms to confuse rival drug gangs and move freely through city streets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Militares piratas en M\u00e9xico|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/militarespiratasenmexico-523317.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=La Vanguardia|date=23 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n'''Transportation'''\nDue to the Gulf Cartel's territory in northern [[Tamaulipas]], primarily in the border cities of [[Reynosa, Tamaulipas]] and [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], they have been able to establish a sophisticated and extensive drug trafficking and distribution network along the U.S.\u2013Mexico border in [[South Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|title=South Texas High Intensity Drug Trafficking Area Drug Market Analysis|url=http://www.justice.gov/ndic/pubs27/27513/drugover.htm|publisher=National Drug Intelligence Center|accessdate=8 December 2011}}</ref> The Mexican drug cartels that operate in the area are currently employing gang members to distribute drugs and conduct other criminal activities on their behalf.<ref>{{cite web|title=South Texas High Intensity Drug Trafficking Area|url=http://www.justice.gov/ndic/dmas/South_Texas_DMA-2011(U).pdf|publisher=U.S. Department of Justice|accessdate=8 December 2011}}</ref> Among these gangs, that range from street gangs to prison gangs, are the [[Texas Syndicate]], the [[Latin Kings (gang)|Latin Kings]], the [[Mexican Mafia]], the Tango Blast (Vallucos), the Hermandad de Pistoleros Latinos, and the Tri-City Bombers\u2014all based in the [[Rio Grande Valley]] and [[Webb County, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Texas Gang Threat Assessment 2010|url=http://montgomerytx.countymonitor.com/files/2010/10/TxGngThrtAssessment2010.pdf|publisher=Texas Department of Public Safety|accessdate=8 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426041257/http://montgomerytx.countymonitor.com/files/2010/10/TxGngThrtAssessment2010.pdf|archive-date=26 April 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Narco submarine seized in Ecuador 2010-07-02 1.jpg|thumb|A [[narco submarine]] seized in Ecuador in July 2010]]\nWhile the entire [[Mexico\u2013United States border]] has experienced high levels of drug trafficking and other illegal smuggling activities for decades, this activity tends to be concentrated in certain sectors within Texas. Two such sectors are the [[Rio Grande Valley]] and [[West Texas]], near the [[El Paso\u2013Ju\u00e1rez]] metropolitan area. The high level of legitimate travel and movement of goods and services between border cities in the U.S. and Mexico facilitates the drug business in the area. The majority of the commerce between the United States and Mexico passes through the state of Texas.<ref>{{cite web|title=An Overview of Federal Drug Control Programs on the Southwest Border|url=https://www.ncjrs.gov/ondcppubs/publications/enforce/border/intro_2.html|publisher=Office of National Drug Control Policy|accessdate=8 December 2011}}</ref> Due to its multifaceted transportation networks and proximity to major production areas right across the border in Mexico, Texas is a major hub for drug trafficking. According to the [[National Drug Intelligence Center]], drug traffickers commonly use private vehicles and commercial trucks to traffic narcotics throughout the state. The drug organizations usually use the Interstates [[Interstate 10 in Texas|10]], [[Interstate 20 in Texas|20]], [[Interstate 25|25]], [[Interstate 30|30]], and [[Interstate 35 in Texas|35]], as well as U.S. Highways [[U.S. Route 59 in Texas|59]], [[U.S. Route 77|77]], [[U.S. Route 83|83]], and [[U.S. Route 281|281]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Texas Drug Threat Assessment|url=http://www.justice.gov/ndic/pubs5/5624/overview.htm|publisher=National Drug Intelligence Center|accessdate=8 December 2011}}</ref> The [[Gulf of Mexico]] also presents a danger to the flow of drugs to Texas; the [[Port of Houston]] and the [[Port of Brownsville]] enable traffickers to use small vessels and pleasure craft to transport illicit drugs into and from southern Texas.<ref>{{cite web|title=South Texas Border and San Antonio Market Areas (2008)|url=http://www.justice.gov/ndic/pubs27/27513/border.htm|publisher=National Drug Intelligence Center|accessdate=8 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIllicit drugs also are smuggled into and through Texas via commercial aircraft, cars, buses, passenger trains, pedestrians, and package delivery services. Narcotics are also smuggled through the railroads that connect the U.S. and Mexico. Moreover, the Mexican drug traffickers often use small boats to transport drugs through the coastal areas of South Texas, usually operating at night to prevent them from being spotted by law enforcement officials.<ref>{{cite web|title=South Texas Border and San Antonio Market Areas (2007)|url=http://www.justice.gov/ndic/pubs22/22796/border.htm|publisher=National Drug Intelligence Center}}</ref> Another avenue that they have implemented is to construct [[tunnel]]s to get their product across the border. By constructing a tunnel, the cartel is able to get their product across the tight border security with the possibility of no detection.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nogales drug tunnel found|url=https://www.usatoday.com/USCP/PNI/NEWS/2011-11-23-PNI1123met-nogales-tunnelPNIBrd_ST_U.htm|accessdate=8 December 2011|newspaper=USA Today|date=23 November 2011}}</ref> Apart from using these common ways, once the product is across the border, common cars and trucks are utilized for faster distribution in different cities. In an effort to use the seas, the cartel also implemented the use of [[narco submarine]]s.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Kraul | title=Drug traffickers use submersibles to ferry narcotics | date=6 November 2007 |work=Los Angeles Times | url =https://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-narcosub6nov06,0,6804696.story | accessdate =19 February 2010 }}</ref><ref name=jitfs>{{Cite journal |title=Self-Propelled Semi-Submersible (SPSS) - Fact Sheet |publisher=Joint Interagency Task Force South |year=2008 |url=http://media.mcclatchydc.com/smedia/2008/07/18/17/Hall-SPSS-factsheet.source.prod_affiliate.91.pdf |access-date=19 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=Tamil >{{cite news | first=David | last=Kushner | title=Drug-Sub Culture | date=23 April 2009 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/26/magazine/26drugs-t.html?_r=1 | work =The New York Times | accessdate =25 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Indictments==\nOn 21 July 2009, the United States [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]] announced coordinated actions against the Gulf Cartel and [[Los Zetas]] drug trafficking organizations.  [[Antonio Ezequiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], [[Jorge Eduardo Costilla S\u00e1nchez]], [[Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano]] and 15 of their top lieutenants, have been charged in U.S. federal courts with drug trafficking-related crimes,<ref name=drive >{{cite news | first= Glenn| last= Somerville| title=U.S. launches drive against Mexican drug cartel | date=20 July 2009 | url =https://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSN2091449 | work =Reuters | accessdate =18 August 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Alleged Mexican Cartel Leaders, Associates Targeted in Newest Effort to Combat Drug Trafficking Organizations|url=http://www.justice.gov/dea/pubs/pressrel/pr072009.html|accessdate=14 December 2011|newspaper=Drug Enforcement Administration|date=20 July 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114044432/http://www.justice.gov/dea/pubs/pressrel/pr072009.html|archive-date=14 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> while the U.S. State Department announced rewards totaling $50 million [[USD]] for information leading to their capture.<ref name=drive />\n\nIn May 2013, [[Aurelio Cano Flores]] (alias ''El Yankee'') was sentenced to 35 years in prison for conspiring to import multi-ton quantities of marijuana and cocaine into the United States. Cano Flores, also known as \"Yeyo\", was a former Mexican police officer and is the highest ranking Gulf Cartel member to be convicted by a U.S. jury in 15 years.<ref name=BBYankee>{{cite press release |title=CDG's 'El Yankee' Sentenced in D.C. to 35 Years |url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2013/05/cdgs-el-yankee-sentenced-in-dc-to-35.html|website=Borderland Beat |publisher=DEA-DOJ}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 June 2019, Mario Alberto C\u00e1rdenas Medina, the son of Osiel's brother Mario, was arrested in the state of Mexico.<ref>https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&u=https://www.univision.com/noticias/america-latina/autoridades-mexicanas-capturan-a-mario-cardenas-el-betito-sobrino-del-exlider-del-cartel-del-golfo&prev=search</ref><ref>https://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/cae-en-naucalpan-el-betito-sobrino-de-osiel-cardenas/1321715</ref> He was arrested with a female companion identified as Miriam \"M\" and is accused of being responsible for recent violence in Tamaulipas<ref>https://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/police-arrest-ex-drug-lords-nephew/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Illegal drug trade in Colombia]]\n*[[List of gangs in Mexico]]\n* [[List of Mexico's 37 most-wanted drug lords]]\n* [[M\u00e9rida Initiative]]\n* [[Mexican Drug War]]\n* [[Operation Solare]]\n* [[Timeline of the Mexican Drug War]]\n* [[War on Drugs]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/mexico/etc/gulf.html PBS Frontline: The Gulf Cartel], ''PBS'' (1997)\n* [http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/mexicos_cartel_wars_20110516/ Cartel Wars by Michael Deibert, Truthdig, 16 May 2011]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Drug Wars: Narco Warfare in the twenty first century. Flemming, Gary. Booksurge, 2008.\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3HEpDwAAQBAJ&dq|title=Los Zetas Inc.: Criminal Corporations, Energy, and Civil War in Mexico|last=Correa-Cabrera|first=Guadalupe|publisher=[[University of Texas Press]]|year=2017|isbn=978-1477312773|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Mexican Drug War}}\n\n{{Organized crime groups in America}}\n\n[[Category:Drug cartels in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Gangs in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mexican Drug War]]\n[[Category:Hispanic-American gangs]]\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gulf_Cartel"}
{"title_page": "SS Cape Gibson (AK-5051)", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=S.S. Cape Gibson (AK-5051).jpg\n|Ship caption=Former Merchant Marine Academy flagship SS ''Cape Gibson'', ex-SS''Indian Mail''.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1963}}\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship name=SS ''Indian Mail'', later changed to SS ''President Jackson''\n|Ship owner=American Mail Lines, then sold to [[American President Lines]]\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Newport News Shipbuilding and Dry Dock Co., [[Newport News, Virginia]]\n|Ship cost=\n|Ship yard number=588<ref name=\"COLTON\">{{cite web|last1=Colton|first1=Tim|title=Newport News Shipbuilding, Newport News VA|url=http://www.shipbuildinghistory.com/history/shipyards/2large/active/newportnews.htm|website=Shipbuilding History|publisher=ShipBuildingHistory.com|accessdate=15 October 2016}}</ref> \n|Ship way number=517717\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship acquired=13 December 1968\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship striken=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship homeport=[[Seattle, Washington]]\n|Ship identification=*{{IMO Number|6821614}}\n*{{MMSI Number|367076000}}\n*[[Maritime call sign|Callsign]]: KADB\n|Ship fate=Transferred to [[MARAD]], placed in the [[National Defense Reserve Fleet]] at [[Alameda, California]]. \n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship flag=[[Image:Flag of the United States.svg|48px|center]]\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship name=T.S. ''Texas Clipper IV''\n|Ship owner= United States Maritime Administration\n|Ship operator=[[Texas A&M University at Galveston]]\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=19 October 2009\n|Ship out of service=2012\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship homeport=[[Galveston, Texas|Galveston]], [[Texas]]\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=designated for disposal\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class= Breakbulk cargo ship, Training Ship\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement=9,779&nbsp;tons light, 31,995&nbsp;tons fully loaded\n|Ship length={{convert|605|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|82|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draft={{convert|35|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship power=24,000 shp at 105 rpm\n|Ship propulsion=Single steam turbine, two boilers, single propellor\n|Ship speed=11&nbsp;kt cruise\n|Ship capacity=22,216 DWT\n|Ship crew=32\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''SS ''Cape Gibson'' (AK-5051)''' is a Cape G Class [[break bulk cargo|Break bulk cargo ship]] of the [[United States Maritime Administration]], last used as a training ship at [[Texas A&M University at Galveston]]. Currently she is mothballed in the [[Beaumont Reserve Fleet]].\n\n==History==\nThe ship was originally delivered as SS ''Indian Mail'' a [[Type C5 class ship|class C5-S-75a ship]], to American Mail Line Ltd., of [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]] in 1968 as one of five C5-S-75a class breakbulk cargo container ships (the others being SS ''Alaskan Mail'', SS ''American Mail'', SS ''Korea Mail'', and SS ''Hong Kong Mail'').<ref name=\"COLTON\" />   With the onset of containerization, this type of cargo ship was approaching obsolescence, but this class was well equipped for handling a wide variety of cargoes. The ship was later acquired by [[American President Lines]] and name was changed to SS ''President Jackson''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apl.com/wps/wcm/connect/7dada969-07ff-4230-95d9-f63fbb305b4e/APL%2BHistory.pdf?MOD=AJPERES&CVID=l8CO50S |title=History of the American President Lines |publisher=American President Lines |access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> In 1988 the ship was transferred to [[MARAD]], renamed SS ''Cape Gibson'' and mothballed in the [[National Defense Reserve Fleet]] at [[Alameda, California]]. She was assigned to the [[Military Sealift Command]] as a  [[Maritime prepositioning ship#Activated Ready Reserve Fleet Ships|Modular Cargo Delivery System Ship]] and capable of being reactivated in five days.<ref name=\"navsource\">{{cite news |last=Priolo |first=Gary |url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/09/13/135051.htm |title=NavSource Online: Service Ship Photo Archive SS Cape Gibson (AK-5051) |work=NavSource Naval History |date=2010-11-19 |accessdate=2014-06-01 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 SS ''Cape Gibson'' was reactivated as training ship for Texas A&M Maritime Academy cadets, serving until 2012 until being replaced by [[USNS Contender (T-AGOS-2)|TS ''General Rudder'']]. She was subsequently placed in the Beaumont Reserve Fleet.<ref name=\"tamug\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tamug.edu/corps/trainingship.html |title=Training Ship GENERAL RUDDER |publisher=Texas A&M University |year=2013 |accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> In August 2016 she was designated for disposal.<ref>{{cite web|title=NATIONAL DEFENSE RESERVE FLEET INVENTORY MAR-612:  RESERVE FLEET MANAGEMENT SYSTEM MONTHLY REPORT AS OF August 31, 2016|url=https://www.marad.dot.gov/wp-content/uploads/pdf/i160831.pdf|website=MARAD - National Defense Reserve Fleet|publisher=U.S. Department of Transportation Maritime Administration|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/systems/ship/cape-g.htm  Cape G class breakbulk maintenance in the 1990s]\n*[http://drawings.usmaritimecommission.de/drawing_ma/drawings_c5_s_75a_des.htm  Detailed description of C5-S-75a cargo ships]\n <!-- non-breaking space to keep AWB drones from altering the space before the navbox-->\n\n{{United States Training Ships}}\n{{Surviving ocean going ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cape Gibson, SS}}\n[[Category:United States Merchant Marine]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Newport News, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Beaumont Reserve Fleet]]\n[[Category:Type C5 ships]]\n[[Category:1968 ships]]\n\n\n{{ship-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=S.S. Cape Gibson (AK-5051).jpg\n|Ship caption=Former Merchant Marine Academy flagship SS ''Cape Gibson'', ex-SS''Indian Mail''.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1963}}\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship name=SS ''Indian Mail'', later changed to SS ''President Jackson''\n|Ship owner=American Mail Lines, then sold to [[American President Lines]]\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Newport News Shipbuilding and Dry Dock Co., [[Newport News, Virginia]]\n|Ship cost=\n|Ship yard number=588<ref name=\"COLTON\">{{cite web|last1=Colton|first1=Tim|title=Newport News Shipbuilding, Newport News VA|url=http://www.shipbuildinghistory.com/history/shipyards/2large/active/newportnews.htm|website=Shipbuilding History|publisher=ShipBuildingHistory.com|accessdate=15 October 2016}}</ref> \n|Ship way number=517717\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship acquired=13 December 1968\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship striken=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship homeport=[[Seattle, Washington]]\n|Ship identification=*{{IMO Number|6821614}}\n*{{MMSI Number|367076000}}\n*[[Maritime call sign|Callsign]]: KADB\n|Ship fate=Transferred to [[MARAD]], placed in the [[National Defense Reserve Fleet]] at [[Alameda, California]]. \n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship flag=[[Image:Flag of the United States.svg|48px|center]]\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship name=T.S. ''Texas Clipper IV''\n|Ship owner= United States Maritime Administration\n|Ship operator=[[Texas A&M University at Galveston]]\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=19 October 2009\n|Ship out of service=2012\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship homeport=[[Galveston, Texas|Galveston]], [[Texas]]\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=designated for disposal\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class= Breakbulk cargo ship, Training Ship\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement=9,779&nbsp;tons light, 31,995&nbsp;tons fully loaded\n|Ship length={{convert|605|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|82|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draft={{convert|35|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship power=24,000 shp at 105 rpm\n|Ship propulsion=Single steam turbine, two boilers, single propellor\n|Ship speed=11&nbsp;kt cruise\n|Ship capacity=22,216 DWT\n|Ship crew=32\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''SS ''Cape Gibson'' (AK-5051)''' is a Cape G Class [[break bulk cargo|Break bulk cargo ship]] of the [[United States Maritime Administration]], last used as a training ship at [[Texas A&M University at Galveston]]. Currently she is mothballed in the [[Beaumont Reserve Fleet]].\n\n==History==\nThe ship was originally delivered as SS ''Indian Mail'' a [[Type C5 class ship|class C5-S-75a ship]], to American Mail Line Ltd., of [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]] in 1968 as one of five C-5-S-75a class breakbulk cargo container ships (the others being SS ''Alaskan Mail'', SS ''American Mail'', SS ''Korea Mail'', and SS ''Hong Kong Mail'').<ref name=\"COLTON\" />   With the onset of containerization, this type of cargo ship was approaching obsolescence, but this class was well equipped for handling a wide variety of cargoes. The ship was later acquired by [[American President Lines]] and name was changed to SS ''President Jackson''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apl.com/wps/wcm/connect/7dada969-07ff-4230-95d9-f63fbb305b4e/APL%2BHistory.pdf?MOD=AJPERES&CVID=l8CO50S |title=History of the American President Lines |publisher=American President Lines |access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> In 1988 the ship was transferred to [[MARAD]], renamed SS ''Cape Gibson'' and mothballed in the [[National Defense Reserve Fleet]] at [[Alameda, California]]. She was assigned to the [[Military Sealift Command]] as a  [[Maritime prepositioning ship#Activated Ready Reserve Fleet Ships|Modular Cargo Delivery System Ship]] and capable of being reactivated in five days.<ref name=\"navsource\">{{cite news |last=Priolo |first=Gary |url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/09/13/135051.htm |title=NavSource Online: Service Ship Photo Archive SS Cape Gibson (AK-5051) |work=NavSource Naval History |date=2010-11-19 |accessdate=2014-06-01 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 SS ''Cape Gibson'' was reactivated as training ship for Texas A&M Maritime Academy cadets, serving until 2012 until being replaced by [[USNS Contender (T-AGOS-2)|TS ''General Rudder'']]. She was subsequently placed in the Beaumont Reserve Fleet.<ref name=\"tamug\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tamug.edu/corps/trainingship.html |title=Training Ship GENERAL RUDDER |publisher=Texas A&M University |year=2013 |accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> In August 2016 she was designated for disposal.<ref>{{cite web|title=NATIONAL DEFENSE RESERVE FLEET INVENTORY MAR-612:  RESERVE FLEET MANAGEMENT SYSTEM MONTHLY REPORT AS OF August 31, 2016|url=https://www.marad.dot.gov/wp-content/uploads/pdf/i160831.pdf|website=MARAD - National Defense Reserve Fleet|publisher=U.S. Department of Transportation Maritime Administration|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/systems/ship/cape-g.htm  Cape G class breakbulk maintenance in the 1990s]\n*[http://drawings.usmaritimecommission.de/drawing_ma/drawings_c5_s_75a_des.htm  Detailed description of C5-S-75a cargo ships]\n <!-- non-breaking space to keep AWB drones from altering the space before the navbox-->\n\n{{United States Training Ships}}\n{{Surviving ocean going ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cape Gibson, SS}}\n[[Category:United States Merchant Marine]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Newport News, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Beaumont Reserve Fleet]]\n[[Category:Type C5 ships]]\n[[Category:1968 ships]]\n\n\n{{ship-stub}}\n", "name_user": "BoH", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SS_Cape_Gibson_(AK-5051)"}
{"title_page": "Amalia Ercoli Finzi", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian astrophysicist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Amalia Ercoli Finzi\n| image              = Amalia_Ercoli_Finzi.jpg\n| birth_date         = 20 April 1937\n| birth_place        = [[Gallarate]], [[Italy]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Polytechnic University of Milan]]\n| employer           = [[Polytechnic University of Milan]]\n| known_for          = Aerospace engineering <br>\n[[Philae (spacecraft)]]\n}}\n\n'''Amalia Ercoli Finzi''' (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' '''Amalia Ercoli'''; born 20 April 1937) is an Italian astrophysicist and professor, Principal Investigator of the SD2 drill aboard the [[Philae (spacecraft)|Philae spacecraft]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nIn 1962 she was the first Italian woman to graduate in aeronautical engineering, from the [[Polytechnic University of Milan]], with a final grade of 100/100 [[cum laude]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://video.repubblica.it/rubriche/rnews/rnews-amalia-finzi-io-ingegnere-e-nonna-vi-svelero-i-segreti-della-cometa/183387/182222|title=RNews, Amalia Finzi: 'Io ingegnere e nonna vi sveler\u00f2 i segreti della cometa'|date=2014-11-14|website=Repubblica Tv - la Repubblica.it|language=it|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.museoscienza.org/attivita/spalle_giganti/download/biopic_finzi.pdf|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi|last=|first=|date=|website=Museo Nazionale della Scienza e della Tecnologia Leonardo da Vinci|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ilquorum.it/essere-una-donna-e-ancora-motivo-di-discriminazione-intervista-ad-amalia-ercoli-finzi/|title=\"Essere una donna \u00e9 ancora motivo di discriminazione\". Amalia Ercoli-Finzi {{!}} Il Quorum|date=2016-04-13|work=Il Quorum|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career ==\nShe has taught at the [[Polytechnic University of Milan]] for more than fifty years,<ref>{{Citation|last=PoliMi|title=Qua e l\u00e0 nello spazio (A. E. Finzi)|date=2017-06-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L51Vm2V2eA8|accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> becoming associate professor in 1980 and professor in 1994. She has served as Professor of Orbital Mechanics, Director of the Department of Aerospace Engineering and on the board of Directors of the [[Museo Nazionale Scienza e Tecnologia Leonardo da Vinci|National Museum of Science and Technology]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She has considerable experience in space flight dynamics. She has served as a scientific advisor for [[NASA]], [[Italian Space Agency|ISA]] and [[European Space Agency|ESA]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ingegneri.info/news/professione-e-previdenza/amalia-ercoli-finzi-donne-ingegnere-aerospaziale/|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi: parla la prima donna ingegnere aeronautico d\u2019Italia|date=2017-12-21|work=Ingegneri.info|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amishotelgalliffet.com/amalia-ercoli-finzi-ingenieur-des-cometes/#more-4070|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi, ing\u00e9nieur des com\u00e8tes {{!}} Les amis de l'Hotel Galliffet|website=www.amishotelgalliffet.com|language=it-IT|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\nShe has been involved with several [[NASA]] - [[Italian Space Agency]] missions, including [[space tether missions]], [[MiTEx]] and [[Columbus (ISS module)]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She was responsible for the SD2 instrument, which drilled the surface of [[67P/Churyumov\u2013Gerasimenko]], collected materials and took them for analysis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://science.closeupengineering.it/intervista-ad-amalia-ercoli-finzi-la-mamma-di-rosetta/8147/|title=Intervista ad Amalia Ercoli Finzi, la \"mamma\" di Rosetta {{!}} Close-up Engineering|last=Piazzolla|first=Antonio|date=2015-11-18|work=Close-up Engineering {{!}} Science & Tech|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infoclio.ch/fr/donne-nella-scienza-amalia-ercoli-finzi|title=Donne nella scienza: Amalia Ercoli Finzi {{!}} infoclio.ch|website=www.infoclio.ch|language=fr|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.glistatigenerali.com/robotica_tech-media/amalia-ercoli-finzi-litaliana-che-ha-portato-philae-vicino-al-sole/|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi, l\u2019italiana che ha portato Philae vicino al sole|date=2014-11-22|work=Gli Stati Generali|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref>\n\nErcoli is married to Filiberto Finzi, son of Italian mathematician [[Bruno Finzi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ilsudonline.it/le-eccellenze-del-made-in-italy-amalia-ercole-finzi-da-angelo-del-focolare-a-signora-delle-stelle/|title=Le eccellenze del Made in Italy, Amalia Ercole Finzi: da angelo del focolare a signora delle stelle - IlSudOnLine|date=2014-12-25|work=IlSudOnLine|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref> The couple have five children.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ilsudonline.it/le-eccellenze-del-made-in-italy-amalia-ercole-finzi-da-angelo-del-focolare-a-signora-delle-stelle/|title=Le eccellenze del Made in Italy, Amalia Ercole Finzi: da angelo del focolare a signora delle stelle - IlSudOnLine|date=2014-12-25|work=IlSudOnLine|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://27esimaora.corriere.it/articolo/amalia-ercoli-finzi-con-cinque-figli-grattugiavo-mele-in-continuazione/|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi: \"Con cinque figli grattugiavo mele in continuazione\"|last=Agnese|first=Maria Luisa|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honors ==\nIn 2012 she won the [[Franck J. Malina Astronautics Medal]] from the [[International Astronautical Federation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iafastro.org/biographie/amelia-ercoli-finzi/|title=Amelia ERCOLI-FINZI {{!}} Iaf|website=www.iafastro.org|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> She was also awarded the Leonardo Award for Lifetime Achievement from the Italian Association of [[Science journalism|Science Journalists]] for her contributions to the exploration of space and education.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://orbiter.it/cms/amalia-ercole-finzi-premio-leonardo-alla-carriera/|title=Amalia Ercole Finzi, Premio Leonardo alla carriera - Orbiter|date=2012-12-03|work=Orbiter|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref> Ercoli is an advocate for women in science, and speaks up against stereotypes and bias.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/scienze/2017/11/07/news/amalia_ercoli-finzi_alle_bambine_regalate_le_bambole_e_il_meccano_cosi_io_sono_diventata_la_signora_delle_comete_-180471033/?refresh_ce|title=Amalia Ercoli-Finzi: \"Alle bimbe regalate bambole e meccano, cos\u00ec sono diventata la signora delle comete\"|date=2017-11-07|work=Repubblica.it|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://libreriamo.it/libri/amalia-ercoli-finzi-anche-le-donne-possono-farsi-spazio-in-ambiti-prevalentemente-maschili/|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi, \"Anche le donne possono farsi spazio in ambiti prevalentemente maschili\"|website=libreriamo.it|language=it-IT|access-date=2018-04-16|date=2016-10-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.funweek.it/tv/amalia-ercoli-finzi-figli-che-tempo-che-fa/|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi a Che tempo che fa, sapete quanti figli ha? - Funweek|date=2016-09-26|work=Funweek|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417105540/https://www.funweek.it/tv/amalia-ercoli-finzi-figli-che-tempo-che-fa/|archive-date=2018-04-17|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2017 she won the ''Premio Porto Venere Donna'' award which is given annually by the Provincial Council of Women to recognise the most influential women in Italy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://discoverportovenere.com/premio-porto-venere-donna-2017/|title=\"Comet Lady\" Amalia Ercoli Finzi to be awarded in Portovenere|date=2017-07-23|work=Discover Portovenere Blog|access-date=2018-04-16|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2018, the asteroid [[24890 Amaliafinzi]] was named after her.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finzi, Amalia Ercoli}}\n[[Category:Italian astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Women astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Italian aerospace engineers]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian women engineers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian engineers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian engineers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women engineers]]\n[[Category:Polytechnic University of Milan alumni]]\n[[Category:Polytechnic University of Milan faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century women engineers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian astrophysicist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Amalia Ercoli Finzi\n|image = Amalia_Ercoli_Finzi.jpg\n| alma_mater         = [[Polytechnic University of Milan]]\n| employer           = [[Polytechnic University of Milan]]\n| known_for          = Aerospace engineering <br>\n[[Philae (spacecraft)]]\n}}\n\n'''Amalia Ercoli Finzi''' (born 20 April 1937) is an Italian astrophysicist who was the Principal Investigator of the SD2 drill aboard the [[Philae (spacecraft)|Philae spacecraft]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nIn 1962 Ercoli was the first Italian woman to graduate in aeronautical engineering, from the [[Polytechnic University of Milan]], with a final grade of 100/100 [[cum laude]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://video.repubblica.it/rubriche/rnews/rnews-amalia-finzi-io-ingegnere-e-nonna-vi-svelero-i-segreti-della-cometa/183387/182222|title=RNews, Amalia Finzi: 'Io ingegnere e nonna vi sveler\u00f2 i segreti della cometa'|date=2014-11-14|website=Repubblica Tv - la Repubblica.it|language=it|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.museoscienza.org/attivita/spalle_giganti/download/biopic_finzi.pdf|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi|last=|first=|date=|website=Museo Nazionale della Scienza e della Tecnologia Leonardo da Vinci|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ilquorum.it/essere-una-donna-e-ancora-motivo-di-discriminazione-intervista-ad-amalia-ercoli-finzi/|title=\"Essere una donna \u00e9 ancora motivo di discriminazione\". Amalia Ercoli-Finzi {{!}} Il Quorum|date=2016-04-13|work=Il Quorum|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career ==\nFinzi has taught at the [[Polytechnic University of Milan]] for more than fifty years.<ref>{{Citation|last=PoliMi|title=Qua e l\u00e0 nello spazio (A. E. Finzi)|date=2017-06-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L51Vm2V2eA8|accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> She was appointed Associate Professor in 1980 and Professor in 1994. She has served as Professor of Orbital Mechanics, Director of the Department of Aerospace Engineering and on the board of Directors of the [[Museo Nazionale Scienza e Tecnologia Leonardo da Vinci|National Museum of Science and Technology]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Ercoli has considerable experience in space flight dynamics. She has served as a scientific advisor for [[NASA]], [[Italian Space Agency|ISA]] and [[European Space Agency|ESA]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ingegneri.info/news/professione-e-previdenza/amalia-ercoli-finzi-donne-ingegnere-aerospaziale/|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi: parla la prima donna ingegnere aeronautico d\u2019Italia|date=2017-12-21|work=Ingegneri.info|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amishotelgalliffet.com/amalia-ercoli-finzi-ingenieur-des-cometes/#more-4070|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi, ing\u00e9nieur des com\u00e8tes {{!}} Les amis de l'Hotel Galliffet|website=www.amishotelgalliffet.com|language=it-IT|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\nShe has been involved with several [[NASA]] - [[Italian Space Agency]] missions, including [[space tether missions]], [[MiTEx]] and [[Columbus (ISS module)]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Ercoli was responsible for the SD2 instrument, which drilled the surface of [[67P/Churyumov\u2013Gerasimenko]], collected materials and took them for analysis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://science.closeupengineering.it/intervista-ad-amalia-ercoli-finzi-la-mamma-di-rosetta/8147/|title=Intervista ad Amalia Ercoli Finzi, la \"mamma\" di Rosetta {{!}} Close-up Engineering|last=Piazzolla|first=Antonio|date=2015-11-18|work=Close-up Engineering {{!}} Science & Tech|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infoclio.ch/fr/donne-nella-scienza-amalia-ercoli-finzi|title=Donne nella scienza: Amalia Ercoli Finzi {{!}} infoclio.ch|website=www.infoclio.ch|language=fr|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.glistatigenerali.com/robotica_tech-media/amalia-ercoli-finzi-litaliana-che-ha-portato-philae-vicino-al-sole/|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi, l\u2019italiana che ha portato Philae vicino al sole|date=2014-11-22|work=Gli Stati Generali|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref>\n\nErcoli is married to Filiberto Finzi, son of Italian mathematician [[Bruno Finzi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ilsudonline.it/le-eccellenze-del-made-in-italy-amalia-ercole-finzi-da-angelo-del-focolare-a-signora-delle-stelle/|title=Le eccellenze del Made in Italy, Amalia Ercole Finzi: da angelo del focolare a signora delle stelle - IlSudOnLine|date=2014-12-25|work=IlSudOnLine|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref> She has five children.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ilsudonline.it/le-eccellenze-del-made-in-italy-amalia-ercole-finzi-da-angelo-del-focolare-a-signora-delle-stelle/|title=Le eccellenze del Made in Italy, Amalia Ercole Finzi: da angelo del focolare a signora delle stelle - IlSudOnLine|date=2014-12-25|work=IlSudOnLine|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://27esimaora.corriere.it/articolo/amalia-ercoli-finzi-con-cinque-figli-grattugiavo-mele-in-continuazione/|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi: \"Con cinque figli grattugiavo mele in continuazione\"|last=Agnese|first=Maria Luisa|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honors ==\nIn 2012 she won the [[Franck J. Malina Astronautics Medal]] from the [[International Astronautical Federation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iafastro.org/biographie/amelia-ercoli-finzi/|title=Amelia ERCOLI-FINZI {{!}} Iaf|website=www.iafastro.org|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> She was also awarded the Leonardo Award for Lifetime Achievement from the Italian Association of [[Science journalism|Science Journalists]] for her contributions to the exploration of space and education.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://orbiter.it/cms/amalia-ercole-finzi-premio-leonardo-alla-carriera/|title=Amalia Ercole Finzi, Premio Leonardo alla carriera - Orbiter|date=2012-12-03|work=Orbiter|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT}}</ref> Ercoli is an advocate for women in science, and speaks up against stereotypes and bias.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/scienze/2017/11/07/news/amalia_ercoli-finzi_alle_bambine_regalate_le_bambole_e_il_meccano_cosi_io_sono_diventata_la_signora_delle_comete_-180471033/?refresh_ce|title=Amalia Ercoli-Finzi: \"Alle bimbe regalate bambole e meccano, cos\u00ec sono diventata la signora delle comete\"|date=2017-11-07|work=Repubblica.it|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://libreriamo.it/libri/amalia-ercoli-finzi-anche-le-donne-possono-farsi-spazio-in-ambiti-prevalentemente-maschili/|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi, \"Anche le donne possono farsi spazio in ambiti prevalentemente maschili\"|website=libreriamo.it|language=it-IT|access-date=2018-04-16|date=2016-10-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.funweek.it/tv/amalia-ercoli-finzi-figli-che-tempo-che-fa/|title=Amalia Ercoli Finzi a Che tempo che fa, sapete quanti figli ha? - Funweek|date=2016-09-26|work=Funweek|access-date=2018-04-16|language=it-IT|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417105540/https://www.funweek.it/tv/amalia-ercoli-finzi-figli-che-tempo-che-fa/|archive-date=2018-04-17|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2017 she won the ''Premio Porto Venere Donna'' award which is given annually by the Provincial Council of Women to recognise the most influential women in Italy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://discoverportovenere.com/premio-porto-venere-donna-2017/|title=\"Comet Lady\" Amalia Ercoli Finzi to be awarded in Portovenere|date=2017-07-23|work=Discover Portovenere Blog|access-date=2018-04-16|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2018, the asteroid [[24890 Amaliafinzi]] was named after her.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finzi, Amalia Ercoli}}\n[[Category:Italian astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Women astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Italian aerospace engineers]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian women engineers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian engineers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian engineers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women engineers]]\n[[Category:Polytechnic University of Milan alumni]]\n[[Category:Polytechnic University of Milan faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century women engineers]]\n", "name_user": "Mssddmit", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amalia_Ercoli_Finzi"}
{"title_page": "Missa Atropos", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Missa Atropos\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Gazpacho (band)|Gazpacho]]\n| cover      = Missa Atropos cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 26, 2010\n| recorded   = 2009-2010\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Progressive rock]], [[alternative rock]]\n| length     = 59:07\n| label      = HWT Records/[[Kscope]]\n| producer   = Gazpacho\n| prev_title = A Night At Loreley\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| next_title = [[March of Ghosts]]\n| next_year  = 2012\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Missa Atropos\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Defense Mechanism <small>(Radio)</small>\n | single1date = September 28, 2010\n}}\n}}\n'''''Missa Atropos'''''  is the sixth studio album by Norwegian [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Gazpacho (band)|Gazpacho]]. The album released on September 15, 2010 in [[Norwegia]] by ''HWT Records'' and it released in [[United Kingdom]] and worldwide on March 22, 2011 by ''[[Kscope]]''.<ref name=\"KS\">[http://www.kscopemusic.com/gazpacho/missaatropos/album-info.php Kscope Music - Missa Atropos info page]</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIn the early days of 2010 a replacement for recently departed drummer Robert R Johansen was found in Lars Erik Asp, just in time for him to get to know the music before the second part of the \"Tick Tock\" tour kicks in. It was planned to again visit 6 countries in the March/April period but due to a plane tragedy in Poland giving rise to a week of mourning the Polish promoter decided to postpone the concerts planned for Poland on 16\u201318 April. The dates were rescheduled for September 2010. On 1 May 2010 the first concert in the U.S.A. took place as part of a prog festival at the Majestic Theater in Gettysburg Pennsylvania. For the later German/Italian festivals and the Polish gigs in September they hired a stand-in guitarist by the name of Micheal Krumins to cover for Jon-Arne following the arrival of his first child and his decision to give priority to his family. Meanwhile, in July 2010 the band announced that they should still go on without Robert Johanson and recording of the new album is almost over and it will be out by the end of the year. they also revealed the name of the album a month after that during a gig.\n<br />During the Tick Tock Tour on September gigs, pre printed copies of the new album Missa Atropos were available to the present audience. And even before the official release of the new album (November 26) it was already number 1 charted at a Dutch prog site in October and November. The new album is intended to be another album in the series of films without pictures that they started back in 2007 with \"Night\". In other words, a concept album intended to give the listener a chance to take some time off from the world.\nIn December 2010, Gazpacho brought the news that they have licensed \"Missa Atropos\" to ''Kscope''<ref name=\"KS\"/> in the UK. They will have the rights to the album worldwide. The new album was accompanied by a 12 gig tour in 5 different countries in January / February 2011.\n\n==Story==\n[[File:Fates tapestry -460755563.jpg|thumb|right|Atropos Alongside of her sisters while their ending a life.]]\nThe story of the album is about [[Atropos]] goddess of [[Moirai|fate]] and [[destiny]] in [[Greek mythology]], one of the [[Moirai]]. The Story goes on when Atropos decided to choose the mechanism of death instead of mortality and ended their life cutting their thread with her special scissor which they call it \"Abhorred Shears\". She wasn't all alone in this, her other two sister; [[Lachesis (mythology)|Lachesis]] and [[Clotho]] helped her. Clotho was the youngest of all sisters and Lachesis was the kindest one. But as Atropos was so inevitable and hard she used her power to convince them to help her to destroy mortality.\n<br />They say Atropos was jealous of her sisters because they were deciding for humans' lives. Clotho was responsible for spinning the thread of human life and Lachesis was the apportioner, deciding how much time for life was to be allowed for each person or being.<ref>Hamilton, Edith (1942). ''Mythology'', p. 49. Little, Brown and Company, Boston. {{ISBN|978-0-316-34114-1}}</ref>  She measured the thread of life with her rod. She is also said to choose a person's destiny after a thread was measured. In Greek mythology, it is said that she appears with her sisters within three days of a baby's birth to decide its fate. In between all these Atropos was the only one who should have sat somewhere and watches her youngest sisters doing their jobs, so that's when her jealousy overcame her feelings and made her to choose the mechanism of death, then she would have been a part of this circle to end humans' lives on certain time which Lachesis decides.\n<br /> The album characterizes a person who becomes trapped in a lighthouse after leaving the earth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazpachoworld.com/media/discography/ |title=gazpachoworld.com |publisher=gazpachoworld.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-02}}</ref> He tries to fight against his destiny, which Atropos and her other two sisters decided for him but he finds out he can't overcome his destiny so he starts writing his \"Will to Live\". And in the end when he's dying, he's saying his last words in \"An Audience\" that he feels Atropos is standing next to him and she's ready to cut his thread of life and finish him. But we find out that this person was in love with Atropos and he was waiting for his time to come, which Atropos comes along then he can see her face and say goodbye to this world. That's when he starts describing beauty of Atropos to his only audience that was watching him dying, which is a \"Snail\" and asking that snail to describe Atropos' beauty to anyone he see.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = Prog Archives\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}\n| rev2 = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock Prog]]\n| rev2Score = Very Positive\n| rev3 = Dangerdog Music Reviews\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}\n\n}}\nThe album mostly received positive reviews. Website ''[[Prog Archives]]'' gave a positive review to the album and awarded it with 4 star out of 5 and called it: \"Excellent addition to any prog rock music collection.\"<ref>[http://www.progarchives.com/album.asp?id=30228 Progressive Archives/ Gazpacho - Missa Atropos Reviews]</ref> Craig Hartranft of ''Dangerdog Music Reviews'' gave 3 and half star out of 5 to the album and wrote: \"This work is both hard and hearty to digest. It's progressive, art, and alternative at its best with a dark sense.\" and described the album as \"dark, despondent, but artfully creative progressive rock.\" <ref>[http://www.dangerdog.com/2011-music-reviews/gazpacho-missa-atropos-review.php Review : Gazpacho - Missa Atropos :: New Music Review ::  Progressive Rock :: CD Album Music Review : Craig Hartranft]</ref> Jerry Ewing of ''Classic Rock Prog'' gave very positive review to the album and wrote: \"A delightfully mellifluous selection. They won\u2019t be Norway\u2019s best kept secret much longer\".<ref name=\"KS\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length  = {{Duration|m=59|s=07}}\n| all_lyrics  = Jan Henrik Ohme\n| all_music   = Gazpacho\n| title1 = Mass For Atropos, Part 1\n| length1 = 1:43\n| title2 = Defense Mechanism\n| length2 = 6:29\n| title3 = I Was Never Here\n| length3 = 3:12\n| title4 = Snail\n| length4 = 3:39\n| title5 = River\n| length5 = 6:07\n| title6 = Mass for Atropos, Part 2: You're Going to Die Up There\n| length6 = 2:06\n| title7 = Missa Atropos\n| length7 = 8:25\n| title8 = She's Awake\n| length8 = 3:42\n| title9 = Vera\n| length9 = 7:26\n| title10 = Will To Live\n| length10 = 3:07\n| title11 = Mass For Atropos, Part 3\n| length11 = 1:40\n| title12 = Splendid Isolation\n| length12 = 8:33\n| title13 = An Audience\n| length13 = 2:52\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits confirmed by [[Allmusic]]:<ref>[http: