{"title_page": "USCGC Onondaga (WPG-79)", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[Image:USCGC Onondaga (WPG-79).jpg|300px|USCGC Onondaga (WPG-79)]]\n|Ship caption=USCGC ''Onondaga'' (WPG-79).\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|United States|coast guard}} {{USN flag|1947}}\n|Ship name=\n|Ship namesake= [[Onondaga people|Onondaga]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=2 August 1934\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=11 September 1934\n|Ship decommissioned=24 July 1947\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=sold 7 December 1954\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship displacement={{convert|1005|LT|abbr=on}}\n|Ship length={{convert|165|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|36|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|12|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship speed={{convert|13|kn|abbr=on|lk=in}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement= 105\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*2 \u00d7 3-in. guns\n*3 \u00d7 20mm AA guns\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''USCGC ''Onondaga'' (WPG-79)''', a [[United States Coast Guard]] [[Cutter (ship)|cutter]], was built by [[Defoe Shipbuilding Company|Defoe Boat Works]] in [[Bay City, Michigan]], commissioned on 11 September 1934.  From her commissioning until 1941, ''Onondaga'' was stationed at [[Astoria, Oregon]], where she performed important law enforcement duties and rendered much assistance to ships in distress.  Each year she patrolled the annual [[Pelagic zone|pelagic]] seal migration to the [[Pribilof Islands]], and she attempted to prevent out of season [[halibut]] fishing.\n\nExecutive Order 8929 of 1 November 1941 transferred the Coast Guard to the [[United States Navy|Navy]].  ''Onondaga'' continued on general [[patrol]] duty, with her base of operations alternating between [[Seattle, Washington]] and [[Ketchikan, Alaska]].  When the [[United States|American]] [[cargo ship|merchantman]] ''Mauna Ala'' went aground on 10 December 1941 on [[Clatsop Beach, Oregon]], during a blackout test, ''Onondaga'' rushed to the scene and rescued thirty-six crewmen.\n\nThen assigned to [[Escort destroyer|escort]] duty in the area of [[Womens Bay, Alaska|Women's Bay]] and [[Kodiak, Alaska]], she was later ordered to escort duty between [[Cape Spencer (Alaska)|Cape Spencer]] and [[Dutch Harbor, Alaska]], as well as [[anti-aircraft]] and escort patrol off Dutch Harbor.\n\nWhen the Navy learned that the [[Japan]]ese planned a thrust into [[Alaska]]n waters as part of their [[Battle of Midway|Midway]] operation, [[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[Chester W. Nimitz|Nimitz]] allocated five [[cruiser]]s, fourteen [[destroyer]]s, six [[submarine]]s, and suitable auxiliaries to counter the opposing forces in the North.  Five years before the outbreak of war the area had been virtually undefended.  But by September 1941, [[Sitka, Alaska|Sitka]], Kodiak, and Dutch Harbor had been commissioned as [[Naval Air Station]]s, and both Kodiak and Sitka were able to service submarines.  In mid-1940, the [[United States Army|Army]] had established the [[Alaska Defense Command]], with [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[Simon Bolivar Buckner, Jr.|Simon Bolivar Buckner]] in command; and the Navy created an [[Alaskan Sector]] under the [[13th Naval District]], appointing [[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]] [[Ralph C. Parker]] to the command.\n\nParker's \"Alaskan Navy\" consisted of the gunboat, [[USS Charleston (PG-51)|''Charleston'']], as headquarters and flagship, along with the ''Onondaga'' and three former [[fishing boat]]s (''[[USS YP-72|YP-72]]'', ''[[USS YP-73|YP-73]]'', ''[[USS YP-74|YP-74]]''), converted to patrol craft.\"  [[Commander (United States)|Commander]] Charles E. (\"Squeaky\") Anderson, [[United States Navy Reserve|USNR]], a \"local character of infinite resource, energy, and cunning,\" controlled the YP fleet with ''YP-72'' as his unofficial flagship.<ref name=Dictionary>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EpXkkl3QgqcC&pg=PA158&lpg=PA158&dq=%22alaskan+navy%22+Onondaga&source=bl&ots=Ad4-jGCJEN&sig=ACfU3U3mpnIyzxpy9dJlE5ExIxIydKm0Hw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiE-MGMqpnoAhULTawKHb18DusQ6AEwAXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22alaskan%20navy%22%20Onondaga&f=false|first=|last=|authorlink=|title=Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships, Volume 5|pages=157-159 |publisher=[[United States Navy]], Naval History Division|date=1970|ASIN=B000TRP0JU}}</ref> Parker also had three [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] [[lighthouse tender]]s available (''[[USCGC Alder (WAGL-216)|Alder]]'', ''[[USCGC Hemlock (WAGL-217)|Hemlock]]'' and ''[[Cedar (WAGL-207)|Cedar]]'').<ref>{{cite book|url=|first=|last=|authorlink=|title=The Coast Guard at War|pages=59 |publisher=[[United States Coast Guard]]|date=February 15, 1946|quote=The district also had three tenders in commission, Alder, Cedar, and Hemlock.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wTi8mFT53IwC&pg=PA373&lpg=PA373&dq=ALDER#v=onepage&q=ALDER&f=false|first=Paul|last=Silverstone|authorlink=|title=The Navy of World War II, 1922-1947|pages=370 |publisher=[[Routledge]]|date=September 10, 2012|ASIN= B009E1NGUM}}</ref><ref>Silverstone, p. 373 [https://books.google.com/books?id=f8yoVMmEMlQC&pg=PA373&lpg=PA373&dq=Alder#v=onepage&q=Alder&f=false]</ref>   \n\nBy May 1942, Captain Parker expanded his fleet with two old destroyers ([[USS King (DD-242)|''King'']], [[USS Talbot (DD-114)|''Talbot'']]), four additional Coast Guard cutters ([[USCGC Haida (WPG-45)|''Haida'']], [[USCGC Atalanta (WPC-102)|''Atalanta'']], [[USCGC Aurora (WPC-103)|''Aurora'']], [[USCGC Cyane (WPC-105)|''Cyane'']]),<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-_BNt02kWdIC&pg=PA138&dq=onondaga+alaska+sector&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjB7ePe66voAhXBW80KHd6eBOoQ6AEwAXoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=onondaga%20alaska%20sector&f=false|first=Thomas P.|last= Ostrom|authorlink=|title=The United States Coast Guard in World War II: A History of Domestic and Overseas Actions|pages=140 |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|date=May 13, 2009|ISBN=9780786442560}}</ref> some more converted fishing boats (''[[USS YP-86|YP-86]]'', ''[[USS YP-152|YP-152]]'', ''[[USS YP-153|YP-153]]'', ''[[USS YP-400|YP-400]]''),<ref>{{cite magazine|url=|first=|last=|authorlink=|title=Aleutian Heroes, the \"Yippiees\"|pages=7-8 |magazine=Pacific Motor Boat|date=}}</ref> and three seaplane tenders ([[USS Williamson (DD-244)|''Williamson'']], [[USS Gillis (DD-260)|''Gillis'']], and [[USS Casco (AVP-12)|''Casco'']]) with twenty [[PBY Catalina]]s.  ''Charleston'' alone possessed sonar, or guns larger than three inch.  She, together with the destroyers and cutters, saw constant use as escorts for the [[cargo ship|freighter]]s that brought workers and material to the new bases and airfields, none of which were complete at this time.\n\nToward the end of May, when the Japanese sent one task force towards Midway and another towards the [[Aleutians]], tension quickened throughout the Pacific.  [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Robert A. Theobald]], USN, Commander [[North Pacific Force]], who had been headquartered at Kodiak through the early part of May, put to sea on 1 June in [[USS Nashville (CL-43)|''Nashville'' (CL-43)]] and rendezvoused with his augmented cruiser task force to thwart the Japanese Alaska venture.  However, \"Efforts to meet the enemy,\" writes Willoughby \"were unavailing, and there was no fleet action in Alaskan waters.\"\n\nCutter ''Onondaga'', with [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] S. P. Mehlman, USCG, in command, joined with the other patrol craft (''Charleston'', ''Haida'', ''Cyane'', ''Aurora'', ''Bonham'', and 14 YP patrol vessels) and an old ocean tugboat ([[USS Oriole (AT-136)|''Oriole'']]) formed the Surface Search Group of this Northern Pacific Force.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://digital-commons.usnwc.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1021&context=historical-monographs|first=Milan |last=Vego|authorlink=|title=HM 22 2nd Ed.: Major Fleet-versus-Fleet Operations in the Pacific War, 1941\u20131945|pages=126 |publisher=[[Naval War College]]|date=January 1, 2016|ISBN=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/NHC/NewPDFs/USAAF/United%20States%20Strategic%20Bombing%20Survey/USSBS%20Campaigns%20of%20Pacific%20War.pdf|first=|last=|authorlink=|title=THE CAMPAIGNS of the PACIFIC WAR|pages= 101|publisher=[[United States Navy]] United States Strategic Bombing Survey (PACIFIC) Naval Analysis Division|date=1946|ISBN=|quote=Surface Search Group, Commander Alaskan Sector, (Capt. Parker): One gunboat, 1 mine sweeper, 5 Coast Guard cutters, 14 small patrol vessels}}</ref><ref>Vego lists the Oriole as an oiler (AO) although she was designated a tugboat (old) or ATO on 15 May 1944. The Strategic Bombing Survey lists a minesweeper (AM) which was Oriole's designation until 1 June 1942 when she was designated an ocean tugboat (AT)</ref> They were to be assisted by the [[Air Search Group]], composed of twenty PBYs and one [[B-17 Flying Fortress]]. Together these forces were to act as [[Picket (military)|pickets]] to signal any Japanese approach.\n\nIn fact, the Japanese sought to capture nothing east of Adak, which is nearly five hundred miles from Dutch Harbor.  No Japanese plan for invading the Alaskan mainland, [[Canada]], or the United States existed.  The Aleutian section of the Midway operation was essentially defensive, although also diversionary.  Its object was to prevent a U.S. invasion of Japan.\n\nAmerican search flights commenced about 28 May, and the 5 cutters, 1 gunboat, and 14 converted fishing craft deployed as pickets on both the Pacific and [[Bering Sea]] approaches to Dutch Harbor.  In view of his expectation of an attack on Dutch Harbor, Admiral Theobald's operating area south of Kodiak was well chosen.  But because he guessed incorrectly, the main body of his cruiser task force was removed from the scene of action.\n\nJapanese [[aircraft carrier|carrier]] planes launched [[Battle of Dutch Harbor|two attacks against Dutch Harbor]] on 3 June, inflicting considerable damage and killing about twenty-five American soldiers and sailors.  Cutter ''Onondaga'' and destroyers [[USS King (DD-242)|''King'']] and [[USS Talbot (APD-7)|''Talbot'']], seaplane tender [[USS Gillis (AVD-12)|''Gillis'']], army transports ''President Fillmore'' and ''Morlen'', and submarine [[USS S-27 (SS-132)|''S-27'']] went to general quarters and made haste to get underway and stand out to sea, but none cleared the [[harbor]] until the attack was over.  One Japanese plane was shot down.\n\nThe next day, another Japanese carrier-based attack was launched against Dutch Harbor.  About eighteen more Americans died in this attack, but at least five Japanese aircraft were shot down.  The Aleutian part of the Midway operation ended in mid-June.  The Japanese occupied [[Attu Island|Attu]] and [[Kiska]], two islands of little except nuisance value.  A phase began on 11 June which witnessed Japanese attempts to hold what they had, while the American forces prepared to blast them out.\n\nEssentially, the Aleutian battle was a contest of air power, as was Midway.  Weather consistently aided the offensive by shrouding ships in protective mist, while sweeping land targets clear.  In May 1943, Attu was in American hands, and on 15 August U.S. Forces found that the Japanese had completely abandoned Kiska.\n\nCutter ''Onondaga'' and the other ships assigned to the Northern Pacific Force remained on patrol in northern waters through the end of the war.  She returned to the [[United States Treasury Department]] on 1 January 1946, and resumed patrol duties out of Astoria.\n\nThe ''Onondaga'' also gained fame for having rescued the survivors of the liner S S Yukon wrecked near Seward, Alaska in February 4, 1946.<ref>{{Cite news|first= |last= |authorlink=   |title= Alaskan Ship Breaks Up, Rescue Work Continues |newspaper=[[Saskatoon Star-Phoenix]]|date=February 5, 1946 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=urtjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=O3oNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2302,2823519&dq=cutter+onondaga&hl=en  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n''Onondaga'' was decommissioned on 24 July 1947, she was sold on 7 December 1954 to [[Foss Launch and Tug Company]] of Seattle, Washington.\n\n==Update==\n\nApril, 2011, Environmental Protection Agency divers surveyed the Onondaga's hull, which had been shorn of its superstructure, sunk at a pier in the Lake Washington Ship Canal near Seattle.  They found no pollutants, but a recently passed state law calling for the removal of abandoned boats and barges in Washington State waters may herald her demise.<ref>http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2014884767_apwaepadive.html</ref>\n\nTwo of ''Onondaga''s sisters ships became museum ships.  The [[USCGC Comanche (WPG-76)|''Comanche'' (WPG-76)]] served as a museum ship at Patriot's Point, South Carolina before being sunk as an artificial reef. The [[USCGC Mohawk (WPG-78)|''Mohawk'' (WPG-78)]] served as of museum ship in Key West, Florida before being sunk as an artificial reef in July 2012.\n\nA letter appeared in the June 2, 2011 Nome Nugget noting the dearth of WW II museum and/or memorial ships preserved in Alaska even through both it and Hawaii were the front-lines of the conflict.  Four ships have been set aside in Hawaii as memorial and/or museum ships.  They are the USS Arizona, the USS Utah, the USS Missouri and the USS Bowfin.<ref>http://www.nomenugget.net/20110602/index.php</ref> The letter called for the Onondaga to be retrieved for such a purpose, using the salvage and restoration of the WW I Turkish mine-layer [[Nusret (ship)|Nusret]] as a precedent.  The TGC Nusret N-16 was in a similar decrepit condition as the Onondaga at this writing.\n\n==References==\n:{{DANFS}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.uscg.mil/history/webcutters/Onondaga_WPG_79.pdf  uscg:mil: U.S. Coast Guard Cutter ''Onondaga'' WPG-79]\n*[http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/sh-us-cs/uscg-sh/cgsh-o/onondaga.htm  history.navy.mil: U.S. Coast Guard Cutter ''Onondaga'' (CG-59, later WPG-79), 1934-1954]\n*[http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/o3/onondaga-iii.htm  history.navy.mil: DANFS entry on USS ''Onondaga'']\n*[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=urtjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=O3oNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2302,2823519&dq=cutter+onondaga&hl=en Alaskan Ship Breaks Up, Rescue Work Continues]\n*[http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2014884767_apwaepadive.html EPA divers to survey sunken vessel in Lake Washington Ship Canal]\n*{{Cite web|first= |last= |authorlink=   |title= U.S. Coast Guard & Revenue Cutter Logbooks - National Archives Record Group 26: Records of the U.S. Coast Guard, 1785-2005  |website=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|date= |url=https://www.pmel.noaa.gov/rediscover/us-coast-guard-revenue-cutter-logbooks  |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}\n\n{{Algonquin-class cutter}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:USCGC ''Onondaga'' (WPG-79)}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Onondaga (WPG-79)}}\n\n[[Category:Algonquin-class cutters]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Bay City, Michigan]]\n[[Category:1934 ships]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[Image:USCGC Onondaga (WPG-79).jpg|300px|USCGC Onondaga (WPG-79)]]\n|Ship caption=USCGC ''Onondaga'' (WPG-79).\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|United States|coast guard}} {{USN flag|1947}}\n|Ship name=\n|Ship namesake= [[Onondaga people|Onondaga]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=2 August 1934\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=11 September 1934\n|Ship decommissioned=24 July 1947\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=sold 7 December 1954\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship displacement={{convert|1005|LT|abbr=on}}\n|Ship length={{convert|165|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|36|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|12|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship speed={{convert|13|kn|abbr=on|lk=in}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement= 105\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*2 \u00d7 3-in. guns\n*3 \u00d7 20mm AA guns\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''USCGC ''Onondaga'' (WPG-79)''', a [[United States Coast Guard]] [[Cutter (ship)|cutter]], was built by [[Defoe Shipbuilding Company|Defoe Boat Works]] in [[Bay City, Michigan]], commissioned on 11 September 1934.  From her commissioning until 1941, ''Onondaga'' was stationed at [[Astoria, Oregon]], where she performed important law enforcement duties and rendered much assistance to ships in distress.  Each year she patrolled the annual [[Pelagic zone|pelagic]] seal migration to the [[Pribilof Islands]], and she attempted to prevent out of season [[halibut]] fishing.\n\nExecutive Order 8929 of 1 November 1941 transferred the Coast Guard to the [[United States Navy|Navy]].  ''Onondaga'' continued on general [[patrol]] duty, with her base of operations alternating between [[Seattle, Washington]] and [[Ketchikan, Alaska]].  When the [[United States|American]] [[cargo ship|merchantman]] ''Mauna Ala'' went aground on 10 December 1941 on [[Clatsop Beach, Oregon]], during a blackout test, ''Onondaga'' rushed to the scene and rescued thirty-six crewmen.\n\nThen assigned to [[Escort destroyer|escort]] duty in the area of [[Womens Bay, Alaska|Women's Bay]] and [[Kodiak, Alaska]], she was later ordered to escort duty between [[Cape Spencer (Alaska)|Cape Spencer]] and [[Dutch Harbor, Alaska]], as well as [[anti-aircraft]] and escort patrol off Dutch Harbor.\n\nWhen the Navy learned that the [[Japan]]ese planned a thrust into [[Alaska]]n waters as part of their [[Battle of Midway|Midway]] operation, [[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[Chester W. Nimitz|Nimitz]] allocated five [[cruiser]]s, fourteen [[destroyer]]s, six [[submarine]]s, and suitable auxiliaries to counter the opposing forces in the North.  Five years before the outbreak of war the area had been virtually undefended.  But by September 1941, [[Sitka, Alaska|Sitka]], Kodiak, and Dutch Harbor had been commissioned as [[Naval Air Station]]s, and both Kodiak and Sitka were able to service submarines.  In mid-1940, the [[United States Army|Army]] had established the [[Alaska Defense Command]], with [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[Simon Bolivar Buckner, Jr.|Simon Bolivar Buckner]] in command; and the Navy created an [[Alaskan Sector]] under the [[13th Naval District]], appointing [[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]] [[Ralph C. Parker]] to the command.\n\nParker's \"Alaskan Navy\" consisted of the gunboat, [[USS Charleston (PG-51)|''Charleston'']], as headquarters and flagship, along with the ''Onondaga'' and three former [[fishing boat]]s (''[[USS YP-72|YP-72]]'', ''[[USS YP-73|YP-73]]'', ''[[USS YP-74|YP-74]]''), converted to patrol craft.\"  [[Commander (United States)|Commander]] Charles E. (\"Squeaky\") Anderson, [[United States Navy Reserve|USNR]], a \"local character of infinite resource, energy, and cunning,\" controlled the YP fleet with ''YP-72'' as his unofficial flagship.<ref name=Dictionary>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EpXkkl3QgqcC&pg=PA158&lpg=PA158&dq=%22alaskan+navy%22+Onondaga&source=bl&ots=Ad4-jGCJEN&sig=ACfU3U3mpnIyzxpy9dJlE5ExIxIydKm0Hw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiE-MGMqpnoAhULTawKHb18DusQ6AEwAXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22alaskan%20navy%22%20Onondaga&f=false|first=|last=|authorlink=|title=Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships, Volume 5|pages=157-159 |publisher=[[United States Navy]], Naval History Division|date=1970|ASIN=B000TRP0JU}}</ref> Parker also had three [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] [[lighthouse tender]]s available (''[[USCGC Alder (WAGL-216)|Alder]]'', ''[[USCGC Hemlock (WAGL-217)|Hemlock]]'' and ''[[Cedar (WAGL-207)|Cedar]]'').<ref>{{cite book|url=|first=|last=|authorlink=|title=The Coast Guard at War|pages=59 |publisher=[[United States Coast Guard]]|date=February 15, 1946|quote=The district also had three tenders in commission, Alder, Cedar, and Hemlock.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wTi8mFT53IwC&pg=PA373&lpg=PA373&dq=ALDER#v=onepage&q=ALDER&f=false|first=Paul|last=Silverstone|authorlink=|title=The Navy of World War II, 1922-1947|pages=370 |publisher=[[Routledge]]|date=September 10, 2012|ASIN= B009E1NGUM}}</ref><ref>Silverstone, p. 373 [https://books.google.com/books?id=f8yoVMmEMlQC&pg=PA373&lpg=PA373&dq=Alder#v=onepage&q=Alder&f=false]</ref>   \n\nBy May 1942, Captain Parker expanded his fleet with two old destroyers ([[USS King (DD-242)|''King'']], [[USS Talbot (DD-114)|''Talbot'']]), four additional Coast Guard cutters ([[USCGC Haida (WPG-45)|''Haida'']], [[USCGC Atalanta (WPC-102)|''Atalanta'']], [[USCGC Aurora (WPC-103)|''Aurora'']], [[USCGC Cyane (WPC-105)|''Cyane'']]),<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-_BNt02kWdIC&pg=PA138&dq=onondaga+alaska+sector&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjB7ePe66voAhXBW80KHd6eBOoQ6AEwAXoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=onondaga%20alaska%20sector&f=false|first=Thomas P.|last= Ostrom|authorlink=|title=The United States Coast Guard in World War II: A History of Domestic and Overseas Actions|pages=140 |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|date=May 13, 2009|ISBN=9780786442560}}</ref> some more converted fishing boats (''[[USS YP-86|YP-86]]'', ''[[USS YP-152|YP-152]]'', ''[[USS YP-153|YP-153]]'', ''[[USS YP-400|YP-400]]''),<ref>{{cite magazine|url=|first=|last=|authorlink=|title=Aleutian Heroes, the \"Yippiees\"|pages=7-8 |magazine=Pacific Motor Boat|date=}}</ref> and three seaplane tenders ([[USS Williamson (DD-244)|''Williamson'']], [[USS Gillis (DD-260)|''Gillis'']], and [[USS Casco (AVP-12)|''Casco'']]) with twenty [[PBY Catalina]]s.  ''Charleston'' alone possessed sonar, or guns larger than three inch.  She, together with the destroyers and cutters, saw constant use as escorts for the [[cargo ship|freighter]]s that brought workers and material to the new bases and airfields, none of which were complete at this time.\n\nToward the end of May, when the Japanese sent one task force towards Midway and another towards the [[Aleutians]], tension quickened throughout the Pacific.  [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Robert A. Theobald]], USN, Commander [[North Pacific Force]], who had been headquartered at Kodiak through the early part of May, put to sea on 1 June in [[USS Nashville (CL-43)|''Nashville'' (CL-43)]] and rendezvoused with his augmented cruiser task force to thwart the Japanese Alaska venture.  However, \"Efforts to meet the enemy,\" writes Willoughby \"were unavailing, and there was no fleet action in Alaskan waters.\"\n\nCutter ''Onondaga'', with [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] S. P. Mehlman, USCG, in command, joined with the other patrol craft (''Charleston'', ''Haida'', ''Cyane'', ''Aurora'', ''Bonham'', and 14 YP patrol vessels) and an old ocean tugboat ([[USS Oriole (AT-136)|''Oriole'']]) formed the Surface Search Group of this Northern Pacific Force.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://digital-commons.usnwc.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1021&context=historical-monographs|first=Milan |last=Vego|authorlink=|title=HM 22 2nd Ed.: Major Fleet-versus-Fleet Operations in the Pacific War, 1941\u20131945|pages=126 |publisher=[[Naval War College]]|date=January 1, 2016|ISBN=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/NHC/NewPDFs/USAAF/United%20States%20Strategic%20Bombing%20Survey/USSBS%20Campaigns%20of%20Pacific%20War.pdf|first=|last=|authorlink=|title=THE CAMPAIGNS of the PACIFIC WAR|pages= 101|publisher=[[United States Navy]] United States Strategic Bombing Survey (PACIFIC) Naval Analysis Division|date=1946|ISBN=|quote=Surface Search Group, Commander Alaskan Sector, (Capt. Parker): One gunboat, 1 mine sweeper, 5 Coast Guard cutters, 14 small patrol vessels}}</ref><ref>Vego lists the Oriole as an oiler (AO) although she was designated a tugboat (old) or ATO on 15 May 1944. The Strategic Bombing Survey lists a minesweeper (AM) which was Oriole's designation until 1 June 1942 when she was designated an ocean tugboat (AT)</ref> They were to be assisted by the [[Air Search Group]], composed of twenty PBYs and one [[B-17 Flying Fortress]]. Together these forces were to act as [[Picket (military)|pickets]] to signal any Japanese approach.\n\nIn fact, the Japanese sought to capture nothing east of Adak, which is nearly five hundred miles from Dutch Harbor.  No Japanese plan for invading the Alaskan mainland, [[Canada]], or the United States existed.  The Aleutian section of the Midway operation was essentially defensive, although also diversionary.  Its object was to prevent a U.S. invasion of Japan.\n\nAmerican search flights commenced about 28 May, and the 5 cutters, 1 gunboat, and 14 converted fishing craft deployed as pickets on both the Pacific and [[Bering Sea]] approaches to Dutch Harbor.  In view of his expectation of an attack on Dutch Harbor, Admiral Theobald's operating area south of Kodiak was well chosen.  But because he guessed incorrectly, the main body of his cruiser task force was removed from the scene of action.\n\nJapanese [[aircraft carrier|carrier]] planes launched [[Battle of Dutch Harbor|two attacks against Dutch Harbor]] on 3 June, inflicting considerable damage and killing about twenty-five American soldiers and sailors.  Cutter ''Onondaga'' and destroyers [[USS King (DD-242)|''King'']] and [[USS Talbot (APD-7)|''Talbot'']], seaplane tender [[USS Gillis (AVD-12)|''Gillis'']], army transports ''President Fillmore'' and ''Morlen'', and submarine [[USS S-27 (SS-132)|''S-27'']] went to general quarters and made haste to get underway and stand out to sea, but none cleared the [[harbor]] until the attack was over.  One Japanese plane was shot down.\n\nThe next day, another Japanese carrier-based attack was launched against Dutch Harbor.  About eighteen more Americans died in this attack, but at least five Japanese aircraft were shot down.  The Aleutian part of the Midway operation ended in mid-June.  The Japanese occupied [[Attu Island|Attu]] and [[Kiska]], two islands of little except nuisance value.  A phase began on 11 June which witnessed Japanese attempts to hold what they had, while the American forces prepared to blast them out.\n\nEssentially, the Aleutian battle was a contest of air power, as was Midway.  Weather consistently aided the offensive by shrouding ships in protective mist, while sweeping land targets clear.  In May 1943, Attu was in American hands, and on 15 August U.S. Forces found that the Japanese had completely abandoned Kiska.\n\nCutter ''Onondaga'' and the other ships assigned to the Northern Pacific Force remained on patrol in northern waters through the end of the war.  She returned to the [[United States Treasury Department]] on 1 January 1946, and resumed patrol duties out of Astoria.\n\nThe ''Onondaga'' also gained fame for having rescued the survivors of the liner S S Yukon wrecked near Seward, Alaska in February 4, 1946.<ref>{{Cite news|first= |last= |authorlink=   |title= Alaskan Ship Breaks Up, Rescur\\e Work Continues |newspaper=[[Saskatoon Star-Phoenix]]|date=February 5, 1946 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=urtjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=O3oNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2302,2823519&dq=cutter+onondaga&hl=en  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n''Onondaga'' was decommissioned on 24 July 1947, she was sold on 7 December 1954 to [[Foss Launch and Tug Company]] of Seattle, Washington.\n\n==Update==\n\nApril, 2011, Environmental Protection Agency divers surveyed the Onondaga's hull, which had been shorn of its superstructure, sunk at a pier in the Lake Washington Ship Canal near Seattle.  They found no pollutants, but a recently passed state law calling for the removal of abandoned boats and barges in Washington State waters may herald her demise.<ref>http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2014884767_apwaepadive.html</ref>\n\nTwo of ''Onondaga''s sisters ships became museum ships.  The [[USCGC Comanche (WPG-76)|''Comanche'' (WPG-76)]] served as a museum ship at Patriot's Point, South Carolina before being sunk as an artificial reef. The [[USCGC Mohawk (WPG-78)|''Mohawk'' (WPG-78)]] served as of museum ship in Key West, Florida before being sunk as an artificial reef in July 2012.\n\nA letter appeared in the June 2, 2011 Nome Nugget noting the dearth of WW II museum and/or memorial ships preserved in Alaska even through both it and Hawaii were the front-lines of the conflict.  Four ships have been set aside in Hawaii as memorial and/or museum ships.  They are the USS Arizona, the USS Utah, the USS Missouri and the USS Bowfin.<ref>http://www.nomenugget.net/20110602/index.php</ref> The letter called for the Onondaga to be retrieved for such a purpose, using the salvage and restoration of the WW I Turkish mine-layer [[Nusret (ship)|Nusret]] as a precedent.  The TGC Nusret N-16 was in a similar decrepit condition as the Onondaga at this writing.\n\n==References==\n:{{DANFS}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.uscg.mil/history/webcutters/Onondaga_WPG_79.pdf  uscg:mil: U.S. Coast Guard Cutter ''Onondaga'' WPG-79]\n*[http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/sh-us-cs/uscg-sh/cgsh-o/onondaga.htm  history.navy.mil: U.S. Coast Guard Cutter ''Onondaga'' (CG-59, later WPG-79), 1934-1954]\n*[http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/o3/onondaga-iii.htm  history.navy.mil: DANFS entry on USS ''Onondaga'']\n*[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=urtjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=O3oNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2302,2823519&dq=cutter+onondaga&hl=en Alaskan Ship Breaks Up, Rescue Work Continues]\n*[http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2014884767_apwaepadive.html EPA divers to survey sunken vessel in Lake Washington Ship Canal]\n*{{Cite web|first= |last= |authorlink=   |title= U.S. Coast Guard & Revenue Cutter Logbooks - National Archives Record Group 26: Records of the U.S. Coast Guard, 1785-2005  |website=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|date= |url=https://www.pmel.noaa.gov/rediscover/us-coast-guard-revenue-cutter-logbooks  |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}\n\n{{Algonquin-class cutter}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:USCGC ''Onondaga'' (WPG-79)}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Onondaga (WPG-79)}}\n\n[[Category:Algonquin-class cutters]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Bay City, Michigan]]\n[[Category:1934 ships]]\n", "name_user": "Patapsco913", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USCGC_Onondaga_(WPG-79)"}
